<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US-MLS Roundup,0440 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rapids, Fire win in shutouts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DENVER (AP) _ Ross Paule scored his third goal in two games as
the Colorado Rapids beat the San Jose Clash 2-0 Saturday night.
	   Paule scored the game-winner in the 50th minute. Paul Bravo
passed to Adrian Paz on the right flank, and Paz sent a cross to
Paule in the middle of the penalty area. Paule bounced a header
past goalkeeper David Kramer for his fourth goal of the season.
	   Chris Henderson scored his first goal of the season in the 56th
minute to ice the victory. Henderson beat Kramer with a shot into
the upper corner of the net from 22 yards (20 meters) out.
Defenders Tahj Jakins and Joey DiGiamarino assisted on the play.
	   Rapids goalkeeper Marcus Hahnemann made four saves to earn the
shutout.
	   Colorado's defense has rebounded after a five-game losing streak
in which the Rapids were outscored 17-1. Colorado (6-8) has now won
three straight and outscored its opponents 7-1 during the streak.
	   San Jose (5-9) lost its third straight and has not scored a goal
in 239 minutes. The longest scoreless streak of the season _ 292
minutes _ belongs to the Miami Fusion.
 &UR; Fire 2, Crew 0
	   In Chicago, Fire goalkeeper Zach Thornton posted his
league-leading fourth shutout Saturday night as his team beat the
Columbus Crew 2-0.
	   Rich Kotschau scored just eight minutes into the match,
finishing off a cross from Jerzy Podbrozny. Peter Nowak scored the
insurance goal seven minutes into the second half, breaking through
the center of the defense and beating Columbus goalie Mark
Dougherty from close range.
	   Thornton had to make just one save as the Fire outshot the Crew
17-8.
	   The victory moved Chicago (7-5) past idle Dallas into second
place in the Western Conference, 12 points behind Los Angeles.
Columbus (7-6) remains in second in the Eastern Conference.
 &UR; Wizards 1, Mutiny 0
	   In Kansas City, Missouri, the Wizards Mo Johnston scored on a
header in the 30th minute Saturday night as the Kansas City beat
the Tampa Bay Mutiny 1-0.
	   The game's lone goal came when Johnston headed Paul Wright's
corner kick past Mutiny goalkeeper Thomas Ravelli from 12 yards (11
meters) out.
	   The goal marked the first time in seven games that the Wizards
have scored in the first half.
	   Kansas City had a possession percentage of 53 percent, and made
13 total shots, seven on goal. The Mutiny had nine shots, with two
on goal.
	   Goalkeeper Mike Ammann recorded his third shutout of the season
for Kansas City (6-8).
	   Ravelli saved five Kansas City shots to keep the Mutiny (3-12)
within striking distance.
</TEXT>
