</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Suharto's Birthday </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No birthday celebrations for Indonesia's reclusive ex-president
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GEOFF SPENCER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's ex-President Suharto turns
77 on Monday, but there will be no celebration for the man who last
month surrendered a 32-year-long iron grip over the world's fourth
most populous nation.
	   Forced to quit after mobs went on a rampage and angry protesters
demanded he be tried for corruption, Suharto has said nothing
publicly since his resignation on May 21.
	   In contrast, his successor, President B.J. Habibie, cannot seem
to get enough of the limelight and is basking in the glory of
rolling back many of Suharto's draconian ways.
	   The aloof, king-like Suharto usually avoided the media. But
Habibie chatted for hours on Saturday with editors and foreign
correspondents about his vision for ``accelerated evaluation'' to
bring Indonesia out of its economic crisis.
	   Suharto remains holed up at his private home on Cendana Street,
Central Jakarta, guarded by the powerful military from growing
calls for retribution against him and his super-rich family.
	   He rarely ventures outside the compound. Looking for solace, he
visited a mosque. One family member said the former autocrat has
slipped out to play a few rounds of golf in recent days.
	   Meanwhile, newly sworn-in President Habibie has busied himself
by releasing some political prisoners, lifting bans on labor unions
and abolishing restrictions on press freedoms.
	   He has pledged to cooperate fully with the Washington-based
International Monetary Fund to save the economy.
	   In addition, Habibie has also promised new electoral reforms
laws by August. Bans on the formation of new political parties will
be lifted as well.
	   Parliamentary elections have been scheduled for next May and a
1,000-seat national assembly will chose a new president by December
of 1999.
	   His embrace of reform is a dramatic turnaround for the once
staunch Suharto supporter. A friend of Suharto's since the 1950s,
he was rewarded for his loyalty by being elected vice-president
earlier this year.
	   On Saturday, he recounted how Suharto has told him 24 years ago
that both would one day lead Indonesia into the next century.
	   However, he denies that he is still taking orders from his
former mentor. He claims not have talked with Suharto since the
aging general stepped down.
	   ``Look what we have done,'' he said in reference to the changes
he has wrought in the wake of the end of Suharto's regime.
	   Still, he appears determined to protect his old boss.
	   ``I ask the people of the Republic of Indonesia to concentrate
on the future. It doesn't mean that corruption and nepotism and so
on will be forgotten. I ask them to leave it to the legal
process,'' Habibie said.
	   Many have called for Suharto to face trial for corruption and
abuse of power. Some want the state to seize billions of dollars
amassed by his family.
	   A party was held for Indonesia's former leader Saturday, but it
was not Suharto who was feted.
	   About 90 people gathered to celebrate the birth of Indonesia's
founding President Sukarno, who was replaced by Suharto after an
abortive communist coup in 1965. 	   
</TEXT>
