<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Singapore-Medicine </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singaporeans cross border to Malaysia for cheaper medicine
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Cost-conscious residents of
Singaporean have been heading to neighboring Malaysia for cheaper
medical treatment, a Malaysian newspaper reported Sunday.
	   Singaporeans with diabetes, for example, can buy a month's
supply of treatment medicine for only 2 ringgit (U.S. dlrs 0.5) in
Malaysia, far cheaper than the 600 ringgit (dlrs 153) they would
pay at home, The Star newspaper said.
	   ``I have been told that 10 to 15 foreigners, mostly
Singaporeans, seek treatment at (a local) hospital daily,'' Suresh
Naidu, a Malaysian politician, was quoted as saying by The Star.
	   Malaysia's government-subsidized hospitals charge only a nominal
fee for medical treatment and drugs. 	   
</TEXT>
