<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Train Bomb,0230 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb rips through train killing 20 people
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ A powerful bomb tore through a train
traveling through southern Pakistan on Sunday, killing 20 people
and wounding 25 others, many of them seriously, police and
emergency workers said.
	   The train was six kilometers (three miles) outside Sukkur, some
200 kilometers (120 miles) north of Karachi, capital of the
southern Sindh province, when the bomb shattered the train just
before dawn, police said.
	   The train was headed toward the northwestern city of Peshawar,
they said.
	   No one immediately took responsibility for the bombing, but the
government has blamed rival India, for explosions in the
neighboring Sindh province and in the eastern Punjab province,
which borders India.
	   The government blamed India for a Friday bombing of a theater
that killed three people in eastern Lahore, capital of Punjab
province.
	   The government said it had received intelligence information
that Indian secret service agents would try to infiltrate into
Pakistan to conduct terrorist acts between June 5 and 7.
	   Pakistan and India routinely blame each other for acts of
terrorism on their soil. The two countries have fought three wars
since the South Asian subcontinent gained its independence in 1947
from the departing British.
</TEXT>
