</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Hong Kong-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong leader says economy will rebound after ``some time''
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Hong Kong will rebound from its
current economic downturn, though it will likely take ``some
time,'' the Chinese territory's leader said Sunday.
	   ``We are now in a very painful period of economic restructuring
because of years of high property values, high interest rates and
very high wages have threatened our competitiveness,'' said Hong
Kong Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa.
	   ``It is a period of adjustment, but as before, we come out of it
very well and will be stronger, better and fitter,'' he said.
	   Figures released late last month showed Hong Kong's economy
contracting by 2 percent in the quarter ending in March, the first
period of negative growth in 13 years.
	   Avoiding questions as to whether Hong Kong was at the start of a
full-blown recession, Tung, speaking on a local news program, said
Hong Kong was in ``a process of adjusting ourselves.''
	   ``It will be some time realistically speaking before we will
come out of it,'' he said.
	   Separately, Tung said on the program that he does not believe
China will devalue the Chinese currency as a way to bolster its
economic performance.
	   ``China continues to be very competitive and there is no reason
for China to devalue,'' he said.
	   The Hong Kong leader is scheduled to visit Australia next week.
</TEXT>
