w1086 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge     06-07 0325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Khmer Rouge rebels register for Cambodian election
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Khmer Rouge defectors who were
outlaws just three months ago will for the first time help select
Cambodia's new government with ballots, not bullets, officials said
Sunday.
	   The National Election Commission expects to register more than
10,000 ex-guerrillas and others in the one-time Khmer Rouge bastion
of Anlong Veng to vote in elections July 26, said Sarang Kamsan, an
aide to Chheng Phon, the commission chairman.
	   Anlong Veng came under control of the Phnom Penh government in
March after war-weary guerrillas rebelled against the leadership of
Ta Mok, who is believed to be pressed against the Thai border with
a few hundred die-hard followers.
	   The commission, charged with overseeing the polls, determined it
was technically feasible to let the defectors participate after
they were formally brought under government rule Friday.
	   ``Everyone here who can vote will,'' said Yim Phanna, a former
commander who helped lead the Anlong Veng defections. ``Why not?
Now we are citizens, we have that right.''
	   The Khmer Rouge were a much larger force when they boycotted
U.N.-organized polls in 1993 and threatened to kill Cambodians who
participated. Most Cambodians ignored the threats and voted for the
first time in decades.
	   The Maoist-inspired revolutionaries caused the deaths of as many
as 2 million Cambodians when they ruled between 1975 and 1979.
After they were ousted by a Vietnamese invasion, they continued to
wage civil war against successive governments.
	   The group has been breaking apart since 1996 and is believed to
be on its last legs. Anlong Veng was the last major stronghold.
	   Cambodian strongman Hun Sen has called the elections in a bid to
regain international legitimacy and aid lost after his violent coup
last July against his co-premier, Prince Norodom Ranariddh. 	   
</TEXT>
