r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Turkey-BoatDistress 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Boat Distress, 1st Ld-Writethru,0305 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Boat passengers send distress signal to Turkish
</HEADLINE>
authorities &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Greek authorities saying boat was headed to
Italy. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CANAKKALE, Turkey (AP) _ Passengers aboard a Ukrainian ship sent
out distress signals to Turkish maritime authorities claiming they
were being held hostage, a news report said.
	   The report late Saturday could not be immediately confirmed, and
it wasn't clear if the passengers were in any danger.
	   Turkish authorities asked the captain of the Ukrainian-flagged
ship, the Taras Shevchenko, to stop, but he refused, saying
everything was calm on board, the semi-official Anatolia news
agency said.
	   The ship was traveling through the Dardanelles straits and was
due to pass through Istanbul's Bosphorus straits Sunday morning,
Anatolia said. The two straits connect the Aegean Sea with the
Black Sea.
	   The passengers began sending distress signals when a Turkish
patrol boat approached the ship to carry out a health inspection,
Anatolia said. It wasn't known if the inspection occurred.
	   The passengers, from Azerbaijan, held up ``S.O.S.'' signs and
tossed a message to the patrol boat in a tin can reading:
	   ``On the Ukrainian boat, we are in danger. The children and the
elderly are in danger. The women and children are being held
hostage,'' the message read.
	   They said the boat was bringing the 530 passengers to Odessa, a
Ukrainian port city on the Black Sea, against their wishes.
	   They urged the maritime authorities to relay their message to
the consulates of Azerbaijan, Ukraine, Russia and Germany.
	   According to the Greek coast guard, the ship left the Athens
port of Piraeus with 271 crew members and 517 passengers and told
port authorities it was headed toward Italy.
</TEXT>
