<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Train Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru,0327 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb rips through Pakistani train, killing 20 people
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quote from witness, details of accident; CORRECTS
that accident 30 kilometers sted six outside nearest village; ADDS
byline &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By ZAHID HUSSAIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ A powerful bomb tore through a
cross-country train Sunday in southern Pakistan, killing 20 people
and wounding 25 others, many of them seriously, police and
emergency workers said.
	   The train was passing through a village 30 kilometers (18 miles)
outside Sukkur, some 200 kilometers (120 miles) north of Karachi,
capital of the southern Sindh province, when the bomb shattered the
train just before dawn, police said.
	   The express, with about 1,000 passengers on board, was headed
toward the northwestern city of Peshawar, they said. Among the dead
were four children aged 5 or younger, police said.
	   ``When we arrived, the carriage was destroyed and bodies were
blown to pieces. Many of the passengers were trapped and shouting
for help,'' said ambulance driver Mohammed Hafiz.
	   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the bombing, but
the government has blamed rival India for explosions in the
neighboring Sindh province and in the eastern border province of
Punjab.
	   The government blamed India for a Friday bombing of a theater
that killed three people in eastern Lahore, capital of Punjab
province.
	   The government said it had received intelligence information
that Indian secret service agents would try to infiltrate into
Pakistan to conduct terrorist acts between June 5 and 7.
	   Pakistan and India routinely blame each other for acts of
terrorism on their soil, but they rarely provide evidence to
support their claims.
	   The two countries have fought three wars since the South Asian
subcontinent gained its independence in 1947 from the departing
British.
</TEXT>
