<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Politics-Fire </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Supporters of defeated candidate burn Philippine town hall
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Supporters of a defeated mayoral
candidate in the Philippines allegedly set ablaze a town hall in a
suburb of the capital city, injuring at least seven people, local
officials said Sunday.
	   Scores of rowdy backers of the main opposition party's mayoral
candidate stormed the Navotas town hall Saturday night, and are
suspected of having doused it with gasoline and then setting it on
fire with torches, outgoing Mayor Felipe del Rosario said.
	   ``This is plain and simple arson,'' he said.
	   Police have arrested and begun questioning at least two people
linked to the blaze, fire officials said.
	   Del Rosario also alleged the attackers burned tires on the
street leading to the two-story town hall to block fire trucks.
	   An undetermined number of attackers fled the scene of the fire.
	   Among the injured were two policemen who jumped out of a window
on the second floor of the hall after it was set ablaze, officials
said.
	   The attackers were upset over suspicions of electoral fraud in
the mayoral election, which was won by the outgoing mayor's wife,
the mayor and fire officials said. The wife was scheduled to be
proclaimed as the winner on Monday, officials said.
	   The general elections held May 11 were among the Philippines'
most peaceful ever, although at least 45 people were killed and
protests over alleged electoral fraud broke out in many towns and
cities. 	   
</TEXT>
