<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sport-RugbyL-Australian-Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Johns leads Newcastle to victory
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TONY HARPER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Newcastle scrum half Andrew Johns
backed up from Friday's State of Origin match to push his team to
the outright lead in Australia's National Rugby League competition
on the weekend.
	   The Knights went alone at the top after scoring an 18-16 victory
over Cronulla on Saturday, while St. George fell from the joint
ladder lead with a surprise 22-20 loss at Adelaide.
	   Johns was outstanding in New South Wales' win over Queensland on
Friday and continued his fine form 24 hours later when he played
the full 80 minutes. The Knights were down 16-12 with 12 minutes
left before Johns regathered his own kick ahead and sparked a try
for Mark Hughes.
	   ``They were all over us until then, and probably deserved to
win, but to our guys' credit we showed why we keep winning games
this year,'' Johns said.
	   Adelaide pulled off the upset of the season by beating the
Saints. Former Canberra Raider Graham Appo booted Adelaide home
with a conversion from the sideline after the scores were locked at
20-20 with four minutes left to play.
	   St. George, chasing a club record 10th win in a row, led 20-8
midway through the second half.
	   Melbourne scored a 25-16 win at Balmain to stay one point behind
Newcastle and move above St. George.
	   Brisbane, playing without regulars Steve Renouf and Darren
Smith, had a controversial 20-16 loss to Parramatta at ANZ Stadium
on Sunday.
	   Petero Civonicivea just missed a try in the dying minutes when
his stretch for the line just failed. In the last minute Gorden
Tallis had the ball stripped from him illegally as the Broncos
moved within five meters, but referee Brian Grant waved play on.
	   Brisbane slipped to an 8-5 record after losing the past three in
a row while Parramatta moved into equal third with the Saints.
	   Wests' coach Tommy Raudonikis blasted his team after they
crashed to a dismal 40-10 loss to the North Queensland Cowboys.
	   Raudonikis offered only two sentences at the post-match news
conference before walking out.
	   ``We were bloody disgraceful. We've got plenty of work to do,''
he said.
	   Auckland's Gene Ngamu potted a late field goal to give the
Warriors a 15-14 win over Penrith.
	   Sydney City thrashed South Sydney 30-6, Norths crushed
Canterbury 38-4 and the Gold Coast was dumped 32-10 by Illawarra.
Manly hosts Canberra on Monday.
 &UR; (tjh)	   
</TEXT>
