<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections, 1st Ld,0341 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Beirut fears losing its sectarian balance in municipal polls
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with polls opened. Polls close at 1400 GMT. First
results expected after 2100 GMT. &QL; 
 &UR; By HUSSEIN DAKROUB &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Residents of Beirut went to the polls
Sunday to elect a municipal council that Lebanese leaders hope will
preserve the country's delicate sectarian balance.
	   In the predominantly Shiite Muslim south Lebanon, the race for
municipal posts is between the two largest Shiite factions,
Hezbollah and Amal, to control the region where guerrillas are
fighting against Israeli occupation forces.
	   Polls in Beirut and the southern province opened at 7 a.m. (0400
GMT) and are scheduled to close at 5 p.m. (1400 GMT).
	   There are nearly 400,000 eligible voters in Beirut and 380,000
in the South. At stake are 24 city council seats in the capital and
1,589 municipal posts in the South.
	   There will be no voting in the occupied zone along the border
with Israel.
	   Beirut, the city where the civil war of 1975-90 began, elected a
half-Muslim, half-Christian council in its last local elections 35
years ago. But the city's demography has since changed in favor of
the Muslims.
	   Afraid that minority Christians will fare poorly because of
Beirut's population shift, Prime Minister Rafik Hariri appealed to
voters not to ignore Christians in electing a new city council for
the Muslim majority capital.
	   ``Let's maintain the national balance and give mutual
coexistence top consideration when voting,'' said Hariri, a Sunni
Muslim who has endorsed a slate of candidates that includes
Christians, Sunnis and Shiite Muslims.
	   Christian politicians have voiced fears that their sect will
become marginalized in Beirut's elections.
	   A similar shift has occurred in the northern city of Tripoli,
which on May 31, in the second stage of the four-stage polls,
reduced its Christian minority to a single member on its council.
 &UR; With the, 7th graf pvs
</TEXT>
