<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Chinese </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Indonesian leader wants end to anti-Chinese discrimination
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Indonesia-Suharto Birthday
 &UR; By GEOFF SPENCER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Angry Indonesian mobs blamed the
Southeast Asian country's Chinese minority for the worst economic
crisis in 30 years, burning and ransacking Chinese-owned shops and
homes last month.
	   But Indonesia's new president, B.J. Habibie, has called for an
end to deeply ingrained anti-Chinese sentiment in the world's
fourth most populous nation.
	   His plea was hailed by ethnic Chinese leaders Sunday.
	   Appearing before local media executives and a handful of foreign
correspondents on Saturday, Habibie said all Indonesian-born people
have equal rights.
	   For generations indigenous Indonesia have referred to themselves
as ``pribumi,'' or ``sons of the soil,'' while regarding even
locally-born Chinese as outsiders.
	   But Habibie said Indonesian society should no longer be spilt
along indigenous-versus-Chinese lines.
	   ``I regard all citizens who serve the people, including those of
Chinese-ethnic origin, as pribumi,'' he said.
	   Thousands of fearful Chinese left Indonesia when the violence
erupted, killing almost 1,200 people of both races and helping
force former President Suharto out of office. Many scared
Indonesians painted ``Pribumi'' on their walls and doors to ward
off rampaging mobs.
	   Surya Chandra, who chairs the Indonesian Youth Committee for
Abolition of Race Discrimination, welcomed Habibie's comments.
	   ``It's the first time such a statement has come from an
Indonesian president,'' said Chandra, himself of Chinese stock.
	   But he said Habibie must back up words with action, starting
with tackling discrimination embedded in Indonesia's bureaucracy.
	   For example, he said, while many Chinese have adopted Indonesian
names to fit in with majority, a number code on their identity
cards indicates they are of Chinese origin.
	   Ethnic Chinese people make up only about four percent of
Indonesia's 202 million population. However, they dominate commerce
and industry.
	   Many are Christian or Buddhist in a society that is 90 percent
Muslim.
	   During former President Suharto's 32-year authoritarian rule, a
small clique of Chinese entrepreneurs, along with Suharto's family,
built huge business empires and made fortunes under his patronage.
	   When the economy went sour last year, the whole Chinese
community became scapegoats for soaring prices and mass
unemployment.
	   Until very recently Chinese-Indonesians have tried to keep a low
profile in national affairs. But last week a coalition of Chinese
businessmen said they would form their own political party. 	   
</TEXT>
