<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Sri Lanka-New Zealand </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sri Lanka crush New Zealand by innings and 16 runs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo Planned &QL; 
 &UR; By CALLISTUS DAVY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GALLE, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Nervous New Zealand lost five wickets
for 20 runs in the first hour of play as Sri Lanka won the second
cricket Test by an innings and 16 runs on the final day of the
match in this southern city Sunday.
	   The match was over in the 43rd minute of the fifth day's play
when first slip Sanath Jayasuriya held on to a simple catch from
the last batsman Shyane O'Conner, who went for nought off Muttiah
Muralitheran.
	   New Zealand resumed from an overnight 94 for 5 and hit trouble
in the very first over when left arm spinner Niroshan
Bandaratilleke had Chris Cairns caught by close-in fielder Hashan
Tillekaratne for his overnight score of 16.
	   The New Zealand innings then caved in without resistance, all
out at 114 with Adam Parore remaining unbeaten on 32.
	   After taking a first innings lead of 130 runs, Sri Lanka had
taken five quick wickets on Saturday to leave New Zealand on 94 for
5 with Adam Parore and Cairns struggling at the crease on 25 and 16
respectively.
	   With Sunday's win, Sri Lanka leveled the three-test series. It
lost the first test to New Zealand by 167 runs last week.
	   Bandaratilleke, playing only his second Test, finished with
bowling figures of 9 for 83 but batsman Mahela Jayawardena, Sri
Lanka's rising star, was adjudged man-of-the-match for his innings
of 167.
	   The bus carrying the Sri Lankan team was mobbed outside the
pavilionby autograph hunters and hundreds more waved at the players
on the nearby highway as they drove back to their hotel.
	   The third and deciding Test begins in Colombo on Wednesday.
	    &UR; (str, nnm)
</TEXT>
