<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Drug Summit,0689 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World leaders convene for three-day conference on global drug
</HEADLINE>
problem &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Leaders of the world's major
drug-producing and drug-consuming nations open a three-day
conference Monday to combat trafficking, curb demand and strengthen
global cooperation in the fight against drugs.
	   The goal of the U.N. General Assembly ``special session on
drugs'' is to endorse target dates for governments to enact
legislation on issues such as money-laundering, judicial
cooperation, reducing demand for drugs and stamping out cultivation
of illicit crops.
	   ``Around the world, there is a growing consensus that more needs
to be done to understand and reduce the rising demand for drugs,''
the United Nations said in a report.
	   But critics fear the United Nations is placing too much emphasis
on legal measures, following a path which has largely failed in the
United States, and should consider drugs a health problem.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton, who delivers the opening address
Monday, has pledged to cut drug use by half in the United States _
the world's leading drug consumer _ by the year 2007.
	   Latin American leaders say their own efforts to curtail drug
production and trafficking will fail unless Americans curb their
appetite for narcotics.
	   That message is expected to be delivered forcefully by Latin
American presidents expected at the conference. They include
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, Venezuelan President Rafael
Caldera, Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori, Bolivian President
Hugo Banzer and President Ernesto Samper of Colombia.
	   French President Jacques Chirac and Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi are also among the first day speakers.
	   The conference is expected to approve a plan of action prepared
in March by representatives of 130 countries in Vienna, Austria.
The plan sets a target date of 2003 for countries to pass laws to
control money landering and increase judicial cooperation.
	   It also sets 2008 as the target for significantly reducing
illicit cultivation of cocoa, cannabis and opium poppies and for
controlling the spread of amphetamines.
	   Some critics believe the United Nations should consider drugs as
a health problem and use the resources of the World Health
Organization to develop effective treatment programs.
	   ``Drug policy is a global public health concern,'' said Dr. Alex
Wodak, director of alcohol and drug services at St. Vincent's
Hospital in Sydney, Australia. ``The U.N.'s exaggerated emphasis on
interdiction and criminalization makes it impossible to protect
public health.''
	   In an open letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, about
500 prominent figures from around the world said the ``global war
on drugs is now causing more harm than drug abuse itself.''
	   ``Human rights are violated, environmental assaults perpetrated
and prisons inundated with hundreds of thousands of drug
violators,'' the letter said. It called for a drug program based on
``common sense, science, public health and human rights.''
	   Among the signers were former U.S. Secretary of State George
Shultz, former U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar,
former Australian Prime Minister Paul Keating, and former President
Oscar Arias of Costa Rica.
	   Pino Arlacchi, head of the U.N. drug control office in Vienna,
insists that the United Nations has no intention of promoting a
U.S.-style ``war on drugs'' on a global scale.
	   ``For the first time, we have the issue of demand reduction
included at the same level as other components of narcotics
control,'' Arlacchi said. He cited proposals for treatment,
educational campaigns and incentives to farmers to grow alternative
crops.
	   But the U.N. drug office has frowned on novel experiments, such
as Swiss program to prescribe limited amounts of heroin to addicts.
	   More than two-thirds of the Swiss addicts had been involved in
prostitution, drug trafficking and other criminal activity when
they enrolled in the program. The number dropped to 10 percent, the
study showed.
</TEXT>
