<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Le Mans 24 Hours, 1st-Ld writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Problems at dawn set back Porsches; Toyota in contention
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Race update at 19 hours &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDREAS EVAGORA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LE MANS, France (AP) - Two Porsche cars lost big leads as dawn
broke Sunday morning at the Le Mans 24 hour race, allowing a Toyota
to challenge for the winning spot.
	   With five hours left in the race, a Porsche GT1 driven by Alan
McNish, Laurent Aiello and Stephane Ortelli was in the lead with
275 laps completed.
	   Only 24 seconds behind stood the Toyota GT vehicle in the hands
of Thierry Boutsen, Ralf Kelleners and Geoff Lees.
	   Another Porsche GT One driven by Jorg Muller, Uwe Alzen and Bob
Wolleck, was in third, with 274 laps.
	   Earlier, Porsche cars held a three lap lead at the 12-hour mark
of the endurance race.
	   But Porsche chiefs could only look on as driver error and
mechanical failure left both cars in the pits for more than half an
hour as dayliught came.
	   First the car driven by Muller, Alzen and Wolleck, while in
second place, was in the pits for 31 minutes.
	   The car needed new brakes and a change in undercarriage after
Muller skidded out of control in rain.
	   Within minutes the leading car, the Porsche driven by McNish,
Aiello and Ortelli, was also in trouble.
	   With McNish behind the wheel, the car had a water leak and was
in the pits for 35 minutes.
	   Porsche's problems allowed the Toyota One driven by Boutsen,
Kelleners and Lees to move into contention.
	   Two Nissans R390s were also performing well, lying in fourth and
fifth place.
	   As the drivers prepared for the final five hours, the skies
cleared again and a finish in dry conditions was predicted.
	   (ae)
</TEXT>
