<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Saudi-Evacuees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Over 300 foreigners evacuated from Eritrea arrive in Saudi
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ More than 300 foreigners evacuated
from war-torn Eritrea have arrived in the Red Sea port city of
Jiddah, officials at foreign embassies said Sunday.
	   Of those, 101 foreigners evacuated from the Eritrean capital
Asmara arrived Sunday in Jiddah aboard a British Royal Air Force
plane, the British Embassy said.
	   The embassy statement said 41 of the people evacuated were
British. The remaining 60 passengers were Australian, Canadian and
South African nationals, according to the British Defense Ministry.
	   ``The consulate general has arranged hotel accommodation for the
evacuees and will be helping these British nationals make onward
flight arrangements,'' said the statement.
	   More than 200 Germans, mainly businessmen and their families,
arrived from the Eritrean capital Asmara late Saturday, a German
embassy spokesman said Sunday. They will leave for Germany later
Sunday, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
	   Eritrea and Ethiopia's territorial dispute, which has escalated
into bombing raids, has propelled hundreds of foreigners out of
Eritrea in fears that it will be engulfed in war with Ethiopia.
	   On Saturday, Ethiopian jets again bombed a military-civilian
airport not far from the Eritrean capital Asmara, forcing embassies
to step up their exit plans.
	   American, Italian, German and British planes ferried foreigners
out of harm's way late Saturday after Ethiopia agreed to
temporarily halt bombing.
	   The number of foreigners still waiting to be evacuated from
Eritrea, wedged between northern Ethiopia and the Red Sea, was not
known.
	   Eritrean rebels were instrumental in helping the Ethiopian
People's Revolutionary Democratic Front overthrow a 17-year
military regime in July 1991, and Eritrea gained independence from
Ethiopia in 1993.
	   But the two countries dispute at least six areas along their
common border, which was drawn by Italy after it conquered Eritrea
in 1885.
