<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Beirut fears losing its sectarian balance in municipal polls
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Hariri voting, comments, army deployment. First
results expected after 2100gmt. &QL; 
 &UR; By HUSSEIN DAKROUB &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Prime Minister Rafik Hariri on Sunday
urged Beirut's Muslims and Christians to ``put the war behind
them'' and use the first municipal elections in 35 years to
preserve the city's delicate sectarian balance.
	   In the predominantly Shiite Muslim South Lebanon, the race for
municipal posts is between the two largest Shiite factions,
Hezbollah and Amal, over who controls the region where guerrillas
are fighting against Israeli occupation forces.
	   The government deployed thousands of army troops in armored
vehicles and trucks to ensure safe voting in both regions. Soldiers
manned road intersections and stood on guard outside polling
stations.
	   Polls in Beirut and the southern province opened at 7 a.m.
(0400gmt) and are expected to close at 5 p.m. (1400gmt).
	   There are nearly 400,000 eligible voters in Beirut and 380,000
in the the south. At stake are 24 city council seats in the capital
and 1,589 municipal posts in the south.
	   There will be no voting in the occupied zone along the border
with Israel.
	   Hariri, a Sunni Muslim moderate, has been campaigning for
Christian-Muslim coexistence in the Lebanese capital amid Christian
fears that the Muslim majority could overwhelm them and drive them
out of city council.
	   The prime minister, joined by moderate Muslim clerics, appealed
on television to voters not to ignore Christians in electing a new
city council for the Muslim majority capital.
	   Hariri, who has endorsed a slate of candidates that includes
Christians, Sunnis and Shiite Muslims, appeared confident of a
balanced outcome.
	   After casting his vote Sunday morning, the prime minister called
on residents ``to leave the war behind them and seriously show that
Beirut is the capital of Lebanon, capital of coexistence and
(sectarian) balance.''
	   Beirut, the city where the civil war of 1975-90 began, elected a
half-Muslim, half-Christian council in its last local elections 35
years ago. But the city's demography has since changed in favor of
the Muslims.
	   A similar shift has occurred in the northern city of Tripoli,
which on May 31, in the second stage of the four-stage polls,
reduced its Christian minority to one member on its council. There
had been four in the last elected council.
	   Christian politicians have voiced fears that their sect will
similarly become marginalized in Beirut's elections.
	   In the other part of the country voting on Sunday, the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah and the pro-Syrian Amal groups are vying
for the votes of southern Lebanon.
	   All attempts to get the two Shiite groups to agree on a joint
ticket failed.
	   Hezbollah, whose guerrillas are the most active opponents of the
Israeli occupation of part of southern Lebanon, trounced the
mainstream Amal in municipal elections in Shiite districts of Mount
Lebanon on May 24.
	   Hezbollah hopes the polls will consolidate its claim to lead the
1.2 million Shiites, the country's largest single sect.
	   The municipal polls, widely seen as extending democracy after
the civil war, began in Mount Lebanon and are scheduled to end in
the eastern Bekaa Valley on June 14.
 &UR; pvs-sfg-ggl
</TEXT>
