w1144 &Cx1f; wstm-
R S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Acropol     06-07 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Acropolis Auto Rally </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Acropolis auto rally starts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ The 45th Acropolis motor rally got
underway from Athens Sunday, designed to test drivers and cars in
one of the toughest competitions for the world driving
championship.
	   A total of 32 foreign and 71 Greek drivers were flagged off from
the foot of the Athens Acropolis hill in one minute intervals.
	   The 1,036 kilometers (647 miles) rally takes cars over some of
Greece's best and worst roads through valleys and picturesque
villages. Seventeen special stages totaling 388 kilometers (243
miles) will also test the ability of the drivers to control their
cars at high speeds on narrow dirt roads with sharp turns.
	   Unlike previous races, this year's three-day rally will end in
the western town of Delphi. The ancient Greeks considered Delphi to
be the center of the world. It was also the site of the oracle that
ancient Greeks would seek prophesies of the future.
	   Last year's Acropolis Rally winner, Spain's Carlos Sainz with
co-driver Luis Moya in a Toyota Corolla WRC, is a leading contender
for first place. Sainz, the current leader of the world driving
championship, was also the winner of the 1990 and 1994 Acropolis
rallies.
	   Britain's Colin McRae with co-driver Nicky Grist in a Subaru
Impreza WRC and Finland's Tommi Makinen with co-driver Risto
Mannisenmaki in a Mitsubishi Lancer Evo 5, are also among the
favorites to win the gruelling race.
	   Makinen, who had won twice the title of the world driving
championship but never an Acropolis rally, expressed confidence
that everything will go well.
	   ``It's going to be hard...it's a big fight for sure, but we did
good preparations.''
	   Mitsubishi, Subaru and Toyota, all of Japan, are vying for the
prestigious manufacturer's cup.
 &UR; kc-lo
</TEXT>
