w1147 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-WorldCup-Gam     06-07 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-World Cup-Gambling Fever,0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No team in World Cup, but Thailand in top league for gambling
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BK106 of June 5 &QL; 
 &UR; By JIRAPORN WONGPAITHOON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand has no team in the World Cup
and has struggled to recover from a region-wide economic crisis,
but the Southeast Asian country is still playing for major stakes
in soccer's greatest event _ through illegal gambling.
	   ``Soccer gambling is the police department's top priority to
crack down on at the moment,'' said Pol. Maj. Gen. Chatt Kuldiloke,
adviser to a newly created special World Cup gambling task force.
``We believe the gambling will be intense over France '98.''
	   Police predicted this weekend that 30 billion (dlrs 750 million)
will be gambled and have braced for an increase in suicides and
robberies in the anticipation that fortunes wagered _ and often
lost _ will lead to desperate acts.
	   Gambling is illegal in Thailand, but the laws are widely
ignored. From cockfights to kick-boxing to underground lotteries,
placing bets has become embedded in Thai culture. Money changes
hands openly at arenas, through calls to bookmakers or via Internet
web sites.
	   Channel Islands-based William Hill International even placed an
advertisement Friday in a major newspaper urging readers to ``open
an account now and be ready for the World Cup.''
	   Words like ``gamble'' and ``bet'' were not used, but the message
was clear.
	   Soccer is an increasingly popular gambling vehicle. The World
Cup was broadcast live in Thailand via satellite television for the
first time in 1994 and quickly became a favorite.
	   Fans can now see soccer matches on TV most nights from the
European and South American leagues, but few claim they watch just
for love of the sport.
	   Cup fever has worried Thailand's Education Ministry because
recent research suggests students as young as their early teens are
wagering their lunch money _ and sometimes more _ on soccer.
	   ``More student crimes will occur,'' said Deputy Minister Somsak
Prisana-nantakul. ``But what we're worried of is suicide by those
who cannot pay their debts.''
	   Despite fears of suicides, none have yet been reported. But the
case of a university law student, Rewat Kengsakul, has crystallized
fears of how gambling can corrupt the young.
	   Rewat, 18, was arrested in April after using an air-gun to rob a
gold shop to clear a 9,000 baht (dlrs 225) gambling debt. He was
arrested with 33 gold chains in his possession and is currently
awaiting trial.
	   Students interviewed by the Bangkok Post newspaper say that
soccer gambling is rife and that bookies wait outside campuses. On
weekend nights, when there are several matches, one bookie said he
often collected up to 1 million baht (dlrs 25,000) in bets.
	   Chokchai Banjongsawas, an office worker and soccer fan, summed
up the soccer craze: ``It's a great, fun sport and it only takes 90
minutes to know the outcome of whether we're to win or lose.
Boxing, horse racing are too common and too familiar.''
	   Bookies normally accept no bet lower than 1,000 baht (dlrs 40).
	   Gambling aside, Bangkok pubs foresee a brisk trade during the
tournament and are jostling with each other to publicize the size
of their giant-screen televisions.
	   Cup fever, along with a special promotion, was attributed by
sales staff at a Bangkok department store for the doubling of TV
sales ahead of the tournament, economic slump notwithstanding.
	   ``I want a big screen,'' said Surat Saicharoen, 37. ``If the
screen is big, the ball will also be big. I think it affects your
cheers.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Thailand-World Cup-Gambling Fever; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
