<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan,0434 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Tea-growing region breeds Japan's soccer stars
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ It's probably not the water, just
hard work and good coaching. Nine of the 22 players on Japan's
World Cup team hail from the same state.
	   If any spot on the island nation can be called the heart of
Japanese soccer, it would be Shizuoka (she-zooh-OH-kah), a region
famous for green tea. Located 150 kilometers west of Tokyo, the
state has long been the breeding ground for Japan's top stars. No
other state sent more than two players to the World Cup team.
	   One reason is that Shizuoka has the best high school soccer
teams in Japan and the best training programs for kids. Competition
is intense.
	   ``It's a great environment to see quality soccer while you're
growing up,'' midfielder Hiroshi Nanami, 25, said after Saturday's
practice in this French spa. ``And you get the best coaching in
Japan.''
	   More remarkably, four players now on the national team _
including Nanami and starting goalkeeper Yoshikatsu Kawaguchi _
trained under the same high school coach.
	   ``I'm as happy as a proud father,'' coach Masayoshi Otaki of
Shimizu Municipal Commercial High School said in a recent interview
in Shizuoka.
	   Otaki acknowledged he sometimes hits his student-players _ a
coaching style that is becoming less popular but remains
surprisingly commonplace in tradition-bound Japan.
	   ``I scold them a lot,'' said Otaki, 46, an unpretentious,
energetic man, who has been coaching for 25 years. ``Sometimes
words aren't enough.''
	   Otaki became all gentle smiles when describing his World
Cup-bound players: Kawaguchi was the one who worked extra hard;
Nanami was never afraid to be a little different; Shinji Ono showed
up at practice first and left last.
	   ``I was truly lucky to have met such a good person,'' the
18-year-old Ono said of his high school coach. The midfielder
recalled that Otaki took him to classical music concerts.
	   Nanami, who wears the No. 10 jersey, also said Otaki had a
profound impact on his development as a player.
	   ``He was extremely strict,'' he recalled. ``He taught us the
discipline of soccer.''
	   But Masashi Nakayama, 30, suggested people shouldn't make too
much of the Shizuoka magic.
	   ``It's not that special,'' he said.
	   The Shizuoka-born striker, who is expected to start in Japan's
opener against Argentina, is the top J-League scorer, netting a
league-record four consecutive hat tricks this season.
</TEXT>
