<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Both sides in Air France strike show willingness for new talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with poll, latest on train strike &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available &QL; 
 &UR; By DEBORAH SEWARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ With the World Cup four days away, both sides in a
strike by Air France pilots appeared willing Sunday to begin new
talks aimed at ending the walkout now in its seventh day.
	   Airline officials said Saturday evening they were in contact
with the pilots about resuming negotiations but none had been set.
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin also said Saturday the government was
prepared to intervene but no concrete proposals have emerged.
	   Talks between Air France and the pilots were suspended Saturday
after the pilots walked out of negotiations.
	   Meanwhile, public support for the strike appeared lukewarm.
	   A poll that appeared in Sunday's edition of Le Journal du
Dimanche showed just 38 percent of those surveyed were sympathetic
to the strike, while 34 percent opposed it. In contrast, 79 percent
of those polled supported truckers in a strike in Novemember 1997.
	   The poll was carried out Friday by the CSA polling agency among
1,004 people. No margin of error was given.
	   The pilots appeared divided about new talks, with the head of
the main pilots' union indicating a new round could take place
Monday and a spokesman saying they could resume over the weekend.
	   Both sides were under pressure to end the strike from the
government, worried about France's image and embarrassed by the
strike, which has threatened to tarnish the soccer championship.
	   Air France is the official World Cup carrier and is committed to
transporting the teams from one venue to another.
	   The pilots were protesting pay cuts planned by Air France, which
is currently restructuring and needs to free up capital to
modernize the company and its planes.
	   Talks between Air France management and the striking pilots
broke off Saturday after all night negotiations.
	   The stumbling blocks remained planned salary cuts and an Air
France proposal to give pilots stock in exchange for the pay
reductions, as well as a two-tier pay scale in which younger pilots
earn less.
	   Only about 25 percent of Air France's flights were expected to
take off Sunday. Meanwhile, a train strike disrupted provincial
service and service was expected Sunday, especially in the south.
	   Once the air strike ends, Air France says it will take three
days for service to be restored fully to normal.
	   (dgs)	   
</TEXT>
