</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Vatican-Deaths </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mother skeptical as young Swiss guard's final letter published
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) _ The final letter of Cedric Tornay,
the young Swiss guardsman who the Vatican says fatally shot the
Swiss Guards' commander and his wife, raises more questions than it
answers, his mother was quoted as saying Sunday.
	   ``I'm not saying my son didn't do it,'' Muguette Baudat-Tornay
told the Lausanne daily Le Matin.
	   ``But it still has to be clearly proved whether, and above all
why, he did it,'' she added.
	   The Vatican says Tornay, 23, bitter because of a reprimand by
commander Alois Estermann and the latter's failure to award him a
medal, fatally shot Estermann and his wife, Gladys Meza Romero, and
then killed himself, in the couple's Vatican apartment last month.
	   Le Matin published the brief letter from Tornay, addressed to
his mother and written in French, which appears to back that
version of events.
	   ``Mom, I hope you will forgive me for what I have done, it was
they who pushed me,'' the letter started.
	   ``I must perform this service for all the remaining guardsmen as
well as the (Roman) Catholic church,'' one passage read. ``I swore
to give my life for the pope and that's what I'm doing.''
	   But Baudat-Tornay was quoted by the newspaper as saying she had
asked for a handwriting analysis, as the letter was not written on
Tornay's usual paper and was addressed to her married name, which
her son never used.
	   The letter also said he been in the pope's army for ``three
years, six months and six days'' _ more than a month too long,
according to Baudat-Tornay.
	   Baudat-Tornay was given the letter, apparently given by Tornay
to another guardsman, identified only as C.G., shortly before the
shootings, two days later.
	   In a telephone call on the afternoon of the killings, Tornay had
seemed happy and talked of coming to Switzerland in June, she said.
	   Tornay's mother was also quoted as claiming her son had told her
last autumn that he was investigating the traditionalist and
secretive Opus Dei movement. ``More recently, he had even started
to fear this organization ... why?''
	   In a statement last week, the organization dismissed rumors that
Estermann was a member of Opus Dei, Le Matin said.
	   On Tuesday, Pope John Paul II named Swiss army colonel Pius
Segmueller as the new commander of the tiny force.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
