w1196 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Egypt-Politics     06-07 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egypt holds mid-term elections for Parliament's upper house
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Mid-term elections were held Sunday for half
the elected members of the 264-seat Shura Council, or Consultative
Council, which boasts Egypt's elite as members but has little
power.
	   Egypt's 13 opposition parties boycotted the elections to
Parliament's upper house, saying they would not trust the results.
In the last elections in 1995, the opposition charged widespread
vote-rigging.
	   President Hosni Mubarak appoints one-third of the Shura
Council's seats, with elections for half the others held every
three years.
	   Of the 88 seats up for grabs Sunday, 22 went uncontested to
members of the ruling National Democratic Party or independents who
support it. One uncontested seat was that of the council's
president, Mustafa Kamal Helmy.
	   The council's members are writers, intellectuals, professors and
scientists. It serves mainly as an advisory body. The lower house,
or People's Assembly, has the real power. Like the Shura Council,
it is dominated by the ruling party.
	   Shura Council elections usually draw little attention; on Sunday
even government newspapers carried only brief stories on the
balloting. After the vote, Mubarak will appoint half his allotment,
or 44 members.
	   The Interior Ministry listed 24,000 polling stations throughout
Egypt, but had no figure for eligible voters. Newspapers put the
number at around one million.
	   Polls opened at 8:00 a.m. (0500gmt) and were to close at 5:00
p.m. (1400gmt). Results are expected within 48 hours.
	   Of the 628 candidates who entered the race, 19 were excluded as
unworthy by a judicial committee and 190 withdrew. A re-vote will
take place June 14 in cases where candidates did not get the
necessary 50 per cent, plus one vote.
 &UR; ms-ggl
</TEXT>
