<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tehran mayor goes on trial for corruption, pleads not guilty
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS in grafs 5-8 judge's statement, color. &QL; 
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ The trial of Tehran mayor Gholamhossein
Karbaschi started Sunday, with the reformist mayor describing as
``lies'' the corruption charges brought against him.
	   Karbaschi, 44, arrived at the courtroom in his trademark dark
blue suit, flanked by his two lawyers, looking relaxed and
confident.
	   In front of a packed courtroom at the Imam Khomeini Judiciary
Complex in central Tehran, Karbaschi pleaded innocent. He said the
charges of embezzlement, fraud, and mismanagement of public funds
brought against him were trumped up.
	   ``All of the charges against me are absolute lies. I don't
accept any of them,'' the black-bearded Karbaschi told the judge
calmly.
	   The judge, Gholamhossein Mohseni-Ejaei, a cleric, wearing a
white turban and brown robe, said:
	   ``I'm not happy today to try a manager of the Islamic Republic
of Iran, but we know that the law should be implemented and there
are no exceptions. Nobody is above the law.''
	   The trial was adjourned until Thursday. As Karbaschi left the
courthouse, about 200 supporters greeted him with shouts of ``Long
live Karbaschi,'' while another 50, standing nearby, yelled,
``Death to Karbaschi.''
	   Some 130 citizens attended the trial _ those who arrived early _
along with about 70 journalists. A crowd of several hundred watched
the four-hour hearing on two 28-inch television screens outside the
courthouse, where extra police were assigned to keep order.
	   Karbaschi was arrested April 4 when Chief Judge Ayatollah
Mohammad Yazdi, a hard-liner, accused him of involvement in a
wide-ranging corruption scandal and ordered him detained.
	   But the move was widely seen as a bid to topple key officials
allied with moderate Iranian President Mohammad Khatami who took
office in August. Karbaschi had run Khatami's election campaign.
	   In the scandal, more than a dozen senior municipality officials
have been put on trial since last October. Most were accused of _
or sentenced for _ issuing building permits in restricted zones in
return for large kickbacks.
	   Karbaschi was freed April 15 after a series of street protests
that turned violent.
	   He was released after the intervention of Iran's spiritual
leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, considered an ally of hard-liners.
	   Karbaschi's arrest ignited a long-simmering power struggle
between moderate and hard-line clerics. His case has gripped the
nation, generating hundreds of stories for and against the mayor.
	   As mayor since 1989, Karbaschi has improved the capital's
appearance as well as public services for its 8 million residents.
	   Despite his popularity, he has critics who consider his
administration high-handed and who dislike him for taxing the
powerful merchants who make up the hard-liners' power base.
	   The mayor went back to work days after his release. But
according to Iranian law, he is not allowed to work while the trial
is under way.
 &UR; av-fsa-ggl-sf
</TEXT>
