w1204 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Switzerland-GeneVote     06-07 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Gene Vote </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss vote to decide future of genetic engineering
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Will be led with votes. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ Swiss voters were set to decide Sunday
whether to outlaw the production and patenting of genetically
modified plants and animals, in a vote which both sides claim could
have catastrophic results.
	   A close outcome is likely in the referendum on ``The Initiative
for the Protection of Life and the Environment against Genetic
Manipulation.''
	   The most recent poll pointed to a defeat for the initiative,
which Swiss industry and government say would force a ``draconian''
shutdown on research in Switzerland, sending highly paid jobs to
other countries.
	   But other studies have shown voters more evenly divided, with
many voters swayed by arguments that tampering with genes poses
``incalculable risks'' for the environment and the prospect of
unethical treatment of animals used in experiments.
	   Environmentalists and consumer activists who back the proposal
say too little is known about the consequences of letting
genetically modified organisms into the food chain.
	   But the issue of jobs is also highly sensitive to the
resource-poor country of 7 million. Despite Switzerland's small
size, it is a leading force in biotechnology.
	   Basel-based pharmaceutical giants Novartis and Roche rank with
competitors such as Monsanto, of St. Louis, among world leaders in
the field.
	   The Swiss pharmaceutical industry and the government say the
initiative would keep the companies from doing some of their best
research in Switzerland.
	   The traditionally environment-conscious German-speaking majority
is expected to be more favorable to the proposal than the French
speakers of western Switzerland.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Switzerland-Gene Vote; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
