<SLUG> BC-Iran-Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,0433 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tehran mayor goes on trial for corruption, pleads not guilty
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with judge's statement, color. &QL; 
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ With supporters gathered outside the
courtroom, Tehran's popular mayor went on trial Sunday to defend
himself against corruption charges that critics say are politically
motivated.
	   Mayor Gholamhossein Karbaschi arrived in court flanked by his
two lawyers, looking confident and relaxed. During the four-hour
hearing, he pleaded innocent and called the charges against him
``lies.''
	   ``All of the charges against me are absolute lies. I don't
accept any of them,'' he said before a packed courtroom at the Imam
Khomeini Judiciary Complex in central Tehran.
	   Karbaschi, 44, is charged with embezzlement, fraud, and
mismanagement of public funds.
	   The judge, Gholamhossein Mohseni-Ejaei, a cleric, said he was
not happy about having to try a ``manager of the Islamic Republic
of Iran,'' but that the law must be implemented.
	   ``Nobody is above the law,'' the judge said.
	   The trial was adjourned until Thursday.
	   As Karbaschi left the courthouse, about 200 supporters greeted
him with shouts of ``Long live Karbaschi.'' Another 50 people,
standing nearby, yelled, ``Death to Karbaschi.''
	   Mayor of Iran's capital since 1989, Karbaschi has gained fans by
adding color to the polluted, congested city of 8 million, painting
buses bright colors, building roads, and opening sports and culture
centers.
	   His reforms, however, have also earned him enemies.
	   Karbaschi was arrested April 4 when Chief Judge Ayatollah
Mohammad Yazdi, a hard-liner, accused him of involvement in a
wide-ranging corruption scandal and ordered him detained.
	   But the move was widely seen as a bid to topple key officials
allied with moderate Iranian President Mohammad Khatami who took
office in August. Karbaschi had run Khatami's election campaign.
	   Karbaschi was freed April 15 after a series of street protests
that turned violent, but his arrest ignited a long-simmering power
struggle between moderate and hard-line clerics. His case has
gripped the nation, generating hundreds of stories for and against
the mayor.
	   Despite his popularity, he has critics who consider his
administration high-handed and who dislike him for taxing the
powerful merchants who make up the hard-liners' power base.
	   The mayor went back to work days after his release. But
according to Iranian law, he is not allowed to work while the trial
is under way.
</TEXT>
