<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Gene Vote,0272 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss vote to decide future of genetic engineering
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Last polls close at 1200 GMT. First results expected after
1530 GMT. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ With both sides predicting a national
catastrophe if they lose, Swiss citizens voted Sunday on whether to
outlaw the production and patenting of genetically modified plants
and animals.
	   The most recent poll on ``The Initiative for the Protection of
Life and the Environment against Genetic Manipulation'' pointed to
a defeat for the initiative, which Swiss industry and government
say would force a ``draconian'' shutdown on research in
Switzerland, sending highly paid jobs to other countries.
	   But other studies have shown voters more evenly divided, with
many swayed by arguments that tampering with genes poses
``incalculable risks'' for the environment and the prospect of
unethical treatment of animals used in experiments.
	   Environmentalists and consumer activists who back the proposal
say too little is known about the consequences of allowing
genetically modified organisms into the food chain.
	   But the issue of jobs is also highly sensitive to the
resource-poor country of 7 million, which is a leading force in
biotechnology.
	   Basel-based pharmaceutical giants Novartis and Roche rank among
world leaders in the field.
	   The Swiss pharmaceutical industry and the government say the
initiative would shackle the companies research.
	   The traditionally environment-conscious German-speaking majority
is expected to look more favorably on the proposal than are the
French speakers of western Switzerland. 	   
</TEXT>
