w1261 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-ForeignIn     06-07 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Foreign Investment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine president-elect to seek constitutional change to spur
</HEADLINE>
investment &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ President-elect Joseph Estrada said
Sunday he will seek an amendment of the constitution to allow full
foreign ownership of Philippine businesses by foreigners.
	   Estrada spoke to reporters after meeting Taiwanese tycoon Chang
Yungfa, who has interests in shipbuilding, construction and
airlines.
	   He said he urged Chang to invest in Philippine seaports but that
Chang was apprehensive due to a constitutional limit on foreign
ownership of most businesses at 40 percent.
	   Estrada said many foreign investors have gotten around the limit
by using Filipino dummy companies. But Chang said foreign
businessmen are leery of such arrangements because dummy companies
sometimes break under-the-table agreements designed to get around
the investment law.
	   ``The Philippines should not fear foreign investments,'' Chang
told reporters through an interpreter.
	   Estrada said he would prefer that the incoming Congress convene
as a constituent assembly.
	   Many in the Philippines, including the Roman Catholic Church,
oppose tinkering with the constitution, fearing that politicians
may go too far and limit democracy.
	   Last year, tens of thousands of pro-democracy activists rallied
against plans by President Fidel Ramos' supporters to change the
constitution to allow him to seek reelection. Philippine presidents
are limited to single six-year terms.
	   Estrada said he would only remove constitutional provisions
hindering investment and economic growth.
	   Congress has proclaimed Estrada, a former movie star, winner of
the May 11 presidential elections. He will be inaugurated as the
country's 13th president on June 30. 	   
</TEXT>
