r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APNewsSummary     06-07 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0626 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ With a border dispute escalating into
bombing raids, hundreds of foreigners scrambled out of Eritrea on
Sunday, fearing it will be engulfed in war with Ethiopia. One of
their main escape routes earlier came under attack for a second
straight day. Ethiopian jets bombed a military-civilian airport on
the outskirts of Asmara on for the second time Saturday, forcing
embassies to step up their exit plans. American, Italian, German
and British planes ferried foreigners out of harm's way late
Saturday and early Sunday after Ethiopia agreed to temporarily halt
bombing. (Eritrea-Ethiopia)
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq will turn down any further shipments
of humanitarian aid ferried by friendly countries or organizations,
Baghdad newspapers said Sunday. The papers said a Cabinet meeting
chaired by President Saddam Hussein late Saturday told the donors
that Iraq would prefer its supporters to work for the lifting of
trade sanctions instead of sending aid. ``Iraq is not in need of
aid and its people are not so lazy to ask assistance from others,''
the official Al-Qadissiya said, quoting a statement by the Cabinet.
It is not clear why Iraq made the decision when aid shipments have
been gathering momentum and when the government has complained
bitterly about a lack of medicines causing serious health problems
for the 22 million Iraqis. (Iraq-Aid)
	   PARIS (AP) _ With the World Cup four days away, both sides in a
strike by Air France pilots appeared willing Sunday to begin new
talks aimed at ending the walkout now in its seventh day. Airline
officials said Saturday evening they were in contact with the
pilots about resuming negotiations but none had been set. Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin also said Saturday the government was
prepared to intervene but no concrete proposals have emerged. Talks
between Air France and the pilots were suspended Saturday after the
pilots walked out of negotiations. Meanwhile, public support for
the strike appeared lukewarm. (Air France-Strike)
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan (AP) _ Aid workers were trying Sunday to
assess whether serious disease has broken out in remote villages of
northern Afghanistan devastated during last weekend's earthquake.
The quake killed up to 4,700 people and injured thousands of
others, according to Afghan authorities. An outbreak of bloody
diarrhea was reported in the Chah-ab region, about 60 kilometers
(38 miles) west of Faisabad, said U.N. spokesman Rupert Colville.
Red Cross helicopters postponed some emergency food deliveries and
set out for the region to investigate whether the outbreak might
signal shigella or dysentery. Both diseases spread quickly when
water supplies are polluted. In addition to destroying wells, the
May 30 quake cut channels and pipes carrying spring water to
villages, and landslides accompanying the quake have filled rivers
with mud. (Afghanistan-Quake).
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ A powerful bomb gutted a train
traveling through southern Pakistan on Sunday, killing 26 people
and wounding 45 others, many of them seriously, police and
emergency workers said. The bomb exploded just before dawn,
shattering the train as it passed through a village 30 kilometers
(18 miles) outside Sukkur and 200 kilometers (120 miles) north of
Karachi, capital of the southern Sindh province, police said. The
18-carriage express, with a capacity of 1,800 passengers, was
headed toward the northwestern city of Peshawar, they said. Among
the dead were four children aged 5 or younger, police said.
(Pakistan-Train Bomb)
</TEXT>
