<SLUG> BC-Greece-Murder </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Murder victim found near airport identified as Irish woman
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ The body of a woman found murdered outside
a golf club in a southern Athens suburb a week ago was identified
Sunday as that of 35-year-old Marie Cronin from Dublin, Ireland,
authorities said.
	   Cronin's body was found hidden underneath bushes outside the
Glyfada golf course, which borders on Athens' international
airport, on May 30. She had been due to return to London, where she
was working for a medical insurance company, later that day, police
said.
	   According to a coroner's report, Cronin died of multiple head
injuries caused by a sharp, heavy object such as an axe or meat
cleaver. She also suffered defensive injuries on her arms.
	   Her family in Ireland became concerned when she did not arrive
in London as scheduled. Her body was reportedly identified by her
brothers.
	   Cronin had arrived in Greece on May 22 for a week-long vacation
on the Saronic Gulf island of Spetses, about 63 kilometers (30
miles) southwest of Athens. She left the island by hydrofoil for
the port city of Piraeus on May 29, and was scheduled to catch a
flight back to London early the next day.
	   No suspects have been arrested in the case.
	   (eb)
</TEXT>
