<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rescue workers probe earth near Germany's train crash site
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IAN MADER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Rescue workers dug to depths of four
meters (yards) Sunday for clues to help identify victims in postwar
Germany's deadliest train crash.
	   At least 102 people were killed when high-speed InterCity
Express 884 derailed and slammed into the concrete supports of an
overpass that crashed down onto the jackknifed passenger cars.
	   Rescuers in the northern city of Eschede, 50 kms (35 miles)
north of Hanover, believe it is unlikely they will find more
bodies, and were sifting through sandy dirt for personal effects,
such as jewelry and wallets. So far, just 39 bodies found at the
scene have been identified.
	   Officials expected to call off the search by nightfall, leaving
the tracks to investigators and repair crews. Workers were
preparing new sections of rail to reopen the Hanover-Hamburg
stretch by the middle of this week.
	   Investigators have pointed to the wheel failure as the likely
cause of the derailment, prompting rail officials to pull Germany's
59 original high-speed trains out of service for ultrasound wheel
inspections. Rail delays continued throughout Germany on Sunday.
	   Inspectors said it will take 15 days to complete the tests of
wheels and wheel casings.
	   Federal rail authorities expected to have three first-generation
trains back on the rails at normal top speed of 280 kilometers (175
miles) an hour by Sunday afternoon.
	   Maximum speed on the trains was reduced to 160 kilometers (100
miles) an hour after the accident.
	   Germany's second-generation ICEs, introduced in 1996, have a
different wheel system, and have been left in service.
	   In the small, red-brick village of Eschede, residents laid a
wooden cross Sunday on a road near the crash site and placed a
flower pot on top in memory of the victims.
	   (im-aet-cb) 	   
</TEXT>
