<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Aid,0411 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq will not accept any more aid shipments from abroad
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq will turn down any further shipments
of humanitarian aid sent by friendly countries or organizations,
Baghdad newspapers said Sunday.
	   The Cabinet, in a meeting chaired by President Saddam Hussein
late Saturday, thanked those who have ferried aid to Iraq, but
urged them to shift their attention to ending the ``unfair
embargo'' that the United Nations imposed on Baghdad to punish its
1990 invasion of Kuwait.
	   ``Iraq is not in need of aid and its people are not so lazy to
ask assistance from others,'' the official Al-Qadissiya newspaper
said, quoting a Cabinet statement.
	   It is not clear why Iraq made the decision when aid shipments
have been gathering momentum and when the government has complained
bitterly that a lack of medicine has caused serious health problems
for the 22 million Iraqis.
	   But diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Iraq
felt humiliated by some small aid shipments that drew extensive
media coverage.
	   The Cabinet statement carried in newspapers seemed to reflect
such hurt pride. ``At one time Iraq used to offer humanitarian aid
to many countries, establishments and personalities,'' it said.
	   The U.N. humanitarian spokesman in Iraq, Eric Falt, said he did
not believe Iraq's decision would have any bearing on humanitarian
goods purchased under the U.N.-approved oil-for-food deal.
	   Private aid workers from Western non-governmental organizations
based in Iraq said they did not think the decision would affect
their operations.
	   Some 23 flights carrying humanitarian aid have arrived since
January, mostly from Arab countries and others friendly to Iraq.
	   Aid also flowed from the United States, with approximately 80
tons of medicines and medical supplies shipped to Iraq by two U.S.
aid organizations so far this year.
	   The diplomats noted that last month Iraqi officials were shocked
when a Russian plane landed with only 50 kilograms (110 pounds) of
medical supplies.
	   A Jordanian aid plane, whose arrival drew extensive coverage
from official media, landed last Thursday with a delegation of
health officials and no aid.
	   Later, the press reported that Jordanian officials came to
Baghdad in hope of signing contracts to sell more pharmaceuticals
to Iraq under the country's oil-for-food deal with the United
Nations. 	   
</TEXT>
