<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-France,0288 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: French coach sees few goals in first round
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Eleven players playing defense.
	   It's a horror scenario for anyone who wants to see more goals
and open, fluid play, but French coach Aime Jacquet sees it coming
anyway _ especially against his offensively-challenged team.
	   ``I'm telling you, they will play with 11 behind,'' Jacquet told
the Sunday paper Le Journal du Dimanche. ``What do you think? It is
the setup of modern soccer.''
	   France opens its World Cup campaign Friday against South Africa,
and its ineptitude in front of the goal is a major problem. No
striker on the team has been impressive.
	   France got a taste of what's to come against Finland in an
exhibition game Friday, scraping through with a 1-0 win after David
Trezeguet scored a late goal. The Finns kept the French in check
with the type of physical play that is expected to be a fixture in
many of the 64 World Cup matches.
	   ``It was scandalous,'' Jacquet said. ``Did you see what they did
to (midfielder Zinedine) Zidane? ... Are these referees part of
FIFA or not?''
	   Jacquet realizes he will need Zidane to be at his best if France
is to make a challenge for the Cup, and he's worried about his star
player getting injured.
	   ``Opponents will put up blocks,'' Jacquet said. ``So it is the
team with the most imaginative technician that will make the
difference.''
	   Still, Zidane needs someone to set up.
	   The French league's top scorer, Stephane Guivarc'h, has hit only
one goal in his seven internationals, and he has failed to set up a
good partnership with Zidane and Youri Djorkaeff.
	   (rac/jw)
</TEXT>
