<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train-Emergency Stop </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Engine troubles cause high-speed train to make emergency stop
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MELISSA EDDY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Concerned by noises coming from the
locomotive, the driver of a high-speed train made an emergency stop
to unload passengers left jittery by last week's deadly rail crash,
officials said Sunday.
	   The InterCity Express ``Prinz Eugen'' was approaching Regensburg
in southern Bavaria state Saturday at about 3 p.m., en route from
Vienna to Hamburg, when the driver heard unusual noises, said
German railway spokesman Martin Katz.
	   The ``Prinz Eugen'' was one of the first-generation InterCity
Express trains, the same type that derailed and smashed into a
bridge in the northern town of Eschede on Wednesday, killing 102
people.
	   A broken wheel has been identified as the likely cause, and the
``Prinz Eugen'' was making a final run before a mandatory
ultrasound inspection of its wheels. The train had been put back in
service after passing a preliminary sight inspection ordered, and
before the wheels became investigators' focus.
	   Katz said the driver stopped the train, then continued slowly to
the next station at Neumarkt, where 150 passengers were transferred
to other trains.
	   Authorities who later inspected the train confirmed the driver's
suspicions that the noises had come from the engine. They did not
identify the cause.
	   Passengers also said they heard strange sounds, although
inspectors say that was unlikely.
	   ``I don't want to rule out, after what happened in Eschede, that
some passengers might say they thought they heard something before
the train stopped,'' said Katz. ``But passengers wouldn't have been
able to hear anything from the locomotive.''
	   The train was traveling at a reduced speed of 160 kilometers
(100 miles) an hour instated after the crash.
	   Federal rail authorities expected to have the first three
first-generation trains back on the rails at normal top speed of
280 kilometers (175 miles) an hour by Sunday afternoon.
	   (im-me-cb) 	   
