w1318 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kosovo militants call for more help to fight Serb forces
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with pope, Kinkel, newspaper report on low police
morale, more background &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Kosovo's rebel army appealed Sunday
for more ethnic Albanians to join them and ``fight for freedom''
from the Serbian forces waging a fierce offensive against them.
	   The call, published in the Albanian-language daily Koha Ditore
in Kosovo's capital Pristina, showed that the Serbs' latest
campaign in the secessionist province has not broken the will of
the outgunned Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   The Serbs' latest offensive in the Decani region of western
Kosovo has left at least 50 people dead and 200 missing, according
to ethnic Albanian officials, in addition to sending thousands of
residents fleeing from ruined villages.
	   Serbian officials have characterized it as a response to
increasing attacks by the KLA, a loosely formed group of
self-described freedom fighters who claim to control some 40
percent of the southern province of Yugoslavia's Republic of
Serbia.
	   But the Serbs' stepped-up efforts to wipe out militant
resistance to their authority seem only to have increased the KLA's
backing among the province's young people as well as Kosovo-born
emigres abroad who supply and fund them.
	   ``Come to strengthen our troops against the enemy artillery and
enemy infantry,'' the KLA statement said.
	   It appealed ``for the last time'' to ethnic Albanian political
organizations to give up their policy of a peaceful struggle for
independence and join the KLA.
	   There were no immediate reports Sunday about new clashes in
western Kosovo, which remained sealed off and inaccessible for
foreign journalists.
	   Federal authorities in Yugoslavia, which now consists of just
Serbia and Montenegro, on Sunday escorted more than 40 diplomats
into the besieged region. But journalists were excluded from the
tour, except for the state-run Serbian Radio Television and the
official Tanjug news agency.
	   Kosovo's ethnic Albanians make up about 90 percent of the 2.2
million people living in the province, and most demand to secede
from Serbia and Yugoslavia. Western powers are against any change
of borders in the volatile Balkans but want the Serbs to cease
their offensive and give Kosovo the autonomy taken away by Serbia
in 1989 as a way to suppress the independence movement.
	   The offensive that began in late May has stirred increasing
international concern and fears of igniting a wider war in the
Balkans. The United States is expected to reimpose sanctions
against Serbia after a White House meeting on Monday.
	   On Sunday, Pope John Paul II called on the world to act against
violence and repression in Kosovo.
	   ``Not far from us, in Kosovo, violent options, repression and
the flight of peoples must not leave the international community
inert,'' he said at the Vatican. The violence, the pope said,
``recalls the tragic recent history of the Balkans.''
	   The exodus of more than 10,000 Albanians into Albania last week,
and others into Montenegro, also has stirred worry in the West.
	   In Germany, Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel told the Welt am
Sonntag newspaper his country is afraid of being flooded with
refugees, so it is working with international refugee agencies to
assist them in the Balkans.
	   About 400,000 ethnic Albanians already live in Germany.
	   Serbs vow never to allow the secession of Kosovo, which has many
ancient Orthodox monasteries and which they consider to be the
cradle of their history. Ethnic Albanians, who have long objected
to the Serbs' forceful rule in Kosovo, declare their own historical
claim to the land by saying they are descendants of the ancient
Illyrians, the region's first inhabitants.
	   The Serb community in Kosovo is dwindling in numbers and there
have been reports of low morale among the police deployed to fight
the militants.
	   Belgrade-based Dnevni Telegraf reported Sunday that a total of
363 policemen are leaving the force because they do not want to
fight in Kosovo.
	   (ih/ms/dc)
</TEXT>
