<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Zamorano Injured,0242 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zamorano sustains minor injury, sits out practice
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SERGIO CARRASCO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARIGNAC, France (AP) _ Ivan Zamorano, half of Chile's
high-scoring front line, sat out practice Sunday with what team
doctor called a ``minor'' knee injury.
	   Doctor Eugenio Valdecantos said the injury would not keep the
31-year-old forward out of Chile's World Cup debut against Italy on
Thursday.
	   ``There is no reason for concern,'' Valdecantos said. ``This a
very minor, easy-to-cure injury.''
	   As coach Nelson Acosta directed a two-hour practice session at
the Robert Brettes Stadium in southern France, Zamorano watched
sitting on the sideline, a white bandage and ice around his right
leg.
	   Zamorano did not appear worried as he smiled and waived at
reporters as he walked, limping slightly, to the team bus for the
ride back to the hotel.
	   Valdecantos said the injury is ``a contusion to the right leg
meniscus caused by a bad fall from a jump, a very common injury
among soccer players.''
	   Valdecantos said he ordered Zamorano to rest for one day, which
would also allow the Inter Milan striker to chance to ``cure a
painful scratch to his left heel.''
	   Zamorano sustained the injury Saturday during a practice match
against a Chilean youth team now touring Europe. Chile won 5-0,
with Zamorano scoring one goal.
	   (sc/jw)
</TEXT>
