<HEADLINE>
South Africa avoids the follow-on
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) _ South Africa avoided the follow-on
with the penultimate ball before lunch Sunday as it worked on
saving the first cricket test against England at Edgbaston.
	   The visitors were 264 for seven at the break after rain robbed
39 minutes from the fourth morning.
	   South Africa resumed the day on 192 for five, and still trailed
England's 462 by 198 runs.
	   Jonty Rhodes and Lance Klusener came to the rescue of South
Africa in an undefeated 40-run stand for the eighth wicket.
	   They came together at 224 for seven after medium paceman Angus
Fraser had grabbed two quick wickets.
	   Fraser, who claimed the wicket of Daryll Cullinan (78) five
minutes before stumps on the third day, removed Shaun Pollock and
Mark Boucher in the space of 12 balls.
	   Fraser had Pollock (16) caught hooking and two overs later had
Mark Boucher (0) edging a catch to 'keeper Alec Stewart.
	   Jonty Rhodes, fresh from a 78-ball century in his last
first-class outing, held the South African middle order together
with an unbeaten 68.
	   Klusener was on 20.
	   Rhodes was dropped by substitute fielder Ben Spendlove at
long-leg with a difficult catch off medium-paceman Dominic Cork
just before the break.
	   Fraser has taken 3-67 while Cork, who took the first four South
African wickets, has 4-62.
