<SLUG> BC-Saudi-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saudi Arabia offers humanitarian aid to Iraq
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ Saudi Arabia on Sunday said it was
planning to send humanitarian aid to Iraq, but the statement came
as Iraq announced it would no longer accept such aid.
	   The official Saudi Press Agency reported the kingdom's first
such offer of aid from Saudi Arabia, which was the launching pad
for a U.S.-led allied coalition that ousted Iraq from Kuwait in
1991.
	   King Fahd has ordered that food and medical supplies be sent to
Iraq, ``to help ease the suffering of the Iraqi people who are in
dire need of food and medicine,'' the agency said. It did not say
how much aid the Saudis had in mind, nor how they wanted to send
it.
	   Iraq's 22 million people are suffering from crippling United
Nations sanctions imposed after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The
sanctions severely limit the export of oil, Iraq's main earner of
foreign currency.
	   Baghdad newspaper reported Sunday that Iraq had said it would
turn down any further shipments of humanitarian aid ferried by
friendly countries or organizations.
	   Iraq will ask donors to work on lifting trade sanctions instead
of sending aid, the reports said. Iraq gave no reason for the
decision, but diplomats in Baghdad suggested the government felt
humiliated at the publicity given aid shipments to the once wealthy
country. The diplomats spoke on condition of anonymity.
