<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Le Mans 24 Hours 2nd-ld writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDS: UPDATES with race finsh; AMs planned
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Agony for Toyota as Porsche triumphs again at Le Mans
 &UR; By ANDREAS EVAGORA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LE MANS, France (AP) - Porsche won its third successive Le Mans
24 hour race in dramatic fashion Sunday, after the leading Toyota
GT One withdrew with gearbox problems less than 90 minutes before
the end of the contest.
	   A Porsche GT1 driven by Alan McNish of Britain and France's
Laurent Aiello and Stephane Ortelli won the 66th Le Mans race,
having covered the 13.6-kilometer (8.456-mile) circuit 352 times.
	   The winning Porsche covered about 4787 kilometers (2,976 miles)
less than the 4.909.6 kilometers (3,050 miles) recorded by last
year's winner, the TWR Porsche driven by Michele Alboreto. This
year's winners averaged around 199 kph (124 mph).
	   Another Porsche GT1, driven by Germany's Jorg Muller and Uwe
Alzen and Bob Wolleck of France, was second with 351 laps.
	   In third place was the Nissan R390 driven by Japan's Kazuyoshi
Hoshino, Aguri Suzuki and Masahiko Kageyama, with 349 laps.
	   It was all so different only 90 minutes before the checkered
flag was raised.
	   Toyota mechanics - who had begun to sense the manufacturer's
first ever Le Mans win - were in tears as their Toyota GT1 limped
into the pits when more than 30 seconds ahead.
	   The car, being driven by lead driver Thierry Boutsen, officially
withdrew just 70 minutes from the end, with transmission failure.
	   ``Thierry deserved to win after driving so well overnight,''
said Toyota teammate Martin Brundle. ``The whole team has worked so
hard and we are all terribly disappointed to lose the race this
way. It's awful to go out so close to the end.''
	   Only one Japanese manufacturer, Mazda in 1991, has ever won the
Le Mans race.
	   Porsche, the most successful Le Mans mark ever, demonstrated its
renowned reliability to win its 16th contest.
	   The company, which won seven straight Le Mans races in the
1980s, has won the last three contests here.
	   After Mercedes and BMW each lost both of their cars early in the
race Saturday afternoon, the stage soon became set for a scrap
between Toyota, Porsche and Nissan.
	   Boutsen was leading for more than four hours on Saturday, but it
was Porsche that dominated at the halfway stage, when its two cars
were three laps ahead of the field.
	   An early leader, the Toyota was only fifth at the halfway point,
but clawed its way back to the head of the field Sunday morning.
	   Porsche chiefs could only look on as driver error and mechanical
failure left both its cars in the pits for more than half an hour
at 6 a.m.
	   First, the car driven by Muller, Alzen and Wolleck, while in
second place, was in the pits for 31 minutes.
	   The car needed new brakes and a change in undercarriage after
Muller skidded out of control in rain.
	   Within minutes the leading car, the Porsche driven by McNish,
Aiello and Ortelli, was also in trouble.
	   With McNish behind the wheel, the car had a water leak and was
in the pits for 35 minutes.
	   Toyota took advantage, only to fall close to the finish.
	   The fastest lap of the race, 3:41.809 was recorded by early in
the race by Brundle in another Toyota GT1.
	   Brundle's car fell out of the race after 14 hours with engine
failure.
	   The Mercedes of German Bernd Schneider, which was fastest in
practice, fell out of the race with motor failure after just 90
minutes.
	   The best placed prototype was the Ferrari 333 driven by Wayne
Taylor, Eric van de Poele and Fermin Velez, which came eighth.
	   (ae-sz)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Le Mans 24 Hours 2nd-ld writethru; CT:s; 
