<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Japan roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fighters beat Marines 6-1
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Nigel Wilson singled home two runs in a three-run
fifth inning and Hiroshi Numata hurled a five-hitter as the Nippon
Ham Fighters beat the Chiba Lotte Marines 6-1 at Tokyo Dome Sunday
to move to the top of the Pacific League.
	   Wilson, formerly with the Cleveland Indians, hit the single
after three straight walks by Lotte hurler Juichiro Mutoh left the
bases loaded.
	   Numata (2-0) went the distance for the first time in his
three-year pro career.
	   The Fighters moved one game ahead of the Fukuoka Daiei Hawks,
who lost to the Kintetsu Buffaloes 1-0 at Fukuoka Dome and fell to
second place.
	   Hiroshi Takamura held the Hawks to six hits for his second
victory against four defeats.
	   Catcher Hideaki Okubo hit a triple and scored the Buffaloes's
only run in the second inning off of Norihiro Nakamura's single
against Brian Williams.
	   Williams, formerly with the Baltimore Orioles, took the loss and
slipped to a record of 1-2.
	   At Seibu Dome, pinch hitter Yoshiaki Kanemura drove in the
winning run in the bottom of the 12th inning with a sacrifice fly
as the Seibu Lions edged the Orix BlueWave 9-8.
	   Trailing 1-8, the Lions scored five runs in the seventh with
five hits and two walks. Domingo Martinez added another run with a
homer in the eighth and the tying run came on third baseman Akihito
Igarashi's error in the ninth.
	   Martinez, formerly with the Triple-A Rochester, has 11 homers.
	   In the Central League, Tomohito Itoh pitched a five-hitter and
Takahiro Ikeyama slugged a home run in the fifth inning as the
Yakult Swallows edged the front-running Hiroshima Toyo Carp 2-1 in
Fukushima.
	   Itoh is 1-3 and Ikeyama has eight homers.
	   The Carp still are a half game ahead of the second-place Yomiuri
Giants as the Chunichi Dragons beat the Giants 4-2 at Nagoya Dome
and ended their losing streak at three.
	   The Dragons' Koichi Sekikawa went 3-for-4 and drove in three
runs, including a two-run triple in the third inning.
	   Sun Dong-yol, formerly with the Hai Tai Tigers of South Korea's
professional league, gave up one hit in the ninth inning for his
10th save against two victories.
	   At Sapporo, Hiroshi Yagi hit a two-run double in the sixth
inning as the Hanshin Tigers beat the Yokohama BayStars 5-1.
 &UR; (sk) 	   
</TEXT>
