w1362 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Switzerland-GeneVote 2ndLd-Writethru   06-07 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Gene Vote, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss voters reject restrictions on genetic engineering
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with rejection of initiative. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ After an emotive campaign, Swiss voters
on Sunday decisively rejected a proposal to outlaw the production
and patenting of genetically modified plants and animals.
	   In the run-up to the vote, Swiss industry and government say
would force a ``draconian'' shutdown on research in Switzerland,
sending highly paid jobs to other countries.
	   With results in from more than half of Switzerland's 26 cantons
(states) by mid-afternoon, not a single canton had voted in favor
of the tough restrictions which ``The Initiative for the Protection
of Life and the Environment against Genetic Manipulation'' would
have imposed.
	   For a proposal to be passed, there has to be both a majority of
cantons and of voters in favor.
	   Early exit polls published by Swiss television predicted that 64
percent of the electorate would reject the proposals.
	   Polls before Sunday's vote had pointed to a narrower defeat for
the initiative.
	   Environmentalists and consumer activists who backed it say too
little is known about the consequences of letting genetically
modified organisms into the food chain.
	   In a note to voters, the backers argued that tampering with
genes poses ``incalculable risks'' for the environment and the
prospect of unethical treatment of animals used in experiments.
	   But the issue of jobs is also highly sensitive to the
resource-poor country of 7 million. Despite Switzerland's small
size, it is a leading force in biotechnology.
	   Basel-based pharmaceutical giants Novartis and Roche rank with
competitors such as Monsanto, of St. Louis, among world leaders in
the field.
	   The Swiss pharmaceutical industry said the initiative would keep
the companies and academic researchers from doing some of their
best research, especially medical research involving genetically
modified animals, in Switzerland.
	   In Basel itself, 67.3 percent of voters were against the
restrictions.
	   Switzerland's German-speaking majority was, as expected, more
favorable to the proposal than the western French-speaking states.
In one of these, Neuchatel, 77.5 percent of voters rejected it.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Switzerland-Gene Vote, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
