<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Boat Distress, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Passengers of Ukrainian ferry claim being duped
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with ferry leaving Istanbul, report of Russian agency
in 8th graf; RECASTS, EDITS throughout; no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By PATRICK QUINN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Hundreds of angry passengers on Sunday
accused the captain of a Ukrainian cruise ship of cutting their
trip short and forcibly taking them back to Ukraine.
	   The passengers, mainly Russians and Ukrainians, threw messages
in plastic bottles to members of the media, who approached the ship
with small boats, begging for help from their consulates.
	   After restocking food supplies, the ferry left Istanbul for
Odessa, Ukraine, the Anatolia news agency said.
	   The passengers sent distress signals to a Turkish coast guard
boat on Saturday as the ship passed through the Dardanelles, a
strait that passes from the Aegean Sea to the Black Sea.
	   The captain of the Taras Shevchenko refused Turkish calls to
stop, saying everything was calm on board, the semi-official
Anatolia news agency reported.
	   ``These people have stolen our money. We want our money back,''
shouted several passengers as they held huge banners reading
``S.O.S. Help''
	   ``We were supposed to go to 12 ports and we did not,'' Vladimir
Kryzhanovskiy said aboard the ship while it was moored in the
international waters off Istanbul.
	   Russian news agency ITAR-Tass said on Sunday that the problem
surfaced because the tour company which organized the cruise failed
to transfer the money to the shipping company in time.
	   The captain locked the ship's exists to prevent passengers from
boarding supply barges tied up next to the ship.
	   The ship set sail May 30 from Odessa for a three-week
Mediterranean cruise of seven countries and 12 ports. The minimum
ticket price was dlrs 1,500. It reached the Athens port of Piraeus
on June 1. It left Piraeus on Friday, the Greek coast guard said.
	   The coast guard said the ship had 271 crew members and 517
passengers aboard.
	   ``We were even not allowed to go off the boat in Piraeus as we
anchored there for five days,'' said Kryzhanovskiy, a producer with
private ART television based in Odessa, Ukraine.
	   Greek authorities said the ship was on transit status, and that
no legal arrangements had been made for a stop there.
	   (djw) 	   
</TEXT>
