<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Bergkamp,0301 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Injured Dutch striker may miss first two qualifying matches
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Injured Dutch striker Dennis
Bergkamp may miss the Netherlands' first two World Cup finals
qualifying matches as he struggles to reach match fitness following
a lengthy layoff.
	   Bergkamp is recovering from a hamstring injury and has not yet
trained with the Dutch World Cup squad as it prepares for the June
10-July 12 finals in France. He was with the team Sunday meeting
fans at Amsterdam's Arena stadium and was not scheduled to train.
	   ``He is kicking the ball a little on his own, but has not yet
joined team training,'' Dutch coach Guus Hiddink said following
Friday's crushing 5-1 defeat of Nigeria by the Dutch. ``He is
getting better but he hasn't played for six weeks and is missing
match fitness.''
	   Bergkamp is almost certain to miss the opening Dutch Group E
qualifying match, June 13 in St. Denis against Belgium, and may
also be forced out of the second, against South Korea on June 20 in
Marseille. The Netherlands' final group match is against Mexico on
June 25.
	   Bergkamp, who scored 16 league goals for his English club
Arsenal this season has not pulled on a Dutch shirt for any of the
three tune-up matches the Netherlands has played in the last two
weeks.
	   Hiddink has repeatedly said he will not play Bergkamp unless he
is 100 percent certain of his fitness. ``If he starts playing a
minute too soon we could lose him for the whole tournament,''
Hiddink said recently.
	   In his absence, the Dutch scored 10 goals and conceded just two
in their last two warm-up games against World Cup-bound opposition
Paraguay and Nigeria.
	   Bergkamp has scored 33 goals for the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
