<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rescue workers dig for clues in identifying train crash victims
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RAISES number of bodies identified to 51 from 39; SUBS
overline &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN MADER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Rescue workers dug to depths of four
meters (yards) Sunday for clues to help identify victims in postwar
Germany's deadliest train crash.
	   At least 102 people were killed when high-speed InterCity
Express 884 derailed and slammed into the concrete supports of an
overpass that crashed down onto the jackknifed passenger cars.
	   Rescuers in the northern city of Eschede, 50 kms (35 miles)
north of Hanover, believe it is unlikely they will find more
bodies, and were sifting through sandy dirt for personal effects,
such as jewelry and wallets. So far, 51 bodies found at the scene
have been identified.
