<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Nuclear,0489 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan says it cannot be forced to sign nonproliferation
</HEADLINE>
treaties &QL; 
 &UR; By ARTHUR MAX &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan said Sunday it cannot be
compelled to sign the nuclear arms control treaties, and accused
the U.N. Security Council of ignoring the new reality of South
Asia's nuclear status.
	   The council, which condemned last month's nuclear tests by India
and Pakistan, had taken an approach that was ``manifestly lopsided,
unjust and unrealistic,'' said a statement from the Foreign
Ministry.
	   It also expressed disappointment that the resolution adopted
Saturday did not offer concrete steps toward resolving Pakistan's
dispute with India over the Himalayan territory of Kashmir, which
both claim.
	   Nuclear tensions exploded on the Indian subcontinent May 11 when
India tested a series of nuclear devices, demonstrating a
capability to build strategic and tactical nuclear weapons.
	   Pakistan, resisting international pressure not to respond,
detonated its own nuclear devices two weeks later.
	   Both countries demanded entry into the exclusive five-member
club of official nuclear states recognized by international arms
control regimes.
	   The Security Council denied them that legal status and urged
them to sign the nonproliferation treaties, which they have
resisted for decades.
	   ``The council has ignored the reality on the ground,'' the
Pakistani statement said.
	   ``Treaty provisions cannot be enforced on non-parties. Treaty
obligations can only be assumed on a voluntary basis,'' it said.
Trying to impose a treaty ``is by its very nature unequal and
unsustainable.''
	   The statement did not refer specifically to the resolution's
call against deploying missiles capable of carrying nuclear
warheads.
	   Hours before the resolution, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
reiterated his offer to hold ``a meaningful dialogue'' with Indian
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee. In New Delhi, Vajpayee
welcomed the idea of talks. The two men are to attend a regional
summit in Sri Lanka in July.
	   But leaders of the two countries have met regularly over the
years without breaking new ground. Lower level officials also have
met periodically, but each round of talks has broken down over
unbridgeable difference about Kashmir.
	   The Security Council called on the two rivals to exercise
restraint and find ``mutually acceptable solutions'' to the ``root
causes of those tensions, including Kashmir.''
	   Pakistan had clearly hoped the international community would get
directly involved in the Kashmir dispute, overriding Indian
objections that the problem is for India and Pakistan to sort out
themselves.
	   Two of the subcontinent's three wars in the last 50 years were
fought over Kashmir, a former kingdom that had a Muslim majority
and a Hindu ruler. Pakistan holds two-thirds of the territory and
India one-third.
</TEXT>
