<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Reporters, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court acquits BBC reporters
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CLARIFIES reasons for acquittal in 4th-7th grafs. &QL; 
 &UR; By AHMAD AL-HAJ &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Three British Broadcasting Corp. television
journalists charged with filming without government permission were
acquitted by a Yemeni court Sunday.
	   Judge Haikal Ahmed Othman ordered the release of BBC producer
Robin Barnwell, reporter Rageh Ommar and cameraman Frank Smith
after viewing the tapes they filmed and listening to witnesses'
testimony.
	   ``Yemen believes in the freedom of the press, and the press is a
necessity in this age. The world has become a village as a result
of advanced technology and information,'' Othman said before
announcing the verdict.
	   Othman said that the reporters did not break any laws and were
visiting Yemen legally and that the prosecution did not prove its
case against the three men.
	   ``The authorities were aware of their presence and the films
they shot did not insult the government or the Yemeni people,'' he
said.
	   The three men were accused of not informing the government of
their plans to film, but had made clear their intention in their
visa application.
	   Othman said the three journalists also did not break the law by
failing to state they would film where kidnappings have taken
place. He said a law requiring such advance notice applies only to
resident journalists.
	   Dozens of journalists and Yemenis attending the trial, which
began Saturday, cheered the verdict and congratulated the three men
and their lawyer al-Sheik Tareq Abdullah.
	   ``I'm very proud not only because I won the case but because
this case is historical. This is a victory for Yemen and the Yemeni
people,'' Abdullah said.
	   The journalists were arrested after returning to the capital
San`a after spending a week with the Bani Dhabyan tribe near Marib,
170 kilometers (105 miles) northeast of San`a.
	   The Bani Dhabyan have carried out numerous kidnappings,
including the seizure of a British teacher, David Mitchell, his
wife Caroline, and their 14-year old son, Ben.
	   Armed tribesmen who rule over large parts of Yemen have
kidnapped foreigners and demanded concessions from the government
in return for their release. The hostages are usually well treated
and released unharmed.
 &UR; pvs-ti-ggl
</TEXT>
