<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-England-Alcohol </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Offers of help for Gascoigne; crackdown on alcohol
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ England teammates and recovering alcoholics Tony
Adams and Paul Merson have offered to help dropped midfielder Paul
Gascoigne.
	   And England coach Glenn Hoddle has promised a crackdown on
drinking during the World Cup.
	   The two players, speaking in the Independent on Sunday, said
Gascoigne needed to decide if drinking was wrecking his life.
	   ``I just hope he sorts out his life and can be happy,'' said
Adams, who stopped drinking two years ago. ``Only he can decide if
he has a problem, but if he wants to choose my path then he knows
where I am.''
	   Merson, who plays with Gascoigne on England's Middlesbrough
club, echoed Adams.
	   ``I hope he can find it inside himself to want to do something
about the way things have been with him,'' Merson said.
	   Gascoigne, perhaps the most talented England player of his
generation, was cut from the England side a week ago when Hoddle
said he was out of shape, partly due to his late-night partying and
drinking.
	   On Saturday, England midfielder Teddy Sheringham apologized for
partying until dawn last week in a Portuguese night club. And
teammate Darren Anderton was reported on the fringe of a brawl last
week at a club in Bournemouth, England.
	   Hoddle promised a crackdown.
	   ``I am not going to ban alcohol and on occasion the players will
be allowed a couple of beers or a glass of wine. But only at the
right times,'' Hoddle told the newspaper.
	   ``Alcohol can also affect injuries and that was the
disappointing thing with Paul Gascoigne,'' he added. ``In England
that's what we have had all through our careers _ get in the
players' bar and have a beer. But that's detrimental and won't
happen in France.''
	   The newspaper pointed out that FIFA, the world governing body of
soccer, looks for alcohol during its drug tests.
	   ``The degree of (alcohol) use can be checked in the breath or
the blood and if it was heavy, it may lead to sanctions,'' the
newspaper quoted a FIFA spokeswoman as saying.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
