<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Austria,0389 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: light training and video viewing before Cameroon game
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARGAUX, France (AP) _ When the Austrian team congregates in
front of the television set in their hotel after a training
session, more work lies ahead _ studying a video of resurgent
Cameroon, its first World Cup opponent
	   Austrian ``spies'' were on hand when Cameroon upset Denmark 2-1
last week in Copenhagen. A video of the game was handed to Coach
Herbert Prohaska at Vienna airport on Saturday, just before the
team flew to France.
	   Part of the Austrians' task ahead of its match on Thursday in
Toulouse is to lay out a strategy to contain the young and
aggressive African players.
	   ``We have the tape and we'll be looking at it,'' Prohaska said
Sunday. ``The games against the Netherlands and Denmark have shown
that Cameroon is a strong team we'll have to watch out for.''
	   Cameroon beat the Danes after holding the Netherlands to a
scoreless draw in a World Cup warmup 10 days ago in Arnhem. Even
without star midfielder Marc Vivien Foe _ sidelined since May with
a broken leg _ Cameroon showed the spark that earned it a berth in
the quarterfinals in the 1990 World Cup, the only African side to
advance so far in World Cup history.
	   Austrian forward Anton Polster said part of any winning formula
has to be to play as a team.
	   ``We want to present a solid squad,'' Polster told reporters.
``We're full of energy and are concentrating on what's ahead.''
	   The Austrians are based at a luxury hotel in Arsac, a
picturesque wine-growing town north of Bordeaux and near Margaux,
site of Sunday's press briefing.
	   Prohaska wasn't committing himself publicly to a lineup this
early. But he said ``nine or 10'' of the players he fielded in the
``A'' practice squad _ including Michael Konsel in goal and Anton
Pfeffer, Peter Schottel, Harald Cerny, Roman Mahlich, Anton
Pfeffer, and Dietmar Kuehbauer on the field _ might see action
against Cameroon.
	   In a training session Saturday, Hannes Reinmayr, the Sturm Graz
playmaker, collided with Wolfgang Feiersinger and hurt his knee.
Prohaska said Reinmayr would ``likely'' be fit by the Cameroon game
Thursday. Another team workout was scheduled Sunday afternoon.
</TEXT>
