<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Abacha </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Junta drafts new law to allow Abacha's presidency
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ A new law that would clear the way for
military strongman Gen. Sani Abacha to become president has been
drafted by his ruling regime and will soon be passed, a newspaper
reported Sunday.
	   Quoting a member of the military junta, the Lagos Punch
newspaper said the new law would circumvent existing legislation
that bars armed forces officers from holding political office in
Nigeria.
	   When passed, the law would effectively nullify all legal
opposition to Abacha's eligibility, the newspaper reported, quoting
the unnamed official.
	   In April, Abacha became the only candidate for president in
August elections when he was nominated by all five state-sanctioned
political parties.
	   The nomination process triggered an uproar from opposition
leaders and pro-democracy groups who say Abacha manipulated the
system to eliminate any competition.
	   Anti-Abacha groups have since sought to use legal measures to
stop the military ruler's rise to the presidency.
	   A bid to use the federal courts to block Abacha's nomination was
dismissed on the grounds that Abacha had not yet officially
accepted the presidential nomination.
	   Abacha seized power five years ago after canceling presidential
elections and jailing the presumed winner Moshood Abiola. Although
the military junta has pledged to stand down and allow for a
civilian government, it has repeatedly reneged on the pledge.
	   Under Abacha's rule, Nigeria has become an international pariah,
accused of widespread human rights abuses and rampant corruption.
 &UR; (fa/ad/ids)
</TEXT>
