w1427 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-Politics     06-07 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan's independence opposition elects die-hard chairman
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ A one-time political prisoner looked set
Sunday to become the chairman of the opposition Democratic
Progressive Party in an election delayed by violence.
	   With a quarter of the 92,504 votes counted, Lin Yi-hsiung led
his main opponent, legislator Chang Chun-hung, by a two to one
margin, the party said.
	   If he wins, Lin will lead the party in December's elections for
lawmakers and the crucial posts of Taipei and Kaohsiung mayors.
Those polls are widely considered a dry run for the 2000
presidential election that represents the DPP's best chance yet to
capture the central government from the ruling Nationalists.
	   Lin supports Taiwan's formal and permanent independence from
China, a view the DPP officially espouses but has softened in
recent years.
	   He can be expected to seek to wrest power over the DPP's
direction from party factions and local political machines, and
expand membership, said You Nai-hsiang, a party commentator.
	   Formerly a local council deputy, Lin was among eight opposition
figures jailed for helping organize a 1978 pro-democracy
demonstration that turned into a violent confrontation with police.
	   While behind bars, Lin's mother and twin daughters were murdered
at his home. The crime has never been solved, but is widely
considered to have been an act of political revenge.
	   The DPP was banned in the years before 1987 when the
Nationalists governed an authoritarian state under martial law. The
Nationalists moved their government to Taiwan after being swept out
of China by Mao Tse-tung's Communists in 1949, and still propose
eventual reunification with China.
	   The DPP last year made major gains at the polls and now governs
over 70 percent of Taiwan's population at the local level. The
party controls about one third of seats in the national
legislature.
	   Party leaders were forced to hold a second round of voting in
the southern city of Kaohsiung after men believed to be supporters
of one candidate for chief of the DPP's Kaohsiung headquarters
overturned ballot boxes on May 24.
	   The men claimed their candidates' opponent was cheating by
allowing supporters to vote more than once.
	   Voting was completed in other areas, but ballot boxes were
sealed and votes were not counted until Sunday. This time, cameras
were set up at all polling places and voting proceedings broadcast
on screens at party headquarters to avoid further controversy. 	   
</TEXT>
