<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Train Bomb, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0475 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb rips through train killing 26 people
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: UPDATEs with accusation against India; background &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos KAR101, LAR101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By ZAHID HUSSAIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ A powerful time bomb tore through a
train traveling through southern Pakistan on Sunday, killing 26
people and wounding 45 others, many of them seriously, police and
emergency workers said.
	   The government accused India's intelligence service of
responsibility. India dismissed the charge as ``preposterous.''
	   The train was passing through a village 30 kilometers (18 miles)
outside Sukkur, some 200 kilometers (120 miles) north of Karachi,
capital of the southern Sindh province, when the bomb exploded just
before dawn, police said.
	   The 18-carriage Khyber Mail express, with a capacity to carry
1,800 passengers, was headed from Karachi to the northwestern city
of Peshawar, they said. Among the dead were four children aged 5 or
younger, police said.
	   ``When we arrived, the carriage was destroyed and bodies were
blown to pieces. Many of the passengers were trapped and shouting
for help,'' said ambulance driver Mohammed Hafiz.
	   Information Minister Mushahid Hussain said evidence had been
found linking India's Research and Analysis Wing to a spate of
bombings.
	   India and Pakistan routinely exchange accusations after apparent
terrorist actions, but they rarely provide evidence to support
their claims. Both countries also have internal ethnic and
religious conflicts that often lead to killings, bombings and
riots.
	   However, it would be hard to put Sunday's train bomb in an
ethnic context since it did not seem to have a specific target and
the explosive device was more powerful and more professionally
assembled than is usually seen in local disturbances.
	   India is trying to ``destabilize Pakistan through acts of
terrorism,'' said Hussein in an interview with the British
Broadcasting Corp.
	   Linking the attack to the heightened nuclear tensions in the
region, Hussein said India ``wants to divert attention from its own
domestic frustrations because its nuclear explosion backfired.''
	   He also said a suspect had been captured in connection with a
theater bombing Friday that killed three people in the eastern city
of Lahore, capital of Punjab province.
	   Another alleged Indian agent had confessed to being involved in
10 bomb blasts within nine weeks earlier this year, said a
statement from Hussain's office.
	   Earlier, the government said it had received intelligence
information that Indian secret service agents would try to
infiltrate Pakistan to conduct terrorist acts between June 5 and 7.
	   The two countries have fought three wars since the South Asian
subcontinent gained its independence in 1947 from the departing
British. 	   
</TEXT>
