<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Saudi-Pakistan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan seeks Saudi help on nuclear crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ Visiting Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif on Sunday sought Saudi Arabia's help in getting the
United States lift sanctions imposed after its nuclear tests last
month, a diplomat said.
	   Sharif asked Crown Prince Abdullah to use Saudi influence with
the United States to end the sanctions, the diplomat said, speaking
on condition of anonymity. He did not elaborate.
	   Sharif arrived here earlier Sunday on the second stop of his
Gulf tour to discuss the consequences of the Indian and Pakistani
nuclear tests and secure credit to maintain oil imports.
	   Pakistan bought dlrs 1.2 billion of petroleum products from Gulf
states during the nine months up to March.
	   Sharif arrived in this Red Sea port city from the United Arab
Emirates, where he met with President Sheik Zayed bin Sultan Al
Nahyan on Saturday. Sharif is expected to meet King Fahd later
Sunday.
	   He is accompanied by Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan and
Petroleum Minister Chaudhry Nisar Ali Khan.
	   Led by the United States, several countries imposed economic
sanctions against Pakistan and India in a bid to block foreign
investment and credit to punish them for starting the nuclear
crisis.
	   The two nations have a history of enmity since Islamic Pakistan
was carved out in 1947 from predominantly Hindu India.
	   Fears of a nuclear arms race in the region began after India
tested five nuclear devices on May 11 and 13. Pakistan replied with
six nuclear tests, despite warnings from the U.N. Security Council,
the United States and other nations.
	   Islamabad expects the sanctions to cut off financing for aid
projects from the International Monetary Fund, and to lower
Pakistan's credit rating, making borrowing more expensive. Oil
concessions from the oil-rich Gulf could help offset the effect of
the sanctions.
	   Last week, both Saudi Arabia and the Emirates expressed
understanding for Islamabad's view that its nuclear tests were a
means to preserve its security and territorial integrity. However,
both countries also said the tests increased tension in the region.
	   Sharif will leave Monday for Kuwait.
