<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Bookmakers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police smash bookmaking sydnicates
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) - Police have arrested 19 people and smashed 16
bookmaking syndicates that accepted bets on horse racing from
people in Macau and the Chinese mainland, the government reported
Sunday.
	   Officers from the Organized Crime and Triad Bureau arrested the
people following raids throughout Hong Kong on Saturday, the
government said in a statement.
	   Betting and bank records seized during the raids indicated that
the turnover of the sydnicates could reach 80 million Hong Kong
dollars (U.S. dlrs 10.2 million) for a single horse race, it said.
	   One of the syndicates even accepted bets on soccer matches, the
statement said.
	   Under the law, Hong Kong bookmakers who accept bets from outside
the territory could face charges of money laundering. The maxium
penalty for the offense is 14 years in jail and a fine of five
million Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 641,000). 	   
</TEXT>
