<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Government </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yemen government wins vote of confidence
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AHMED AL-HAJ &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Yemen's new government easily won a vote of
confidence Sunday from the 301-member Parliament.
	   Prime Minister Abdel-Karim al-Iryani's Cabinet won 226 votes
while 17 deputies voted against and 26 abstained. The remaining 32
deputies did not attend the session.
	   The vote of confidence, which is a formal approval of the
government, comes less than a week after al-Iryani presented his
policy plan to Parliament, which included a pledge to continue with
a three-year-old program of economic and administrative reforms.
	   In his statement to Parliament last Monday, al-Iryani cautioned
that the Asian economic crisis and the fall in oil prices will have
a negative effect on the economy and further increase the budget
deficit to 36.2 billion rials (dlrs 275 million).
	   Oil revenues, which represent about 40 percent of the country's
total income, are Yemen's main source for foreign currency.
	   The 1998 budget projects oil income will increase 3 percent to
dlrs 1 billion from dlrs 970 million estimated for 1997. The
government aims to raise oil output capacity to 500,000 barrels per
day by 2000 from around 350,000 barrels daily now. Yemen's fiscal
year begins April 1.
	   The World Bank has approved a dlrs 80 million credit to Yemen to
support its economic reform program. The government has already cut
back subsidies and stepped up privatization of state-controlled
companies as part of reforms required by the International Monetary
Fund.
	   Still suffering from a devastating 1994 civil war, Yemen has a
foreign debt of some dlrs 10 billion it cannot serve. Most of its
17 million people live in poverty.
	   Al-Iryani took office on May 17, replacing Faraj bin Ghanem who
resigned amid differences with President Ali Abdullah Saleh, the
real power in the country, over political and economic reforms.
Ghanem spent less than one year in office.
 &UR; str-ti-ggl
</TEXT>
