<SLUG> BC-Bangladesh-Peace Accord,0288 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security alert in tribal areas ahead of opposition march
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HASAN SAEED &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ Bangladeshi security forces went into
high gear Sunday to prevent possible political clashes during an
opposition march this week against a peace accord that ended two
decades of bush war, officials said.
	   A senior official at the Home (Interior) Ministry said the army,
the paramilitary and the police had been put on alert to prevent
violent confrontations between opposition activists and government
supporters in the southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts during the
two-day protest.
	   The 2,000 Buddhist rebels of the Shanti Bahini or Peace Force
agreed to end their bush war last December after the government
promised them greater control over the region, rich in timber and
natural gas resources.
	   But seven right-wing opposition parties led by former Prime
Minister Khaleda Zia are opposing the peace accord, saying the
government had given away too much to the tribal insurgents.
	   The ruling Bangladesh Awami League of Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina, who signed the peace accord with tribal insurgents last
year, has ordered a rival ``Peace March'' to match the opposition
program.
	   '' If the peace accord is scrapped, the region will again plunge
into violence and there will be a blood bath,'' Hasina said at a
public meeting in the capital Dhaka on Saturday.
	   The conflict has claimed nearly 20,000 lives since it started in
1975.
	   Opposition leaders have said hundreds of thousands of people
from across the country will assemble in Dhaka and Chittagong, 176
kilometers (110 miles) southeast of Dhaka, for the grand march.
</TEXT>
