<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Wagner,0254 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel's opera company decides against performing Wagner
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's only opera company said Sunday that
Israeli audiences are not ready to hear works by German composer
Richard Wagner, whose operas blared over loudspeakers in Nazi death
camps.
	   The Tel Aviv-based New Israeli Opera held a public meeting
Saturday to gather audience response to the idea of staging a
Wagner work. The forum _ Wagner, Artist or Symbol _ turned
emotional, with audience members shouting down a singer and a
pianist who tried to perform a sample Wagner piece.
	   The public is still too divided over the issue to justify going
ahead, said opera spokeswoman Varda Zimmerman.
	   ``If there is still opposition to Wagner opera, it will not be
performed,'' she said.
	   Wagner was a self-declared anti-Semite who railed against what
he considered the undue influence of Jews in Germany's music
circles. Adolf Hitler, who came to power 50 years after the
composer's death, considered his music a glorification of a master
race.
	   The New Israeli Opera said the issue of Wagner's works will be
discussed at a future meeting of the opera board. The question has
sparked stormy protest in the past in Israel.
	   When after a 1981 Israel Philharmonic Orchestra concert,
conductor Zubin Mehta announced as an encore the prelude to the
Wagner opera ``Tristan and Isolde,'' the audience cried, ``Shame!''
and an usher rushed to the stage, pulling up his shirt to show
Nazi-inflicted scars. 	   
</TEXT>
