<SLUG> BC-Saudi-Pakistan,0226 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan seeks Saudi help on nuclear crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif asked Sunday for Saudi Arabia's help in fighting sanctions
imposed after its nuclear tests last month, a diplomat said.
	   Sharif asked Crown Prince Abdullah to use Saudi influence with
the United States to end the sanctions, the diplomat said on
condition of anonymity. He did not elaborate.
	   Sharif arrived in Saudi Arabia on Sunday on the second stop of
his Gulf tour to discuss the consequences of the Indian and
Pakistani nuclear tests and to secure credit to maintain oil
imports.
	   Sharif arrived in the Red Sea port city of Jidda from the United
Arab Emirates. Sharif is expected to meet King Fahd later Sunday.
	   He is accompanied by Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan and
Petroleum Minister Chaudhry Nisar Ali Khan.
	   Led by the United States, several countries imposed economic
sanctions against Pakistan and India in a bid to block foreign
investment and loans to punish it for the nuclear crisis.
	   Fears of a nuclear arms race in the region began after India
tested five nuclear devices on May 11 and 13. Pakistan replied with
six nuclear tests, despite warnings from the U.N. Security Council,
the United States and other nations.
	   Sharif will leave Monday for Kuwait. 	   
</TEXT>
