w1478 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Kuwait-Iraq     06-07 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kuwait-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kuwait alarmed at alleged Iraqi remarks about border demarcation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Kuwait said Sunday it was ``worried and dismayed''
about reported Iraqi remarks that a post-Gulf War demarcation of
the border between the two countries had no legal standing.
	   Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid also criticized
the remarks, which apparently were made by Iraq's vice president,
Taha Yassin Ramadan, in the Moroccan capital of Rabat.
	   A Kuwait Cabinet statement said Ramadan's statement is ``a
serious threat that uncovers the real aggressive Iraqi intentions
towards Kuwait,'' which Iraq invaded in 1990.
	   The statement also called on the world community to take
``serious and practical steps in order to guarantee'' that the
borders were respected.
	   Ramadan was reported to have told a group of Arab journalists
last week that a U.N. resolution ``that demarcated the border
between Iraq and Kuwait does not have any legal value.'' He said
the United Nations has no mandate to fix borders of its member
states.
	   The remarks were published Thursday by Abu Dhabi's Al-Ittihad
newspaper.
	   Ramadan's office did not immediately confirm if he had made
those comments.
	   Iraqi troops occupied Kuwait for seven months before a U.S.-led
coalition fought the Gulf War to evict them in February 1991.
	   Baghdad, however, formally recognized Kuwait as a sovereign
state only in November 1994. It also recognized the border between
the two countries as demarcated by a U.N. commission after the war.
	   Kuwait has now launched a diplomatic campaign to protect its
rights, the official Kuwait News Agency reported.
	   Following Kuwait's plea to the Arab League to condemn the
``irresponsible'' remarks, Secretary General Abdel-Meguid said on
Sunday that all Arab countries should refrain from ``issues which
can negatively affect Arab relations and slow down
confidence-building between the brothers.''
 &UR; de/vj
</TEXT>
