w1488 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Vatican-Pope 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vatican-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pope deplores violence in Kosovo, Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES pvs, ADDS byline, photo slug &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By DANIEL J. WAKIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ Pope John Paul II on Sunday called on the
world to act against violence and repression in Kosovo, the ethnic
Albanian province of Yugoslavia.
	   He also said he was worried by the growing conflict between
Ethiopia and Eritrea in Africa.
	   ``Let God spare the dear peoples of Africa, already so troubled,
from further suffering,'' he said after his regular Sunday blessing
in St. Peter's Square.
	   ``Not far from us, in Kosovo, violent options, repression and
the flight of peoples must not leave the international community
inert,'' he said. The violence ``recalls the tragic recent history
of the Balkans.''
	   John Paul called on the parties to take up the road to dialogue,
``longer but more effective for all.''
	   Serb forces have stepped up their campaign to crush Albanian
separatists fighting heavy-handed rule by Serb authorities in
Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians represent 90 percent of the
population of 2.2 million.
	   He also said he hoped that a U.N. conference on fighting drugs
opening Monday would give a ``new and concrete impulse'' toward
cooperation on the issue.
	   Drug trafficking, production and use ``constitute a market of
death, which corrodes and weakens the human being,'' he said.
	   In the morning, the pope embarked on one of his regular parish
visits, this time visiting St. Nicholas of Bari in Ostia, a seaside
community a half-hour outside the city.
	   He went by helicopter because of the distance. He usually
travels to the parishes by car.
	   The visit combined touching and humorous moments. When
9-year-old Giorgio Galante broke down in tears during his welcoming
speech, he was brought up to the pontiff, who embraced and kissed
the boy to comfort him.
	   ``Giorgio Galante spoke with tears, and with these tears he said
more than with beautiful words,'' the pope told a group of
children. ``I will remember this visit as one where a boy welcomed
me with tears, because he was so moved.''
	   Later, a girl scout called John Paul a ``young pope who loves
young people.'' The pontiff, who turned 78 on May 18, responded
with a smile: ``The only thing I can do is pretend to still be
young.''
	   (dp/djw) 	   
</TEXT>
