----
PAKISTAN: BLAST - APTV is seeking pictures from the scene of a
passenger train blast in southern Pakistan that has claimed at least
26 lives and injured nearly 50 others.   (F-L-A-S-H after 1500)
----
ALBANIA: REFUGEES - We are pursuing pictures from a hospital at
Bajram Curri in Albania where ethnic Albanian refugees from the
troubled province of Kosovo are seeking treatment.  Also shots of
the refugees as they flee across the border to safety.  (F-L-A-S-H
after 1600)
----
GERMANY: ERITREA - APTV will have pictures of the latest arrivals in
Germany of Europeans and Americans who fled the fighting in Eritrea.
(F-L-A-S-H after 1700)
----
ITALY: POPE - Pope John Paul II has called on the world to intervene
in the crisis between Serbs and ethnic Albanians in the Yugoslav
province of Kosovo. APTV has highlights from his weekly address to
pilgrims in St. Peter's Square in Rome.  (F-L-A-S-H after 1300)
----
FRANCE: WORLD CUP - The world football body FIFA picks a new
president to succeed Joao Havelange.  APTV covers the announcement
occurring just days before the kickoff of the World Cup. (F-L-A-S-H
after 1700)
----
US: TONYS - Highlights expected overnight from the Tony Awards,
America's highest coveted prize in theater, taking place at New York
City's Radio City Music Hall this evening.   (T-B-A overnight)
----
RUNNING:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
IRAN: MAYOR - APTV covers the opening of the trial of Tehran mayor
Gholamhossein Karbaschi, where the reformist mayor has pled innocent
to corruption charges and challenged the competence of the court.
Karbaschi, a key ally of moderate Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami, is portraying himself as a target of the Islamic hardline
court.  (First Run Americas 0900)
----
IRAQ: FUNERAL - Protestors demonstrated against international
sanctions against Iraq in front of United Nations offices in
Baghdad.  They walked with small white coffins representing the
Iraqi children they say have died at the hands of the sanctions.
Iraq announced it would not accept any more aid shipments from
neighbours, the last of which arrived on Friday.  (First Run
Americas 0900)
----
JERUSALEM: POSTERS - Posters of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu wearing Arab headdress in the style of Yasser Arafat have
appeared in Jerusalem.  APTV has shots of the posters.
(First Run Americas 0900)
----
LEBANON: ELECTIONS - The Lebanese people went to the polls on Sunday
in the third stage of municipal elections - the first there in 35
years.  Item includes soundbites from voters and Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri, who said the vote should help Lebanese put their
decades of war behind them.  (First Run 1130 Europe Update)
----
WORLD CUP: ST DENIS - The Paris suburb of Saint Denis is home to the
Stade de France stadium where the football World Cup final will be
played.  The suburb officially kicked off its celebrations on
Saturday evening in honour of the World Cup tournament's kickoff
this week. (First Run Europe Early 0300)
----
JAPAN: LOVEGETY - From the land of gadgets comes another gizmo: the
lovegety - a love detector that bleeps when the chance of romance
comes near. APTV finds out how it works, talks to lovegety users and
the company that manufactures them and has comment from a couple
that met as a result of the lovegety. (First Run Asia Pacific Late
0715)
----
SAFRICA: RHINO - Not content with using ordinary paper, one artist
in South Africa is going to the extraordinary length of having paper
specially made from rhinoceros dung. APTV has the story of Deryck
Healey and his "recycled" art. (First Run Europe Early 0300)
