<SLUG> BC-Tanzania-Students Suspended,0222 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Medical students in Dar es Salaam suspended
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) _ The government has suspended
every medical student at a Tanzanian university for ``security
reasons,'' state radio reported Sunday.
	   Radio Tanzania quoted Vice Chancellor Mathew Luhanga as saying
the 445 medical students at Muhimbili University College of Health
Sciences were sent home because of the ``prevailing situation at
the college.''
	   On Thursday, riot police dispersed the undergraduate students
after they stormed a conference hall where Health Minister Aaron
Chiduo was meeting university officials, the broadcast said.
	   The students boycotted classes Thursday and Friday to protest
the upgrading of the college, formerly a constituent of the
University of Dar es Salaam, to a university. The students said
they were not consulted.
	   The government also suspended indefinitely the publication of
three privately-owned Swahili language newspapers for publishing
pornographic cartoons, the broadcast said.
	   It said the cartoons were harmful to the country's culture and
the editors had refused to comply with state requests to tone them
down.
	   Tanzanian law permits the government to suspend publications if
they are seen to deviate from their declared editorial policies. 	   
</TEXT>
