<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Local elections in Italy choose 73 mayoralties
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: results expected Monday morning, time uncertain &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ While national politicians maneuver to resuscitate
lifeless reform efforts, Italian voters on Sunday worried about
more direct concerns: whom to put in city hall.
	   The center-right opposition and governing center-left alliance
of former communists and Christian Democrats went head-to-head in
most of the 73 mayoralties up for grabs in run-off local elections.
	   Candidates in the first round on May 24 who captured more than
50 percent of the vote were declared winners.
	   At stake Sunday were provincial presidencies in Treviso in the
north and Caltanissetta and Siracusa in Sicily and mayoralties in
16 provincial seats up and down Italy, including Asti, Cuneo, Como,
Verona, Parma, Piacenza, Lucca, L'Aquila, Frosinone, Isernia,
Matera, Oristano, Enna, Siracusa, Trapani and Ragusa.
	   Results were not expected until sometime Monday morning. Some
3.5 million Italians were eligible to vote. The opposition, led by
media magnate and former Premier Silvio Berlusconi, came out best
in the first round.
	   On Wednesday, Parliament is expected to reconvene to ponder the
fate of constitutional reforms designed to stabilize a political
system than since World War II has produced 55 governments.
	   Party bickering last week prompted most leaders to declare the
18-month reform effort dead. But Massimo D'Alema, leader of the
dominant Democratic Left party and chairman of the reform
committee, has been seeking to revive the effort by sounding out
other party leaders over the weekend, newspapers reported.
	   (djw) 	   
</TEXT>
