<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Insurance,0237 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India mulls opening insurance sector
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NEELESH MISRA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ A regulatory body to be set up later
this year will determine how much foreign interest will be allowed
when India's potentially lucrative insurance market is opened to
private companies, the finance minister was quoted as saying
Sunday.
	   Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha proposed the opening of the
state-controlled industry to homegrown private competition in the
annual budget presented last week. Home TV quoted him as saying
Sunday that he would soon introduce legislation to set up an
Insurance Regulatory Authority.
	   Foreign companies are already linking with Indian firms in
anticipation, but it will be up to the regulatory authority to
determine how welcome they will be.
	   Sinha's nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party has pledged to
protect Indian industry, particularly in the areas of consumer
goods and services. But the finance minister said he had not ruled
out the possibility of foreigners working with Indians to sell
insurance.
	   ``The government is under great pressure, there are many
inhibiting factors, but I believe it is sincere in its promise and
the sector will be opened up'' to private firms in which foreigners
have an interest, said M.J. Augustine, whose Indian firm Dabur
Finance has linked with the U.S. company Liberty International.
</TEXT>
