r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Norway-     06-07 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Norway-Flos in France,0649 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Three Flos could play in opener
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEPHAN NASSTROM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LA BAULE, France (AP) _ At 1.93 meters (6-foot-4), Tore Andre
Flo and brother Jostein are among the tallest players in the World
Cup.
	   Their cousin, Havard Flo, is 1.85 meters (6-foot-1).
	   ``The whole family is tall, and we call Havard the midget,''
said Tore Andre Flo, who nicely fits his description as Norway's
biggest offensive weapon.
	   Aerial attacks are a Norwegian speciality. That's why the three
Flos could very well fit into coach Egil ``Drillo'' Olsen's game
plan for Norway's Group A opener against Morocco in Montpellier on
Wednesday.
	   Several brothers have played together in the World Cup. The most
famous pair is Bobby and Jack Charlton, who helped win the World
Cup for England in 1966.
	   But three relatives on the same national team is rare.
	   Olsen still has two more days to think about his starting
liuneup, but he has indicated that he needs strength in the air.
	   ``Morocco has two or there good players in the air, but that's
it,'' Olsen said.
	   On average, one goal is score for every 50 corner kicks in the
World Cup, and Norway hopes to improve that figure.
	   ``I hope it will be easier to score (after a corner) against
Morocco than during our own practice sessions,'' Olsen said.
	   The Flos, who are staying in the same apartment in Norway's team
headquarters at Saint-Andre-des-Eaux west of Nantes, played
together on the same team, Sogndal in Norway, for one-and-a-half
seasons five years ago.
	   ``It would be a dream for us to play again together, but you
have to ask the boss (Olsen) about that,'' said Tore Andre Flo.
	   Tore Andre now plays with Chelsea in England. Havard's club is
Werder Bremen in Germany. Jostein, one of Olsen's favorite players
in the 1994 Cup when Norway was eliminated after the first round,
has returned to Norway and Stromgodset after a stint with Sheffield
United in England.
	   Tore Andre won the European Cup Winners' Cup with Chelsea last
month in Stockholm, Sweden, although Gianfranco Zola scored the
winning goal just 18 seconds after he substituted for the tall
Norwegian against VfB Stuttgart.
	   ``It was absolutely the finest moment in my career,'' Tore Andre
said. ``Only a quarterfinal berth or a medal in the World Cup could
top that. Norway has never reached the quarters'' in two previous
World Cup appearances.
	   Tore Andre Flo has been compared with Kennet Andersson, who was
one of the leading goalscorers in the 1994 finals when Norway's
neighbour Sweden won the bronze medal.
	   ``Tore Andre could be like Kennet four years ago. He can decide
games,'' said Norway's goalkeeper Frode Grodaas.
	   After scoring two goals a year ago in a 4-2 victory against
Ronaldo's Brazil in Oslo, Tore Andre was dubbed ``Flonaldo''. But
the Norwegians' lone man up front _ Olsen is expected to use a
4-5-1 system _ knows the first-round match against the world
champions June 23 will be different.
	   ``Of course we want to beat them again, but we also know it's
very difficult,'' Tore Andre said. ``Brazil is one of the best
teams in the world, maybe the best.
	   ``So maybe our most important matches are against Morocco and
Scotland. I hope that we'll be in a position that we don't need to
beat Brazil. Then I think it will be easier for us. I don't want to
be in that situation that we have to beat Brazil because that's not
easy.''
	   Tore Andre Flo, who clinched Norway's World Cup berth with a
goal in Azerbaijan, believes his side has some advantages compared
with Brazil.
	   ``I think we're physically stronger and maybe we can fight
better,'' he said. ``Brazil is better technically with the ball. We
can't compare with that.''
	   (sn/jw) 	   
</TEXT>
