<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Hundreds of angry passengers on Sunday
accused the captain of a Ukrainian cruise ship of cutting their
trip short and forcibly taking them back to Ukraine.
	   The passengers, mainly Russians and Ukrainians, threw messages
in plastic bottles begging for help from their consulates to
journalists who approached the ship in small boats.
	   Consular officials from Ukraine, Russia and Azerbaijan visited
the ship and called on passengers to maintain order, Russian
Interfax news agency quoted Olexander Mishchenko, Ukraine's Consul
General in Istanbul, as saying.
	   After restocking food supplies, the ship left Istanbul for
Odessa, Ukraine, the Anatolia news agency said.
	   The passengers sent distress signals to a Turkish coast guard
boat on Saturday as the ship passed through the Dardanelles, a
strait that passes from the Aegean Sea to the Black Sea.
	   The captain of the Taras Shevchenko refused Turkish calls to
stop, saying everything was calm on board, the semi-official
Anatolia news agency reported.
	   ``These people have stolen our money. We want our money back,''
shouted several passengers as they held huge banners reading
``S.O.S. Help''
	   ``We were supposed to go to 12 ports and we did not,'' Vladimir
Kryzhanovskiy said aboard the ship while it was moored in the
international waters off Istanbul.
	   Another Russian, news agency, ITAR-Tass said on Sunday that the
problem surfaced because the tour company which organized the
cruise failed to transfer the money to the shipping company in
time.
