<HEADLINE>
items on Syria, Iraq, Kuwait
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RESTORES dropped words in last graf of Iraq item; Contains

<TEXT>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) _ Syria's Communications Authority and the
Swedish telecommunications giant LM Ericsson AB have signed a dlrs
118 million contract to build a new telephone network, Syrian
newspapers reported Sunday.
	   The government daily Tishrin said the network will initially add
one million new telephone lines as a first stage followed by
another 650,000 lines. The deal was signed Saturday.
	   Ericsson is a world leader in the telecommunications field with
activities in more than 130 countries. It focuses on advanced
systems and products for wired and mobile communications in private
and public networks.
 &UR; ___
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Some 120 Egyptian companies will hold a
week-long trade fair in Baghdad beginning June 16 in a bid to
increase the volume of Egyptian exports to Iraq, the official Iraqi
News Agency reported Sunday.
	   It said goods on show will include household utensils,
electronic and electrical appliances as well as medical and food
stuffs.
	   A five-member Egyptian delegation is currently in Iraq to
prepare for the show, the agency said.
	   U.N. figures show that Egypt has exported dlrs 170 million worth
of goods to Iraq since the start of the U.N. oil-for-food deal
program.
	   Egypt plans to boost its share of Iraqi imports under the
current phase of the six-month deal under which Iraq's import bill
is expected to be in the range of dlrs 3.1 billion instead of dlrs
1.3 billion so far.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The volume of Kuwait's foreign trade last year
fell by 5.5 percent from the previous year, reaching 6.78 billion
dinars (dlrs 22.15 billion), Alrs (dlrs 13.98 billion), down 8.3
percent from 1996.
	   Cars accounted for 9.8 percent of last year's imports, followed
by heavy machinery, spare parts and gold, the newspaper reported.
Other than crude, Kuwait's main exports are petrochemical products.
	   Last year, 13.8 percent of Kuwait's imports came from Japan, and
13.6 came from the United States, according to the statistics.
