<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Danger Airports, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pilots' group names 150 airports with safety problems
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS in graf 5 that Kabul is in Afghanistan; ADDS in graf
9 that Hong Kong has good safety record &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ International airline pilots have listed 150
airports with major safety problems and singled out 15 _ including
San Francisco, Nice and Hong Kong, _ which they believe are
``critically deficient,'' the Sunday Times reported.
	   The newspaper said it had been leaked a copy of a report
compiled at a meeting of the International Federation of Air Line
Pilots' Associations, or Ifalpa, in Montreal, Canada in April.
	   ``If airports and airspaces are listed, it means they have
serious deficiencies, not that they are unsafe,'' the Sunday Times
quoted Ifalpa executive directorCathy Bill as saying.
	   ``There are potential dangers, but there are potential dangers
when you get in any plane.''
	   Other airports in the critically deficient category were:
Wellington in New Zealand; Oslo's Fornebu Airport; Suva in Fiji;
Buenos Aires in Argentina; Leticia, Rio Negro and San Andres in
Colombia; Maiquetia in Venezuela; Nauru, one of the Solomon
Islands; Lagos and Port Harcourt in Nigeria and Kabul in
Afghanistan.
	   The Sunday Times said air crews have complained about landing at
airports in popular tourist destinations, such as Greece, ``to find
inadequate runway lighting and no air-traffic controllers on the
ground.''
	   At Argentina's Mendoza Airport, it said, a pilot reported a
horse on the runway. Another aborted a take-off from Buenos Aires
after seeing children playing in his path.
	   At San Francisco, the Sunday Times said, planes land in pairs on
parallel runways with pilots often relying largely on visual
contact. ``It's been know for pilots to start aiming at the wrong
runway and drift across in front of the other plane,'' it quoted an
unidentified pilot as saying.
	   Nice regularly requests planes to make a circular final approach
using a navigation system that can be inaccurate by hundreds of
feet (meters), the Sunday Times said. Although it has had few
serious accidents, Hong Kong is potentially dangerous because of
the proximity of the runway and parallel taxiway, which can be
hazardous in crosswinds.
	    &UR; ``I am, graf 10 pvs
</TEXT>
