w1539 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Palestinians 1stLd-Writethru   06-07 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu: troop-pullback accord not imminent
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES throughout with fresh Netanyahu comment,
clarifies in graf 9 that two percent would be third redeployment;
ADDS in graf 14 settler work in Old City; CHANGES byline; ADDS
photo tag &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos JRL101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By DAFNA LINZER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Dampening hopes for movement in the stalled
Mideast peace process, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
Sunday said no accord was imminent on a West Bank troop pullback.
	   ``I don't work according to a stopwatch,'' Netanyahu told
reporters after meeting with his Cabinet.
	   The prime minister told his Cabinet that ``it is not possible to
say we are on the verge of an agreement,'' said a statement issued
after the meeting.
	   Later, Netanyahu told reporters: ``We're working toward reaching
an agreement. We're not there yet.''
	   In recent days, speculation had grown that Israel was very close
to a decision on an American initiative _ already accepted by the
Palestinians _ that would leave 40 percent of the West Bank under
full or partial Palestinian control and restrict Jewish settlement
expansion.
	   Under the American plan, as reported last week by Israeli media,
Israel would carry out a second redeployment in three stages over
12 weeks. The Palestinians currently have full control over 3
percent of the West Bank and partial control over another 24
percent.
	   However, Netanyahu said there was no agreement on either a
second or third troop redeployment. The cabinet statement said that
Israel and the Palestinians still did not agree on reciprocal steps
the Palestinians would take in exchange for the Israeli pullbacks.
	   Deputy Defense Minister Silvan Shalom told Israel radio that
U.S.-Israeli discussions were focusing on a third redeployment, and
that the government has a parliamentary majority to approve a
second redeployment as long as the Palestinians fulfill their
obligations.
	   Israeli media reports said American envoy Dennis Ross had asked
the Palestinians to accept some changes in the original U.S.
proposal _ which has been widely reported but never formally
unveiled _ and that Palestinians were rejecting American calls for
a small third redeployment of 2 percent.
	   Palestinian officials reiterated Sunday that they would not
agree to changes in the American initiative now.
	   ``It's not up to (Netanyahu) to redesign the peace process in
his own image,'' said senior Palestinian Cabinet minister Hanan
Ashrawi. ``We are not willing to renegotiate the American
proposal.''
	   The American plan reportedly calls for an Israeli promise not to
expand Jewish settlements in a significant way, and to allow
sections of the PLO founding charter calling for Israel's
destruction to be annulled by vote of the 18-member PLO Executive
Committee rather than the much larger Palestine National Council,
as originally demanded by Israel.
	   But Netanyahu and a Cabinet statement, though, indicated the
charter change was still a sticking point.
	   In Jerusalem's Old City, activists from the Ateret Cohanim
settler group fenced off areas and prepared to go ahead with
excavation work in the city's Muslim quarter, captured from Jordan
in 1967 Mideast war and where the group hopes to establish a Jewish
settlement.
	   Right-wing lawmakers have threatened to bring down Netanyahu's
government if he goes ahead with the pullbacks, and Jewish settler
leaders have stepped up a public campaign against troop
withdrawals.
	   In a sign of bitter right-wing opposition to any pullback,
posters were plastered on walls in downtown Jerusalem overnight,
depicting Netanyahu wearing a keffiyeh _ an Arab headdress _ and
emblazoned with the word ``Liar.'' Similar posters with slain
leader Yitzhak Rabin appeared in Jerusalem months before he was
gunned down by a right-wing extremist for making peace deals with
the Palestinians.
 &UR; pvs-dl 	   
</TEXT>
