<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open-Men's Running, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moya leads in men's final by two sets
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Carlos Moya took the first two sets of the French
Open final Sunday over Alex Corretja, 6-3, 7-5.
	   Corretja took an early lead in the second set, when he broke
Moya to go ahead 2-1. But Moya evened it in the next game. Corretja
held off two set points at 4-5, then evened the set at 5-5.
	   But two games later, Corretja got into trouble again on his
serve at 5-6. This time, he couldn't hold off Moya, and dropped
behind two sets.
	   In the first set, Moya had a relatively easy time breaking
Corretja in the first game, and again in the seventh.
	   The windy conditions _ with gusts of up to 50 kph (31 mph) _ cut
short the long rallies for which the Spaniards are known. Misplays
on serves and volleys caused both men trouble.
	   Whoever wins, Spaniards will have swept both singles events at
the French Open.
	   Arantxa Sanchez Vicario won the women's title Saturday, beating
Monica Seles.
	   Spanish men have won the French Open five times previously, but
have only taken three other Grand Slam titles.
	   Moya already has a major clay court title this year, at Monte
Carlo. Corretja lost to Moya there and in the final of another top
clay court tournament in Hamburg.
	   Moya, seeded 12th, is 28-12 this year. Corretja, seeded 14th,
took a 27-8 record into the final.
	   (sz-jn)	   
