<SLUG> BC-Portugal-Hotel Strike,0223 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lisbon hotel workers target Sheraton in latest strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Staff at the five-star Lisbon Sheraton
hotel began a two-day strike Sunday, the latest action in the
capital's hotel workers' campaign for bonuses during the world's
fair.
	   Strikes were also planned at the Lisbon Ritz and the city's four
Tivoli hotels on June 18, the Federation of Hotel Workers' Unions
said. The Tivoli chain was also targeted for action last month.
	   Federation spokesman Rodolfo Caseiro said about 95 percent of
Sheraton workers stayed away from work, seriously affecting the
hotel's services.
	   Lisbon hotels have jacked up prices by as much as 35 percent to
cash in on the increased demand during the Expo 98 world's fair in
the Portuguese capital, according to the Association of Portuguese
Hotels.
	   Some 8.3 million visitors, almost half of them foreign, are
expected at Expo 98. The fair opened May 22 and will close Sept.
30.
	   Manuel Botelho, secretary-general of the hotel association, said
workers had been awarded a 3 percent pay hike at the start of the
year.
	   Caseiro said workers were being asked to make sacrifices to cope
with the extra work and ``wanted something in return.''
	   ``Salaries are low, the hotels are full, prices and profits are
up,'' Caseiro said. 	   
</TEXT>
