<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Security Council, 1st Ld,0358 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India reiterates no outside mediation in Kashmir dispute
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in grafs 6-8 with background on resolution, India's
accusation it violates international law, background on India's
testing moritorium &QL; 
 &UR; By HEMA SHUKLA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India will not accept outside mediation
to settle its Kashmir dispute with neighboring Pakistan, despite
concern voiced over the volatile issue by the U.N. Security
Council, a foreign ministry official said Sunday.
	   A Security Council resolution, accepted unanimously Saturday by
the 15-member council, called on India and Pakistan to resume
dialogue and find ``mutually acceptable solutions'' to the ``root
causes of those tensions, including Kashmir,'' the disputed
Himalayan territory.
	   That marked the first time in 30 years that the Security Council
officially mentioned Kashmir in a resolution, the foreign ministry
spokesman said on customary condition of anonymity.
	   India and Pakistan have fought three wars since they gained
independence from Britain in 1947 _ two of them over Kashmir, which
is divided between the two countries.
	   Recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan stalled talks and
raised concern about nuclear proliferation.
	   Saturday's resolution also called on India and Pakistan to
refrain from further nuclear tests, halt weapons programs and sign
nuclear control agreements unconditionally. But India reacted
strongly saying the resolution was against the spirit of the U.N.
charter and international law.
	   ``Attempts to coerce members to accede to international treaties
is contrary to the norms of international law,'' a statement by the
Foreign Ministry said. ``The council's authority to decide on
disarmament matters is questionable and not in conformity with the
U.N. charter.''
	   India has already declared a moratorium on further testing and
has offered talks on no first use of nuclear weapons with Pakistan.
But India is unwilling to sign nuclear arms control treaties saying
they are weighed in favor of existing nuclear powers.
	    &UR; The Security, 6th graf 	   
</TEXT>
