</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0446 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sectarian balance hangs on Beirut vote
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout. UPDATES with polls closing, details.
CHANGES overline, byline. TRIMS. Results expected by Tuesday &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BEI101 &QL; 
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Lebanon's first municipal elections in 35
years became a referendum Sunday on Christian-Muslim coexistence in
Beirut and a fight for the leadership of Shiite Muslims in southern
Lebanon.
	   To ensure safe balloting, thousands of troops manned road
intersections and guarded polling stations across the capital and
in the south. No violence was reported, and results, to be
tabulated manually, were not expected until Tuesday.
	   Beirut residents and southerners cast their ballots in 10 hours
of voting, during the third phase of a staggered poll being
conducted over four subsequent Sundays. The first province to vote
was Mount Lebanon on May 24 and the last is the eastern Bekaa
Valley on June 14.
	   Nearly 400,000 people were eligible to vote in Beirut, where
more than 200 candidates contested 24 city council seats whose
sectarian balance became the main campaign issue.
	   In the predominantly Shiite south, 380,000 people were eligible
to vote to fill 1,589 municipal posts. However, the vote there is
being seen as a verdict on who shall lead the 1.2 million Shiites
in a nation of 3.2 million. The militant Iranian-backed Hezbollah
or the pro-Syrian mainstream Amal.
	   Hezbollah on Sunday rotated guerrillas out of front line
positions so they could vote. Elsewhere, wealthy candidates
reportedly flew in some 3,000 Shiites emigrants from Africa to
vote.
	   There was no balloting in the southernmost Israeli-occupied
border zone, home to 200,000 people.
	   In Beirut, whose demography has changed in favor of Muslims
since the last election in 1963, the vote Sunday turned into a test
of the groups' willingness to live together after the devastating
1975-90 civil war.
	   Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Sunni Muslim leaders sought to
allay Christian fears of being smothered by the city's Sunni Muslim
majority.
	   The prime minister, a Sunni moderate, is supporting a
half-Christian, half-Muslim ticket that includes some of his
Christian opponents.
	   Opponents accused the Hariri camp of playing on sectarian fears
to drown out the economic and social issues in Beirut, whose
war-wrecked downtown is undergoing major reconstruction by Hariri,
a billionaire businessman.
	   ``Beirut is for all the Beirutis,'' said Widad Zeino, a Muslim
woman who chose the Hariri-backed ticket, but admitted she knew
none of the candidates she voted for. 	   
</TEXT>
