<HEADLINE>
Cameroon team arrives for World Cup without proper papers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MONTPELLIER, France (AP) _ The Cameroon team arrived for the
World Cup without proper entry papers and without its soccer
federation president, who was held back in the capital Yaounde for
interrogation, a police official said Sunday.
	   The Indomitable Lions landed on a chartered plane in this
southern French city Friday night only to be stopped by airport
police, said a police official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
The official said the players could only present copies of their
entry papers, and not the originals.
	   The squad was held up for a few hours before heading to their
luxurious hotel near Beziers, close to the Mediterranean Sea.
	   The 35-member delegation also arrived without its federation
president, Vincent Onana, who is involved in a judicial case
regarding the sale of 3,000 World Cup tickets.
	   The official notice from World Cup organizers marking Cameroon's
arrival made only a vague mention of the incident, referring simply
to ``administrative formalities'' which delayed the team's journey,
without giving any specifics.
	   The notice, however, did point out that Cameroon is the only
foreign team staying in an accommodation that received ``just one
star from the Michelin guide.'' Still, the team's
castle-turned-hotel includes a recreation room, gym, Jacuzzi and a
sauna.
	   Cameroon plays its first Group B game on Thursday against
Austria. Chile and Italy complete the group.
	   (rac/jw) 	   
</TEXT>
