<HEADLINE>
Israeli defense minister meets King Hussein
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Israel-Palestinians &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Israel's Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
discussed with Jordan's King Hussein efforts to restart Middle East
peacemaking amid new hopes of a settlement.
	   After the meeting, Hussein told Israeli reporters that he was
``comfortable'' and ``optimistic'' of progress in the peace
process, Victor Nahmias, a counselor at the Israeli Embassy, told
The Associated Press.
	   Only Israeli reporters and those assigned by the Jordan's
state-run television and news agency, Petra, were allowed to speak
with Mordechai and Hussein after the meeting.
	   Mordechai later returned to Israel.
	   He had made a similar visit to Egypt last Tuesday to meet with
President Hosni Mubarak.
	   Nahmias said Mordechai is planning to meet with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat soon.
	   He quoted Mordechai as saying that the talks with Hussein and
Mubarak will be followed up with the Palestinians ``so that each
side would cooperate with all the possible means to push the peace
process forward.''
	   Nahmias earlier told AP that Mordechai would brief Hussein on
``the cautious optimism which surfaced recently on the issue of the
second troop deployment in the West Bank.'' He declined to
elaborate.
	   In recent days, speculation had grown that Israel is close to a
decision on an American initiative _ already accepted by the
Palestinian _ that would leave 40 percent of the West Bank under
full or partial Palestinian control and restrict Jewish settlement
expansion.
	   But hopes of immediate progress were somewhat dampened Sunday
when Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said no accord was
imminent on a West Bank troop pullback.
	   Under the U.S. plan, as reported last week by Israeli media,
Israel would withdraw troops in three stages over 12 weeks. The
Palestinian currently have full control over 3 percent of the West
Bank and partial control over another 24 percent.
	   An Israeli statement issued after a Cabinet meeting quoted
Netanyahu as telling his government that ``it is not possible we
are on the verge of an agreement.''
	   Later, Netanyahu told reporters: ``we're working toward reaching
an agreement. We're not there yet.''
