<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-England-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rhodes and Klusener rescue South Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with tea score
 &UR; By IHITHISHAM KAMARDEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) _ England deprived Jonty Rhodes of a
well deserved century but not before the righthander had batted
South Africa to safety in the first cricket test at Edgbaston
Sunday.
	   Rhodes, dismissed for 95, shared a forceful 104-run stand with
Lance Klusener (57) after South Africa had slumped to 224 for
seven.
	   The visitors were eventually bowled out for 343, trailing
England's 462 by 119 runs.
	   England lost opener Mark Butcher (11) but first innings
centurian Mike Atherton and Nasser Hussain took England to 29 for
one at tea on the fourth day.
	   The home side enjoys an overall lead of 148 runs.
	   Atherton is on nine and Hussain is yet to score.
	   A draw now looks a likely result with just four sessions left in
the test and the threat of bad weather on the last day, Monday.
	   Rhodes and Klusener took the attack to England after Angus
Fraser had claimed Shaun Pollock and Mark Boucher in a 12-ball
spell.
	   The pair gradually batted South Africa to safety in a near
two-hour alliance. They first avoided the follow-on and then opened
out after the lunch break.
	   Rhodes and Klusener hammered 15 boundaries between them, four of
them by the latter in eight balls from medium-paceman Dominic Cork
after lunch.
	   Cork, who picked up the first four South African wickets, caught
and bowled Allan Donald to finish with 5-93.
	   Cork, returning to the side after a 16-month absence due to
injuries, claimed his first five-wicket haul since taking 5-116
against Pakistan at Leeds in 1996.
	   Fraser, Cork's new ball partner in the absence of the injured
Darren Gough, finished with 4-103.
	   Rhodes, South Africa's in-form batsman, shared two innings
building stands _ with Daryll Cullinan and then Klusener.
	   Cullinan was dismissed for 78 on the third evening to end a
66-run stand with Rhodes.
	   Rhodes, edged Fraser to 'keeper Alec Stewart after a 229-minute
vigil that yielded eight boundaries and a six.
	   Klusener's entertaining 90-ball knock included 11 fours in 117
minutes. Both Rhodes and Klusener were dismissed in the space of
five balls.
	   (ik)	   
</TEXT>
