<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Prisons </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Beatings, malnutrition common in Egyptian prisons
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Severe malnutrition, skin and respiratory
diseases and torture are widespread in 10 Egyptian prisons, a human
rights group said in a report released Sunday.
	   The Human Rights Center for the Assistance of Prisoners urged
Egyptian authorities to provide better monitoring system for those
prisons.
	   Inmates suffer from severe anemia, tuberculosis and scabies due
to poor hygiene, lack of sun and ventilation, the report said and
charged that prisoners were denied proper medical care.
	   Also, there is evidence of torture from beatings with batons and
electric rods, it said.
	   Naela Gabr, assistant foreign minister for human rights affairs,
refused to comment, saying she had not seen the report yet.
	   The 100-page report says that hopefully public opinion will put
pressure on authorities to change these prisons into ``real
institutions'' for social rehabilitation of prisoners.
	   The Human Rights Center said its report was based on testimonies
of prisoners, detainees, their families and lawyers gathered in the
past year.
	   The 10 prisons listed in the report include four on the
outskirts of the capital, Cairo, and the other six in remote, arid
areas south of Cairo.
	   The report said cells are overcrowded with between 15 and 20
inmates to each cell. Inmates had to drink from buckets of muddy
water and eat rice and beans infested with worms, it said.
	   New inmates are kicked, punched and forced to stand naked for
hours, the report added.
	   The Center said that in the past 12 months, it had sent 441
complaints to the Interior Ministry, the prosecutor general and the
head of the prisons' authority, but received no response.
 &UR; ms-sf/vj
</TEXT>
