<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Spanish Successes,0484 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Spain hopes to ride tide of national sporting success
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CIARAN GILES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHANTILLY, France (AP) _ Riding the wave of major titles in
tennis, motorcycling, soccer and golf, Spain hopes its recent good
sporting fortune will continue at the World Cup.
	   On Sunday, Spaniard Carlos Moya defeated countryman Alex
Corretja in the men's final of the French Open tennis tournament. A
day earlier, Arantxa Sanchez Vicario took the women's trophy.
	   On Saturday, in golf, 18-year-old Sergio Garcia won the British
Amateur Championship. He is expected to be Spain's next great
player, following in the tradition of Seve Ballesteros and Jose
Maria Olazabal.
	   Last month, Alex Criville won the French Grand Prix in the
500-cc motorcycle category. Also in May, soccer powerhouse Real
Madrid won a record seventh European Champions Cup.
	   ``Things seem to be happening for Spain and that gives everyone
that extra bit of confidence,'' defender Rafael Alkorta said.
``They're like premonitions. We are here, too, and hoping to
conquer in France.''
	   In nine World Cup appearances, Spain's best placing was fourth
in 1950. On Saturday it begins its 10th quest when it faces Nigeria
in Group D.
	   Historic underachievers, Spain has had a feeling in recent weeks
of a surge in confidence that _ maybe this year _ this team can
pull it off.
	   ``For talent and technique, we're capable of beating all,'' said
substitute goalkeeper Santiago Canizares. ``We're just need that
moment of fortune which has escaped us in the past.''
	   What's undeniable is that Spain is sailing through its golden
age in international sports.
	   The Spanish national team's last major title was the European
Championship in 1964 when the country was in the midst of the
nearly four-decade Franco dictatorship.
	   Real Madrid won the European Champions Cup in 1966, which drew a
virtual curtain on major international successes for some 20 years.
	   After a featureless 1970s, Spain began to remerge strongly in
the late 1980s and early 1990s.
	   Most notable were Miguel Indurain and Pedro Delgado, who
dominated in cycling with successive triumphs in the Tour de
France. Indurain won five straight times.
	   Then came the massively successful and popular 1992 Olympics in
Barcelona. Spain's soccer team won gold as the country picked up
more than a dozen gold medals, its best performance ever.
	   And, in 1992, FC Barcelona took the European Cup back to Spain.
	   In the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, Spain again won more than its
expected share of medals.
	   ``Things are moving,'' said defender Carlos Aguilera. ``We came
here with hopes and enthusiasm to do something major. Let's hope
it's the beginning of some great celebrations for Spanish fans.''
	   (cg/jw) 	   
</TEXT>
