<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Gene Vote, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss voters reject tough restrictions on genetic engineering
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with final result, reactions, ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By IRENE HARNISCHBERG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ After an emotive campaign, Swiss voters
on Sunday decisively rejected a proposal to outlaw the production
and patenting of genetically modified plants and animals.
	   In the run-up to the vote, Swiss industry and government said
the plan would force a ``draconian'' shutdown on research in
Switzerland, sending highly paid jobs to other countries.
	   By a bigger margin than expected, some 67 percent of voters _
1.25 million people _ threw out the ``The Initiative for the
Protection of Life and the Environment against Genetic
Manipulation.''
	   Not one of Switzerland's 26 cantons (states) voted in favor of
the tough restrictions which it would have imposed.
	   For a proposal to be passed, there has to be both a majority of
cantons and of voters in favor. Only 33 percent, or some 625,000
voters, supported the initiative. Turnout was low, at just over 40
percent.
	   Environmentalists and consumer activists who backed the
initiative say too little is known about the consequences of
letting genetically modified organisms into the food chain.
Tampering with genes poses ``incalculable risks,'' they argued.
	   But the issue of jobs is also highly sensitive to the
resource-poor country of 7 million. Despite Switzerland's small
size, it is a leading force in biotechnology.
	   Basel-based pharmaceutical giants Novartis and Roche rank with
competitors such as Monsanto, of St. Louis, among world leaders in
the field. In Basel itself, some 67 percent of voters threw out the
restrictions.
	   The Swiss pharmaceutical industry, which had warned the
initiative would shackle the companies and academics in their
research efforts in Switzerland, greeted the vote with relief.
	   ``The way is now open for Switzerland's industry and
universities to carry on into the future with their biomedical and
pharmaceutical research,'' Roche said in a statement.
	   ``The people obviously listened to our arguments,'' said
Novartis research chief Paul Herrling.
	   ``For me personally, it means that I can stay in Switzerland,''
said Charles Weissmann, a Zurich-based researcher.
	   Disappointed campaigners for the initiative put a positive spin
on their defeat.
	   ``We'll certainly carry on,'' prominent environmental campaigner
Florianne Koechlin told Swiss radio.
	   The months of debate on the uses and dangers of genetic
engineering had been useful in themselves, Green Party lawmaker
Ruth Gonseth said.
	   The initiative, backed by Switzerland's Green Party and some 60
environmentalist and consumer organizations including the World
Wildlife Fund and Greenpeace, was launched in 1993. The committee
behind the proposal had gathered more than 110,000 signatures
backing it.
	   Sunday's vote against it ranged from some 56 percent in rural,
eastern Appenzell Outer Rhodes to almost 85 percent in the western
Valais and Vaud cantons.
	   The traditionally environment-conscious German-speaking majority
was more favorable to the proposal than the French-speaking
minority, but still delivered a solid no vote.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
