<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Arafat </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinian leader urges Arab summit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat urged Arab
leaders Sunday to hold a summit soon to discuss the faltering
Mideast peace process, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
	   Arab leaders must come together ``not just to face the stalemate
in the peace process, but also ... to renew Arab cooperation,''
Arafat said at a joint news conference with Sudanese President Omar
el-Bashir in Khartoum, the Sudanese capital.
	   His comments were carried by MENA.
	   El-Bashir said Sudan supported the idea of holding a summit.
	   Arafat has been pushing for the summit to pressure Israel to
accept a U.S. proposal for an Israeli troop withdrawal from 13.1
percent of the West Bank.
	   But Arab governments have been unable to agree on a date, an
agenda and participants for a summit.
	   Arafat and el-Bashir are expected to leave for Burkina Faso to
attend a summit Monday of the Organization of African Unity on due
Monday.
 &UR; ms-sf/vj
</TEXT>
