<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru,0550 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid workers try to assess danger of epidemics in Afghanistan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS in 3rd graf that 102 people evacuated; ADDs five grafs at
end, Taliban stopping U.N. food convoy, food blocked in Faisabad &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos FBD101-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By JUDITH INGRAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FAISABAD, Afghanistan (AP) _ Aid workers were trying Sunday to
assess whether serious disease has broken out in remote villages of
northern Afghanistan devastated during last weekend's earthquake.
	   The quake killed up to 4,700 people and injured thousands of
others, according to Afghan authorities. It smashed houses, buried
wells and swallowed crops and livestock.
	   The United Nations and Red Cross have evacuated 102 of the most
seriously injured people from remote villages, and delivered food
to 31 of the approximately 100 damaged and destroyed villages.
	   An outbreak of bloody diarrhea was reported in the Chah-ab
region, about 60 kilometers (38 miles) west of Faisabad, said U.N.
spokesman Rupert Colville. Red Cross helicopters postponed some
emergency food deliveries and set out for the region to investigate
whether the outbreak might signal shigella or dysentery.
	   Both diseases spread quickly when water supplies are polluted.
In addition to destroying wells, the May 30 quake cut channels and
pipes carrying spring water to villages, and landslides
accompanying the quake have filled rivers with mud.
	   Chris Johnson, a water specialist with the Oxfam relief
organization, said that the remoteness of the affected villages,
and the fact that most people appeared to be staying put, could
help stem any serious epidemic.
	   ``What we're all really worried about is the possibility of a
lot of displaced people concentrating,'' Johnson said.
	   About 700 families were reported to be walking from Malwan,
about 35 kilometers (22 miles) west of Faisabad, to Rostaq, a
provincial center about 30 kilometers (20 miles) to the southwest,
Johnson said.
	   Oxfam has sent a representative to try to find out whether the
approximately 4,000 people are on the move because they are hungry
or because they fear further earthquakes. If they are afraid to go
home, aid workers will have to organize camps for them, Johnson
said.
	   Soldiers of the Taliban religious movement, which governs 85
percent of Afghanistan but not this northeastern corner, stopped a
U.N. World Food Program convoy in Ghazni province in southern
Afghanistan two days ago, said Saeed Bashir Muzaffri, the WFP
coordinator in Faisabad.
	   He said the 40-truck convoy was carrying 600 tons of wheat flour
to Hazarajad in central Afghanistan, where people are suffering
from hunger.
	   Bashir said the food was part of an agreement between the
Taliban and the WFP. The Taliban said they were waiting for a
decision from their leadership, Bashir said.
	   More than 100,000 people are suffering from hunger in central
Afghanistan. WFP got permission only recently for one convoy to
cross the front line into central Afghanistan, and this was to have
been the second convoy under the agreement.
	   Even for short distances, logistics were a nightmare. Officials
said 230 tons of wheat were sitting in Faisabad because the road to
the airport five miles (9 kms) away was washed out. 	   
</TEXT>
