<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Officials lower death toll in Germany's high-speed rail crash
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to LOWER death toll, based on new analysis of remains;
RAISES the number of identified victims. CHANGES byline &QL; 
 &UR; By COLLEEN BARRY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ In a sign of just how horrible the
deadly train wreck in Eschede really was, officials on Sunday
lowered the death toll to below 100 based on new analysis of human
remains found at the scene.
	   Officials were not sure exactly how many people died because
many of the bodies were so mutilated. After reporting 97 bodies had
been removed from the wreckage of Wednesday's crash, officials now
believe they have found just 93 or 94 bodies or sets of remains,
said police spokesman Juergen Weinrich.
	   Five other people died in hospitals.
	   The high-speed InterCity Express train was traveling 200
kilometers (125 miles) an hour when it derailed and slammed into
the concrete supports of an overpass. The impact sent 200-300 tons
of concrete crashing down the jackknifed passenger cars.
	   The severity of the disaster has made identifying victims a
painstaking process involving forensic dentists, doctors,
fingerprint experts and photographers.
	   Some bodies and remains are so badly mangled that DNA tests will
have to be ordered, and rescuers at the site were sifting through
loose dirt for personal effects, such as jewelry and wallets, that
could help with identification.
	   So far, 60 bodies have been identified.
	   Recovery efforts at the scene in Eschede, 50 kilometers (35
miles) north of Hanover, were wrapping up Sunday, leaving the
tracks to investigators and repair crews. Workers were preparing
new sections of rail to reopen the Hanover-Hamburg stretch by the
middle of this week.
	   Investigators have pointed to wheel failure as the likely cause
of the derailment, prompting rail officials to pull Germany's 59
original high-speed trains out of service for ultrasound wheel
inspections. Rail delays continued throughout Germany on Sunday.
	   Inspectors said it will take 15 days to complete the tests of
wheels and wheel casings.
	   Federal rail authorities expected to have three first-generation
trains back on the rails at normal top speed of 280 kilometers (175
miles) an hour by Sunday afternoon.
	   Maximum speed on the trains was reduced to 160 kilometers (100
miles) an hour after the accident.
	   Germany's second-generation ICEs, introduced in 1996, have a
different wheel system, and have been left in service.
	   In the small, red-brick village of Eschede, residents laid a
wooden cross Sunday on a road near the crash site and placed potted
flowers on top in memory of the victims.
	   (im-aet-cb) 	   
</TEXT>
