<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections, 4th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sectarian balance hangs on Beirut vote; Shiite split in south
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with 13 arrests; First results expected by Tuesday &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BEI-101 &QL; 
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Lebanon's first municipal elections in 35
years on Sunday became a referendum on Christian-Muslim coexistence
in Beirut and a fight for control over Shiite Muslims, the nation's
largest sect, in southern Lebanon.
	   To ensure safe balloting, thousands of troops backed by armor
manned road intersections and guarded polling stations across the
capital and in the south. Thirteen people were arrested after minor
scuffles, the army said.
	   First firm results are not expected until Tuesday as votes are
counted manually.
