</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> LACK-OF-LOANS-POSES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lack of loans poses threat to many students, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Lack of loans poses threat to many students, NATION &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   PRAPASRI OSATHANONASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CLOSE to 1,000 vocational teachers have been laid off, and the
fate of 50,000 students in private vocational schools throughout
the country is hanging in the balance owing to a lack of education
loans.
	   Veerawat Wannasiri, chairman of the Private Vocational Schools
Association, said that teachers in urban vocational schools were a
prime target for lay-offs as economic conditions deteriorated.
	   There are 335 private vocational schools with 17,000 teaching
staff and 466,000 students in total.
	   He said that admissions to vocational schools had dropped 30 per
cent, which had had a direct effect on the employment of teachers.
	   Several private schools, he said, have had to employ marketing
strategies to attract students, otherwise they would not have
sufficient numbers.
	   Somyos Meeprasertkul, president of Uttradit Technology
Institute, said his school offered an installment plan for new
students so that only 50 per cent of tuition fees was required on
admission.
	   The most suitable way to ensure the survival of private
vocational schools, Veerawat pointed out, is to increase student
loans. At least 50,000 students have indicated that they would like
to take out loans for their education.
	   Throughout the country, education loans are in need of an
additional Bt1.5 billion and within the metropolitan area an
additional Bt800 million.
	   He said the Education Ministry had been informed of the current
difficulties. ''Without timely assistance, half of the 50,000
students may have to leave their schools,'' he said, adding that
most of them were students from the North and Northeast regions.
	   Chatchai Phudyaphorn, chief of the Thai-Tech Group, an umbrella
organisation which comprises several private vocational schools,
said he could not guarantee how long his schools could endure the
current crisis.
	   He added that 30 per cent of them had been forced to shut and
predicted that several others would face the same fate within the
next three years if the government did not give a helping hand.
	   
</TEXT>
