<SLUG> HUNDRES-OF-GAMES-SEIZED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hundreds of games seized in massive Customs swoop, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Hundreds of games seized in massive Customs swoop, NATION &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CUSTOMS officials on Saturday seized 371 smuggled electronic
game machines worth over Bt50 million from Bangkok shops and
department stores, Customs Department Director-General Somchainuk
Engtrakul said.
	   With support from Army personnel and transportation, nearly 100
officials were deployed to department stores throughout Bangkok,
including Seacon Square, where 138 game machines were seized,
Mahboonkrong (36 seized), Siam Jusco (43), and The Mall's
Ngamwongwon branch (84).
	   Owners of the banned machines were fined, although under the law
they could face up to 10 years imprisonment if convicted.
	   Somchainuk said the department would sell the seized games to
countries which allowed the import of the electronic devices.
	   ''Normally we destroy smuggled items, but since the country is
in dire need of funds, we think selling them would help bring in
some money,'' he said.
	   Somchainuk said the government would further restrict game
operators and players by banning young children from playing the
games and forcing operators to limit service hours.
	   ''Most of the games do not enhance any of the children's skills
and only cause social problems,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
