<HEADLINE>
BMA urges entrepreneurial use of seized plots of land, NATION
</HEADLINE>
BMA urges entrepreneurial use of seized plots of land, NATION &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Bangkok Metropolitan Administration plans to ask for the
temporary use of land plots seized by Siam Commercial Bank to turn
them into community markets to help the unemployed, Deputy City
Clerk Kriangsak Lohachala said on Saturday.
	   The properties, whose previous owners could no longer afford to
pay for them, would also be used as utility plazas to serve as
recreational sites for nearby communities as well as being utilised
as sites for the establishment of new businesses to help the
jobless make a living.
	   Kriangsak said it had yet to be decided whether the project,
scheduled to begin in August at the latest, would initially be run
solely by the BMA at its expense or jointly with the bank through a
joint-venture entity.
	   The first land to be selected is a 10-rai plot in Soi Sua Yai
Uthit off Ratchadiphisek Road in Bang Khen district under a
three-year contract which requires that no permanent large
buildings be built on the property.
	   
