<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moya wins French Open final
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Combines urgent series, adds quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By JOCELYN NOVECK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ In an all-Spanish final between clay-court
specialists, Carlos Moya defeated his good friend Alex Corretja
Sunday to win his first Grand Slam title, 6-3, 7-5, 6-3.
	   The match was expected to be more competitive, but Moya was
simply the more versatile player. He served better and dominated
Corretja with his powerful forehand.
	   Corretja seemed never to find his rhythm after being broken in
the first game of the match.
	   ``For two weeks I'll be a king,'' Moya said, referring to the
period before Wimbledon. ``It's an unbelievable feeling to win a
Grand Slam.''
	   Corretja, who earlier in the tournament played a five-hour,
31-minute match over two days that was the longest in the open era,
said he'd gotten tired after the second set.
	   ``It would have been tough, mentally, to go five sets,'' he
said.
	   Even before Sunday's results were known, a Spanish sweep of the
singles titles was assured. Arantxa Sanchez Vicario won the women's
title Saturday in an emotional match against Monica Seles.
	   Moya, seeded 12th, and Corretja, seeded 14th, reached the final
after the men's field was decimated early in the tournament.
Top-seeded Pete Sampras lost in the second round, and No. 2 seed
Petr Korda lost in the first.
	   Moya knocked off the consensus favorite, No. 3 seed Marcelo
Rios, in the quarterfinals. By contrast, Corretja did not meet one
seeded player until the final.
	   In the first set Sunday, Moya gave a hint of things to come by
breaking Corretja in the first game.
	   The windy conditions _ with gusts of up to 50 kph (31 mph) _ cut
short some of the long rallies for which the Spaniards are known.
Misplays on serves and volleys caused both men trouble.
	   Corretja took an early lead in the second set, breaking Moya to
go ahead 2-1. But Moya evened it in the next game. Corretja held
off two set points at 4-5 to even the set at 5-5.
	   Two games later, Corretja got into trouble again on his serve at
5-6. This time, he couldn't hold off the more powerful Moya, and
dropped behind two sets.
	   In the third, with Corretja coming out to serve at 1-4, the
crowd did the wave to try to breathe some new life into the
contest. Corretja did hold serve, then saved a match point to win
his next service game.
	   But serving at 5-3, Moya set up a second match point with an ace
for 40-0. Corretja netted a backhand service return to end the
match. Moya fell on his back in joy, and Corretja hurdled over the
net to congratulate his friend.
	   Soccer star Pele awarded the trophy to Moya, who saluted
Corretja in his acceptance speech. Then both players joined Pele
for an impromptu romp with a soccer ball, heading it back and
forth.
	   Spanish men have won the French Open five times previously, but
have only taken three other Grand Slam titles.
	   Moya, born and raised on island of Majorca, came into view at
last year's Australian Open, where he defeated Boris Becker in the
first round, then reached the final, losing to Sampras.
	   He gets dlrs 650,000 for winning here.
	   This was the 37th all-Spanish final on the men's tour since
1990.
	   (jn)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
