<HEADLINE>
Prachakorn Thai rebels to litigate, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Prachakorn Thai rebels to litigate, NATION &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE group of dissident MPs from the Prachakorn Thai Party will
next week file a lawsuit asking for measures to protect their
rights in case they are eventually ousted from the party, a group
member said on Saturday.
	   Group member Samret Achariyaprasit said the draft of the suit
was complete pending final editing and would be filed towards the
end of next week at the latest.
	   The 12-member group lodged a lawsuit in November last year
calling for a denunciation of a party resolution which was
endangering their party memberships. The Civil Court on Wednesday
accepted the first lawsuit.
	   Samret said all group members would accept the court'Cy join a single party due to their political differences
and acceptance on an individual basis by other parties.
	   Democrat secretary-general Sanan Kachornprasart has maintained
his unclear stance as to whether or not his party would accept all
or any of the dissident members, saying that the final decision
would be made after the current Prachakorn Thai memberships were
finalised by the party in July.
	   Sanan also denied that his party had approached the Chat Pattana
Party to ask it to join the coalition to strengthen the
government's position, saying that the rumour was persisting
because several MPs from both parties had close connections and
used to work together in the past.
	   Prime Minister and Democrat leader Chaun Leekpai refused to
comment on the 12 dissidents' future, saying that it would rest
solely on the Prachakorn Thai decision but he would still accept
them as members of the coalition.
	   
</TEXT>
