</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> CHAVALIT-URGED-BY-PM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chavalit urged by PM not to tarnish the South, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Chavalit urged by PM not to tarnish the South, NATION &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PRIME Minister Chuan Leekpai on Saturday urged opposition leader
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh to keep politics in the South free from
vote-buying.
	   His comment came after Chavalit began his extensive tour of the
Southern provinces, considered to be the stronghold of Chuan's
Democrat party.
	   ''I hope that [Chavalit's] New Aspiration Party will cooperate
and keep it that way,'' said Chuan, whose party has long won almost
all the parliamentary seats in the region, including 47 out of a
possible 52 in the last general election in Nov 1996.
	   NAP leader Chavalit has been using his two-day trip in the
South, which began on Friday and ended on Saturday, to seek more
support from locals to fulfil his party's new strategies, which
have recently been decided upon.
	   The prime minister hopes that no political party will use social
discrimination as a political tactic, a sentiment echoed by
Democrat secretary-general Sanan Kachornprasart, who said he did
not want to see the division of people either by wealth or region
of origin.
	   When asked about the Democrat's reported estimate that it would
win at least 200 parliamentary seats in the next election, Sanan
said the figure would also depend on other factors and public
acceptance of the party in the future.
	   He refused to predict when the next election would take place,
saying that the government still had enough public support.
''Otherwise there would be a lot of people gathering on the
street,'' he quipped.
	   NAP deputy leader Wan Mohammad Noor Matha hit back at Chuan,
saying that the premier's remarks on vote-buying were not
constructive and he did not approve of them.
	   Speaking at an NAP seminar in Songkhla, Wan Noor said Chuan's
remarks had been meant to flatter himself and cast aspersions on
others. ''His words implied that all 125 NAP MP seats had been won
by vote-buying,'' he addded.
	   Claiming that he could prove that some of the Democrat's 123
parliamentary seats had been secured in that way, the Parliament
speaker said a Democrat minister had had to defect to the NAP
because he had not been able to put up with the rampant vote-buying
in the last general election.
	   He admitted that some NAP MPs had got into Parliament on
vote-buying tactics but insisted it was a very low percentage. He
also attacked the ruling coalition party for accepting a Solidarity
Party MP whose canvassers had been jailed for vote-buying as a
Cabinet member despite its denunciation of him in the past.
	   Wan Noor said it would be a well-run race if the NAP succeeded
in gaining at least 20 seats in the South, adding: ''It could
prevent a political monopoly and stop the delusions of a certain
political party.'' Launching a more robust counter-attack, NAP
deputy secretary-general Areephen Utarasin accused Sanan of
attempting to use his connections with a convicted drug trader and
political figure in Narathiwat to build up strength for his party.
	   Areephen, a leading figure in the NAP's Muslim Wadah group, said
he had also learned that Sanan was scheduled to meet the person,
who he said had recently completed a 20-year jail sentence for drug
offences, at his birthday party on June 27 in Narathiwat.
	   ''Sanan's presence at the party would prove my remarks about the
Democrat Party's build-up plans,'' he added.
	   Areephen, a Narathiwat MP, predicted that the NAP would sweep
all three seats in Yala and win two more in Pattani and Narathiwat.
''We will prove that there are some in the South not obsessed with
the Democrat Party,'' he added.
	   Democrat deputy leader Banyat Bantadtan said the government had
no intention of staying in office until 2000 when its four-year
term would expire.
	   He admitted that political competition in smaller
constituencies, in the South or elsewhere, would under the new
Constitution become much more difficult.
	   ''But we have a slight advantage over other parties, having more
experience in these situations,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
