<SLUG> CONVICTS-SENT-TO-FARMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Convicts sent to farms to avoid crowded jails, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Convicts sent to farms to avoid crowded jails, NATION &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   PREECHA SA-ARDSORNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CONVICTS will be sent to work on farms to help solve the problem
of overcrowded prisons across the country, Interior Ministry
spokesman Jakraphan Yomchinda says.
	   ''The Corrections Department still has a vast area to turn into
farmlands. So the ministry has decided that more inmates be
consigned to the farms instead of prisons,'' he said.
	   The scheme is in line with His Majesty the King's initiation of
self-reliance communities, Jakraphan said, adding that it had been
in operation for more than a year.
	   So far the project has covered 26 provinces, mainly Chon Buri,
Nakhon Ratchasima, Nakhon Pathom, Chiang Rai, Nakhon Si Thammarat,
Surin, Chanthaburi, Phatthalung, Prachin Buri, Nakhon Sawan,
Rayong, Pitsanulok, Ratchaburi, Krabi, Petchaburi, Phetchabun,
Trang, Trat, Kalasin, Narathiwat, Sukhothai, Chai Nat, Roi Et, Khon
Kaen, Nan and Buriram.
	   Director of the Corrections Department's vocational investment
division Surang Ekachote said the department had earned at least
Bt10 million from the sale of crops produced at these farms over
the past year.
	   She added that the department planned to send more prisoners to
these farms because at present only 719 inmates were involved in
the programme.
	   ''Compared with the 20,000 inmates we have in jail, there are
only few being sent to work in the fields. Our target is to send
about 1,000 or 1,500 prisoners to the farms,'' she said.
	   The main obstruction in expansion of the project is the lack of
warders, she said.
	   ''We can hardly solve the problem of overcrowding if we do not
have enough warders,'' Surang said.
	   However, the department expects to expand the project to 38
provinces in a short time, she added.
	   According to Surang, convicts who have been selected to join the
programme are those with good records and those who have to serve
one or two more years. These convicts would live on the farms
behind barbed wire.
	   Warders are still needed, even though the department does not
think these well-behaved inmates would escape.
	   ''The best part of it is that most of them already have
agricultural backgrounds, so they can easily adapt themselves to
the new environment. I think the project will benefit the country,
because these inmates will disseminate the self-reliance concept to
people in their communities in the future,'' she said.
	   Basically, however, the project will be used to solve the acute
overcrowding problem, Surang said.
	   ''Normally a 16-metre cell accommodates one prisoner, but now
there are two or four inmates confined in such a miniscule area.
That's why fights break out between them,'' she said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
