<BODY>
<SLUG> ACADEMICS-TELL-GOVT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Academics tell govt to set up safety net, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Academics tell govt to set up safety net, NATION &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   ANAN PAENGNOYASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LEADING academics will next week propose to the government that
it immediately establish an unemployment security fund by using Bt6
billion from the Social Investment Fund (SIF) as part of the effort
to prevent social unrest as a result of growing unemployment as the
economic slump persists.
	   Prof Nikom Chantrawitoon, a labour expert who is drafting the
proposal, said the government cannot cite a tight budget as an
excuse for not providing a social security net for workers who are
struggling to survive the economic crisis.
	   ''The government must provide an unemployment security system
for workers who have been laid off because if the economy does not
bounce back, more than half of the workers who have lost their jobs
will go hungry -- what would happen then?,'' Nikom said.
	   The proposal came after the government has come under growing
criticism for failing to provide workers with a social safety net
and accusations that the government is only helping the rich while
ignoring the plight of the poor.
	   Under the Social Security Act 1990, which does not specify the
time frame for the setting up of the unemployment security fund,
the government can issue a Royal Decree to establish an
unemployment security fund if it is deemed necessary, such as
during a period of economic turmoil.
	   Nikom said that since employers and employees are still reeling
from the economic slump, the government should be able to spend
around Bt6 billion from the total Bt20 billion SIF it received from
the World Bank and Asian Development Bank to help create an
unemployment security fund. Under the proposal, the government,
employees and employers would contribute 0.5-1 per cent of
employees' salaries to the fund.
	   ''Using only Bt6 billion from the SIF fund, the government would
greatly improve the security of workers who helped to build the
country's economy during the boom. There is every reason to enact
this as these workers deserve support and are not to blame for the
current economic mess,'' Nikom said.
	   The idea to immediately establish the fund came at the end of a
seminar attended by government representatives along with
employees' and employers' groups at the Royal Hotel last Sunday.
	   The Labour Ministry estimates that the number of unemployed will
reach two million this year while the Thailand Development Research
Institute came up with an even higher figure. TDRI's recent report
revealed that by the middle of the year, three million people will
be unemployed.
	   Anunsorn Thamchai, an economist who helped to draft the proposal
said that if the six million workers contributed one per cent of
their monthly salary or Bt100 per month, and the government and
employers contributed the same amount, the proposed unemployment
security fund would receive Bt1.8 billion in contributions every
month.
	   If the fund were used to buy the Government Housing Bank's bonds
which pay 11-13 per cent interest, the fund would earn Bt234
million per month or Bt2.8 billion per year.
	   The unemployed (who had contributed to the fund) would receive
Bt3,000 per month to help pay their living expenses. ''The reason
behind giving them such a tiny amount of money is to create an
incentive for them to look for jobs otherwise they may want to live
on social security for the rest of their lives and take advantage
of others,'' Ansorn said.
	   The unemployed (who had not contributed to the fund) would be
supported through another Bt450 million fund to provide each of
them with a food coupon worth Bt50 per day each for a six-month
period.
	   In addition, a Bt500 million fund would be used to support the
unemployed who wish to start a new business, providing each of them
with around Bt10,000-50,000. Another Bt1 billion would be used for
those who have been unemployed for more than six months who would
be entitled to apply for a Bt100,000 loan with a two per cent
interest rate over a 20-year period.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
