<SLUG> POLICE-CRACK-DOWN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police crack down on World Cup gambling, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Police crack down on World Cup gambling, NATION &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   PONGSAK BAI-NGERNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AS THE World Cup fast approaches, the police are clamping down
on soccer gambling operators who are set to earn an estimated Bt30
billion during the four-week competition.
	   Like an epidemic, gambling fever has spread everywhere -- from
private firms to government offices and from schools to local
banks. With such huge stakes being bet, the notorious underground
lottery bookmakers have temporary shifted their focus towards
soccer.
	   Thai Farmers' Research Centre estimates that the 64-soccer
matches would generate as much as Bt30 billion in Thailand as each
Bangkok gambler will spend an average of Bt38,880, 35 per cent more
than during the 1994 World Cup.
	   Central Investigation Bureau deputy commissioner Pol Maj Gen
Chat Kuldilok, acknowledged that lots of lottery bookmakers had
taken up soccer gambling because more money is being spent on this
sport.
	   He said that Police chief Gen Pracha Promnok had instructed the
police to set up a central unit to crack down on the
gambling-related businesses. ''We have asked police in each
jurisdiction to come up with a list of people who are involved in
the gambling business,'' Chat said.
	   Furthermore, the Police Department has also sought cooperation
from banks, the Education Ministry, University Affairs Ministry and
the mass media to help in monitoring the situation.
	   Chat said he had requested the banks check on ''suspicious''
transfers of large amounts of money among their customers.
	   ''As for the media, we plead with them not to tacitly support
gambling. I know some of them even suggest betting prices,'' he
said referring to newspaper columns which provide insights into
soccer matches.
	   But Chat confessed that clamping down on such an illegal
business was a daunting task.
	   Education Ministry deputy permanent secretary Surat Silapanand
concurred that soccer gambling is very popular among students,
especially as there are now web sites available for gambling on the
Internet.
	   He said he had circulated letters to directors,
secretary-generals and rectors of schools, colleges and
universities asking them to prevent the illegal activities among
youngsters.
	   ''Teachers should pay more attention to students during the
World Cup. They have to take special care of their computers,
preventing children from using the Internet to bet on soccer
games,'' he said.
	   Surat said if schools have problems in dealing with mischievous
students, they can call the Student Patrol Division on 215-3537,
215-8221 or 282-1758 at the Police Department or contact any police
station.
	   Education Ministry's Student Patrol Division Nikhom Charumanee,
said that many students would sneak out of their classrooms to
wander around shopping centres, computer game shops and theatres to
bet on soccer matches.
	   He called on all sides to help children to divert their
attention from gambling. ''Student patrols are not enough to deal
with these students, we would like to ask shops to cooperate with
us as well,'' he said.
	   An interview with an underground lottery bookmaker, who prefers
to be called Wad, said that most gamblers are 45 years old or less.
''They are office workers and executives in private companies. They
normally opt to bet Bt10,000 on each match,'' Wad said.
	   To deal with an increasing number of customers, Wad said he had
expanded his network by setting up a special pub. However, he said
the pub is exclusivelyfor ''loyal'' customers.
	   ''We have already screened our customers, so there shouldn't be
any problem. We bet just for fun and most of our clients are
financially sound. We are not destroying the country, or the
cashflow in Thailand,'' he said.
	   Another bookmaker, Suwanna (real name withheld), said that her
customers had urged her to receive bets on the 1998 World Cup.
	   ''I'm not really familiar with it but my son, who is an ardent
soccer fan, will take care of it,'' she said.
	   For her, the difference between underground lottery and soccer
betting is that customers can still negotiate the odds in football
but not in the underground lottery.
	   ''Underground lotteries have standard odds and customers will
win if they bet on the right numbers. But when you bet on soccer,
your chance is based on the ability of the players of the team on
which you are betting,'' she said.
	   Although she received soccer bets, she said she had to be
careful in screening customers to avoid those who would fail to pay
once they had lost.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
