<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0641 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kosovo militants call for more help to fight Serb forces
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with reports of shelling in 8th graf, ADDS quote from
refugees in Montenegro in 16th and 17th graf &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Kosovo's rebel army appealed Sunday
for more ethnic Albanians to join them and ``fight for freedom''
from the Serbian forces waging a fierce offensive against them.
	   The Serbs' latest offensive in the secessionist province has
left at least 50 people dead, 200 missing and thousands fleeing
their destroyed villages, according to ethnic Albanian officials.
	   Serbian officials have characterized the flights as a response
to increasing attacks by the Kosovo Liberation Army, a loosely
formed group of self-described freedom fighters who claim to have
wrested control of about 40 percent of the province from Serbia.
	   ``Come to strengthen our troops against the enemy artillery and
enemy infantry,'' read the KLA's statement, published Sunday in the
Albanian-language daily Koha Ditore in Kosovo's capital Pristina.
	   It appealed ``for the last time'' to ethnic Albanian political
organizations to give up their policy of a peaceful struggle for
independence and join the KLA.
	   Kosovo's ethnic Albanians make up about 90 percent of the 2.2
million people living in the province, and most want to secede from
Serbia and Yugoslavia. Western powers are against any border change
in the volatile Balkans but want the Serbs to cease their offensive
and give Kosovo the autonomy taken away by Serbia in 1989 as a way
to suppress the independence movement.
	   Serbs vow never to allow the secession of Kosovo, which has many
ancient Orthodox monasteries and which they consider to be the
cradle of their history.
	   Albanian TV said the Serbs shelled at least two Kosovo villages
Sunday. It also said ethnic Albanian militants blew up the police
headquarters in Ratkoc, and amid fierce fighting between the two
sides all the Serb residents and police had fled.
	   Federal authorities in Yugoslavia, which comprises Serbia and
Montenegro, on Sunday escorted more than 40 diplomats into the
besieged region. The state-run Serbian Radio Television and the
official Tanjug news agency were the only news organizations
allowed on the trip.
	   The offensive that began in late May has stirred increasing
international concern and fears of a wider war in the Balkans. The
United States is expected to reimpose sanctions against Serbia
after a White House meeting on Monday.
	   On Sunday, Pope John Paul II called on the world to act against
violence and repression in Kosovo.
	   ``In Kosovo, violent options, repression and the flight of
peoples must not leave the international community inert,'' he said
at the Vatican. The violence, the pope said, ``recalls the tragic
recent history of the Balkans.''
	   The exodus of more than 10,000 Albanians into Albania last week,
and another 7,000 to 10,000 into Montenegro, also has stirred worry
in the West.
	   In Germany, Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel told the Welt am
Sonntag newspaper his country is afraid of being flooded with
refugees, so it is working with international refugee agencies to
assist them in the Balkans.
	   About 400,000 ethnic Albanians already live in Germany.
	   Refugees in Montenegro said they walked for three days through
woods before reaching safety. Most are women, children and elderly
men.
	   ``There were 30 soldiers in the barracks who took turns when
they beat us,'' Dervis Alimehaj, of the Kosovo town of Decane, told
Associated Press Television, showing the bruises on his body.
``They also threatened us by putting knives under our throats,'' he
said in the town of Plav in eastern Montenegro, where more than
1,000 refugees have gathered.
</TEXT>
