<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Reporter Fined </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reporter fined dlrs 2,950 in libel case
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ A court on Sunday fined a weekly newspaper
reporter the equivalent of dlrs 2,950 for libeling a former adviser
to the trade minister, but acquitted the newspaper's chief editor.
	   Judge Mohamed Khalifa also ordered the reporter, Moemen Ahmed,
and editor Mustafa Bakry to pay 500 Egyptian pounds (dlrs 147) in
compensation to Rushdy Saqr. They can appeal the sentence.
	   Saqr had filed the libel suit in 1997 in response to articles in
the Al-Osboa newspaper that alleged he was corrupt.
	   The case is the latest by Egyptian government officials or
former officials targeting journalists
	   At present four reporters are serving jail sentences for libel
cases that press groups in Egypt and abroad have condemned as a
setback for press freedom.
 &UR; str-ms/vj
