<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France tries to prevent conflict from spreading
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. NEW with Air France meeting with employees, Djibouti
flight, taxi protest, train strike threat, conflict likely to enter
second week. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PAR104/105 &QL; 
 &UR; By DEBORAH SEWARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ With the World Cup three days away, Air France
officials held an emergency meeting Sunday with ground personnel
and flight attendants in an effort to keep a crippling pilots' from
spreading.
	   The strike seemed certain to enter its second week Monday, as no
new talks between the pilots and Air France have been set.
	   Air France has said it will take three days for service to
return to normal once the strike ends, meaning the walkout was sure
to disrupt the soccer championship, which begins Wednesday.
	   Meanwhile, the company met Sunday with ground personnel and
flight attendants, who have expressed concern they have been left
out of salary talks between Air France and the pilots.
	   One of the unions representing ground personnel, the
Communist-backed General Labor Confederation (CGT), warned Friday
of a ``spread of the conflict'' unless Air France included other
airline workers in the talks.
	   Both the pilots and Air France were under pressure to end the
strike from the government, worried about France's image and
embarrassed by the walkout.
	   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said Saturday the government was
prepared to intervene but no concrete proposals emerged.
	   Talks between Air France and the pilots were suspended Saturday
after the pilots walked out of negotiations.
	   Public support for the pilots appeared lukewarm.
	   A poll in Sunday's edition of Le Journal du Dimanche showed just
38 percent of those surveyed were sympathetic to the strike. In
contrast, 79 percent of those polled backed truckers in a strike
last fall.
	   The poll was carried out Friday by the CSA polling agency among
1,004 people. No margin of error was given.
	   The strike has inconvenienced thousands, including foreigners
fleeing the violence in Eritrea who had hoped to return to Europe
on an Air France flight from Djibouti that was canceled Sunday.
	   Air France is the official World Cup carrier and is committed to
transporting the teams from one venue to another.
	   The pilots are protesting pay cuts planned by Air France in
order to save 500 million francs (dlrs 83 million) a year the
company says is needed to modernize the company.
	   The obstacles to an agreement are proposed salary reductions and
a plan to give pilots stock in exchange for the pay cut, as well as
a two-tier pay scale in which younger pilots earn less.
	   Only about 25 percent of Air France's flights were expected to
take off Monday.
	   Trains were expected to run on schedule Monday after strikes
disrupted service this weekend. Trains conductors have threatened a
walkout Wednesday.
	   Taxi drivers in Paris planned demonstrations Monday to protest
the killing of a taxi driver last week.
	   (dgs-parf)	   
</TEXT>
