<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Elections, 4th Ld,0130 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sectarian balance hangs on Beirut vote
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in 2nd graf with 13 arrests. Results expected by
Tuesday &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BEI101 &QL; 
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Lebanon's first municipal elections in 35
years became a referendum Sunday on Christian-Muslim coexistence in
Beirut and a fight for the leadership of Shiite Muslims in southern
Lebanon.
	   To ensure safe balloting, thousands of troops manned road
intersections and guarded polling stations across the capital and
in the south. Thirteen people were arrested after minor scuffles,
the army said.
	   No violence was reported, and results, to be tabulated manually,
were not expected until Tuesday.
	    &UR; Beirut residents, 3rd graf 	   
</TEXT>
