<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Balkans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kosovo crisis could derail high-level Balkan meeting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PATRICK QUINN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Fighting in Kosovo and Yugoslavia's
refusal to allow what it considers foreign meddling in the troubled
province could derail a meeting of Balkan foreign ministers.
	   Foreign Ministers from Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia,
Romania and Yugoslavia will attend the two-day meeting that starts
Monday, while Bosnia and Slovenia have sent deputy ministers. They
are nominally to discuss economic cooperation and the region's
communications, energy and transportation infrastructure.
	   But sources close to the foreign ministers said Sunday that
Yugoslavia's refusal to allow any reference to the
Albanian-dominated secessionist Serbian province of Kosovo could
torpedo a joint declaration calling for closer regional
cooperation.
	   Meeting along the shores of the Bosphorous, which separates
Europe from Asia, the foreign ministers will also set the agenda
for a meeting of their heads of state next fall.
	   Yugoslavia has made it clear that it will not accept any
reference to Kosovo in the Istanbul Declaration, something the
other ministers say they will not swallow.
	   Traditional rivals Greece and Turkey have put aside their own
thorny disputes and are working together to try and convince the
Yugoslavs to accept some kind of compromise in order not to
diminish the importance of the meeting.
	   Diplomatic sources said it would be difficult to contain
Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadezhda Mikhailova or Greek Foreign
Minister Theodoros Pangalos should Yugoslavia refuse. Albanian
Foreign Minister Pascal Milo will also have difficulty accepting
any kind of joint declaration with no reference to Kosovo.
	   ``Kosovo can't be ignored, there has to be some reference,''
said one Turkish diplomatic source.
	   A possible compromise would be a reference calling for the
return of thousands of Kosovo Albanians who have fled across the
border during the recent fighting.
	   It would be qualified with a call for a solution inside the the
current borders of Yugoslavia.
	   ``The problem with that is that you can't water down the
statement to the point where it is meatless,'' said another
diplomat.
	   Kosovo's ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the 2.2 million
inhabitants, and most demand to secede from Serbia and Yugoslavia.
Western powers are against any change of borders in the volatile
Balkans, but want the Serbs to cease their offensive and give
Kosovo the autonomy taken away by Serbia in 1989 as a way to
suppress the independence movement.
	   ``Where there is a will there is a way,'' said one senior
Turkish diplomatic official.
 &UR; (sf)	   
</TEXT>
