<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Newspaper </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jerusalem Post publisher resigns, paper announces major management
</HEADLINE>
reshuffle &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ One month after merging with a major
competitor, The Jerusalem Post announced the resignation Sunday of
its publisher and president, Norman Spector and a major management
reshuffle.
	   Sources at the Post said Spector's resignation, which he said
was for personal reasons, came as a surprise. The former Canadian
ambassador to Israel took over the Post, owned by the Canada-based
Hollinger International chain, last year.
	   Post editor Jeff Barak said Spector would return to Canada as a
columnist for The Globe and Mail, a national Canadian daily,
``writing on provincial, national and Middle East affairs.''
	   In an effort to reduce administrative costs and look for new
revenue opportunities, the Post entered into a strategic alliance
with one of its key competitors last month, the Israel-based
Jerusalem Report, a bi-monthly newsmagazine which covers Israel and
Jewish affairs. As part of the deal, Spector was to become chief
executive officer of the magazine but his resignation will affect
that post as well.
	   Barak said Spector would be replaced by a four-man team which
will report directly to F. David Radler, chairman of the board of
the Post.
	   The new management structure will include publisher Tom Rose of
Hollinger, Paul Staszewinski, who moves from vice president of
finance and administration to president of the newspaper and vice
chairmen Avi Golan, who has served as executive vice president and
Hirsh Goodman.
	   Goodman, who established The Jerusalem Report eight years ago,
returned to the Post, where he once worked as a defense
correspondent, as part of the deal between the two publications.
	   Spector's resignation was to take effect immediately.
 &UR; dl
</TEXT>
