w1697 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 3rdLd-Writethru   06-07 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb police beat protesters in Pristina; KLA seeks more help
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES and RECASTS with police crackdown, discovery of
mutilated corpse; trims. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serbian police used clubs Sunday to
beat and disperse protesters at a rally for Kosovo's independence,
and ethnic Albanian officials said dozens of people were injured.
	   Dozens of plainclothes policemen joined about 100 in uniforms to
violently break up the demonstration by ethnic Albanians in
Pristina, capital of the secessionist province of Serbia where
ethnic Albanians comprise a 9-to-1 majority.
	   At least half a dozen ralliers received serious body injuries,
according to the Kosovo Information Center.
	   The unexpected violence in Pristina came as Serbian forces
pressed their fierce offensive against militants in western Kosovo,
where shelling reportedly continued Sunday.
	   The stepped-up campaign launched in late May has left at least
50 people dead and 200 missing, according to ethnic Albanian
officials, in addition to sending thousands fleeing from ruined
villages.
	   Pristina itself has remained largely free of violence despite
months of clashes this year between Serbs trying to assert their
control over the province and the self-described Kosovo Liberation
Army, made up of ethnic Albanians who want to drive Serb
``occupiers'' out.
	   But on Sunday, seemingly without warning, police charged the
approximately 1,000 protesters gathered for the 57th consecutive
daily rally against the Serbs' violent rule in Kosovo.
	   One protester could be seen bleeding in the street after he was
hit in the head by a policeman's gun butt and then kicked
repeatedly.
	   It was the first beating of protesters in Kosovo since March,
when thousands of ethnic Albanians were attacked for protesting
against an earlier crackdown by government forces on the KLA.
	   Albanian TV in Tirana reported that the Serbs shelled at least
two Kosovo villages Sunday. It also said ethnic Albanian militants
blew up the police headquarters in Ratkoc, and amid fierce fighting
between the two sides all the Serb residents and police had fled.
	   It is not clear how much of a setback the Serb offensive has
dealt Kosovo's clandestine rebel army, which claims to control some
40 percent of the southern province of Yugoslavia's Republic of
Serbia, and which enjoys growing popularity.
	   The Kosovo Liberation Army appealed in a statement published
Sunday in the newspaper Koha Ditore for more ethnic Albanians to
join them and ``fight for freedom'' from Serbian forces.
	   ``Come to strengthen our troops against the enemy artillery and
enemy infantry,'' the KLA statement said.
	   It appealed ``for the last time'' to ethnic Albanian political
organizations to give up their policy of a peaceful struggle for
independence and join the KLA.
	   Western powers oppose Kosovo's bid for independence, fearing the
consequences of another border change in the volatile Balkans, but
want the Serbs to cease their offensive and give Kosovo the
autonomy taken away by Serbia in 1989.
	   The offensive that began in late May has stirred increasing
international concern and fears of igniting a wider war in the
Balkans. The United States is expected to reimpose sanctions
against Serbia after a White House meeting on Monday.
	   On Sunday, Pope John Paul II called on the world to act against
violence and repression in Kosovo.
	   ``Not far from us, in Kosovo, violent options, repression and
the flight of peoples must not leave the international community
inert,'' he said at the Vatican. The violence, the pope said,
``recalls the tragic recent history of the Balkans.''
	   The exodus of more than 10,000 Albanians into Albania last week,
and another 7,000 to 10,000 into the neighboring Yugoslav republic
of Montenegro, also has stirred worry in the West.
	   In Germany, Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel told the Welt am
Sonntag newspaper his country is afraid of being flooded with
refugees, so it is working with international refugee agencies to
assist them in the Balkans. About 400,000 ethnic Albanians already
live in Germany.
	   While the United Nations has condemned the Serbs for atrocities,
the Serbs say the KLA has forced entire Serb villages to flee and
is brutally targeting Serb civilians and pro-Serb Albanians. On
Sunday, the pro-Serb Media Center reported the discovery of the
mutilated corpse of an Albanian loyal to federal authorities, with
head and both arms cut off.
	   (ih/ms/dc)
</TEXT>
