<HEADLINE>
Antismoking campaign, JAKARTA POST
</HEADLINE>
Antismoking campaign, JAKARTA POST &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   JAKARTA POST
   INDONESIA
   ENGLISH
   MAHADEVAN WISWANATHANASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   It was like a whiff of fresh air to note that an awareness is
being created by antismoking campaigners to cleanse the body and
mind of this nation's tobacco smokers, both the active and the
passive ones.
	   News reports say that this country has the dubious distinction
of being the world's fourth-least aware smokers, after China, the
United States and Japan, when it comes to realizing the bad effects
of smoking on a person's health.
	   Strike while the iron is hot says an English proverb. The recent
change in this nation's political arena, which was considered,
hitherto, as unimaginable, has proven the strength and power of the
united students and an awakened mass. Why don't we harness the
energy of the same students to achieve a cleaner, healthier and
more beautifully green country, that has been a land of our dreams.
	   With the country reeling under an unprecedented economic crisis,
time could not be more opportune to educate the masses of this
nation about the need to stop smoking, thereby improving the
quality of their life, as also that of their near and dear ones.
The students could help spread the message in rural areas too.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 JAKARTA POST all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
