<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Scots say underdog role a boost against Brazil
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-REMY-DE-PROVENCE, France (AP) _ Scotland relishes the role
of underdog against defending champion Brazil and will be spurred
on by doubters in the World Cup opener Wednesday, manager Craig
Brown said Sunday.
	   ``The persecution complex suits the Scots. The mentality we have
is 'we will show them,''' Brown said before Scotland's workout
Sunday in their south of France training venue, a session that was
closed to the news media.
	   Scotland and Brazil meet Wednesday at Stade de France outside
Paris in the opening game of the month-long France 98 tournament.
Brown acknowledged that the Scots will have to be in peak form, but
said he was sure they would be up to the challenge.
	   The Scots are accustomed to ``pressure games and big crowds. My
team will not be unnerved by Brazil,'' the manager declared.
	   Striker Gordon Durie said he knew exactly what Scotland must do
to overcome Brazil: ``We must go for the throat.''
	   The Rangers star was on the bench eight years ago when Brazil
beat Scotland 1-0 in the World Cup in Italy. Many people have
written off the Scots at this World Cup, and Durie said he wants to
prove them wrong by pulling off what would be a huge upset.
	   ``We have to attack Brazil in much the same way as they will try
and do,'' Durie said. ``If we sit in and try and defend, then they
have the players who can destroy you.''
	   While stressing that Scotland aimed to disprove the odds, Brown
acknowledged that Brazil was a strong bet to advance to the latter
stages of the World Cup, along with Germany and Spain. Of host
France, he said, ``they will be under a lot of pressure.''
	   Along with Brazil, Scotland has Group A first-round matches with
Morocco and Norway.
	   (dm)
</TEXT>
