<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-English Open, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Westwood wins second straight European event; takes English Open
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS leads, adds more quotes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WARE, England (AP) _ Lee Westwood, encouraged by his new-found
putting stroke, won his second straight European Tour event when he
closed the English Open with a 4-under-par 68 for a two-stroke
victory Sunday.
	   The Englishman, a 25-year-old Ryder Cup player, finished
17-under at 271. Olle Karlsson of Sweden, who shot a 66, and
Australian Greg Chalmers, who had a 69, wound up tied for second
after 72 holes at the Marriott Hanbury Manor course.
	   ``It's just clicked recently and I'm holing a few putts, which I
wasn't before,'' said Westwood, whose win also moved him atop the
European money list for the first time in his career.
	   ``Life couldn't be better right now,'' he added. ``I'm just on a
wave and trying to ride it.''
	   Westwood, who won last week in the TPC of Europe in Hamburg,
Germany, is 40-under par in his last eight rounds and playing as
well as anyone in the world right now.
	   He left immediately after the win to fly to the United States
for this week's Buick Classic in Rye, New York, and the U.S. Open
the following week in San Francisco.
	   ``I set goals and it's nice to keep ticking them off,'' he said.
``The next one has to be a major. I seem to be playing well enough
and I'm looking forward to what is sure to be a tough and tight
course (in the U.S. Open).
	   ``That suits me, I think. Mind you, I think most courses are
suiting me at the moment.''
	   Westwood, who led Chalmers by one stroke after three rounds,
trailed him by two with 11 holes to play on Sunday. But he birdied
four of the next six holes, dropped a 30-foot par-saving putt on
the 16th, and then got home safely on the final two holes.
	   On Saturday, the Australian lefthander shot a course-record
11-under par 61 to get into contention.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
