<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Romania arrives with Colombia on its mind
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VIOREL URMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALBI, France (AP) _ Tired but upbeat, the Romanian national team
arrived in France on Sunday for the World Cup, still focusing on
its opener against Colombia.
	   ``We're in a good mood. Our players are well prepared and
optimistic, despite some problems which we hope we'll be able to
fix before our first game against Colombia'' on June 15, coach
Anghel Iordanescu said.
	   The 22-man side and officials looked tired and upset after the
flight from Bucharest to Toulouse, and their longer-than-expected
bus rid to Albi, 80 kilometers (50 miles) away.
	   Romanian captain and playmaker Gheorghe Hagi waved away
reporters.
	   ``Just leave me alone,'' he said. ``I won't make any statements
for now.''
	   La Reserve Hotel welcomed the team with colorful posters in both
French and Romanian, while stringent security measures failed to
keep three local dogs from roaming the premises and between
reporters' legs.
	   The team arrived without Atletico Madrid defender Daniel Prodan,
who was unable to recover from a left knee injury last month.
	   ``We don't have an adequate substitute for the central marking
defender, which was Prodan's role,'' said Adalbert Kassai, general
secretary of the Romanian Football Federation.
	   He would not say who would replace Prodan, but Iordanescu has
called up Cristian Dulca, who plays for Rapid Bucharest in the
Romanian first division.
	   ``Our first game against Colombia will be the most important for
us. The Colombian players want to avenge their loss, 3-1, at the
'94 World Cup and will spare no efforts to do that,'' Kassai said.
	   All the other players were reported fit, he said.
</TEXT>
