<SLUG> BC-Iran-Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tehran mayor goes on trial for corruption, pleads not guilty
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with court rejecting mayor's
objection; raises context; background on possible sentence &QL; 
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Tehran mayor Gholamhossein Karbaschi went on
trial for corruption Sunday, and suffered his first setback when
the court refused to declare itself incompetent to hear the case.
	   Judge Gholamhossein Mohseni-Ejaei ruled that Karbaschi, 44, had
no basis to claim that his court lacked the jurisdiction to hear
the case, Iranian state-run television reported.
	   Mohseni said that Karbaschi's argument ``is unacceptable to the
court'' the television reported, adding that the judge will explain
his ruling in detail in the next session, scheduled for Thursday.
	   Appearing before the Imam Khomeini Judiciary Complex in central
Tehran, Karbaschi also pleaded innocent and said the charges of
embezzlement, fraud and mismanagement of public funds against him
were trumped up.
	   Karbaschi's trial is widely seen as an attempt by the hard-line
elements in the ruling clergy to topple key officials allied with
moderate Iranian President Mohammad Khatami who took office in
August. Karbaschi had run Khatami's election campaign.
	   ``All of the charges against me are absolute lies. I don't
accept any of them,'' the black-bearded Karbaschi told the judge, a
cleric, wearing a white turban and brown robe.
	   The judge said: ``I'm not happy today to try a manager of the
Islamic Republic of Iran, but we know that the law should be
implemented and there are no exceptions. Nobody is above the law.''
	   Karbaschi's arrest on April 4 brought into open a long-simmering
power struggle between moderate and hard-line clerics. Karbaschi
was freed April 15 after a series of street protests turned
violent, forcing Iran's spiritual leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei,
considered an ally of hard-liners, to intervene.
	   The case has gripped the nation, generating hundreds of stories
for and against the popular mayor.
	   If convicted, Karbaschi faces up to 10 years in jail, a fine and
a ban from holding any government post. The trial is expected to
last for weeks.
	   Karbaschi arrived in the packed courtroom in his trademark dark
blue suit, flanked by his two lawyers, looking relaxed and
confident.
	   As he left the courthouse, about 200 supporters greeted him with
shouts of ``Long live Karbaschi.'' Another 50, standing nearby,
yelled, ``Death to Karbaschi.''
	   Some 130 citizens attended the trial _ those who arrived early _
along with about 70 journalists. A crowd of several hundred watched
the four-hour hearing on two 28-inch television screens outside the
courthouse, where extra police were assigned to keep order.
	   Karbaschi's troubles began when Chief Judge Ayatollah Mohammad
Yazdi, a hard-liner, accused him of involvement in a wide-ranging
corruption scandal and ordered him detained.
	   In the scandal, more than a dozen senior municipality officials
have been put on trial since last October. Most were accused of _
or sentenced for _ issuing building permits in restricted zones in
return for large kickbacks.
	   As mayor since 1989, Karbaschi has improved the capital's
appearance as well as public services for its 8 million residents.
	   Despite his popularity, he has critics who consider his
administration high-handed and who dislike him for taxing the
powerful merchants who make up the hard-liners' power base.
	   The mayor went back to work days after his release. But
according to Iranian law, he is not allowed to work while the trial
is under way.
 &UR; av-fsa-ggl-sf/vj
</TEXT>
