<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Britain </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin and Blair hold telephone talks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin spoke to British Prime
Minister Tony Blair by telephone Sunday evening to discuss a number
of issues, including the situation in southeast Asia and the unrest
in Kosovo.
	   According to the Kremlin press service, Yeltsin and Blair agreed
that a coordinated effort by the leading states of the world was
needed to curtail the spread of nuclear weapons following a spate
of underground tests by India and Pakistan.
	   The two leaders also agreed that it was necessary to quickly
halt the conflict in the Serbian region of Kosovo, but without
breaching Yugoslavia's territorial integrity, the press service
said.
	   Russia on Thursday proposed that a United Nations force in
Macedonia be used to monitor the border between neighboring Albania
and Kosovo. The U.N. peacekeeping force was sent to Macedonia in
1992 to prevent the spread of ethnic conflicts in other parts of
the former Yugoslavia.
	   (jai)
</TEXT>
