<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moya wins French Open final
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with color, Corretja quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By JOCELYN NOVECK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Carlos Moya captured the French Open on Sunday,
beating friend, compatriot and fellow clay-court specialist Alex
Corretja 6-3, 7-5, 6-3 for his first Grand Slam title.
	   ``For two weeks I'll be a king,'' Moya said, referring to the
period before Wimbledon. ``It's an unbelievable feeling to win a
Grand Slam.''
	   The all-Spanish final was expected to be more competitive, but
Moya was simply the more versatile player. He served better and
dominated with his powerful forehand. Corretja seemed unable to
find his rhythm after being broken in the opening game.
	   Corretja, who earlier in the tournament played a 5-hour,
31-minute match over two days that was the longest in the open era,
said he'd gotten tired after the second set.
	   ``It would have been tough, mentally, to go five sets,'' he
said.
	   But he appeared to be a happy loser.
	   ``I'm really happy because I've been playing well for the last
two weeks, and I lost to a really good friend of mine,'' he
explained.
	   Even before Sunday's outcome was known, a Spanish sweep of the
singles titles was assured. Arantxa Sanchez Vicario won the women's
title Saturday, beating Monica Seles.
	   On the winning point, a netted backhand, Moya fell on his back
in joy. Corretja hurdled the net to congratulate his friend, who
earned dlrs 650,000 for the victory.
	   Soccer great Pele awarded the trophy to Moya, who saluted
Corretja in his acceptance speech. Then both players joined Pele
for an impromptu romp with a soccer ball, heading it back and
forth.
	   That light moment got one of the biggest rounds of applause of
the day, certainly more than the sometimes tedious tennis.
	   Spanish men have won the French Open five times previously, but
have taken only three other Grand Slam titles.
	   Moya, born and raised on island of Majorca, came into view at
last year's Australian Open, where he defeated Boris Becker in the
first round, then reached the final, losing to Pete Sampras.
	   Moya, seeded 12th, and Corretja, seeded 14th, reached the final
after the men's field was decimated early in the tournament.
Top-seeded Sampras lost in the second round and No. 2 seed Petr
Korda lost in the first.
	   Moya knocked off the consensus favorite, No. 3 seed Marcelo
Rios, in the quarterfinals. Corretja did not meet one seeded player
until the final.
	   The windy conditions _ with gusts of up to 50 kph (31 mph) _ cut
short some of the long rallies for which the Spaniards are known.
Misplays on serves and volleys caused both men trouble.
	   Corretja took an early lead in the second set, when he broke
Moya to go ahead 2-1. But Moya evened it in the next game. Corretja
held off two set points at 4-5 to even the set at 5-5.
	   Two games later, Corretja got into trouble again on his serve at
5-6. This time, he couldn't hold off the more powerful Moya, and
dropped behind two sets.
	   In the third, with Corretja coming out to serve at 1-4, the
crowd did the wave to try to breathe life into the match. Corretja
did hold serve, then saved a match point to win his next service
game.
	   But serving at 5-3, Moya set up a second match point with an ace
for 40-0. Corretja netted a backhand service return to end the
match.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Tennis-French Open, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
