<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup,0870 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Players, FIFA candidates are confident as games, election loom
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOSEPH WHITE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The imminent start of the World Cup has brought
brave talk of victory, not only from coaches and players but mostly
from the two candidates vying to win election Monday to the
presidency of FIFA.
	   While coaches lined up their teams on practice fields throughout
France and in neighboring countries, Lennart Johansson arrayed his
team of supporters _ including Brazilian superstar Pele _ to make
one last pitch for votes in his heated battle against Sepp Blatter
for FIFA's top office.
	   ``I'm very confident of victory,'' Johansson, the Swedish
president of the UEFA, said Sunday. ``See what kind of people are
surrounding me.''
	   Both Johansson and Blatter, FIFA's general secretary and choice
of outgoing president Joao Havelange, claim they have enough votes
to carry the day. Right up to the end, there are still contentious
issues to solve, including the method the 192 national federations
will use to cast their votes.
	   Johansson is promising to make FIFA more open, responsive and
democratic, a contrast to the dictatorial style associated with
Havelange. Blatter's platform is much the same, but his ties to
Havelange and late decision to enter the race has Johansson
accusing his opponent of jumping on the bandwagon.
	   ``His program is a bad copy of mine,'' Johansson said.
	   All will be decided Monday at the FIFA Congress, and the outcome
will be greeted with relief for those anxious to shift the focus
from the politicians to players, assuming all is not disrupted by
the continuing Air France strike.
	   The work stoppage entered its seventh day Sunday and the airline
has said it would take three days for service to return to normal
once the matter was settled. That means even if pilots and
management came to an agreement Monday, it would spill over into
the start of the World Cup on Wednesday.
	   With the opening nearing, more teams arrived to settle into
various posh castle-turned-hotel accommodations throughout France.
Germany, one of the favorites and brimming with confidence after a
series of good performances in exhibition games, took up residence
in the hills above the Mediterranean resort of Nice and practiced
late in the day.
	   ``We are on a very, very good direction,'' captain Juergen
Klinsmann said before the team boarded the plane in Frankfurt.
	   Meanwhile, Scotland, faced with the dubious honor of playing
world champion Brazil in the tournament's opening game, was making
the most of its underdog role as it worked out at
Saint-Remy-De-Provence.
	   ``The persecution complex suits the Scots,'' manager Craig Brown
said. ``The mentality we have is, `We will show them.' ''
	   Even Tunisia, which is expected to go home after three games
perhaps without even a point, was sounding an upbeat note.
Preparing for their arrival Monday, the North Africans sounded
eager to make some noise in their June 15 opener against England.
	   ``We are ready for you,'' Tunisia's Polish coach Henry
Kasperczak said, reflecting on a 4-0 victory Saturday over
non-qualifier Wales in Tunis. ``We are fit and ready.''
	   Not ready is famed Dutch striker Dennis Bergkamp, who could miss
the Netherlands' first two games with a hamstring injury. Coach
Guus Hiddink said Sunday that Bergkamp, who has scored 33 goals for
the national team, is taking longer than expected to recover.
	   Ivan Zamorano, half of Chile's high-scoring front line, sat out
his team's Sunday practice with a minor knee injury. The team
doctor said the 31-year-old forward was suffering from a
``contusion to the right leg meniscus'' and would be ready for
Chile's World Cup debut against Italy on Thursday.
	   ``There is no reason for concern,'' doctor Eugenio Valdecantos
said. ``This a very minor, easy-to-cure injury.''
	   In England, coach Glenn Hoddle promised a crackdown on alcohol
use by his squad. Three players _ Paul Gascoigne, Teddy Sheringham
and Darren Anderton _ have made headlines recently over their
behavior at nightclubs. Excessive drinking was cited as one of the
reasons Gascoigne was out of shape and dropped from the team.
	   ``I am not going to ban alcohol, and on occasion the players
will be allowed a couple of beers or a glass of wine. But only at
the right times,'' Hoddle told the Independent on Sunday newspaper.
	   ``In England that's what we have had all through our careers _
get in the players' bar and have a beer. But that's detrimental and
won't happen in France.''
	   Actually, the big story in France on Sunday was the final of the
French Open tennis tournament, the final major sporting event
before the calendar clears for the World Cup. The Spanish team,
training in Chantilly, was keenly interested in the outcome, given
that Spaniards Carlos Moya and Alex Corretja were contesting the
title at Roland Garros.
	   ``Things seem to be happening for Spain and that gives everyone
that extra bit of confidence,'' defender Rafael Alkorta said.
``They're like premonitions. We are here, too, and hoping to
conquer in France.''
</TEXT>
