<SLUG> SURPRISINGLY-SWEDEN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Surprisingly Sweden has lots to offer, JAKARTA POST
</HEADLINE>
Surprisingly Sweden has lots to offer, JAKARTA POST &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   JAKARTA POST
   INDONESIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Alfred Nobel, Greta Garbo, Ingmar Bergman, Ingrid Bergman, ABBA
-- while most people know that these people are Europeans, fewer
probably are aware they hail from Sweden.
	   Despite its comparative low-profile, the country and its people
have a lot to offer.
	   Sweden is the third largest country in Europe. It has 100,000
lakes and half the land is covered by forests. The country's
coastline is 2,700 kilometers long, from Norway in the west to
Finland in the east. Its land borders run 2,200 km.
	   Waterways are intimately associated with Swedish culture,
recreation, businesses and defense policy. Today, water remains an
essential transportation route, and such Swedish goods as motor
vehicles, iron ore pellets and forest products are exported by sea.
Crude oil -- which Sweden lacks entirely -- is among the many
imports that arrive by sea.
	   Sweden's three largest cities -- Stockholm, Goteborg and Malmo
-- are located on the coast.
	   While traditional Swedish maritime sectors such as shipbuilding,
merchant shipping and fishing have declined in importance,
recreational fishing still thrives and anyone is allowed to fish
along the coast. Passenger vessels shuttle tourists and Swedish
vacationers between urban centers and the thousands of archipelago
islands that dot the coastline.
	   Swedish cities have been largely shaped by nature, rather than
taming and dominating it. Stockholm, the capital, occupies hilly
terrain and a number of islands. For most of its existence it was
an impoverished little town, despite Swedish monarchs having
resided there for more than four centuries. About 1.6 million of
Sweden's population of 8.8 million currently live in Stockholm.
	   Two of Sweden's best-known older cities, Uppsala and Lund, grew
up around universities that were founded in the 15th century and
17th century respectively. Many cities and towns experienced a
growth surge in the early years of the industrial era, when many of
today's leading Swedish engineering companies were founded.
	   Many a Swede's paradise is a little red cottage in the country.
Many of them realize this dream; there are 700,000 second homes in
Sweden.
	   The Swedish love of nature is facilitated by the right of common
access, an ancient custom that entitles everyone to roam freely in
forests and meadows without asking the owner's permission. They may
also pick flowers, berries and mushrooms, provided they show
consideration to the environment.
	   Swedish agriculture today is entirely mechanized and very
efficient, employing less than 3 percent of the labor force. Tight
environmental standards have forced farmers to limit their use of
environmentally hazardous substances. Strict regulations on animal
and food imports have helped wipe out certain diseases entirely.
	   Swedes celebrate many special occasions close to nature; for
example, on Walpurgis Eve, April 30, they light bonfires outdoors
and groups of choral singers sing a number of songs which are the
same everywhere in the country; it is said that this evening marks
the end of winter and the coming of spring. On Midsummer Eve, they
desert their cities and join festivities in the countryside. At
Christmas, their homes are decorated with spruce trees, lingonberry
branches and hyacinths.
	   A northern mountain range covers nearly one-fourth of Sweden's
geographic area: a unique wilderness landscape of treeless massifs,
pristine rivers and vast forests. Sweden is bigger than California
and nearly as big as Spain. The warm Gulf Stream in the Atlantic
makes the whole country habitable but only 15 percent of the
population lives in its northern half.
	   With a climate characterized by long dark winters, and short
intensive summers when the sun never sets -- the midnight sun --
the north is not especially suited to agriculture but is cherished
by people who travel there to hike and enjoy the silence. Sweden's
northern mountain fauna includes such protected animals as wolves,
wolverines and bears.
	   The original inhabitants of northern Sweden were the Sami
people, previously called Lapps, who were pushed back as the
Swedish majority population expanded its settlements. About 17,000
Sami live in Sweden but only 3,000 still make their living from
traditional reindeer husbandry. Their herds, about 300,000 animals
in all, graze across large tracts.
	   Swedes consume a lot of energy. About half their electricity is
based on hydroelectric power, primarily from northern rivers, but
Parliament has decided that for environmental reasons, four wild
and scenic rivers in the north will not be harnessed.
	   The rest of Sweden's electricity comes mainly from nuclear
reactors, whose continued use is being widely questioned by the
public. After an advisory referendum in 1980, Parliament decided
that the use of nuclear power should be phased out by 2010.
	   In February 1997 the Inter-Party Agreement on energy policy
concluded that the two reactors in Barseback are to be
decommissioned in 1998 and 2001 respectively. A final year for the
total phasing out of nuclear power has not been determined.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 JAKARTA POST all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
