<HEADLINE>
Israeli defense minister raises hope for restarting peace talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Israel-Palestinians &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to UPDATE with elaboration of quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By JAMAL HALABY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Israel's Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
Sunday offered hope for restarting the Middle East peace process,
saying his government colleagues will ``soon'' reach an agreement
on pulling back troops from West Bank.
	   After talks with Jordan's King Hussein, Mordechai told reporters
that he hoped ``Israel and the Palestinians will find a way to move
forward with the peace process.''
	   Hussein, speaking alongside Mordechai, said: ``After hearing
Defense Minister Mordechai I am more optimistic.''
	   Only Israeli reporters and those working for Jordan's state-run
television and news agency, Petra, were allowed at the impromptu
news conference. The Associated Press later obtained a transcript
of their comments.
	   The comments by Mordechai, a dove in the Israeli government,
tempered Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's statement earlier
Sunday that no accord was imminent on a West Bank troop pullback.
	   Netanyahu told reporters after a Cabinet meeting: ``We're
working toward reaching an agreement. We're not there yet.''
	   Mordechai, however, told the Israeli and Jordanian reporters
that his government will ``soon'' reach an agreement on troops
pullout from West Bank.
	   Asked if that would happen in days or weeks, Mordechai again
said ``soon,'' and refused to elaborate.
	   ``There are some projects and some ideas that need to be
encouraged by everyone _ in the Israeli side, in the Palestinian
side,'' he said. Mordechai returned to Israel later Sunday.
	   In recent days, speculation had grown that Israel is close to a
decision on an American initiative _ already accepted by the
Palestinian _ that would leave 40 percent of the West Bank under
full or partial Palestinian control and restrict Jewish settlement
expansion.
	   Under the U.S. plan, as reported last week by Israeli media,
Israel would withdraw troops in three stages over 12 weeks. The
Palestinian currently have full control over 3 percent of the West
Bank and partial control over another 24 percent.
	   Mordechai had made a similar visit to Egypt last Tuesday to meet
with President Hosni Mubarak, and is planning to meet with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat soon, Victor Nahmias, a counselor
at the Israeli Embassy, said.
	   Nahmias earlier said that Mordechai's mission was to brief
Hussein on ``the cautious optimism which surfaced recently on the
issue of the second troop deployment in the West Bank.'' He
declined to elaborate.
