<BODY>
<SLUG> SWEDEN'S-PRODUCTION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sweden's production, policies, relations, JAKARTA POST
</HEADLINE>
Sweden's production, policies, relations, JAKARTA POST &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   JAKARTA POST
   INDONESIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The end of the Cold War and political division of Europe has
changed Sweden's foreign and security policy situation. It has
created new opportunities to participate in the process of
integration and in the emerging new security structure in Europe.
	   Sweden has been a full member of the European Union (EU) since
January 1995. It now participates in the EU decision-making
process.
	   Following dramatic changes in Central and Eastern Europe, Sweden
has taken part in the task of securing democracy and new security
structures for the continent as a whole.
	   Sweden has also taken up observer status in the Western European
Union. It also actively participates in the Partnership For Peace
and has contributed forces to UNPROFOR and IFOR/SFOR in the former
Yugoslavia. It is a member of the UN Security Council for
1997/1999.
	   A strong and independent national defense system is a
fundamental element of Sweden's security policy. Its armed forces
is based on general male conscription.
	   Other basic elements are the promotion of human rights,
democracy and the rule of law, international disarmament and
protection of the environment. There is far-reaching cooperation
between the Nordic countries in social welfare, cultural affairs
and a joint labor market.
	   Industry and economy
	   At the beginning of this century, Sweden was a largely agrarian
economy, and one of the poorest nations in Europe. However, a rich
domestic supply of iron ore, timber and water power, as well as
skilled engineers and a qualified workforce has transformed Sweden
into a modern welfare state.
	   Despite its modest share of GDP (21 percent in 1996),
manufacturing still plays a dominant role in Swedish exports. In
1996, manufactured products accounted for more than 80 percent of
total exports. Large international companies such as Ericsson, ABB,
Electrolux, Volvo and Saab account for nearly 60 percent of
employment in manufacturing and more than 80 percent of exports of
manufactured products.
	   About 460,000 small and medium sized enterprises, mostly in
services and oriented toward the home market, employ close to 1.4
million people. Although these enterprises generally remain small,
they account for most of the net job creation in the private sector
since the mid 1980s.
	   Iron ore mines are situated in the far north, with production
mainly being exported. Cheap hydropower was a major factor in
Sweden's industrial development.
	   Sweden is also a relatively important exporter of technically
more sophisticated productions like telecommunications equipment,
specialized machinery and motor vehicles. Science-based products --
for example pharmaceuticals -- account for about 10 percent of
manufacturing value added.
	   Sweden's vast forests of spruce, pine and other softwoods supply
a highly developed sawmill, pulp, paper and finished wood product
industry. And despite high domestic consumption, Sweden exports
about 60 percent of its forest products.
	   Indonesia
	   The bilateral relations between Sweden and Indonesia are broad
and deep, shown not least by the fact that Sweden was one of the
first European countries to open an Embassy in Indonesia after the
proclamation of the Republic of Indonesia.
	   Today, relations can be said to emphasize trade, with most of
the major Swedish companies represented in Jakarta doing business.
	   Sweden is now offering a larger development cooperation
assistance, which has, in some ways, been concentrated on the
forestry sector. Since Sweden, like Indonesia, has large forest
resources, there is a large scope for cooperation in this area.
Other cooperation projects include air traffic safety, medical
registration systems and quality management developments, among
others.
	   Within the area of cultural exchange, much has been achieved but
much, of course, remains to be done. The interest for Indonesia in
Sweden is growing, shown not in the least by the growing numbers of
Swedish tourists that each year visit Indonesia.
	   Although small, the number of Swedish students studying Bahasa
Indonesia is growing by each year. The Swedish Lund University has
an exchange program with Gadjah Mada University, and Swedish
students can be found in Yogyakarta as well as in Jakarta and other
places. The number Indonesian students to Sweden, enrolling in
everything from master courses to short-term courses, is also
growing.
	   
</TEXT>
