<BODY>
<SLUG> CELEBRATION-NATIONAL-DAY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Celebration of a national day, JAKARTA POST
</HEADLINE>
Celebration of a national day, JAKARTA POST &QL; 
   June 06, 1998
   JAKARTA POST
   INDONESIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   In every country, the people's pride can be especially expressed
during national day celebrations. While the national days of
countries like Indonesia, the Philippines or the U.S. are fairly
common knowledge, the founding of those of other countries might
need to be given in an abridged history lesson for us to understand
the origins of national days.
	   In Sweden, one of the first dates to be held in esteem was
November 6, 1632, observing the death of King Gustavus Adolphus,
who died during the Battle of Lutzen against German Imperial
forces, though this is no longer celebrated.
	   At around the turn of the century (1900), many Swedes wanted
fervently to have a national day, like other countries. But this
enthusiasm was postponed with the advent of WW I.
	   What originally resulted, from private initiatives, was Swedish
Flag Day, which was celebrated on June 6. This date was chosen
because Gustav Vasa, who delivered Sweden from a Middle Ages forced
union with Denmark, was elected King of Sweden on June 6, 1523. It
was chosen because on that date in 1809 the first Swedish
Constitution was signed.
	   For the first time, on June 6, 1916, the king of Sweden
presented the flag to various corporations in a parade at Stockholm
Stadium. The presentation was subsequently moved to Skansen
open-air museum. This was continued until 1983, when June 6
officially became Swedish National Day.
	   And even though this is Sweden's national day, the country does
not take a holiday for it. Instead, holding flag presentations and
ceremonial speeches in many cases is done in the evening. The royal
presentation of flags is still held at Skansen.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 JAKARTA POST all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
