<HEADLINE>
U.S. Commerce Secretary seeks Ulster-American business ties
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ U.S. Commerce Secretary William
Daley arrived Sunday at the start of a five-day push for new
business links between America and the north of Ireland following a
peace agreement in this British province.
	   ``This region has much to offer _ an educated, skilled and
motivated workforce,'' said Daley, before heading for dinner with
Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam at Hillsborough
Castle, her official residence southwest of Belfast.
	   The visit by Daly with a delegation of executives from 17 top
U.S. companies comes two weeks after voters in Northern Ireland and
the Irish Republic ratified the Belfast peace accord.
	   ``President Clinton has been committed to the peace process and
asked me to lead this mission because he believes, as I do, that
peace and economic opportunity go hand in hand,'' Daley said.
	   The trip will highlight the already substantial U.S. business
interests in Northern Ireland and the five counties of the Irish
Republic that border the British-ruled province.
	   Daley made no specific promises of new investment in advance of
consultations with business leaders in Belfast on Monday, Northern
Ireland's second-largest city of Londonderry on Tuesday, and the
western Irish port of Sligo on Wednesday.
	   On Thursday he is scheduled to meet Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern in Dublin before flying back to Washington.
	   Among the delegation are Richard James, European regional
president of The Boeing Co. of Seattle; James Smith, president of
of the industrial group of Fluor Daniel Inc. of Irvine, Calif.;
William Farley, chairman of Fruit of the Loom Inc. of Chicago;
Eugene Murphy, vice chairman of General Electric Co. of Fairfield,
Conn.; John Mitchell, vice chairman of Motorola Inc. of Schaumberg,
Ill.; Arnold Donald, senior vice president of Monsanto Co. of St.
Louis; and Henry McKinnell, president of Pfizer Pharmaceuticals of
New York City.
	   On Monday Daley will address council members at Belfast City
Hall and speak to employees at a factory of the Canadian-owned
aerospace firm Short Brothers PLC, Northern Ireland's largest
private-sector employer and a Boeing subcontractor.
	   (sp-mj)
</TEXT>
