<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Acropolis Rally, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First day of Acropolis rally ends, favorite forced out
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: updates with first day of competition, RECASTS throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Finland's two-time winner of the world
driving championships, Tommi Makinen, was forced out of the
Acropolis Auto Rally on the opening day Sunday when his Mitsubishi
developed electrical problems.
	   Driving a Mitsubishi Lancer Evo V, Makinen with co-driver Risto
Mannisenmaki, was dropped from the rally when he did not show up on
time for the second special stage because of the technical problem.
	   Later, organizers had to cancel that stage when thousands of
spectators clogged the roads, making fast driving impossible.
	   Of the 103 cars which set off from the foot of the Athens
Acropolis hill, 80 are still in the gruelling rally.
	   Unlike previous races, this year's rally will end in the western
town of Delphi. The ancient Greeks considered Delphi to be the
center of the world. It was also the site of the oracle that
ancient Greeks consulted for prophesies of the future.
	   Britain's Richard Burns and co-driver Robert Reid in a
Mitsubishi Carisma GT lead the list of participants at the end of
the first day with one hour, 18 minutes, 28 seconds. They are only
two seconds ahead of Colin McRae, also of Britain, with co-driver
Nicky Grist in a Subaru Impreza WRC.
	   Spain's Carlos Sainz, presently at the top of the general
classification for the world driving championship and last year's
Acropolis rally winner, was in sixth place with 59 minutes 37.7.
	   Drivers will cover 1,036 kilometers (647 miles) through Greece's
best and worst roads in the three-day rally.
