<SLUG> DIOKNO-DOUBTS-SURPLUS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Diokno Doubts Surplus by June Jan. to Mid-May BOP Surplus at $2.05B, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Diokno Doubts Surplus by June Jan. to Mid-May BOP Surplus at $2.05B, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Jenniffer D. BaldivinoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Incoming Budget Secretary Benjamin Diokno said yesterday it was
unlikely the Ramos administration would deliver on its promise to
post a P1-billion fiscal surplus in the first half of the year.
	   ``It is highly unlikely that we will have surplus by turnover,''
said Diokno.
	   He said he doubted the current deficit in the country's fiscal
position could be reversed less than a month before the new
government takes over.
	   President-elect Joseph Estrada is set to take over from
President Fidel Ramos on June 30.
	   Despite a P2-billion surplus posted in April, the country's
fiscal position was still at a deficit of about P11.37 billion.
	   Finance officials have blamed the deficit on poor revenue
collections and incentives granted to investors.
	   Diokno, a budget undersecretary under former President Corazon
Aquino, said there was nothing alarming over a fiscal deficit
during an economic slowdown, ``but we should make up for it.''
	   ``If it is temporary, that's okay.But you should not sustain
it,'' he said.
	   Diokno said a long-running deficit would send signals that
government was incapable of spending within its means.
	   He said any fiscal deficit should only represent 2% of gross
domestic product for the economy to stay healthy.
	   Acting Budget Secretary Emilia Boncodin said earlier a
P5-billion fiscal surplus by the end of the year was hardly
possible unless imports recovered or some state-owned assets were
immediately privatized.
	   A ranking finance official had said a P50-billion deficit that
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) predicted appeared
inevitable, particularly with the incoming administration's plan to
scrap the gross receipts and documentary stamp taxes.
	   In its latest review, the IMF said it did not see any progress
in tax administration and recommended that government tighten its
watch on the country's biggest taxpayers.
	   Collections from the country's top 10 taxpayers dropped 33.5% to
P2.113 billion in the first quarter.
	   The finance official said the Estrada administration would lose
as much as P26 billion should it push through with plans to remove
these taxes.
	   Diokno said, however, he would focus on spending and prioritize
government financing rather than on taxation.
	   ``It is a wrong strategy to focus on taxation to reduce the
deficit,'' he said.
	   He said there was a need for government to rationalize
incentives given to firms registered with the Board of Investments
(BOI).
	   ``The sooner we rationalize (the incentives), the better. We
should reduce them and make them universally applicable rather than
have the BOI and government-chosen winners enjoy the incentives,''
he said.
	   The country's balance of payments (BOP), meanwhile, climbed to a
surplus of $2.05 billion from January to the middle of May.
	   The country's BOP surplus was $1.8 billion by mid-April.
	   Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas Managing Director Amando Tetangco
Jr. said the improvement in the current account and inflows from
loans and investments propped up the country's external account.
	   The central bank borrowed $750 million in a club loan and
government raised $492 million from its 10-year global bond in the
period.
	   Tetangco did not give any other details, other than to say the
central bank did not buy any dollars in the foreign exchange market
between the end of April to May 14. 
</TEXT>
