<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-FIFA Congress,0547 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIFA takes time off presidential race to honor soccer greats
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SLOBODAN LEKIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ FIFA opened its pre-World Cup Congress Sunday, a
two-day session that will be highlighted by the election of its
first new president in 24 years.
	   A tight vote is expected Monday in the bitter race between
Lennart Johansson, the head of Europe's UEFA union, and Sepp
Blatter, FIFA's general secretary, over who will succeed Brazilian
industrialist Joao Havelange as the head of the world's largest
sports federation.
	   ``I'm confident going into tomorrow morning into this
election,'' Blatter said.
	   Johansson, holding a separate press conference, matched him
almost word for word.
	   `I'm very confident of victory,'' said Johansson, showing off a
long table of supporters from each continent, including Brazil's
Pele. ``See what kind of people are surrounding me.''
	   As the anticipated heightened, the world soccer governing body
took time off from its war of succession to honor a dozen great
players and promoters with its own Order of Merit.
	   Those awarded included Germany's former international Gerd
Muller, described as ``one of the deadliest goal-poachers in
football history;'' Brazil's stellar goalkeeper Gilmar, ``the last
line of defense (in the 1950s-60s) where all the spotlight was on
the forwards;'' and U.S. women's national team forward Michelle
Akers, ``an outstanding representative of women's football.''
	   Also awarded FIFA's top medal was South African President Nelson
Mandela for his role in reintegrating his country into world soccer
after an absence from 1976 to 1992 because of its apartheid
policies.
	   ``He is being honored for his tremendous contribution to
reuniting football in his country in the post-apartheid period,''
declared Havelange.
	   The glitzy ceremony appeared designed to cover up deep rifts
that have appeared within FIFA in the past 2 1/2 months, after
Blatter announced he would challenge Johansson for the presidency.
	   While no future president is expected to repeat Havelange's
quarter-century tenure, the ballot may prove crucial in determining
the direction in which world soccer will develop well into the next
century.
	   Johansson has accused Blatter of being Havelange's hand-picked
choice for the top position, while Blatter's camp has denounced
Johansson as a puppet of the powerful German and Italian soccer
federations.
	   The two men are estimated to have spent well over a million
dollars on the rowdy campaign, an unprecedented amount for a
traditionally tightlipped organization where behind-the-scenes
deals are the usual modus operandi.
	   Most analysts agree that Johansson would move to break the
stranglehold that Europe and the South America have maintained over
FIFA by giving African and Asian nations a more prominent voice.
However, Blatter has vowed to bring the World Cup to Africa in
2006.
	   After it admits four new members during its current congress,
the 94-year-old association will number 202 national committees,
more than the United Nations, the International Olympic Committee,
or any other world body.
	   (sl)
</TEXT>
