<SLUG> BAD-LOANS-HURTING-RP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bad Loans Hurting RP Banks, Says Fitch IBCA, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Bad Loans Hurting RP Banks, Says Fitch IBCA, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   International rating agency Fitch IBCA yesterday said the rising
number of bad loans would affect the earnings outlook of the top
five Philippine banks.
	   Fitch IBCA said non-performing loans would rise beyond 10% of
the total commercial loans by the end of the year, up from 6.7% at
the end of February and 4.7% at the end of 1997.
	   ``Rising non-performing loans and the need to raise higher
specific loan loss provisions will have an adverse affect on bank
profitability,'' Fitch IBCA said in a statement where it assigned
its ratings on the top five banks.
	   It added banks would tend to tighten their credit due to
concerns over problem loans specially foreign currency loans and
loans to the slumping property sector.
	   Fitch, however, said the major banks can weather the financial
crisis given their high capital base and wide net interest margins,
mainly due to large pools of low cost deposit funds.
	   It gave a C/D rating to Bank of the Philippine Islands, Far East
Bank and Trust Co., Metropolitan Bank and Trust Co., and Philippine
Commercial International Bank.
	   ``Fitch IBCA's ratings reflect the banks' deteriorating
operating environment rather than the fundamentals of the banks
themselves,'' it said.
	   Fitch, however, gave a lower rating of D/E to Philippine
National Bank.
	   ``The high interest rate environment has taken a greater toll on
its borrowers than has been the experience of other large banks. It
also appears that PNB maintains exposures to most of the troubled
high profile corporates, and should endure a deterioration from a
lower asset quality base,'' Fitch added.
	   
</TEXT>
