<HEADLINE>
Tehran mayor goes on trial for corruption, pleads not guilty
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with court rejecting mayor's objection;
raises context; background on possible sentence &QL; 
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Tehran Mayor Gholamhossein Karbaschi went on
trial for corruption Sunday, and suffered his first setback when
the court refused to declare itself incompetent to hear the case.
	   Judge Gholamhossein Mohseni-Ejaei ruled that Karbaschi, 44, had
no basis to claim that the court lacked the jurisdiction to hear
the case, Iranian state-run television reported.
	   Mohseni will explain his ruling in detail in the next session,
scheduled for Thursday, the television reported.
	   Appearing before a packed courtroom at the Imam Khomeini
Judiciary Complex in central Tehran, Karbaschi also pleaded
innocent and said the charges of embezzlement, fraud and
mismanagement of public funds against him were trumped up.
	   Karbaschi's trial is widely seen as an attempt by the hard-line
elements in the ruling clergy to topple key officials allied with
moderate Iranian President Mohammad Khatami, who took office in
August. Karbaschi had run Khatami's election campaign.
	   ``All of the charges against me are absolute lies. I don't
accept any of them,'' the black-bearded Karbaschi told the judge, a
cleric, wearing a white turban and brown robe.
	   Karbaschi's arrest on April 4 revealed a long-simmering power
struggle between moderate and hard-line clerics. Karbaschi was
freed April 15 after a series of street protests turned violent,
forcing Iran's spiritual leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, considered
an ally of hard-liners, to intervene.
	   The case has gripped the nation, generating hundreds of stories
for and against the popular mayor.
	   If convicted, Karbaschi faces up to 10 years in jail, a fine and
a ban from holding any government post. The trial is expected to
last for weeks.
	   As Karbaschi left the courthouse, about 200 supporters greeted
him with shouts of ``Long live Karbaschi.'' Another 50, standing
nearby, yelled, ``Death to Karbaschi.''
	   Some 130 citizens attended the trial, along with about 70
journalists. A crowd of several hundred watched the four-hour
hearing on two television screens outside the courthouse, where
extra police were assigned to keep order.
	   Karbaschi's troubles began when Chief Judge Ayatollah Mohammad
Yazdi, a hard-liner, accused him of involvement in a wide-ranging
corruption scandal and ordered him detained.
	   More than a dozen senior municipality officials have been put on
trial in the scandal since last October. Most were accused of _ or
sentenced for _ issuing building permits in restricted zones in
return for large kickbacks. 	   
</TEXT>
