<BODY>
<SLUG> ARIANESPACE-SHAKES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arianespace Shakes But Stays 'In Orbit' Despite Asian Crisis, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Arianespace Shakes But Stays 'In Orbit' Despite Asian Crisis, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Mel S.ElonaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SINGAPORE-Arianespace, the world's first commercial space
transportation company, has shuddered from the currency turmoil in
Southeast Asia but remained confident it could weather the crisis
and even up its market share in the coming months - thanks partly
to Europe's high expectations stirred by preparations for the
launching of the Euro.
	   In a press briefing here, Arianespace Chair and Chief Executive
Officer Jean-Marie Luton said that although the ''negative
influence'' of the currency crisis ''caused the delay of a certain
number of programs,'' he believed an economic rebound in the region
would not be far ahead.
	   Arianespace controls more than half of the global market share.
	   Luton did not give details on the extent of Asian crisis' effect
on his company's operations, but a senior Arianespace official told
reporters after the briefing that the firm's market contracted by
an average of 15% in the past months. The official stressed,
however, that the satellite business in the region would likely
perk up again in two years.
	   Luton stated that the Asian problem was not very different from
the one experienced in 1992 by Britain and Italy whose respective
currencies - pound and lira - suffered devaluation but recovered
quickly.
	   ''So although we are not economists we are all obliged to make
economic judgments when we are in business and our judgment is that
there is every reason to expect a rebound in the region's
economies,'' Luton maintained.
	   The Arianespace executive said the optimism was largely fueled
by the likelihood of an ''unprecedented period of growth'' for
Europe and the ''efficiencies that monetary union will
bring.''Europe will have a single currency - Euro - by January
1999. The development, Luton pointed out, ''will benefit all
economies and will help the recovery of Southeast Asia.'' Moreover,
Arianespace, according to Luton, acknowledged the immensity of the
Asian market which has 413 million television households - more
than four times larger than the United States.' The figure is
expected to grow to 516 million by 2007 while cable and satellite
homes are projected to reach 160 million in the same year from the
current 82 million.
	   The Asia-Pacific region alone is being served by 34 satellites
in orbit and 26 more are being planned for launch in the next few
years, as against North and South America's combined total of 45 in
orbit and 18 being readied for launch.
	   ''Put into this context, the absolute number of satellites
planned for Asia-Pacific does not seem unreasonable,'' Luton
explained adding that Arianespace has launched 25 satellites in the
region since 1987, or roughly two every year.
	   Arianespace launched four satellites in 1996, five in 1997, and
one this year. Seven more would be launched in the region over the
next two years - including ones for India, Singapore, Indonesia,
South Korea, Laos, and Japan. In the past nine years, Arianespace
has launched two-thirds of the West's telecommunications
satellites.
	   Arianespace, formed in March 1980 and capitalized at 270 million
francs, has 53 shareholders ''representing the technical,
financial, and political capabilities'' of 12 European countries -
France, Belgium, Denmark, Germany, Ireland, Italy, the Netherlands,
Norway, Spain, Sweden, and the United Kingdom. Arianespace's
headquarters is in Evry near Paris.
	   Arianespace reported global net sales of 4.6 billion francs in
1994, 7.02 billion francs in 1995, and 6.3 billion in 1996.
	   Net profits reached 140 million francs in 1994, 190 million in
1995, and 135 million in 1996.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
