</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Too Fast? </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
High-speed crash raises the question: Are we going too fast?
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Germany-Train Derails; BC-Germany-Train Emergency Stop &QL; 
 &UR; By MELISSA EDDY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ The crash of InterCity Express 884 was
unimaginable.
	   In the confusing hours after the accident, police believed a car
found smashed in the wreckage had plunged from an overpass onto the
speeding train.
	   In fact, the likely cause was a flaw in the train itself: a
wheel had broken. The crash was no longer a freak accident but a
reality check for a country _ and a world _ where people want to go
faster and faster, to get there and back in a day.
	   Investigators still don't know how a wheel on Germany's premier
rail system could have broken, causing the train to derail and
smash into the supports of an overpass. Nearly 100 people were
killed.
	   It was the prospect of swift, yet safe, travel that drew
passengers back to the train in 1991 with the debut of the
InterCity Express, developed as an alternative to the expense of
air travel and the traffic jams of the German autobahn.
	   The trains have been running at top speeds of 280 kilometers
(175 miles) an hour for seven years without major technical
failures. But Wednesday's crash has forced both experts and
passengers to ask: Are we going too fast?
	   Spooked by the ICE wreck, Japan's main railway ordered emergency
inspections of the wheels and axles of its 1,100 high-speed bullet
trains, which run at a similar maximum speed.
	   The French, however, stayed cool. Though their 350 high-speed
trains edge Germany's by about 20 kilometers (12.4 miles) an hour,
French officials believe their wheel system _ set at the coupling
between cars _ is more stable than the German model, located at the
end of each wagon.
	   Spain and Korea have opted for the French design, and plans in
the United States to open a high-speed line along the East Coast
also are based on the ``Train de Grande Vitesse.''
	   After the crash, German rail officials ordered all high-speed
trains to slow to 160 kilometers (100 miles) an hour. The original
ICE fleet has been recalled for ultrasound checks of the wheels.
	   Even so, passengers who once marveled at the speed have grown
wary.
	   After a 3 hour, 15 minute train trip Sunday from Essen to
Frankfurt, an American here on business said some of her fellow
passengers were commenting on how fast the train was going.
	   ``I looked out the window and thought, `Wow, this train really
IS going fast,''' said Betty Ann Murphy, 33, an art museum employee
from Washington, D.C.
	   And yet compared to cars and planes, trains are the safest way
to go - at least statistically. In Germany, nearly 11 people die in
traffic accidents per billion kilometers (620 million miles)
traveled. That's compared to three people who die in airplane
crashes over the same distance and fewer than one in trains.
	   Safety was a key concern when Germany built its high-speed
network, covering 3,500 kilometers (2,175 miles) to connect its
major cities.
	   Monitors in some 60 stations across the country are always in
radio contact with the InterCity Express trains, and can throw an
emergency brake if they lose contact with the train's engineer.
	   But the high speed puts much more stress on the ICE equipment.
Wheels wear down within months and require regular checkups every
two or three trips. As an added precaution, Transport Minister
Matthias Wissmann is now considering adding alarm systems to alert
drivers to problems in the wheels.
	   However, he will not consider permanently slowing the trains
down.
	   (me-aet-cb) 	   
</TEXT>
