<SLUG> SHELL-CALTEX-HIKE-OIL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shell, Caltex Hike Oil Prices by P0.40/Liter, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Shell, Caltex Hike Oil Prices by P0.40/Liter, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Marc G. DimenASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Pilipinas Shell Petroleum Corp. and Caltex (Philippines) Inc.
raised yesterday the prices of three deregulated petroleum products
by an average P0.40 a liter.
	   Gasoline dealers said Shell raised the prices of premium
gasoline by P0.44 to P12.05 a liter, unleaded gasoline by P0.45 to
P11.67 a liter and diesel by P0.34 to P8.36 a liter.
	   They said the adjustments were effective Wednesday midnight.
Pilipinas Shell, a member of the Royal Dutch/Shell group, is the
country's second biggest oil refiner.
	   Caltex, a joint venture of Texaco Inc. and Chevron Corp.,
announced that it likewise raised the prices of premium gasoline by
P0.41 to P12.04 a liter, unleaded gasoline by P0.47 to P11.69 a
liter and diesel by P0.33 to P8.35 a liter.
	   The adjustment took effect at 2 p.m. yesterday, the company
said.
	   Pilipinas Shell and Caltex raised their prices a day after
Petron Corp., the country's biggest refiner, marked up its rates.
	   Petron, which is 40% owned by Saudi Aramco, raised the prices of
premium gasoline by P0.42 to P12.03 a liter, unleaded gasoline by
P0.42 to P11.69 and diesel by P0.31 to P8.36.
	   The oil firms said they had to adjust their prices because of
the higher landed cost of crude and the weak peso.
	   The price of Dubai crude went up $0.49 to $12.69 a barrel in May
from the previous month's level.
	   The peso slid to 39.32 last month from 36.43 in April.
	   These adjustments came following an announcement from the Energy
Regulatory Board that it would raise the prices of three
socially-sensitive oil products by an average P0.24 a liter.
	   Under a recently passed oil deregulation law, oil firms can
freely adjust prices of petroleum products except for regular
gasoline, kerosene and liquefied petroleum gasoline, which are
still under government control. - 
</TEXT>
