<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-ANGLE-OF-THE-BULGE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The Angle of the Bulge, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
The Angle of the Bulge, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Marilitz DizonASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The quality of a man's personality is seen in his upright
posture. The more relaxed a person is, the more he can achieve
centeredness. A stiff posture indicates an underlying menace or
defiance. The upright man learns to stay upright in a correct
manner. His weight descends normally along the strong patterns of
the muscle and bone alignment, without any tension showing anywhere
or any stiffening of the muscles, especially those of the legs.
	   If you stand correctly, you will be centered, balanced - able
and readyto consciously shift from rest to motion. This exercise of
standing is performed by consciously relaxing and allowing the
weight of the upper body to descend naturally, according to the
pull of gravity. Besides being more balanced from correct posture,
you can also determine whether or not you're a candidate for the
battle of the bulge.
	   Fat people are teased and harassed unmercifully when they are
children.
	   Thus, they learn to put on an armor of jovial good humor and wit
to cover their misery, or resort to petulant silence and grumbling.
By the time they mature, because their large digestive machinery
ensures the maximum utilization of food intake, they have gained
considerable size and strength, but most are mentally attuned to
being dominated.When they apply for work, the odds are stacked
against them because they are seen to be sometimes clumsy, slow,
accident-prone, and sweaty. Very fat people may be stared at in the
streets and avoided in buses, aircraft, or pubs, where they take up
too much room.
	   In an upright posture, you can measure the angle that the ribs
make where they join the bottom of the breastbone. If the angle is
greater than average, the abdomen is wide and deep with plenty of
room for large, digestive organs. But if the chest is comparatively
small, the lung capacity is also small. Studies show that this type
has greater strength but a tendency to be fat, with limited
stamina.
	   If the angle is smaller than average, the abdomen is narrow and
shallow with a small digestive system. But the chest is long with
comparatively large lungs. Such people have great stamina, but
their strength is poor, and they tend to be thin.
	   This angle is referred to as the ``Angle of Obesity.''
	   Dr. Victor Baker made extensive researches on the treatment of
heart and circulation with reference to posture and joint mobility.
In 1973, when Dr.
	   Baker was working as a school medical officer in England, he
conducted a study involving 143 children. He chose to work with
children because their degree of obesity had not yet been greatly
affected by their work patterns or posture. The children were
divided into several groups: normal, tending to be fat, fat,
tending to be thin, and thin.
	   His hypothesis of the ``Angle of Obesity'' was well founded, as
ne0 to 130 degrees.
	   Below 70 degrees, the children were skinny; above 110 degrees
they were definitely fat.
	   It is very easy to measure the angle of obesity. Simply run your
fingers down the front of your chest bone until the bone
disappears. Mark a cross on your skin there. Now, run your hand
down the lower border of your ribs on the left side and mark
another cross at the outer edge of this border, approximately where
your elbow touches the side of your chest. Do the same on the right
side. Now measure the angle between the side crosses and the center
cross with a protractor.
	   Anyone with an angle greater than 100 degrees is going to fight
the battle of the bulge all their life. For those with an angle
above 110 degrees, even the smell of food will make them put on
weight.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
