<SLUG> BC-Guatemala-Elections,0137 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Local elections in Guatemala
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CHINAUTLA, Guatemala (AP) _ Guatemalans in 30 municipalities
turned out in huge numbers Sunday to elect mayors and city
councils.
	   Voting is obligatory in Guatemala, so even people with no
interest in the elections showed up at the ballot boxes.
	   ``I came to vote because I'm registered here, but I don't know
who the candidates are, and I don't know who I'll vote for,'' said
Maria del Rosario Munoz, a 27-year-old Indian in traditional dress
from this town six miles (10 kms) northwest of Guatemala City.
	   The elections Sunday were selecting local officials for 30 of
Guatemala's 320 municipalities, with 395,262 voters registered. The
mayors and town councils will be in power for 18 months, until
general elections next year replace them. 	   
</TEXT>
