<BODY>
<SLUG> STOCK-ANALYSTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stock Analysts, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Stock Analysts, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   In the course of the last month or so, many stock brokerage
firms have been reducing their staff because of the decline in
their trading. To some extent this decline has been self inflicted
with the poor quality of their analytical work, which has tended to
be much too optimistic, with little real understanding of the
implications of the currency crisis and a failure to recognize the
dangers created by excessive over-construction of high-rise
buildings.
	   According to a report quoted on the Internet, there was
remarkably little resemblance between the forecast earnings of
companies which were supposedly analyzed by 12 brokerage houses,
andactual earnings results achieved by those companies. When work
is so obviously seen to be performed in such a sloppy manner, it
has a very disparaging impact on the integrity of underestimating
earnings than of overestimating them. Nobody complains if earnings
are better than indicated but everyone feels cheated when earnings
are below forecasted expectations.
	   An example of the published analytical anomalies is Petron,
which some analysts were estimating to have earnings of anything
between P2.6 billion and P4.6 billion. But, it actually achieved a
loss of P631 million. Such a wide disparity cans only mean that the
analysts concerned were hopelessly incompetent.
	   I have frequently been critical of locals analysts in this
column precisely because they have little regard for the real facts
of life and they tend to be promoters of their inflated dreams.
	   The fact of the matter is that there are very few stocks
available where the return on equity exceeds the costs of capital
which, put in more simple language, means that most shares are
expensive even at today's prices.
	   Furthermore, the shortfall in government revenues can only lead
to higher interest rates later in the year, and this will make most
issues in our stock markets look even more expensive.
	   This is not to suggest that there will not be some expectations
which will go against the trend, but these are more likely to be
found among those companies which have been out of favor for some
time. One such company is House of Investments (HI) which has
survived many crises in the past and which had substantial
interests in some 20 companies, among which is a 51% ownership of
EEI. I believe that there is a very good chance that HI will come
out of the current dull period with flying colors. It has had the
benefit of being out of favor for quite some time and of having
been largely ignored by the fraternity of analysts.
	   
</TEXT>
