<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs,0590 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Includes items of World Cup wedding; Thai gambling; cycling
</HEADLINE>
Norwegian; Gascoigne and drinking &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NANTES, France (AP) _ While many fans thought it was frustrating
getting tickets for the World Cup, just consider the plight of a
smaller group of people who simply want to attend a wedding during
the tournament.
	   According to FIFA, a couple identified only as Karl and Nadege
sent out wedding announcements with a special insert requesting
them to return their confirmations to attend with copies of their
automobile registration papers.
	   The reason was that the wedding is scheduled as the same day the
Spain-Nigeria match on June 13, and the Saint-Joseph de Porteri
church is within the security perimeter of La Beaujorie Stadium.
	   The requirement was necessary to get clearance for the wedding.
	   Karl and Nadege aren't the only ones who have the hassle. Four
other weddings at the church, all scheduled before the conclusion
of the July 3 quarterfinal in Nantes, must undergo the same
procedure.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Trying to reduce the illegal gambling
in the country, Thai police have established a World Cup gambling
task force in the hopes that it can cut into the 30 billion baht
(dlrs 750 million) expected to be wagered on the tournament.
	   The police also are bracing for an increase in suicides and
robberies in the anticipation that fortunes wagered _ and often
lost _ will lead to desperate acts.
	   Gambling is illegal in Thailand, but the laws are widely
ignored.
	   ``More student crimes will occur,'' said Deputy Minister Somsak
Prisana-nantakul. ``But what we're worried of is suicide by those
who cannot pay their debts.''
	   The case of university law student Rewat Kengsakul has
crystallized fears of how gambling can corrupt the young.
	   Rewat, 18, was arrested in April after using an air-gun to rob a
gold shop to clear a 9,000 baht (dlrs 225) gambling debt. He was
arrested with 33 gold chains in his possession and is currently
awaiting trial.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SAINT-ANDRE-DES-EAUX, France (AP) _ One Norwegian fan is staging
his own version of the Tour de France, an economical way to follow
his country's national team throughout its stay in the World Cup.
	   Peter Garden already has ridden his bicycle 1,800 kilometers
(1,100 miles) from Oslo to the team's training camp in the Loire
Valley and plans to follow them on his two-wheeler to Montpellier,
Bordeaux and Marseille.
	   Garden, sponsored by the Norwegian Football Federation, expects
to collect autographs of celebrities and players' jerseys, and then
auction them off on his way home to raise money for a charity that
caters to Third World orphans.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LONDON (AP) _ Paul Gascoigne, dropped from the English World Cup
side because of fitness problems related to late-night partying and
drinking, has been offered help from recovering alcoholics and
former teammates Tony Adams and Paul Merson.
	   ``I just hope he sorts out his life and can be happy,'' said
Adams, who stopped drinking two years ago. ``Only he can decide if
he has a problem, but if he wants to choose my path then he knows
where I am.''
	   Merson, who plays with Gascoigne on England's Middlesbrough
club, echoed Adams in interviews with the Independent on Sunday.
	   ``I hope he can find it inside himself to want to do something
about the way things have been with him,'' Merson said.
	   (bt/jw)
</TEXT>
