<BODY>
<SLUG> IMF-SAYS-BANK-REFORMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF Says Bank Reforms Still Insufficient, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
IMF Says Bank Reforms Still Insufficient, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE International Monetary Fund (IMF) said the reforms recently
carried out by the Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) were still not
enough to strengthen the banking sector.
	   The IMF noted that while the BSP increased the minimum
capitalization requirement of banks, it did not necessarily follow
that sufficient protection had been laid over the industry.
	   The institution even urged the Philippine Deposit Insurance
Corp. (PDIC) and the BSP to increase capital in lieu with the
general objective.
	   A ranking government official, who was informed of the results
of the deferred IMF review, disclosed Wednesday night that the IMF
had branded the move as ``little steps.''
	   The official also had one-on-one talks with the Bretton Woods
institution.
	   The IMF pointed out that BSP's directive to lift deposit secrecy
in case of banks granting loans for directors, owners,
stockholders, and related interests (Dosri) was also from the
prescribed modification of the Bank Secrecy Law.
	   The IMF and its sister institution, the World Bank, urged
government to further improve the transparency regulations of the
BSP over the banks' financial sheets. They said this could be done
through the revision of the law which central monetary authorities
and bankers had vehemently opposed.
	   Specifically, the IMF wanted bank examiners to be given direct
access to financial records.
	   The Fund realized current validation schemes of the BSP were
``imperfect''
	   given the more than 2,000 account records stocked in the
archives of PDIC estimated to be at P9 million.
	   ``No examiner should be prohibited from inspecting,'' the
official said.
	   ``With regards to that Dosri rule, they (BSP) moved just a
little bit when there was an opportunity to go miles ahead... The
increase in capital adequacy ratios was just the first step. With
this, you cannot say that you are already sound.''
	   The BSP last March pulled up banks' capital build-up to 60%
depending on the category of the banks. The move was in consonance
with the reform agenda outlined in the Memorandum of Economic and
Financial Program (MEFP).
	   MEFP paved way to the two-year precautionary arrangement the BSP
and the Department of Finance forged with the IMF.
	   However, the official said PDIC President Ernest Leung junked
the IMF prescription. The suggestion is expected to encounter
similar resistance from the central monetary authority.
	   The official further said the IMF wanted the BSP to fully adopt
the Basle Core Principles which the Bank for International
Settlements (BIS) had formulated.
	   The BIS is known as the main central bank based in Basle,
Switzerland.
	   
</TEXT>
