<BODY>
<SLUG> ACQUIT-IMELDA-MOVE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bello Sees Nothing Wrong With Acquit-Imelda Move, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Bello Sees Nothing Wrong With Acquit-Imelda Move, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Benjamin B. PultaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Justice Secretary Silvestre Bello III defended yesterday a move
by government's chief lawyer to set aside a 12-year jail term
against former First Lady Imelda Marcos and acquit her of
corruption charges.
	   ``The duty of the (Office of the Solicitor General) is to
protect the innocent,'' Bello told reporters.''His client is not
only the government but also its people.''
	   The outgoing justice secretary, a Ramos appointee, said there
was nothing ``absurd'' about the solicitor general's recommendation
to the Supreme Court to acquit Mrs. Marcos.
	   ``The solicitor general can take a different position from that
originally taken by the government...in the interest of justice,''
said Bello.
	   Bello has already filed a courtesy resignation, and is set to
leave the justice department by the end of the month.
	   In a 34-page comment sent to the high court, Solicitor General
Romeo de la Cruz said state lawyers reviewed the case and found
that the prosecution failed to submit enough evidence to convict
Mrs. Marcos of the charge.
	   An anti-graft court in 1993 found the widow of the late dictator
Ferdinand Marcos guilty of graft and sentenced her to 12 years in
jail.The Supreme Court upheld the verdict last January.
	   Mrs. Marcos had been found guilty of leasing state property to
the Philippine General Hospital Foundation Inc. (PGHFI), a private
foundation she headed, under terms allegedly disadvantageous to
government.The transaction occurred while the Marcoses were still
in power.
	   The property belonged to the Light Rail Transit Authority
(LRTA), which Mrs. Marcos also headed.
	   The two parcels of land were leased to PGHFI at P100,000 a
month.The foundation, through Mrs. Marcos, later entered into an
agreement with two companies that agreed to use the property at
P700,000 a month for 25 years.
	   De la Cruz said state prosecutors failed to establish that Mrs.
Marcos conspired with PGHFI and LRTA to defraud government.He said
the acquittal of then LRTA Vice President Jose Dans should also
work in Mrs. Marcos' favor.
	   The state action was the latest stroke of good fortune for the
Marcos family but it triggered criticisms from anti-Marcos
advocates.
	   ``There's a big question mark now about meting justice on the
Marcoses,''
	   said leftist leader Satur Ocampo, one of thousands of dissidents
tortured by the military during the Marcos era.
	   ``It looks like the political direction is re-accommodating the
Marcoses back to power and setting aside the grievances against
them for plundering the economy and violating human rights,''
Ocampo added.
	   Former Solicitor General Frank Chavez, who prepared the graft
case against Mrs. Marcos, was appalled by the state recommendation
and said he hoped the Supreme Court would stick to its ruling
upholding her conviction.
	   ``It seems to me that they are inching their way back (to
power),'' Chavez said. ``The only problem in this country is you
are presumed guilty until you are proven influential.
	   ``If she is eventually acquitted, then we lose everything. We
lose our right to attain vindication, we lose our right to obtain
justice and we lose the right to be ashamed of ourselves.''

</TEXT>
