<BODY>
<SLUG> FORT-BONIFACIO-PROJECT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MPC Says It's Committed To Fort Bonifacio Project, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
MPC Says It's Committed To Fort Bonifacio Project, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Diversified concern Metro Pacific Corp. yesterday said the
consortium developing Fort Bonifacio at the edge ofMakati financial
district was still committed to the multi-billion peso project.
	   ``We have had recent discussions with all the shareholders of
BLC and they remain fully committed to supporting Fort Bonifacio,''
Metro Pacific Chair Manuel Pangilinan said in a statement.
	   Metro Pacific, the flagship corporation of the First Pacific Co.
Ltd. of Hongkong, is the leader in a 12-member Bonifacio Land Corp.
(BLC) developing the 214-hectare former military camp into the
country's next financial hub.
	   Pangilinan was reacting to newspaper reports saying BLC was
considering selling 64 hectares of the land back togovernment,
since it would not be able to pay the remaining P8.8 billion
balance by the end of the month.
	   Another option being considered by BLC was to pay the balance on
a five-year deferred payment scheme, Bases Conversion Development
Authority (BCDA) Chair Victorino Basco said on Wednesday.
	   He said BCDA, which is the original land owner of Fort
Bonifacio, would allow a deferred payment scheme only if BLC put up
a surety bond.
	   Basco was also quoted by newspapers saying BLC was having a
liquidity problem after several of its consortium members backed
out from the project due to the slumping property market.
	   ``Metro Pacific and First Pacific stand firmly behind the
project. First Pacific has significant free cash balances and as
such is in a position to fully support BLC and the Fort Bonifacio
project,'' Pangilinan added.
	   Metro Pacific, however, did not deny that negotiations were
ongoing regarding the payment of the P8.8 billion balance. BLC has
paid more than P20 billion for the right to develop the large tract
of land.
	   Metro Pacific lost 10 centavos yesterday to close at P1.26.
	   
</TEXT>
