<HEADLINE>
'Inventor' of Microchip To Speak at De La Salle, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
'Inventor' of Microchip To Speak at De La Salle, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Dr. Leo D. Yao,director of Innovative Technology Modules of
Intel Corp., will conduct a lecture on ``The Evolution of
Microprocessor Technology'' at the De La Salle University today,
12:40 to 2:20 p.m. at the Waldo Perfecto Seminar Room. His talk
will focus on technologies behind the Intel computer chips,
specially from the 1386 to current Pentium microprocessors, which
he helped develop.
	   Yao holds the record of being the first Filipino to achieve the
status of a Fellow at Intel Corp. His outstanding achievements and
ingenuity at work earned him this status. Yao has received four
Intel individual achievement awards.
	   A graduate of Electrical Engineering from San Carlos, Cebu City
in 1962, Yao was a co-inventor of the thermally simulated
capacitance transient techniques and published a number of papers
using the technique to determine the energy levels and emission
rates of deep level impurities in silicon.
	   He holds a master's degree in Electric Engineering from the
University of Minnesota, and a doctorate from the University of
Illinois.
	   Yao joined Intel Corp. in 1978, and has since received different
awards and recognition for his technical contributions to
technology developments. He has co-authored over 30 papers and
issued 20 US patents.
	   HI Earns P26.2M in Q1House of Investments (HI) earned P26.2
million in the first quarter of 1998 from revenues amounting to
P60.7 million.
	   Company officers said that although earnings in the first three
months were lower than the P35.3 million company made in the same
period last year, they represented a turnaround in performance.
	   HI reported a loss at yearend 1997. As with many other firms
throughout Asia, the company was not spared by the Asian financial
turmoil that caused the peso's value to plunge from P26.50 in July
to P40.12 by yearend 1997.
	   This forced bank lending rates to move up from 14% to as high as
35%.
	   HI's construction and infrastructure subsidiary, EEI Corp.,
earned P91.7 million, almost double its net income for the first
quarter of last year.
	   Despite the slowdown of the construction sector in general, EEI
increased its already robust project backlog to around P9.9 billion
as of the end of April 1998.
	   HI's consumer finance subsidiaries BA Savings Bank and First
Malayan Leasing and Finance Corp., however, were adversely affected
byhigh interest rates that prevailed from the last half of 1997 to
the present but which are showing signs of easing up.
	   BA Savings also had lower loan bookings, particularly for auto
loans, due to lower sales by the automobile industry. To further
improve the quality of its receivables, BA Savings continues to
make very conservative provisions for possible loan losses.
	   HI also said that, together with its partners, it has decided to
postpone the implementation of the South Western Cement project in
Malabuyoc, Cebu due to unfavorable investment conditions resulting
from the regional financial crisis and because the project's Korean
contractor encountered financial difficulties. HI decided instead
to invest in existing cement companies through South Western Cement
Ventures Inc., a joint venture with Blue Circle Industries Plc.
	   BM-FAVC/6.5 Firstec Expands OperationsFirst Asia Venture Capital
Inc. (FAVC),a major shareholder of Philippine-based First Asia
Systems Technology Inc. (Fastech) and Dutch-owned Silicon Systems
and Services BV (SS&AMP;S) signed a memorandum of agreement to expand
the business activity of its joint venture company Firstec Silicon
and Systems Inc.
	   ``From a mere IC chip design, Firstec will venture into complete
product design and manufacturing to supply the requirements of a
multinational computer company producing smartcard terminals for
the European market,''
	   saidSaturnino G. Belen Jr., Fastech president and chief
executive officer representing FAVC.
	   Belen said that Firstec's operations would translate to an
export potential for the Philippines of $100 million on its first
year and $180 million in its second year. He added that the project
was significant because Filipinos were responsible for thedesign
and manufacturing effortsunder the supervision of SS&AMP;S.
	   Firstec was established in May last year to provide electronics
systems designs.Under the MOA, both FAVC and SS&AMP;S infused capital
and maintained a 60%-40% ownership structure, respectively.
Additional investments include high-end computers, software for IC
design and lay-out, hardware and software for the Printed Circuit
Board system's design development and implementation. Firstec will
also have its own captive manufacturing line for chip-on-board
assembly which will be housed at the Fastech Manufacturing Complex
in Cabuyao, Laguna.
	   Fastech, a company engaged in electronics system and design, was
one of the participants in the recently concluded Hannover Fair in
Germany where the Philippines waspartner country.
	   Nexus WinsNexus Wins HP Resellers of the Year AwardNexus
Technologies Inc., a leading provider of enterprise computing
solutions, has been awarded as the 1997 HP Reseller of the Year.
The recognition was given in an Award Gala Night which highlighted
the Hewlett Packard Asia Pacific and Japan Key Resellers'
Conference held last month in Barcelona, Spain.
	   A leading HP reseller since 1997, Nexus has focused its
marketing and sales efforts on HP PCs and servers. In receiving the
award, Nexus President Juan Chua commented, ``Our success proves
that the Philippine market has long been ready for enterprise
computing solutions that are known for their reliability, value,
and functionality. HP has been proven on all counts and we are
proud to represent the product in the Philippine market.''
	   Chua also cited HP for its marketing and training support to its
resellers.
	   ``We value our partnership with HP for their significant help,
particularly in the technical training of our marketing, sales, and
support staff,'' he added.
	   The conference was attended by executives of reseller companies,
including selected consumer delegates, all over the Asia Pacific
region.
	   
