<BODY>
<SLUG> TASTE-EXPRESS-LUTONG sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taste Express Lutong Capampangan at The Heritage, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Taste Express Lutong Capampangan at The Heritage, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Chona S. TrinidadASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Among the many provinces in the Philippines, Pampanga stands out
when it comes to cuisine. Food is part and parcel of the Pampango
lifestyle, the natives taking pride in their dishes as well as
their confections.
	   )From childhood, the women are taught the basics of cooking, as
the menfolk always look forward to enjoying a good meal, capped by
dessert. In fact, even the men are known to excel in the kitchen.
	   Pampanga is among the top producers of sugar in the country, and
among the best-known sweets from the province are pastillas de
leche, tocino del cielo, turrones de casuy, and tibok-tibok (the
Tagalog version of maja blanca with the exception that the
Pampangos use fresh carabao milk).
	   Tamales is exceptionally good if it comes from Pampanga and this
is very much in demand during the Yuletide season.
	   The Heritage Hotel Manila has invited the charming Pette Jorolan
whose mother established Everybody's Cafe in San Fernando,
Pampanga. Pette recalls how her mother frowned on the use of modern
devices such as blenders and osterizers, preferring to stick to the
almiris (mortar and pestle) for pounding, the itak (cleaver) for
chopping, and well-sharpened knives for slicing. Traditionally,
Pampango cooks do not resort to using instant mixes or additives.
They simply rely on age-old cooking methods to produce authentic
dishes.
	   Many of their dishes have the unmistakable influence of Spain,
as seen in the morcon, relleno, pastel, galantina, cocido, lengua
asado, and bringhe, to name just a few. Even the names are in
Spanish.
	   When traveling through the provinces of Pampanga, it is
customary to stop by pasalubong centers to buy delicacies to bring
home to the family and friends.
	   )From June 10-14, the Heritage Hotel Manila offers the flavors
of Pampanga as prepared by the cooks of Everybody's Cafe. Enjoy a
sumptuous buffet spread served at lunch and dinner at the Riviera
Restaurant. It is also very likely that you will enjoy the fresh
papaya lumpia combining green grated papaya, shrimp, pork,
garbanzos, and bean sprouts complemented by pako (a variety of
fern) salad. During the press lunch, this went over big with
Heritage General Manager Richard Teo, who had two servings, no
less! The Pampango foodfest also showcases selected Pampango
handicrafts, courtesy of the Department of Trade and Industry. This
event is held in cooperation with the Department of Tourism's
Centennial Food Festival.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
