<SLUG> SHIP-RADIO-OPERATORS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ship Radio Operators Battle for Survival, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Ship Radio Operators Battle for Survival, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arthur U. SalaganASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Filipino seafarers holding the position of radio operators have
called on government to take action and allow them to take third
mate examinations so they can still seek employment even after the
hiring of these operators in vessels could be terminated in 1999.
	   By February 1999, the services of radio operators may no longer
be needed when the Global Maritime Distress and Safety System
(GMDSS) would be fully implemented.
	   Reports indicated that even today, some shipowners are no longer
hiring radio operators as most ships are now using the GMDSS.
	   However, experts said the phasing out of radio operators was not
advisable even on ships that have GMDSS equipment sinceships will
always have problems concerning equipment.
	   Mario Maraviles, a radio operator for Baliwag Navigation, said
he was willing to take up courses like watchkeeping and navigation
and then take examinations so that his license could be converted
to that fora third mate.
	   He added that his experience on board ships should be credited
by maritime schools in order to shorten the schooling period just
in case he decides to study nautical science.
	   Other radio operators also urged government to follow the
counter measures being adopted by other countries like Japan and
Singapore which have transferred radio operators to the deck and
engine department.
	   Another Filipino seaman noted that in the early '90s, some ship
firms trained their radio operators as second mates, studying
navigation and cargohandling during their contracts.
	   Radio operators are calling on government to draft a clear
policy exclusively for them and follow other countries which have
already implemented the conversion of radio operators to deck
officers.
	   They also urges the Department of Education and Sports (DECS) to
stop the schools from offering the GRCO course to prevent the
oversupply of radio operators.
	   
</TEXT>
