<BODY>
<SLUG> NEW-ADMINISTRATION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Administration To Review SGS Contract, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
New Administration To Review SGS Contract, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The incoming administration of President-elect Joseph Estrada
would be reviewing the provisions of the three-year contract of
Societe Generale de Surveillance (SGS) which government had granted
earlier this year.
	   Sources said Finance Secretary-in-waiting Edgardo B. Espiritu
has admitted an overhaul in the agreement was a major possibility
owing to the huge amount of the public money involved.
	   However, the sources admitted that termination of the contract
was unlikely to be carried out.
	   ``We will be taking a second look but we cannot rescind the
three-year SGS contract,'' a well-placed source from the Estrada
camp said.
	   SGS, a private inspection firm based in Geneva, Switzerland, was
hired by government during the '80s to conduct pre-inspection on
shipments bound for Philippine ports of entry.
	   Government cannot assess incoming cargo abroad due to issues on
sovereignty.
	   Sources noted that Espiritu was considering fully terminating
the agreement when it expires in year 2000.
	   ``Hopefully, the modernization of the Bureau of Customs (BOC)
would have been finalized by that time,'' another source said.
	   Customs officials as well as key executives of industry
organizations admitted to The Business Dailythat the reforms which
government started to apply earlier this decade were still too
underdeveloped to back the BOC's independence in checking
shipments.
	   ``They (BOC) still badly need SGS' valuation schemes,'' an
executive of a manufacturing firm said.
	   Under thenew contract, the BOC would adopt the Selective
Pre-shipment Inspection and Advance Clearance System (Spacs) which
is considered the ``exit program of government from SGS''.
	   Customs Commissioner Guillermo L. Parayno Jr. said the system
facilitates the principle of ``cargo clearance before the
shipment's arrival'' through a selective pre-shipment inspection
and an advanced cargo clearance process.
	   Moreover, Spacs would be the last reform and modernization
program the BOC would complete prior to the termination of SGS'
services.
	   With these in place, release of shipments will be faster and
import inflows are kept on track via an ``intelligence data base,''
Parayno said.
	   He strongly dismissed reports that former Finance Secretary
Roberto de Ocampo promised Congress not to extend the contract of
SGS after March 1998.
	   ``We have an exit program and we have determined that we have
made good in our reforms. There was really much improvement
achieved. There was a need to fit in a new service to face the
challenge as we are still behind the pack which we must lead,''
Parayno said.
	   Parayno claimed the new contract was cheaper -- 20% lower than
the previous cost. Government was paying P4 billion annually under
the old contract.
	   On the other hand, shift of current export value to transaction
value will be pushed through by government under the Asean Free
Trade Area convention.
	   A uniformed tariff of 3%-5% in the region will be applied in the
region in year 2004.
	   The change in the valuation method was strongly opposed by local
manufacturers as this would result in a cut-throat competition with
their foreign counterparts as imports will be priced lower than the
locally-made commodities.
	   However, Parayno noted the shift will not phase out the local
industries, but rather, make the latter globally competitive as
international trade would be further opened.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:NEW-ADMINISTRATION sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
