<SLUG> VILLAR-WANTS-USE-INERT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villar Wants to Use Inert Party for Speakership Bid, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Villar Wants to Use Inert Party for Speakership Bid, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Ferdinand G. PatinioASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The once formidable Lakas-NUCD may be losing Muntinlupa Rep.
Manuel Villar -one of its top bets for House Speakership - although
not to its political arch-foe but to an inactive and lesser known
party.
	   Meanwhile, Lakassecretary general andPresidential adviser on
political affairs Gabriel Claudio also denied that the party had
already picked its official candidate for Speakership.
	   A veteran lawmaker who spoke on condition that he not be named
said Villar was contemplating using the stagnant Partido ng Masang
Pilipino (PMP) as vehicle for his bid for Speakership.
	   PMP wasfounded by President-elect Joseph Estrada and Sen. Miriam
Defensor Santiago during the 1992 national and local elections. The
party later coalesced with the Laban ng Makabayang Pilipino of Sen.
Edgardo Angara and the Nationalist People's Coalition of Sen.
Edgardo Maceda.
	   Many members of Laban and NPC are now with Laban ng Makabayang
Masang Pilipino (Lammp), Estrada's new political party and Lakas'
arch-rival in the recent elections.
	   ``We don't want to joint Lammp since we'll be treated as mere
second-rates.
	   As the revived PMP, we will be the first among equals,'' a
supporter of Villar at the House of Representatives said.
	   Rumors of Villar's plan to bolt Lakas were bolstered by his
absence at the party's meetings on May 22 and 29.
	   Newly-elected legislators from the Liberal Party, Promdi, Aksyon
Demokratiko and Reporma were also reportedly being wooed by the
Pro-Villar bloc.
	   Lakas boasts of 110 members in the House or enough to elect a
Speaker while Lammp only has 80 members but is relying on the swing
votes from ``closet Lammps.''
	   Sources said it was Estrada himself who told Villar in one of
their meetings ``to get out of Lakas and join PMP.''
	   Some lawmakers who had already expressed support for Villar were
Reps.
	   Marcial Punzalan (Lakas, Quezon), Ralph Recto (Lakas, Batangas),
Angelino Sarmiento (Lakas, Bulacan), Lualhati Antonino (Lammp-South
Cotabato), Herminio Teves (Lakas, Negros Oriental), and ''first
termer'' Aniceto Saludo, Jr. (Lammp-Southern Leyte).
	   Aside from Villar, Lakas' other nominees to the post of Speaker
areDeputy Majority Leader Manuel Garcia, Maguindanao Rep. Simeon
Datumanong, Leyte Rep. Sergio Apostol, Quezon City-Rep. Feliciano
Belmonte, Iloilo Rep.
	   Narciso Monfort,and Quezon Rep. Narciso Suarez.
	   Lammp on the other hand is choosing among Makati Rep. Joker
Arroyo, Isabela Rep. Gilberto Duavit and newly-elected Bohol Rep.
Ernesto Herrera.
	   In denying that Lakas had already anointed a candidate for
Speaker during a meeting recently, Claudio said the party merely
issued a resolution ''for the Lakas congressman to support and
rally behind one common candidate for speaker who should be a
bonafide member.''
	   Claudio also admitted that most of the members of Lakas were
questioning the loyaltyof Villar to the party.
	   ``There were some who would like to be clarified on the actual
status and intentions of Congressman Villar, and there were some
who wanted to be clarified why he did not attend last night's
(Wednesday) caucus,'' Claudio said.
	   Only 70 of the 110 Lakas congressmanattended the party caucus
last Wednesday. Claudio maintained that the Villar case was barely
discussed at the caucus which focused on Lakas' and Lammp's
drafting of a ''common legislative agenda which will support and
help the incoming administration.''
	   
</TEXT>
