<SLUG> LAKAS-SOLONS-TO-DEFER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lakas Solons to Defer Action on Pork Barrel, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Lakas Solons to Defer Action on Pork Barrel, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Maria Mirasol B. NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Lakas party has decided to defer actions against the plan of
President-elect Joseph Estrada to abolish the pork barrel to
prevent a direct confrontation with the incoming administration.
	   The decision was reached during Wednesday's party caucus in
Arlegui where some 100 Lakas members, including 67 winning
candidates, met with Pres.
	   Fidel V. Ramos.
	   In an interview, Rep. Sergio Apostol (Lakas, Leyte)yesterday
said the President asked party members to refrain from making
premature statements on the issue so as not to undermine ongoing
talks on the proposed national unity government.
	   ``The consensus was to defer action on the matter and wait for
definite action on the part of Estrada,'' Apostol said.
	   He explained the party can only take definite actions when
Estrada formally assumes the presidency and when a new Speaker has
already been installed in the Lower House.
	   ``The President has in fact discouraged party members from
making any moves on pork barrel issues,'' the Leyte solon, who is
also aspiring for the Speakership, said.
	   In a party statement released yesterday, Pres. Ramos and Speaker
Jose de Venecia emphasized the need for the Filipino people ``to
unite behind Estrada during a period when the financial storm in
Asia has already triggered an economic collapse in Indonesia,
Thailand and South Korea.''
	   Lakas solons, who have bonded themselves into an informal bloc
called ``blockbusters,'' reportedly wanted the party and Pres.
Ramos to make a definite stand against the scrapping of the
countrywide development fund (CDF) and the congressional initiative
allocation (CIA) derisivelyknown as pork barrels.
	   Rep. Danilo Suarez (Lakas, Quezon) and Apostol, acknowledged
leaders of the group, said they will with reason with Estrada and
stress the importance of retaining the pork barrel in funding
infrastructure projects.
	   Rep. Margarito Teves (Lakas, Negros Oriental) said the pork
barrel need not be totally abolished. The fund, he said, can simply
be reduced by 25% if the objectiveis to have money for agriculture.
	   Estrada, however, said he was determined to keep his campaign
promise of abolishing the pork barrel, allegedly the source of
graft and corruption.
	   The President-elect said the budget for pork will be reduced to
fund his administration's program to modernize agriculture.
	   The Lakas leadership likewise said it was backing the call for a
government of national unity in both houses of Congress under an
Estrada presidency.
	   
</TEXT>
