<SLUG> NDC-TO-PUSH-THROUGH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NDC to Push Through With Sale of Philphos, Pasar, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
NDC to Push Through With Sale of Philphos, Pasar, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 05, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The National Development Co. (NDC) said it would push through
with the privatization of the Philippine Phosphates Fertilizer
Corp. (Philphos) and the Philippine Associated Smelting and
Refining Corp. (Pasar).
	   NDC General Manager Mariano Salazar said they will submit a plan
to the next secretary of the Department of Trade and Industry
(DTI), which will include options on how to attract bidders for the
privatization.
	   As of end-November last year, Philphos and Pasar have
outstanding debts amounting to P43.8 billion and P30.7 billion,
respectively.
	   ``The Committee on Privatization has already approved the
privatization and NDC is just waiting for the valuation which is
expected to be released within the month,'' Salazar said.
	   He said the decision on the sale of state-owned corporations
should be well-timed as government may not allow privatization if
the market is down.
	   Government has a 41.91% stake in Pasar, while 27.78% is
distributed among mining companies Marcopper Mining Corp.,
Maricalum Mining Corp., Philex Mining Corp. and Lepanto
Consolidated Mining. The 30% share of the total equity belongs to
the Japanese investors Marubeni Corp., Sumitomo Corp., and Itomu
Corps.
	   Other government-owned corporations in line for privatization
under the Estrada administration include National Power Corp.and
the Philippine National Bank (PNB).
	   
</TEXT>
