<SLUG> BC-Poland-Government Reform </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opole residents demonstrate to remain a province
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Tens of thousands of people in
southwestern Opole province formed a ``human chain'' Sunday,
demanding their region remain a province when the country's inner
boundaries are redrawn under the government's administrative reform
plan.
	   The provincial reform aims to shed the last of Poland's
communist-era bureaucratic system by reducing the number of
governmental regions from 49 to 12, thereby granting local
governments more power.
	   If the plan goes through as scheduled, as of next Jan. 1, Opole
province, would join with the industrial region of Katowice to
become part of a larger Silesian province.
	   Opole residents, who believe their farming region should remain
independent, joined hands Sunday along a 90-kilometer (56 mile)
stretch of highway linking their provincial capital Wroclaw to
Katowice.
	   Parliament voted Friday to reduce the number of provinces to 12,
but lengthy parliamentary debates and continuing protests forced
the government to add three additional regions to the plan, one of
which would be Opole.
	   (ajs-me)
</TEXT>
