</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> LONG-MARCH-AGAINST-PEACE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Long march is against peace: PM, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Long march is against peace: PM, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Special CorrespondentASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina has expressed her surprise at the
long march programme of the opposition BNP towards the Chittagong
Hill Tracts (CHT) where a peaceful environment is prevailing
following the signing of the CHT accord.
	   Addressing the inaugural function of the Dhaka University Alumni
Association Convention on Saturday, the Prime Minister said that
she had formed the government of consensus to build the country and
included four ministers from other political parties depriving her
own party people who sacrificed a lot in the past to bring the
party into power.
	   ``We want to build the country and to change the fate of the
common people and, therefore, we believe in the politics of
participation and consensus,'' Sheikh Hasina said.
	   She said that responding to her call to join the government of
consensus, two persons joined the government initially and the two
others joined recently. ``But it's unfortunate that the main
opposition party has launched movement against us,'' she said.
	   The Prime Minister said that they (BNP) was pressing for
scrapping the CHT peace accord and the Ganges Water Sharing Treaty.
	   Sheikh Hasina said that there had been disturbance in the CHT
and it was her government which could bring about peace there by
signing the peace accord.
	   ``It will be possible now to develop the one-tenth of the
country because of the signing of the peace accord,'' she said
adding: ``But the peaceful environment there has disturbed this
peace in the minds of some persons and they have planned to go to
the CHT to set ablaze the peace accord.''
	   Without mentioning the name of any party or person, Sheikh
Hasina said that according to the press report, they had planned to
start the 'long march' in a convoy of about 1000 vehicles.
	   The Prime Minister said that disturbance and bloodshed would
start again in the CHT if the peace accord was scrapped. ``I wonder
how a sane person can desire such a situation,'' she said.
	   Add: Hasina
	   UNB adds: Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said no level headed
person can go for a long march against peace, nor want resumption
of warlike situation in the CHT region.
	   ``If the peace agreement is rescinded, the region will again
plunge into violence and blood-bath, a situation none can desire,''
she said.
	   About campus violence, she said the government is determined to
wipe out all kinds of terrorism from the campuses and taking strict
action in this regard.
	   ``The situation has improved a lot,'' she said adding that the
government will never hesitate to take action against the
terrorists whichever party they might belong.
	   ``We've never patronised terrorism and will never do so in
future,'' the Prime Minister said and urged all irrespective of
party affiliation to cooperate in further improving the situation
on the campus.
	   She said the present government has no need to give shelter to
the terrorists, nor use the students in power politics.
	   She added: ``We've a well-knit, strong political organisation
... we also believe that people is the source of all power.''
	   The inaugural function, presided over by Alumni Association
president Prof Muzaffar Ahmed, was also addressed, among others, by
the oldest alumnus Prof Sirajul Haque (1923-27 academic year), DU
Vice-Chancellor and chief patron of the association Prof AK Azad
Chowdhury, convenor of the convention preparatory committee and
former Finance Minister AMA Muhit and another alumnus Din Mohammad
Khan (1956-60 academic year).
	   The Prime Minister said in the past the student forces were used
by the military dictators for capturing and consolidating power.
	   They have given firearms to the innocent students and used them
for their narrow political interest, she said adding, but Awami
League had no need to use the student for political gain.
	   Hasina said in 1993, she imposed a moratorium on the activities
of Chhatra League although, she said, it is not a political wing of
Awami League, rather an individual institution.
	   There is no existence of student front in the constitution of
Awami League.
	   Chhatra League was born a year before the birth of Awami League,
she added.
	   ``Even though, I suspended the activities of Chhatra League and
requested other parties, including BNP, to stop activities of their
student fronts. But my cry was went in vain,'' she added.
	   ``This (Dhaka) University had a glory and tradition, this
university has been considered as the Oxford of the East,'' she
said adding ``being a student of this university I feel proud. But
it had lost its glory and the student had lost their respectable
position.''
	   Now all will have to work together to regain the lost glory of
the students, restore peaceful atmosphere on the campus and regain
the confidence of the people on students.
	   The Prime Minister said the government has attached special
importance to the expansion of education and kept highest budgetary
allocation for education sector.
	   ``We want to remove illiteracy from the country by the year
2006,'' she said elaborating the measures of the government in this
regard.
	   Addressing the function, the oldest alumnus Prof Sirajul Haque
spoke against campus politics saying ``we should give up grouping
and politics for improving campus environment.''
	   Everybody should remain alert in the present situation, said the
oldest alumnus advising all to be a bit sacrificing for greater
interest.
	   VC Prof AK Azad Chowdhury said terrorism and financial scarcity
are the two main problems of Dhaka University.
	   In last two years, the campus situation was improved, he said
and added the situation will improve further if emphasis can be
laid on socio-economic causes behind the terrorism.
	   He pointed out that moral degradation, socio-economic
discrimination, unemployment, lack of tolerance among political
parties, lack of democratic mentality and delay in trial of
terrorists and flexibility towards terrorism are the main causes
behind the deterioration of campus situation.
	   Ministers, MPs, teachers, former students and elite of the city
attended the inaugural function while the alumni passed the whole
day at the green lawn of TSC to enjoy the function and recall the
memories of the old days.
	   
</TEXT>
