<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan-Gueugnon,0304 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Japan beats second division side 1-0 in warmup match
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ Japan's best barely managed a 1-0
win against France's Second Division Gueugnon in a warmup game
Sunday ahead of the World Cup.
	   Forward Masashi Nakayama headed in a goal early in the first
half.
	   Japanese coach Takeshi Okada declared his disappointment. ``I'd
have liked to win 2-0 or 3-0,'' he said after the game in this
lakeside resort that will serve as Japan's base camp during the
tournament.
	   Okada changed all his players except one for the second half,
even using 17-year-old Daisuke Ichikawa, who has been dropped from
the roster but is traveling with the team.
	   ``We wanted the players to get used to the game,'' Okada said.
	   Midfielder Motohiro Yamaguchi, captain in place of injured
defender Masami Ihara, said the main purpose of the game was to
help the players improve their physical condition.
	   ``We also wanted to reconfirm the way we were going to approach
the game,'' he said. ``With every game, the team is getting into
good form.''
	   Okada acknowledged Japan's opener against Argentina was sure to
be far tougher. ``Naturally, we're going to have to play more
defense,'' he said.
	   Gueugnon captain Richard Trivino said he was so impressed with
the Japanese he believes they have a chance against Argentina.
``Anything is possible,'' he said.
	   Gueugnon coach Alain Dessoly also praised the Japanese team.
``France and Japan will go to the finals; how's that?'' he joked.
	   Yamaguchi said all the Japanese players realize Argentina is
heavily favored. ``But we hope to give them one heck of a
surprise,'' he said.
	   (yk-sl)
</TEXT>
