	   Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina on Saturday urged the Awami League
leaders and workers to remain alert against the destructive
activities of the opposition BNP, which is out to foil the existing
peace and stability in the country.
	   ``You have to consolidate party activities and earn people's
confidence to foil the ill motives of the BNP,'' she said while
addressing the leaders and workers of Rajshahi district and city
units of Awami League and its front organisations at Ganobhaban on
Saturday afternoon.
	   She said the people have voted Awami League to power and the
government has a responsibility to serve them and protect their
interests. She said the Awami League leaders and workers made lot
of sacrifices to establish the rights of the people. ``Now you have
to make more sacrifices and work for the emancipation of the
people,'' she said.
	   Sheikh Hasina said the opposition BNP is trying to create chaos
and confusion by making artificial crisis of essential commodities
like salt, rice and onions. ``They are making people hostage to
stage a come back to power,'' she added.
	   She also referred to the attack made on the Speaker at the
Jatiya Sangsad and said all their activities were directed to
create anarchy in society.
	   She said the economic activities in the northern region of the
country would be geared up following the commission of the
Bangabandhu Jamuna Bridge. She said that tourist spots would be
developed at both sides of the bridge while mills and factories
would be set up in the northern region.
	   Food and Agriculture Minister Matia Chowdhury, State Minister
for Primary Education Prof Jinatunnesa Talukdar, Joint General
Secretary of Awami League Mozaffar Hossain Paltu, Publicity
Secretary Abdul Mannan, Office Secretary Abdul Mannan Khan,
Rajshahi District Awami League President Rakhal Chandra Das and
General Secretary Tajul Islam Mohammad Faruque, Rajshahi City Awami
League President Mahbubuzzaman Bhulu and General Secretary
Khairuzzaman Liton, former Rajshahi District Awami League President
Advocate Mohammad Mohsin and former City Awami League President
Mohammad Muniruzzaman were present.
	   
</TEXT>
