<HEADLINE>
JCD, GCO protest, BCL hails PM's visit to DU campus, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
JCD, GCO protest, BCL hails PM's visit to DU campus, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   DU CorrespondentASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Jatiyatabadi Chhatra Dal (JCD) and the Ganotantrik Chhatra
Oikya (GCO) held separate protest rallies, while the
ruling-party-backed Bangladesh Chhatra League (BCL) brought out a
welcome procession over the arrival of Prime Minister's Sheikh
Hasina on the Dhaka University campus on Saturday.
	   The Prime Minister inaugurated the Dhaka University Alumni
Convention at the Teacher-Student Centre (TSC) auditorium on
Saturday morning. A large contingent police was deployed at
different key points on the campus to avert violence the police
restricted the movement of motor vehicles on the campus during the
Prime Minister's presence there.
	   The JCD staged a demonstration protesting ``suppression'' on and
filing of ``false'' cases by the government against its members.
The GCO protested the PM's arrival and demanded that its 10-point
demand be implemented. It condemned police action on the GCO
activists few days back. Female students of the JCD fastened their
mouths with black cloths during the demonstration.
	   Leaders of the JCD while speaking at a rally at the main
building of the Arts Faculty Building demanded immediate release of
the JCD President Shahid Uddin Chowdhury Anee and other arrested
JCD members.
	   The students community had expressed their resentment against
the Prime Minister's arrival on the campus, the JCD leaders said.
	   The JCD's acting President Abdul Khaleq, General secretary
Habibun Nabi Sohel, Organising Secretary Monwar Hossain Rana,
Saiful Islam Nirab, among others, addressed the rally.
	   The GCO, an alliance of the left leaning student organisations
held a rally at the foot of the Aparajaya Bangla. The leaders of
the alliance accused the government of suppressing the students
community with the help of the police.
	   Hasan Hafizur Rahman Sohel, Dipankar Saha Dipu and
Monjur-e-Khoda Tariq, among others addressed the rally.
	   The BCL (S-P), on the other hand, brought out a procession to
welcome the arrival of the Prime Minister at about 10 am.
	   
