<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Protest Crackdown </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Junta opponents say 62 arrested during protests
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ At least one protester was killed and 62
others were arrested during recent anti-government demonstrations
in Nigeria, a leading opposition group said Sunday.
	   The Joint Action Committee for Nigeria did not say where or how
the one person was killed, but claimed it was linked to police
efforts to break up protests last week.
	   The demonstrations in the commercial capital of Lagos and the
nearby university town of Ibadan were held to mark the second
anniversary of the unexplained killing of Kudirat Abiola, wife of
imprisoned politician Moshood Abiola.
	   Authorities in Ibadan had arrested at least seven student
leaders on the eve of the June 4 anniversary.
	   While most of the 62 arrests announced Sunday took place in
Lagos and Ibadan, a number of Joint Action Committee members were
also detained in the northern city of Kano, the group said in a
written statement issued Sunday.
	   Elsewhere, authorities in southern Nigeria ordered three small
college campuses closed in anticipation of more civil unrest.
	   Student activists have vowed to stage large protest marches on
Friday to mark the fifth anniversary of Gen. Sani Abacha's military
coup.
	   June 12 marks the day in 1993 when Abacha canceled presidential
elections and launched his military takeover. Abacha has since been
accused of rampant corruption and widespread human rights abuses.
	   It was about this time when Moshood Abiola _ the apparent winner
of the elections _ was arrested and charged with treason for
declaring himself president.
	   In an attempt to avoid a repeat of anti-Abacha violence on June
12, authorities ordered colleges in Ife, Ilorin and Ogbomosho shut.
	   The military has vowed to step down in favor of an elected
civilian government, but repeatedly reneges on the promise.
 &UR; (fa/ids)
