<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blair calls Clinton and Yeltsin as pressure mounts on Serbs over
</HEADLINE>
Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Starting a week of international pressure on
Yugoslavia over Kosovo, British Prime Minister Tony Blair on Sunday
spoke to U.S. President Clinton and they agreed to send a ``strong
message '' that a Serb offensive in the restive province is
unacceptable, an aide said.
	   Blair, current president of the European Union, also had a
30-minute phone call with President Boris Yeltsin, urging the
Russian leader to use his influence with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to stop Serb forces' ``barbarism'' against
civilians, the aide added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   Earlier, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Milosevic had
``crossed the threshold'' this week with offenses by Serb troops
against ethnic Albanians, who comprise 90 percent of the population
n Kosovo.
	   ``The use of tanks, of artillery, of the might of the military
army against civilian centers of population is wholly unacceptable
within the modern Europe,'' said Cook, answering questions at the
end of a weekend meeting of 1,200 voluntary workers and others from
the EU and neighboring countries.
	   The London meeting, called the People's Europe, was held ahead
of a summit next week of the 15-nation EU.
	   Cook, saying Milosevic must be kept guessing, refused to say
what steps the EU or the six-national Contact Group, which monitors
Yugoslavia and includes Russia and the United States, might take.
	   But there was speculation that the Blair is seeking to get
Russia to agree on possible military intervention in Kosovo.
	   British newspapers reported that Blair told a Cabinet meeting
last week the British troops might have to be sent to Kosovo,
saying ``we have to be'' prepared to use force.
	   In Kosovo, ethnic Albanian officials said the Serbs' latest
offensive has left at least 50 people dead and 200 missing, and
sent thousands fleeing from ruined villages in the west of the
territory, which is a province of Serbia, the dominant republic in
Yugoslavia.
	   The issue will be discussed by foreign ministers of the
15-nation EU in Brussels on Monday, by NATO defense ministers on
Thursday, and in London on Friday by foreign ministers of the Group
of Eight top industrialized nations - the United States, Russia,
Japan, Canada, Britain, France, Germany and Italy.
	   ``We want to make sure that he (Milosevic) is kept guessing as
to what might actually happen,'' said Cook. ``But we want him to
know that he cannot go on this way and expect us to turn a blind
eye. We are not going to do that.''
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
