<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US Training,0461 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Full American team trains together for first time since assembling
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ For the first time since
the Americans assembled in California nearly a month ago, all 22
U.S. players trained together Sunday at the squad's practice site.
	   Frankie Hejduk, who has been bothered by a hamstring injury,
returned Saturday, and Tab Ramos, who's been slowed by a sore right
calf, and Ernie Stewart, hampered by a bad right ankle, rejoined
the group Sunday.
	   It was the first time since U.S. coach Steve Sampson called the
players together on May 11 in San Diego that they practiced as a
full squad.
	   The isolation at Chateau de Pizay in southern France is starting
to get to some players, despite only arriving a day earlier and
even though they say it's good for their concentration.
	   ``We're far away from the World Cup hoopla,'' playmaking
midfielder Claudio Reyna said. ``A lot of guys, me included, would
like to be closer to the action and feel the World Cup spirit.''
	   Reyna is the offensive soul of the American team, having been
handed the reigns of the squad by coach Steve Sampson.
	   The 24-year-old son of an Argentine father and a Portuguese
mother had even more pressure dumped on him in April when Sampson
cut ``captain-for-life'' John Harkes and insinuated that Reyna's
on-field freedom was one of the reasons.
	   ``I do feel pressure and I do feel responsible for how the team
does,'' Reyna said. ``I still don't feel I had any part to do with
him being released.''
	   Many interpreted Sampson's subsequent comments to mean that he
felt Reyna was intimidated by Harkes' presence and didn't have the
confidence to perform at his best.
	   Sampson has tried to install a five-man midfield for over two
years, and after dropping Harkes, broadened it to six with Reyna as
the central figure.
	   ``I think it is an alignment that gives him more freedom, not
that he couldn't play in another formation or system,'' Sampson
said. ``But when there are at least two holding midfielders behind
him, it gives him the freedom to attack more, and a player with
that kind of freedom welcomes it, and you saw the result in
Austria.''
	   The United States dominated the Austrians in Vienna, with Reyna
scoring one and setting up the other two in a 3-0 victory on April
22.
	   With Reyna in the lineup, the Americans beat Kuwait 2-0 last
month. But when he sat out exhibition games against Macedonia and
Scotland, the U.S. team wound up with a pair of scoreless ties.
	   ``There are certain players that need to play well for us to
succeed as a team,'' Sampson said, ``and he is one of them.''
</TEXT>
