<BODY>
<SLUG> OPPOSITION-FEARS-CLASHES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition fears clashes during long march, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Opposition fears clashes during long march, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Staff ReporterASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Brisk preparations are afoot to make the long march to the
Chittagong Hill Tracts a grand success. The two-day long political
showdown by the Opposition BNP and its allies is scheduled to begin
from Dhaka towards the hill district of Khagrachhari on Tuesday.
	   With only two days left for the grand programme, the BNP and its
front organisations have made massive preparations to mobilise
thousands of party workers from different districts and lead them
towards Khagrachhari.
	   The Jamaat-e-Islami, Bangladesh, and the Jatiya Party
(Zafar-Moazzem) have also prepared their workers to join the march
separately.
	   Coinciding with the opposition programme, the ruling Awami
League is preparing to stage peace rallies throughout the country
on June 9 and 10. An announcement in this regard will be made by
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina at a public meeting today.
	   The local units of the BNP in different areas are also making
preparations to bring out peace processions coinciding with the
long march. The opposition parties apprehend that there might be
clashes during the long march in many areas. They fear that Feni
district, through which the marchers will proceed, may be a hot
spot. Meanwhile the rival groups in Feni have also engaged
themselves in clashes centring on the issue of long march. On
Thursday night houses of two leaders of the BNP and the Awami
League were burnt down by the activists.
	   The long march programme was earlier announced by the Leader of
the Opposition, Begum Khaleda Zia, on the conclusion of a token
hunger strike at the Palton ground in Dhaka on May 12.
	   The programme is being organised to oppose the enactment of laws
making provision for a regional council and the hill distinct
council in line with the peace accord signed on the Chittagong Hill
Tracts by the Awami League government.
	   According to the schedule, Begum Khaleda Zia will lead the march
from Dhaka towards Chittagong while Deputy leader of the Opposition
Professor Badruddoza Chowdhury will lead the march from Chittagong
to the Khagrachhari hill district headquarters.
	   Meanwhile, the long march supervisory committee headed by BNP
leader Oli Ahmed held a meeting with the sub-committee members at
the Minto Road office of the Leader of the Opposition last evening
to study the latest situation.
	   The liaison committee for the political and professional groups
also held a meeting in this connection with M. Shamsul Islam Khan,
MP, in the chair yesterday.
	   A joint meeting of different sub-committees formed in connection
with the long march will be held at 29, Minto Road office at 11 am
today.
	   The BNP has already instructed its district units to mobilise at
least one bus from each thana to fetch its workers for the march.
The Dhaka city unit has also arranged accommodation for the large
number of workers who will throng the capital to join the long
march. The party office, community centres and educational
institutions will be used as shelters for the outside workers.
	   The BNP and its front organisations on Saturday organised
processions and rallies at the district level to mobilise public
support for the long march.
	   UNB adds: The opposition camp says, it will absolutely be a
peaceful march, but warned of serious consequences if any
obstruction is created on their way.
	   The government is learnt to have sent necessary instructions to
the district administration to remain alert.
	   Additional police forces are being deployed all along the route
that will pass through thana and district headquarters on June 9-10
(Tuesday-Wednesday) to avert any untoward incident.
	   The Chittagong Metropolitan Police have sought an extra 1,000
police personnel from the headquarters to step up the security
measures.
	   Political sources hinted that strategies of the BNP, the Jamaat
and their allies were engaged in behind-the-scene parleys to
prepare themselves for a follow-up action programme.
	   Opposition leaders are working on two sets of programme, both
soft and tough, to match the situation. This may even mean keeping
an option for a tough programme forcing the government for a
mid-term election.
	   The post-Long March programme may range from countrywide
protests to shutdowns, a close aide of Begum Zia said. ``This is
just the beginning,'' he added.
	   If things go well and end peacefully, the BNP marchers are
scheduled to assemble at the Khagrachhari Outer Stadium, where
Begum Zia will address a public meeting.
	   City Jamaat-e-Islami leaders yesterday called upon all the
patriotic people to take part in the historic long march to make it
a grand success.
	   A meeting of the presidents and secretaries of all the city
thana units of the party yesterday reviewed the preparation of the
long march. The Jamaat City Ameer A T M Azharul Islam presided over
the meeting held at its Paltan office.
	   Our Staff Correspondent from Chittagong adds: BNP organised a
mass procession in the port city and held a public meeting at
Laldighi crossing yesterday to drum up support for the march
towards hill tracts.
	   Chittagong(north) unit of the party told the newsmen that at
least five thousand volunteers would be deployed at key points on
way to Khagrachhari from Mirerswari. Reception centres will be set
up on the way to welcome the marchers.
	   Earlier on Friday, BNP leader Abdullah-Al Noman visited
Khagrachhari and held public meetings at all thana headquarters to
make the long march programme a grand success. He also held a
meeting with the Minister without port folio Kalparanjan Chakma and
the Deputy Commissioner of the district seeking their cooperation
for a peaceful long march.
	   The district administration and the police authorities
separately held meetings with the unity council and the ruling
party in a bid to keep the situation under control. Our Rangamati
Correspondent reports: Parbatya Sarbadaliya Oikya Parishad (the all
party unity council) held a meeting today to make the long march
programme a success.
	   They decided to welcome the marchers in the morning of June 10
at the district entry point at Goderpar and at the pourashava gate
of Manikchhari.
	   A grand rally will also be held at the old court building ground
of the district at 11 am.
	   According to our Bandarban correspondent, preparations have been
completed to mobilise party workers from all the six thanas of the
district and transport them by 30 to 40 buses to Khagrachhari and
Rangamati.
	   District Awami League president Prasanta Kanti Tanchainga and a
Jana Sanghati leader said they were in favour of peace and would
not follow any course of confrontation or counter programme.
	   Council of Hill People (CHP) at a meeting has urged all
patriotic people, students, youths, freedom fighters,
intellectuals, journalists, lawyers and other professionals to make
the long march on June 9 a success.
	   A meeting of the Council was held yesterday at Reserve Bazar,
Rangamati with its central chairman Jalal Uddin Ahmed Chowdhury
Alamgir in the chair.
	   
</TEXT>
