<BODY>
<SLUG> SIX-HOUR-POWER-CUT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Six-hour power cut for big companies, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Six-hour power cut for big companies, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Staff ReporterASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Dhaka Electric Supply Authorities (DESA) , in a drastic move to
save electricity, have asked major industries to shut down for six
hours every day. Industry sources said that it would cause at least
13 per cent production loss if they failed to run industries for
six hours.
	   It seems that the DESA has taken the measures keeping in view
the requirement of increased power for domestic purposes during
ensuing world cup football.
	   The DESA in a letter sent on May 25 to the management of various
industries asked they should keep their operations suspended from 5
p.m. to 11 p.m. every day.
	   ``Acute shortage of electricity during the peak hours has been
the main cause for such directives,'' one DESA official said on
Saturday.
	   He said similar notices had been served on different companies
including British American Tobacco Bangladesh Limited, Philips
Bangladesh Limited and all other enterprises located in Dhaka's
Tejgaon industrial area.
	   Energy ministry officials said Bangladesh required more than
2,200 megawatt of electricity every day but the country generates
only 1700 megawatts.
	   They said the situation turned worse during summer, severely
affecting water supply as well. ``We are trying to improve power
management through efficient rationing and redistribution of supply
as per priority,'' one official said. In an avergae 600 m.w
loadshedding is recorded everyday.
	   Others said the government had asked the DESA to ensure maximum
possible power supply in Dhaka.
	   ``We received the DESA notice asking not to use electricity in
the pick hours. They also warned that if the order is not obeyed
the connections will be cut off,'' said Mahmudur Rahman, chief
corporate manager of B.A.T.
	   ``There will be at least 13 per cent production loss if we close
for six hours, as we used to remain open round the clock,'' Rahman
told The Independent. .
	   ``There will be a revenue loss of six million Taka per day.''
	   DESA officials said the peak hour demand for electricity in the
city's industrial areas, having 416 garment factories and many
others, was 87 megawatt but they could supply less than 50 per cent
only.
	   The government has also asked shopping centres in the capital to
close down by 7 p.m. Electricity connections to many shops have
already been cut off for defying the order, DESA officials said.
	   Operators of irrigation pumps supplying water to agricultural
farms have been asked to switch on between 11 p.m. and 6 a.m.
	   ``The garment sector in the country is losing about 2.4 billion
Taka every month for acute crisis in power supply,'' said an
industrialist.
	   ``The frozen food sector is losing about 10 million Taka per
month,'' another businessman said.
	   The commercial rate for using electricity in normal hours is
2.45 Taka per unit (1,000 watts) and in pick hours (from 5 p.m. to
11 p.m.) is 5.7 Taka, DESA officials said.
	   ``We are ready to pay more than double rates but still we are
not getting power,'' another industrialist said.
	   ``Production in manufacturing units have been declining fast due
to frequent power failure and load-shedding,'' he said.
	   Haider said export-oriented industries might not meet their
production targets and run into problems with the importers.
	   Shop owners said their sales turnover had fallen by up to 60 per
cent as they were forced to pull down shutters by 7 p.m.
	   ``Most of the customers prefer the evening time for shopping,''
a trader at Dhaka's New Market said.
	   The government is under serious pressure from various groups,
including students, to ensure uninterrupted power supply during the
forthcoming soccer World Cup.
	   ``Even we are receiving threats over telephone that power plants
will be set ablaze if electricity supply is not ensured during the
World Cup matches,'' one DESA official said.
	   Officials blame the precarious power situation partly on long
delays in overhauling the old plants and in setting up new ones.
	   
</TEXT>
