<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Africa Arrival,0370 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: South Africa arrives for first World Cup appearance
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITS to fix category coding &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VICHY, France (AP) _ Hundreds of townspeople, including children
holding soccer balls, greeted South Africa's soccer team when it
arrived Sunday in this central French town for its first World Cup.
	   A police motorcade escorted the South African team bus for the
final 10 kilometers (six miles) of the trip, and the crowd cheered
the players when they got off, team manager Augusto Palacios said.
	   ``Wonderful. It was tremendous. The players loved it,'' he said.
	   South Africa will be based in Vichy for the tournament, holding
its training sessions on local sports fields and traveling to
Marseilles, Toulouse and Bordeaux for its three first-round matches
against Pool C opponents France, Denmark and Saudi Arabia.
	   Considered a longshot to advance to the second round, the South
African enter the tournament never having beaten a European or
Middle Eastern country. In their final tuneup on Saturday in
Germany, the South Africans conceded a late goal and settled for a
1-1 draw with Iceland.
	   Benni McCarthy of Ajax Amsterdam scored the South African goal
in the 36th minute, but a 73rd minute strike by Stefan Thordarsen
tied it up for Iceland.
	   South African coach Phillipe Troussier, a Frenchman who took
over in March, has put together a team of mostly European-based
players in hopes of having battle-ready veterans for the
tournament.
	   But the lack of preparation time, and adapting to Troussier's
European-style ball-control system, has caused South Africa
problems in scoring goals in its recent matches. Under Troussier,
South Africa tied Zambia 1-1 and lost 2-0 to Argentina prior to
Saturday night's draw.
	   South Africa plays its first match on Friday against host France
in Marseilles and will be the underdog, a position Troussier says
he likes because it puts pressure on the French to perform in front
of their fans.
	   It is the first World Cup appearance for South Africa, which was
banned from international soccer for 28 years until 1992 because of
apartheid.
	   (tsc-sl)
</TEXT>
