<SLUG> LDCS-URGED-TO-ORGANISE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LDCs urged to organise themselves to realise their rightful demands Tofail briefs representatives to UN in NY, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
LDCs urged to organise themselves to realise their rightful demands Tofail briefs representatives to UN in NY, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Commerce and Industries Ministers Tofail Ahmed has urged the
least developed countries ( LDCs) to organise themselves to realise
their rightful demands, particularly in securing duty-free market
access and opening up to trading opportunities.
	   The minister said this while briefing the permanent
representatives of LDCs to the United Nations in New York
yesterday, according to a message received here yesterday.
	   He hoped that in the upcoming substantive session of the ECOSOC
the LDCs will take united initiative for the implementation of the
preferential treatment for LDCs.
	   Permanent representative of Bangladesh to the United Nations
Anwarul Karim Chowdhury chaired the meeting.
	   Referring to the mandate of the seventh annual ministerial
meeting of LDCs at the UN last year Tofail said Bangladesh Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina had carried out this mandate given by the
ministers of 48 LDCs. While explaining the role of Bangladesh as a
coordinator of LDCs, Tofail referred to the letter written by Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina to British Prime Minister Tony Blair prior
to the G-8 summit in Birmingham on May 17 last.
	   This was in response to a mandate given to her by LDCs at the
seventh annual ministerial meeting in New York, he said.
	   Tofail drew attention of the permanent representatives to the
final outcome of the Birmingham summit and said all the proposals
of Sheikh Hasina had been positively reflected there.
	   He said the announcement provided for duty-free access for the
goods from LDCs, mostly on an autonomous basis, undertook to help
LDCs to make markets of industrialised countries more attractive to
foreign capital flows, recommended the OECD to propose a text by
1999 to unite aid to LDCs and supported speedy implementation of
high indebted poor country ( HIPC) initiative of the international
financial institutions.
	   Earlier, the minister had a meeting with US permanent
representative to the UN Ambassador Bill Richardson. They discussed
issues of mutual interest.
	   
</TEXT>
