</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WORK-ON-TITAS-GAS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Work on Titas Gas transmission line at Narsingdi completes, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Work on Titas Gas transmission line at Narsingdi completes, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NARSINGDI, June 6: The installation work on the 41-km
transmission line of Titas Gas at a cost of Tk 308 crore and 57
lakhs between Narsingdi and Siddhirganj has been completed.
	   The 20-inch diameter line has been sunk 28 feet deep under the
Sitalakhya river bed through 'directional drilling' procedures.
	   With this, the third Natural Gas Development project of the
Titas Gas Transmission and Distribution Company, planned to supply
additional 25 crore cubic feet of gas a day to the outskirts of the
capital, has almost been completed.
	   The work on the project got off to a start in July '94 with the
financial assistance from ADB and the OECE.
	   The Singapore-based American firm Charington Asia Ltd. has taken
up the job of connecting the pipeline with the main supply across
the river.
	   The next phase of the project includes extension of Demra and
Joydebpur city gate stations, construction of regulatory and
monitoring stations at Ghorashal, Palash, and Ashuganj Zia
Fertiliser factories as well as increasing gas supply facilities to
Dhaka and other places.
	   It will now be possible, Titas sources said, to supply gas to
the under-construction 210-mw power station at Siddhirganj as well
as proposed 190, 36 and 200-mw power stations at Haripur after the
construction of the Narsingdi-Siddhirganj pipeline.
	   This will, the sources said, also help to supply gas to the four
barge-mounted power plants.
	   
</TEXT>
