<HEADLINE>
Govt urged to increase alternative assistance to export of Jamdani, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Govt urged to increase alternative assistance to export of Jamdani, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Staff ReporterASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Bangladesh Jamdani Manufacturers and Exporters Association has
urged the government to increase the alternative assistance to the
export of Jamdani to 35 per cent from present 25 per cent in the
coming budget.
	   Convenor of the association Rezaul Haque Chowdhury Mustaq spoke
at a press conference at the Jatiya Press Club yesterday. Vice
president of the association Munir Hossain, member secretary Md
Zahirul Haque, members Komol Sarker, MA Wazed and president of
Bangladesh Tanti League Khagendra Chandra Debnath were present.
	   The association convenor said they came to learn from some
sources that the existing alternative assistance for export of
Jamdani was going to be reduced in next budget. He said it would
adversely affect the promising Jamdani industry of the country.
	   Mustaq said some entrepreneurs had taken the risky initiative of
taking the Jamdani to foreign market. He said they had achieved
some success in creating market for Jamdani in India, the Middle
East, the UK and the USA. He said export of Jamdani could reduce
the existing trade imbalance between Bangladesh and India. He said
reduction of alternative assistance for the export of Jamdani would
nip in the bud the possibility.
	   The association convenor demanded extension of the time limit
for remittance of money from Jamdani export to 180 days from
existing 120 days. He also demanded giving the facility of drawing
90 per cent money through LC to the exporters of Jamdani in case of
export through purchase order which other exporters of the textile
sector were now enjoying. He demanded release of alternative
assistance money to the exporters of Jamdani within shortest
possible time.
	   Mustaq also demanded steps against terrorists who were
threatening the Jamdani industry.
	   He said Tk 26 crore was earned through export of Jamdani from
February to April last year. He said the amount of export of
Jamdani increased substantially following the alternative
assistance.
	   He said about 15,000 weavers are involved in Jamdani industry
whose livelihood would be endangered if the alternative assistance
to the export of Jamdani was reduced. He said reduction of
alternative assistance would mean destruction of Jamdani industry
like Muslin industry.
	   
</TEXT>
