<HEADLINE>
Sea liner urged not to impose surcharge, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Sea liner urged not to impose surcharge, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Chittagong Port Authority (CPA) has requested a
Singapore-based sea liner not to impose surcharge as CPA has taken
some urgent measures to ease congestion.
	   The CAP made the request in a letter on Thursday to Sea
Consortium Pvt Ltd, who last week threatened to slap congestion
surcharge on the country's main seaport from June 16, officials
said yesterday.
	   A senior official of the CPA, reached by phone from Dhaka, told
APB that they had taken some urgent measures to normalise the port
operations after the threat by the feeder liner.
	   The Sea Consortium in a letter to the CPA said they had decided
to impose the penal surcharge on Chittagong Port from June 16 if
the congestion was not removed by June 14.
	   It complained that they have to wait at outer-anchorage for days
just for berth in the port while loading and unloading take much
more time compared to other ports, causing them to bear extra
costs.
	   After receiving the letter, the CPA asked the importers to clear
their containers from the port sheds within 10 days of unloading,
lowering the time-limit from 28 days, or pay fines.
	   The officials said delays in clearing the imported containers
are one of the major causes of congestion in the port as the
importers have a tendency to use the sheds as gowdowns.
	   Also, the port authorities have taken necessary measures to
ensure round-the-clock port activities, they said.
	   Chittagong Feeder Trade Committee, the Singapore-based
association of feeder liners, had imposed congestion surcharge on
the port earlier, which took heavy toll on the country's
businesses.
	   According to an estimate by the Shipping Ministry, the exporters
and importers had to pay around 7 million US dollars extra for the
surcharge, apart from the transport costs.
	   
</TEXT>
