<HEADLINE>
Installation work of Shambhuganj power plant begins, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Installation work of Shambhuganj power plant begins, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MYMENSINGH, June 6: Installation work of a 60-megawatt
barge-mounted power plant, financed by the Asian Development Bank,
has begun at Shambhuganj.
	   Officials said ADB is bearing 70 per cent of the costs,
totalling Tk. 250 crore. The rest will be shared by the government
and five Palli Bidyut samities.
	   A consortium of Mitsubishi Engineering and Shipbuilding Company
of Japan and a European firm is implementing the turbine-driven
power plant on 30 acres of land on the bank of river Brahmaputra.
	   A German company is in charge of overall supervision of the
project and a Chinese firm will work on transmission line, the
officials said.
	   A French firm is making the ``Open Cycle'' generator for the
unit in France. It will be brought into the country and mounted on
a barge at the project site.
	   The project is expected to be completed by April next year.
Initially, the power plant will generate 60 megawatt electricity,
but its capacity will be raised up to 180 MW in phases, Project
Manager Helal Uddin told APB.
	   The electricity from the plant, one of a number of its kind
planned across the country, will be thrown into the power-hungry
national grid through the local Kewatkhali grid.
	   
</TEXT>
