<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0651 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb police beat protesters in Pristina; KLA seeks more help
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Clinton-Blair conversation, comments by British,
Yugoslav and German officials; TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serbian police beat protesters with
clubs as they worked to break up a Kosovo independence rally
Sunday.
	   At least half a dozen demonstrators were seriously injured,
according to the Kosovo Information Center, which is allied with
the separatist ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province.
	   More than 100 uniformed and plainclothes police broke up the
demonstration by ethnic Albanians in Pristina, Kosovo's capital.
Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-to-1 in Kosovo.
	   The unexpected violence in Pristina came as Serbian forces
pressed their fierce offensive against militants in western Kosovo,
where shelling reportedly continued Sunday.
	   The stepped-up Serbian campaign launched in late May has left at
least 50 people dead, 200 missing and thousands fleeing their
destroyed villages, according to ethnic Albanian officials.
	   Pristina itself had remained largely free of violence despite
months of clashes this year between Serbs trying to assert their
control over the province and the self-described Kosovo Liberation
Army, made up of ethnic Albanians who want to drive Serb
``occupiers'' out.
	   But on Sunday, seemingly without warning, police charged the
approximately 1,000 protesters gathered for the 57th consecutive
daily rally against Serbian rule.
	   One protester could be seen bleeding in the street after he was
hit in the head by a policeman's gun butt and then kicked
repeatedly.
	   It was the first attack on protesters since March, when
thousands of ethnic Albanians were attacked for protesting an
earlier crackdown by government forces.
	   Albanian TV in Tirana reported that the Serbs shelled at least
two Kosovo villages Sunday. It also said ethnic Albanian militants
blew up the police headquarters in Ratkoc, and, amid fierce
fighting between the two sides, all the Serb residents and police
had fled.
	   It is not clear how much of a setback the Serb offensive has
dealt Kosovo's clandestine rebel army, which claims to control some
40 percent of the southern province of Yugoslavia's Republic of
Serbia, and which enjoys growing popularity.
	   The KLA appealed in a statement published Sunday in the
newspaper Koha Ditore for more ethnic Albanians to join them and
``fight for freedom'' from Serbian forces.
	   ``Come to strengthen our troops against the enemy artillery and
enemy infantry,'' the statement said.
	   Western powers, fearing another border change in the volatile
Balkans, oppose Kosovo's bid for independence, but want the Serbs
to cease their offensive and give Kosovo the autonomy taken away by
Serbia in 1989.
	   The offensive that began in late May has stirred increasing
international concern and fears of igniting a wider war in the
Balkans. Pope John Paul II called on the world Sunday to act
against violence and repression in Kosovo.
	   The United States and others are deliberating on what steps to
take, with a reimposition of sanctions against Yugoslavia and
military intervention both under consideration.
	   British Prime Minister Tony Blair spoke to U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Sunday and they agreed to send a ``strong message ''
that a Serb offensive in the restive province is unacceptable, a
Blair aide said.
	   ``The use of tanks, of artillery, of the might of the military
army against civilian centers of population is wholly unacceptable
within the modern Europe,'' British Foreign Minister Robin Cook
said earlier.
	   The exodus of some 20,000 Kosovo Albanians into Albania last
week, and another 7,000 to 10,000 into the neighboring Yugoslav
republic of Montenegro, also has stirred worry in the West.
</TEXT>
