</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> RAMPANT-USE-OF-DDT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rampant use of DDT contaminating underground water in rural areas, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Rampant use of DDT contaminating underground water in rural areas, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The reckless use of DDT and heptachlor, the two highly-toxic
pesticides of the so-called dirty dozen family, are heavily
contaminating the underground water in the rural areas, creating
the health hazards for the people.
	   A study conducted by the National Minor Irrigation Development
Project (NMIDP) in collaboration with Bangladesh Atomic Energy
Commission (BAEC) found the sub-soil water of different regions of
the country having traces of toxic residues of pesticides - DDT and
heptachlor which are banned and allowed only for restricted use in
Bangladesh.
	   In most cases, heptachlor residues were found to be beyond the
World Health Organisation (WHO) recommended level of 0.03 microgram
per litre. One of the samples contained heptachlor residue of 0.789
microgram per litre while DDT in another sample measured 1.527
microgram per litre.
	   The sampling spread all over the country and sites adjacent to
sugarcane growing areas where heptachlor applications are
sufficiently permitted, said Ruhul Amin, a senior scientific
officer of the Institution of Food and Radiation Biology (IFRB).
	   He said the total residues of DDT found in some of the water
samples were less than permitted PPB (parts per billion). But, Amin
said, the question is that DDT is not permitted for food and
agriculture use.
	   The presence of DDT and heptachlor residues indicates that the
contraband highly toxic pesticides are still being used
indiscriminately, the study said.
	   The water samples were collected specially from the country's
irrigation-based areas including Laksam, Burirchar and Sarulia in
greater Comilla district, Gopalpur and Ghatail in Tangail,
Gobindaganj and Peerganj in Rangpur, Charbangshi in Noakhali,
Mirershawarai, Patia, Satkania and Rauzan in Chittagong and
Durgapur in Mymensingh.
	   NMIDP, a government project, supplied 169 samples from these
areas to the institution of food and radiation biology (IFRB) of
BAEC to analyse both underground as well as surface water quality.
	   Heptachlor formulation is registered for restricted use only in
sugarcane cultivation in the country.
	   Former chairman of BAEC M A Quayum said percolation of
carcinogenic pesticides including DDT and heptachlor into human
body may lead to cancer and neurological problems.
	   He said the traces of DDT and heptachlor in the underground
water of the country is a threat to human safety as billions of
people survive on tubewell water.
	   Human health would be affected by dreadful diseases if
underground water contamination is not checked by minimising the
use of toxic pesticides in agriculture, Quayum said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
