<BODY>
<SLUG> MUSHROOM-GROTH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mushroom groth of educational institutions, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Mushroom groth of educational institutions, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Staff ReporterASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Dhanmondi, the first planned elite residential area of the
capital, as dreamt by city fathers in the fifties, has now turned
into one of the busy and crowded place due to the mushroom growth
of schools, colleges, clinics and business establishments.
	   ``It looks more like a business centre than a residential place
for families to live in tranquillity and peace,'' said a senior
resident living in this area for the last 40 years.
	   About 140 schools, coaching centres and training institutes,
kindergartens, primary schools, high schools and colleges are
functioning in the area.
	   There are also several universities teaching business, computer,
medical education, agriculture etc. They are functioning in this
residential area claiming affiliation to universities in the UK and
the US and promising certificates acceptable to those universities.
	   Some of the universities here have been offering Doctor of
Philosophy (Ph D) and also Master of Science (MS) degrees to their
students ignoring their minimum standard.
	   Important universities in the area include the People's
University of Bangladesh, Darul Ehsan Medical College and
University, Asian University of Bangladesh, Dhaka International
University, Asia Pacific University, and the Bangladesh University
of Business, Agriculture and Technology.
	   Even the offices of the National University of Bangladesh and
Open University run by the government are located there.
	   Some of these universities seem to be more eager to exploit the
students than imparting them education at reasonable cost.
	   Sources said about 75 per cent of the educational institutions
now functioning in the area had no approval of the Ministries of
Education, Housing and Public Works and Environment, RAJUK, the
Dhaka City Corporation (DCC), and WASA.
	   Although such commercial ventures were not allowed to operate in
the residential areas, they are running business 'by their own
rights' almost totally ignoring traffic jams, snatching, terrorism
and other social evils that have followed their growth in the once
peaceful place of dignified living.
	   Tuition fees in the primary and English medium schools up to O
level are so high that they are above the reach of the middle
income people. And yet these schools are running to their full
capacity.
	   Some of the English medium schools have a fleet of transport
vehicles. One school which has 27 buildings and branches in the
city has up to 200 microbuses according to a source. The tuition
fees in these schools average Tk 3,000 to Tk 4,000 per month and in
some cases even up to Tk 5,000.
	   There are also madrasas, technical schools, language schools,
computer training centres, research centres, professional and human
resources development institutions, staff colleges of banks and
rest houses of public corporations. Some of these institutions have
residential facilities and own multi-storeyed buildings in the
Dhanmondi area and also its adjoining areas like Rayer Bazar, West
Dhanmondi, Jhikatala, Kalabagan, Sukrabad, Lalmatia, Mohammedpur,
Crescent Road and Green Road.
	   About 80 per cent of the students enrolled in these institutions
are outsiders attending classes from different parts of the city
and from the outskirts of the city.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
