<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria Training,0391 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Shakpore gets OK for Italy trip for shoulder
</HEADLINE>
examination &QL; 
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ELINCOURT STE.-MARGUERITE, France (AP) _ His team's backline
already in disarray, Nigeria coach Bora Milutinovic gave permission
Sunday for injured defender Jero Shakpore to fly to Italy and have
his injured shoulder examined by his club doctor.
	   Nigeria has been outscored 12-1 in its last three World Cup
tuneup matches, and Milutinovic has five days to fix the problem
before the Super Eagles open Group D play against Spain.
	   Shakpore, who turned 19 last month, hurt his left shoulder in
Friday's 5-1 rout by the Netherlands. He could be sidelined up to
five weeks.
	   ``My doctor said there is hope (to play in the World Cup) with
the right treatment,'' said the Reggiana defender, who will fly to
Italy on Monday to meet with the club doctor.
	   ``I am very sorry about what happened with Jero. It's impossible
to change bad luck,'' Milutinovic said. ``We need to concentrate on
defense and this doesn't help.''
	   If Shakpore is ruled out _ which seems likely _ Milutinovic may
replace him on the 22-man roster with Mobi Oparaku, a defender for
Belgian club Kapellen.
	   Oparaku and another non-roster player, midfielder Steve Musa,
are with the team at its 16th-century chateau training headquarters
on the outskirts of Elincourt Ste.-Marguerite, about 90 kilometers
(55 miles) north of Paris.
	   Milutinovic conducted a light practice in the rain Sunday with
players who did not see action against the Netherlands. The real
work gets underway Monday, with practices twice a day.
	   Nigeria made the second round of the World Cup in 1994, then won
the Olympic gold medal in 1996. Those successes caused some to
consider Nigeria an outside contender at this year's World Cup.
	   But the defeat by the Netherlands after other poor performances
has brought calls from the Nigerian public and news media for
Milutinovic's ouster, even though he just took over in December.
	   Milutinovic was unwilling to talk much about the rout by the
Netherlands.
	   ``We haven't had good results but we'll be ready for the (World
Cup) games,'' he said. ``I know my players are upset, but you have
to believe.''
</TEXT>
