<BODY>
<SLUG> HISTORIC-7TH-JUNE-TODAY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Historic 7th June today, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Historic 7th June today, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Historic 7th June will be observed today commemorating the
launch of mass movement on six-point demand that culminated in
independence of Bangladesh.
	   On this day way back in 1966, worker Manu Miah and several
others were killed, in police firing in Dhaka during a hartal
enforced by Awami League in the then East Pakistan, to press home
the historic 6-point charter of demands.
	   President Justice Shahabuddin Ahmed and Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina issued separate messages highlighting the significance of
the day and the demands in national life.
	   In his message President Justice Shahabuddin Ahmed said the
historic six-point demand is a charter of flourishing national
entity, and guiding the people towards the fight for protecting
their interests.
	   The subsequent movement, the President said, had unified the
people of all strata with a national spirit leading to emergence of
Bangladesh as an independent state.
	   In her message Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina called for building
a developed and glorious Bangladesh to realise the dreams of the
martyrs of historic 7th June.
	   The Prime Minister said on this day in 1966, Manu Miah, Shafiq,
Shamsul and a number of unnamed people were killed by police and
EPR firings during a hartal, called by Awami League to press for
realisation of the historic 6-point demand.
	   Hasina said the 6-point demand had shaken up the foundation of
the Pakistani autocratic rule and exploitation in this country.
	   The Prime Minister said the autonomy movement, initiated by the
Father of the Nation Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, had
gradually found its way towards the desire for independence and
armed struggle.
	   To observe the day, Awami League and its front organisations
have chalked out elaborate programmes.
	   National and party flags will be hoisted at Bangabandhu Bhaban
and party central office, party leaders will place wreaths on the
portrait of the Father of the Nation, at Bangabandhu Bhaban and a
public meeting will be held at Paltan Maidan in the afternoon.
	   Awami League President and Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina will
place wreath on the portrait of Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujib, at 8 am,
and address the rally as chief guest at 3 pm, party sources said.
	   
</TEXT>
