<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Germany's Arrival, 1st Ld-Writethru,0464 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Germany arrives brimming with confidence
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UDPATES with details of workout in new grafs 8-9; Helmer
re-aggravating thigh injury. &QL; 
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ Three-time champion Germany arrived Sunday
in France brimming with confidence that it may become only the
second nation after Brazil to win four World Cup titles.
	   ``We are on a very, very good direction,'' captain Juergen
Klinsmann before the team left Frankfurt.
	   Arriving in the south of France, the team was whisked off the
plane straight onto a bus to take it to the German training
headquarters at Mas d'Artigny, just outside St-Paul-de-Vence in the
hills above the Mediterranean resort of Nice.
	   Dozens of German fans, including many couples with children,
waited in vain in catch a glimpse of their soccer heroes.
	   Aboard the special Lufthansa flight, team members were presented
with silver key rings bearing the date July 13 _ one day after the
Paris final _ the date they will return home if they win the title.
	   The players were also served desert made in the shape of soccer
balls and shoes.
	   The Germans trained in the early evening at a stadium in Nice
and will play a tuneup game against a local team Monday.
	   All but midfielder Christian Ziege, slowed by a cold, took part
in Sunday's workout, witnessed by about 100 fans. Defender Thomas
Helmer appeared to re-aggravate a right thigh injury and received
massage therapy on the field from team medical personnel.
	   It was not immediately known how serious the injury was.
	   The Germans arrived on the heels of an impressive 7-0 thrashing
of lowly Luxembourg on Saturday in Mannheim. One week ago, Germany
posted a convincing 3-1 victory over World Cup qualifier Colombia.
	   German soccer writers were quick to point out that two years ago
Germany posted a similarly lopsided victory (9-1) over
Liechtenstein, also in Mannheim, just before leaving for England to
capture the European Championship title.
	   But coach Berti Vogts does not have to rely on superstition. The
team, led by Klinsmann, Oliver Bierhoff and Ulf Kirsten, seems to
be peaking at the right time.
	   ``My players are more refreshed now than a week before,'' Vogts
said before team departed.
	   Germany is one of the perennial World Cup favorites and Vogts
and his players are not showing any false modesty, expecting to
reach at least the semifinals.
	   The Germans will train in Nice and fly to their games. They open
against the United States on June 15 in Paris, followed by
first-round games against Yugoslavia on June 21 in Lens and against
Iran on June 24 in Montpellier.
	   (ns/jw)
</TEXT>
