<SLUG> SOCCER-FANS'-ANXIETY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Soccer fans' anxiety over loadshedding mounts, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Soccer fans' anxiety over loadshedding mounts, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   As the France World Cup, the biggest football jamboree, is
nearing on June 10, the football fans in the country are in great
anxiety about the uninterrupted watching of the games.
	   The BTV has already announced to telecast live 56 matches. But
frequent power failure due to short-production of electricity in
the country has threatened the uninterrupted viewing of the
matches.
	   The anxiety has been surfaced in a survey by Democracy Watch.
	   The survey showed that 80.70 per cent spectator will react
against the failure of the government for load shedding during the
World Cup matches.
	   The World Cup is bringing a major rescheduling in the daily
works of the majority of the urban people.
	   Office-goers, examinees, students and even housewives are
sketching new plans of their daily works to accommodate the World
Cup fixture.
	   Some 42.4 percent of the respondents agreed that regular works
would be hampered by the World Cup while 51.8 percent answered
negative.
	   Some 51.6 per cent respondents favoured rescheduling of
examinations during the matches and 47.4 per cent against.
	   Over 86 per cent female respondents will watch the matches while
the male percentage is about 90.
	   Brazil is the top favourite team with 43.7 per cent vote
followed by Argentina with 33.5 per cent, Italy 8.5 and Germany 3.5
and 5.8 per cent supported the other teams.
	   The survey was conducted on May 24-25 at different areas of
Dhaka and Chittagong.
	   Some 486 people were interviewed on various aspects of the forth
coming World Cup.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
