<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-Refugee Children </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kosovo children survive trek to Albania alone
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BAJ101-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By ARLINDA CAUSHOLLI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAJRAM CURRI, Albania (AP) _ Six ethnic Albanian children who
survived a dangerous three-day walk across the mountains from
Kosovo on their own were reunited Sunday with their joyful mothers.
	   ``It is incredible that I'm in the arms of my mother again,''
said 6-year Rexh Sasa of a reunion that her mother had given up
hope for.
	   The children's story provided a rare bright moment in the grim
exodus of what Albanian officials say is 20,000 Kosovo refugees to
their destitute neighboring country in the past week.
	   Another 7,000 to 10,000 ethnic Albanians have fled the Serb
offensive into Montenegro, the other republic left in Yugoslavia
besides Serbia.
	   Many of the villages the refugees left behind are reported badly
damaged or destroyed, and some people died as a result of the
arduous trek.
	   The six children, ranging in age from 4 to 14, left the besieged
village of Decani in western Kosovo as part of a group of over 100
refugees late Wednesday.
	   ``We had to leave _ Decani is completely destroyed by the
Serbian artillery,'' said 34-year-old Fale Caca, mother of four of
the children. ``Because of the Serbs, it has ceased to exist.''
	   On Thursday, the children became separated from the others when
the Serbian military attacked them with grenades, bombs and sniper
fire, according to the ethnic Albanians' account.
	   As of Sunday, Caca said, the extent of any casualties to the
rest of the fleeing group still wasn't known.
	   One of her daughters was the oldest of the missing children. A
small piece of bread she was carrying was all the children had to
eat during the ordeal.
	   ``I was very scared but I didn't want to tell them, otherwise
they would be more scared than me,'' said Shipe Caca, 14, who held
her 4-year-old brother in her arms for most of the trip.
	   A man from the border town of Bajram Curri, 28-year-old Xhevdej
Beqiri, found the children in the mountains on the Albanian side on
Saturday _ exhausted, hungry and with blisters on their bare feet.
He brought them to his apartment, where 25 Kosovo residents now are
staying, including 16 children.
	   The two mothers, who had made their way with the others to the
Albanian border town of Tropoja on Friday, were brought to the
children on Sunday.
	   ``I never believed I'd see my four children again,'' said the
weeping Caca, trembling with emotion. ``It was the most beautiful
gift that God has given me.''
	   (ac/dc)
</TEXT>
