<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Argentina-Rumors ,0404 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Despite denials, suspicions persist over doping
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VICENTE LEONARDO PANETTA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   L'ETRAT, France (AP) _ Official denials didn't quite erase
suspicions Sunday that an Argentine player may have tested positive
for a banned substance in a doping control conducted by the World
Cup team.
	   Coach Daniel Passarella and a player, Juan Veron, angrily denied
any doping after an Argentine radio station reported the case and
suggested that the midfielder was involved.
	   However, the team's physician, Dr. Luis Seveso, looked nervous
and contradicted himself at the news conference Saturday, fueling
the impression that something had happened.
	   ``It's possible that some substance might have showed up, but it
is well known that several players had the flu,'' Seveso said.
	   Other than Veron, offensive midfielder Marcelo Gallardo and
defender Pablo Paz are known to have the flu.
	   Seveso added that no doping had been uncovered and challanged
journalists ``to say what banned substance was involved.''
	   ``People are talking a lot of nonsense,'' he declared.
	   Later, the physician announced he was planning Saturday night to
``visit each room and tell the players not to take any medicine
without my consent.''
	   Passarella said he was ``tired of denying silly rumors. Lets
talk about soccer, please.''
	   Most of the 200 Argentine journalists who followed the team to
France for the month-long World Cup believe there was a drug
violation involving an anti-flu medicine, although probably not
serious enough to prompt sanctions.
	   On Sunday, team officials closed the team headquarters in this
village in the south of France to the news media until Tuesday.
	   The Argentine Soccer Association has acted with a strong hand in
doping cases, mindful of previous incidents that disrupted the
World Cup team.
	   At the 1994 World Cup in the United States, Diego Maradona
tested positive for ephedrine, a banned stimulant, and was
suspended for 15 months. Argentina was eliminated in the second
round.
	   In 1991, Maradona was suspended for 15 months by FIFA and the
Italian soccer federation for using cocaine. Another Argentine
international, Claudio Paul Caniggia, was also banned for 15 months
for using cocaine.
	   Neither Maradona nor Caniggia are in the current team.
</TEXT>
