<SLUG> CHECKPOSTS-TO-WARN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Checkposts to warn pollution prone vehicles in city, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Checkposts to warn pollution prone vehicles in city, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Staff ReporterASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A checkpost has been set up in the city to identify and issue
warnings to the motor vehicles emitting black smoke and generating
high sound.
	   Jointly run by the Department of Environment and the Bangladesh
Road Transport Authority (BRTA), the checkpost was inaugurated by
the Minister for Forest and Environment Syeda Sajeda Chowdhury at
Manik Mian Avenue in front of the Jatiya Sangsad Bhaban yesterday.
	   At the checkpost, the officials will first paste a sticker on
the faulty vehicles and ask for rectification. Next, the owner of
the faulty vehicle will be warned that, if the defect is not
rectified then the licence of the vehicle will be cancelled. The
licence will be finally cancelled if the vehicle's defect is not
removed.
	   Sajeda Chowdhury, who pasted stickers on several vehicles,
called upon the city dwellers to create public awareness against
the bad effect of air and sound pollution caused by faulty motor
vehicles.
	   ``It is impossible for a small Ministry to keep the city free
from pollution,'' she said adding that it needed cooperation of all
concerned to stop the pollution.
	   We are proceeding towards death by inhaling smoke emitted by the
motor vehicles in the city, Sajeda said.
	   The children were growing up amid a great hazard due to the air
pollution, the Minister said and added ``it is shameful that
traffic police in the capital have to perform their duty wearing
masks''.
	   Ahbab Ahmed, Secretary, Ministry of Forest and Environment, AN
Hussain, Chairman of the BRTA and AR Khan, Director General of the
Department of Environment also spoke on the occasion.
	   AN Hussain said that several other checkposts will be set up in
the city soon. Checkposts will also be set up in other metropolitan
cities, he added.
	   
</TEXT>
