<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu: troop-pullback accord not imminent
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Israeli-Palestinian negotiators meeting, report
Netanyahu planning to bring plan to vote this week &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos JRL101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By DAFNA LINZER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Dampening hopes for movement in the stalled
Mideast peace process, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
Sunday said no accord was imminent on a West Bank troop pullback.
	   ``I don't work according to a stopwatch,'' Netanyahu told
reporters after meeting with his Cabinet.
	   The prime minister told his Cabinet that ``it is not possible to
say we are on the verge of an agreement,'' said a statement issued
after the meeting.
	   Later, Netanyahu told reporters: ``We're working toward reaching
an agreement. We're not there yet.''
	   Israel's army radio however, citing sources close to the
premier, said the American plan for a troop withdrawal will likely
to brought to Cabinet for a vote before the end of the week. The
radio reported that Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh,
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and U.S. Ambassador Edward
Walker were meeting later Sunday to discuss aspects of the deal.
