<HEADLINE>
Sacked CMC workers threaten hunger strike, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Sacked CMC workers threaten hunger strike, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Staff ReporterASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Workers and Employees Union of the Social Marketing Company
(CMC) has called upon the company authorities to accept their
demands including the reinstatement of 53 sacked workers and
withdrawal of cases against others.
	   The sacked workers included 29 women. Eight others including two
women were arrested earlier.
	   The Organising Secretary of the union Jamaluddin in a press
release yesterday said they were fighting for their survival. The
workers and employees of the company would begin a hunger strike at
the city's Paltan Maidan on June 12 if the authorities failed to
accept their demands.
	   He said that the company's top-heavy administration exploited
about 75 per cent of the management cost and it was now sacking
workers and employees as a part of cost-cutting measures.
	   Jamaluddin particularly blamed two management officials for the
crisis and called upon the management to accept their demands
immediately.
	   
</TEXT>
