<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy,0485 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Substitute Inzaghi scores three goals in Italy's tuneup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Roberto Baggio and Christian Vieri teamed
in a tuneup game Sunday as they rehearsed Italy's possible
offensive tactic for the World Cup opener against Chile.
	   However it was second-half substitute Filippo Inzaghi who scored
three goals in a 7-0 victory of the ``Azzurri'' against the
regional amateur selection of Oise.
	   It was Italy's final warmup before Thursday's match with Chile
and Inzaghi's outstanding performance possibly posed a problem for
coach Cesare Maldini.
	   Vieri, the leading scorer in the Spanish league with Atletico
Madrid, was somewhat slow and unimpressive during the first half at
Italy's training camp in Senlis.
	   Baggio, a 31-year-old veteran who's starting in his third World
Cup, scored two beautiful goals and produced his usual imaginative
play.
	   Two other of four first-half goals against Oise were tallied by
Chelsea's midfielder Roberto Di Matteo.
	   Maldini said the game, in which he rotated 21 of the players
available, was not a decisive test for the match with Chile.
	   ``It was not intended to decide who must play or sit on the
substitutes bench,'' Maldini said after the tuneup. ``Inzaghi is in
the roster and may be used. Vieri is not yet at 100 percent after
missing the warmup with Sweden (because of stomach problems).''
	   ``Our midfield is the sector which must do much better. I was
not satisfied,'' the coach said.
	   Inzaghi, 24, of Italian champion Juventus of Turin, tallied 16
goals in league matches this year, second only to teammate
Alessandro Del Piero who had 21.
	   Del Piero, just recovered from a right thigh strain, is expected
to be replaced by Roberto Baggio in Italy's first World Cup match
at Bordeaux. He may regain his place on the starting 11 in the next
match against Cameroon.
	   Offensive midfielder Francesco Moriero, of Inter Milan,
alternated with more defensive Angelo Di Livio in a possible option
for the match with Chile.
	   Commenting on reports that Chilean striker Ivan Zamorano may be
sidelined with a knee injury, Moriero said he hoped for a quick
recovery by his Inter teammate.
	   ``I know that he desperately wants to play against Italy. He is
a key player for Chile. I hope he will be starting in Bordeaux
although he could be an additional threat for us, in addition to
(Marcelo) Salas,'' Moriero said.
	   Meanwhile, Maldini was considering the possibility to add
Parma's striker Enrico Chiesa to the Italian list to replace
injured defender Moreno Torricelli.
	   Team officials said that Torricelli may be axed from the Italian
team Monday following a round of medical examinations, including
scanning, to determine the extent of his right ankle injury.
	   (pv-sl)
</TEXT>
