<HEADLINE>
Group of 43 Haitians washes ashore in Jamaica
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ A group of 43 Haitians trying to reach
Miami landed instead on a beach in one of Jamaica's northern resort
areas, police reported Sunday.
	   The group of 36 men, 6 women and a 7-month-old baby were at sea
for nine days on a 30-foot (9-meter) sailboat and had gone six days
without food, authorities said. Staff at the Golden Seas Beach
Hotel in Oracabessa on the north coast, found the Haitians after
they landed Saturday morning.
	   Hotel officials said the migrants were hungry but in good
health. The Haitians told police they left from Port-au-Prince, the
Haitian capital, on May 29 but had run out of food three days
later.
	   Bad weather blew them off course, they said.
	   The migrants were being housed in a shelter in nearby Port Maria
while immigration officials interviewed them and considered
requests for refugee status. 	   
</TEXT>
