<HEADLINE>
APTV 1800 GMT Outlook
</HEADLINE>

  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  APTV 1800 OUTLOOK SUNDAY JUNE 7 1998  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 

 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the
next 12 hours. All times are GMT.  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
EXPECTED: &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
-----
-----
GERMANY : ARRIVALS -- A German airforce A-310 airbus carrying 217
people evacuated from the besieged capital of Eritrea has landed at
Bonn-Cologne airport.   About 34 Germans are reported to be on board
the flight along with other Europeans.   The operation was only
possible after Ethiopia agreed to halt attacks on Eritrea's main
airport on Saturday night to allow foreigners to flee what is known
as the Horn of Africa.  APTV was at the airport.  (First run
expected 1815 gmt F-L-A-S-H)
-----
RUSSIA: MIR -- The crews of the Russian space station ``Mir'' and
space shuttle ``Discovery'' are wrapping up the last docking mission
on a nostalgic note.  The astronauts transferred thousands of pounds (kilograms)
of supplies between the two ships -- and now, they're trying to
figure out what to take back from the aging outpost as a souvenir.
Discovery undocks from Mir on Monday and will bring American Andy
Thomas back to Earth on Friday.   (First run expected 1815 gmt
F-L-A-S-H)
-----
FRANCE: CUP WRAP -- On the eve of the FIFA presidential elections,
the two main contenders Lennart Johansson and Sepp Blatter have been
making their final appeals.
Both men claim to be confident of victory.  The 51st FIFA Congress
will decide on Monday which of the two will replace Joao Havelange
who is stepping down. Package to include new pictures of FIFA
officials arriving and earlier comments from Pele.  (First run
expected 1815 gmt F-L-A-S-H)
-----
MEXICO: DRUGS -- As leaders of the world's major drug-producing and
drug-consuming nations prepare to open a three-day conference to
curb trafficking, curb demand and strengthen global cooperation in
the fight against drugs, APTV reports from Mexico on its plans.
(First run expected 1900 gmt Latin America)
-----
COLOMBIA: REBELS -- Protests have continued in Barrancabermeja,
Colombia, following news of a mass slaughter in which 25 men and
women died.  The victims had been executed by a paramilitary group
for alleged rebel activity though human rights activists say army
and police units were also involved.   A rebel spokesman has vowed
to avenge their deaths.   (First run expected 1900 gmt Latin
America)
-----
US: GAY PRIDE -- More than 70 gay and lesbian organizations took to
the streets of Washington D.C. on Sunday to celebrate the city's
annual Gay Pride Day.  The parade marched through the streets of the
capital, past the White House before stopping at Freedom Place.
APTV joined the colourful march.  (First run expected 1930 gmt North
America Late)
-----
-----
RUNNING:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
----
MONTENEGRO: REFUGEES - Between seven and 10,000 ethnic
Albanians who have fled Kosovo have found shelter in neighboring
Montenegro. A-P-T-V reports from the tiny town of Plav, where many
have sought refuge along the border.  (First run 1130 Europe Update
June 7)
----
ALBANIA: CHILDREN:  APTV follows the story of six young ethnic
Albanian children from Kosovo who wandered neighboring Albania for
three days after being separated from their parents near the border.
APTV has their tearful reunion with their mothers.  (First Run
F-L-A-S-H 1635)
----
UN: DRUGS PREVIEW - Leaders of many of the world's major
drug-producing and drug-consuming nations will be in New York on
Monday to attend a United Nations drugs summit.  I to
intervene in the crisis between Serbs and ethnic Albanians in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo. APTV has highlights from his weekly
address to pilgrims in St. Peter's Square in Rome.  (First Run
Europe Late 1500)
----
FRANCE: PELE- Sweden's candidate for the FIFA election of a new
president won the backing of international football star Pele on
Sunday.  The world football body picks a new president to succeed
Joao Havelange in voting on Monday, just days before the kickoff of
the World Cup. (First Run Europe Late 1500)
----
IRAN: MAYOR - APTV covers the opening of the trial of Tehran mayor
Gholamhossein Karbaschi, where the reformist mayor has pleaded innocent
to corruption charges and challenged the competence of the court.
Karbaschi, a key ally of moderate Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami, is portraying himself as a target of the Islamic hard-line
court.  (First Run Americas 0900)
----
IRAQ: FUNERAL - Protesters demonstrated against international
sanctions against Iraq in front of United Nations offices in
Baghdad.  They walked with small, white coffins representing the
Iraqi children they say have died at the hands of the sanctions.
Iraq announced it would not accept any more aid shipments from
neighbours, the last of which arrived on Friday.  (First Run
Americas 0900)
----
JERUSALEM: POSTERS - Posters of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu wearing Arab headdress in the style of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat have
appeared in Jerusalem.  APTV has shots of the defamatory posters.
(First Run Americas 0900)
----
LEBANON: ELECTIONS - The Lebanese people went to the polls on Sunday
in the third stage of municipal elections - the first there in 35
years.  Item includes soundbites from voters and Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri, who said the vote should help Lebanese put their
decades of war behind them.  (First Run 1130 Europe Update)
----
JAPAN: LOVEGETY - From the land of gadgets comes another gizmo: the
lovegety - a love detector that bleeps when the chance of romance
comes near. APTV finds out how it works, talks to lovegety users and
the company that manufactures them and has comment from a couple
that met as a result of the lovegety. (First Run Asia Pacific Late
0715)
----
