<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Drug Boss,0428 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police capture reputed head of Caribbean cartel
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By FRANK BAJAK &QC; 
 &UR; Associates Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ One of Colombia's last remaining major
drug bosses has been captured in the northern port of Barranquilla,
his appearance altered by hair implants and his pockets full of
cash, the deputy national police director announced Sunday.
	   Caribbean cartel leader Alberto Orlandez Gamboa, alias ``The
Snail,'' allegedly smuggled tons of cocaine to Europe and the
United States since 1991. He has been indicted in Miami federal
court on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering, said the
police official, Gen. Luis Ernesto Gilibert.
	   He said Colombia's foreign ministry would decide whether to
extradite Gamboa for trial to the United States under last year's
law that reinstated extradition.
	   The 43-year-old Orlandez was arrested Saturday, ringed by
bodyguards and carrying false identification documents and dlrs
U.S. 5,000 in cash, police said. He faces charges of murder,
kidnapping and illicit enrichment in Colombia. Police did not
provide details of the murder and kidnapping charges, saying only
that they were related to ``settling of accounts with drug
traffickers.''
	   Orlandez was arrested in 1993 on drug-trafficking charges and
held for 23 months on before authorities were forced to release him
because convictions could not be obtained in any of five cases
against him.
	   Police say Orlandez was one of the last of a nearly extinct
generation of Colombian drug traffickers: kingpins whose large
cartels vertically controlled the cocaine trade from processing to
smuggling to sales abroad. Today's leading traffickers, by
contrast, keep a low profile and operate in much smaller
organizations.
	   Paraded before reporters in Bogota on Sunday, Orlandez looked
worried and unkempt. He wore a blue T-shirt, khaki pants and
sandals, was thin and had hair implants, appearing nothing like the
overweight, balding Orlandez of police wanted poster photos.
	   Gilibert called him ``a highly dangerous individual ... This man
coordinated the largest drug shipments to the United States from
the Atlantic coast and has many years in the drug business.''
	   Orlandez was the last of five major figures of the Caribbean
coast cartel captured this past year, effectively dismantling the
organization, the police general said.
	   More than 5 tons of cocaine shipments owned by Orlandez have
been seized in Miami, New York, Lake Charles, Louisiana, Panama and
other locations since 1991, police said. 	   
</TEXT>
