<SLUG> BC-Britain-Linda McCartney </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Paul McCartney wants memorial service Monday for his wife to be a
</HEADLINE>
celebration &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP ) _ To the strains of ``Let It Be,'' Paul McCartney
will on Monday say a public farewell to his wife, Linda, at a
memorial service at St. Martin-in-the-Fields, a historic London
church overlooking Trafalgar Square.
	   McCartney's office said two other former Beatles, George
Harrison and Ringo Starr, have been invited to the evening service,
but there were no plans for them to sing together.
	   Mrs. McCartney, a longtime crusader for vegetarianism and an
acclaimed photographer, died from breast cancer April 17. She was
56.
	   McCartney will be accompanied by their children, Heather, 36,
his wife's daughter by her first marriage, and Mary, 27, Stella,
26, and James, 21.
	   ``I believe there will be a brief mourning and then a
celebration of Linda's life,'' writer Carla Lane, a longtime friend
of the family, said Sunday. ``Paul does not want it to be a morbid
affair.''
	   Ms. Lane said she would represent hundreds of animal activists
who plan to gather in the square during the service.
	   (mj)
