w1991 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-AutoRacing-Can     06-07 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Canadian GP,0565 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Schumacher wins chaotic Canadian Grand Prix
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KEN BERGER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MONTREAL (AP) _ Michael Schumacher overcame a penalty for
veering wildly out of the pit lane, then zoomed away from his final
pit stop to win a chaotic Canadian Grand Prix on Sunday.
	   In a stunning knockout of the powerful McLaren drivers,
polesitter David Coulthard and Formula One points leader Mika
Hakkinen left early with mechanical problems. Canadian Jacques
Villeneuve was knocked out after briefly taking the lead, returning
for the final few laps to finish last among those left running.
Only 10 of 22 cars completed the race.
	   The victory on a cold, overcast day sent Schumacher, the
two-time series champion, ahead of Coulthard for second place in
the point standings with 34. He trails Hakkinen by 12 points with
10 races remaining.
	   Schumacher was given a stop-and-go penalty on lap 33 for
sideswiping Villeneuve's Williams teammate, Heinz-Harald Frentzen,
on his way out of the pit lane.
	   He drove brilliantly to make up ground, passing rival Damon Hill
for second with a fantastic move, then taking the lead from
Giancarlo Fisichella when the Italian made a pit stop on lap 44.
	   After a 7.2-second pit stop, Schumacher emerged from the pit
lane just in front of Fisichella, slamming the gas and holding his
ground in the same spot where he collided with Frentzen earlier.
	   No one could catch Schumacher's Ferrari on the 12-turn,
2.75-mile (4.43-kilometer) road course thereafter. With the
McLarens and most of the other contenders watching on television,
Schumacher polished off his second victory of the season and 30th
of his career.
	   His average speed was 113.31 mph (182.35 kph).
	   Schumacher is the only driver other than Hakkinen and Coulthard
to win this season.
	   Fisichella was second in his Benetton. Schumacher's teammate,
Eddie Irvine, got his fourth third-place finish of the year in a
Ferrari.
	   If Formula One was looking for a little excitement, the series
found it in treacherous Senna Curve on the first lap.
	   Hakkinen was knocked out with mechanical problems on the restart
that followed a wild, first-turn skirmish. Several cars got
together, and Alexander Wurz's Benetton barrel-rolled three times
before landing off the course on its tires.
	   The Saubers of Jean Alesi and Johnny Herbert were involved,
along with Jarno Trulli. Ralf Schumacher's Jordan Honda stalled on
the starting grid.
	   There was more trouble on the restart, when Hakkinen slowed and
got shuffled to the back. Ralf Schumacher spun in front of several
cars going into the first turn, and Alesi, Trulli and Toranosuke
Takagi got tangled up and knocked out.
	   Coulthard slowed on lap 18, giving Michael Schumacher the lead,
and separate crashes involving Herbert and Mika Salo brought out
the caution. Schumacher made a pit stop while Coulthard headed for
the garage.
	   As he drove out of the pits, Schumacher sideswiped Frentzen near
the pit exit, sending him off the track and his Williams team into
a frenzy. Villeneuve passed Fisichella for the lead as they charged
back to the first turn on the restart, but locked his brakes and
ended up driving across the grass and off the track.
	   Villeneuve, the defending series champion, is still without a
podium finish this season and hasn't won in nine races.
</TEXT>
