<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Relief Drops,0424 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. relief flights drop food in southern Sudan from northern base
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ United Nations relief flights have begun
operating from the government-controlled city of el-Obeid for the
first time, dropping aid to thousands in the country's war-torn
south, the U.N. office in Khartoum said Sunday.
	   Operations began Saturday when flights dropped 16 tons of relief
to 26,000 people in the Bahr al-Ghazal province, about 800
kilometers (500 miles) south of Khartoum, a U.N. statement released
in Khartoum said.
	   Before Saturday, relief operations came from Lokichokkio, in
nearby Kenya, prompting complaints by Sudan's government that
relief flights were being used to transport aid to rebels.
	   Moving relief operations to a government-held town means the
central government in Sudan can monitor the relief operations.
	   Southern rebels have been fighting since 1983 for autonomy and
development in the predominantly Christian, African and animist
south, which has traditionally been dominated by the Muslim and
Arabized north.
	   An estimated 1.5 million people have died in the fighting and
related famines.
	   The United Nations says about 500,000 people in southern Sudan
are in desperate need of emergency relief.
	   The U.N. statement said the World Food Program purchased 4,300
tons of grains in northern Sudan and most has been transported to
el-Obeid in preparation for further drops.
	   It said the WFP moved some employees and a crane to el-Obeid and
set up a warehouse and a communications system there.
	   The move would ``decrease the expense'' of emergency deliveries
because of el-Obeid's proximity to Bahr al-Ghazal, the statement
said.
	   El-Obeid lies about 670 kilometers (415 miles) north of Wau, the
capital of Bahr al-Ghazal while Lokichokkio lies about 920
kilometers (570 miles) south.
	   Relief operations from Kenya, which included between eight to 10
flights per day, used up 130,000 liters (33,800 gallons) of fuel.
The United Nations did not say how much will be used from el-Obeid.
	   Also Sunday, Sudanese army spokesman Gen. Abdel-Rahman Khatim
denied rebel troops have taken control of the garrison town of Ulu
in southern Sudan, 455 kilometers (280 miles) southeast of
Khartoum.
	   ``Military operations are still continuing in the area'' but
government forces are in ``full control,'' Khatim told reporters.
	   The leading southern rebel group, the Sudan Peoples' Liberation
Army, had claimed Tuesday that it had taken control of the town. 	   
</TEXT>
