<SLUG> BC-Libya-Eritrea-Ethiopia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Eritrea, Ethiopia willing to accept cease-fire
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The leaders of Ethiopia and Eritrea are
willing to implement a Libyan plan for a cease-fire and deploy an
African peacekeeping force on their border, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported Sunday.
	   The report could not be independently confirmed in either
Ethiopia or Eritrea, whose border tensions have erupted into air
bombing raids, raising the specter of a full-fledged war.
	   MENA said Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi received messages of
peace from the leaders of Ethiopia and Eritrea in which they
``expressed their willingness'' to accept the Libyan plan.
	   The messages were carried by an official of an African group who
met with the leaders of the two countries this week, MENA said.
	   The African organization is called the Sahel and Saharan
Countries, or the ``coastal and desert countries,'' which groups
Libya, Sudan, Chad, Mali, Niger and Burkina Faso. Gadhafi currently
holds the chair.
