w2046 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia 6thLd-Writethru   06-07 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 6th Ld-Writethru,0692 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eritreans brace for more Ethiopian warplane attacks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with 3 grafs at end with Libyan report that Eritrea,
Ethiopia willing to accept cease-fire. INCORPORATES
Libya-Eritrea-Ethiopia. No pickup &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ASM101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By KARIN DAVIES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Eritreans braced Sunday for more
bombardments from Ethiopian warplanes after a deadline passed for
hundreds of foreigners to flee to safety.
	   Meanwhile, hectic diplomatic efforts were under way to prevent
the border conflict from exploding into a full-scale war.
	   Eritreans scanned cloudless blue skies Sunday and listened for
the high-pitched whoosh of the Ethiopian MiG-23 fighters that had
bombed Asmara's airport Friday and Saturday. None came.
	   Skirmishes were reported, however, along the disputed border.
	   Ethiopia said Sunday it had reoccupied its border town of Zala
Anbessa, 105 kilometers (65 miles) southwest of Asmara, defeating
in a daylong battle Eritrean forces which captured the town last
week.
	   Eritrean government spokesman Isaac Yared said the Eritrean
troops retreated voluntarily to their side of the border. ``They
decided it was time to go,'' he said.
	   President Isaias Afwerki is hopeful that a summit of heads of
state of the Organization of African Unity on Monday will yield new
ideas for a negotiated settlement, his spokesman Yemane Gebremeskel
said.
	   U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Susan Rice left an OAU foreign
ministers meeting Saturday in Ouagadougu, Burkina Faso, apparently
for Ethiopia and Eritrea. She returned to the United States on
Sunday.
	   Rice was promoting a peace plan for the two feuding Horn of
Africa countries that was drafted by the United States and Rwanda.
	   The proposal calls on Eritrea to return to positions held prior
to May 6, when current hostilities reportedly broke out _ in other
words, to withdraw from what Ethiopia considers its territory.
	   Eritrea, wedged between northern Ethiopia and the Red Sea,
however, claims it is rightfully occupying territory defined by
boundaries drawn by Italy when it occupied Eritrea in 1885.
	   Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993 two years
after Eritrean rebels helped the Ethiopian People's Revolutionary
Democratic Front overthrow a 17-year military regime.
	   Gebremeskel said Eritrea broadly agreed with Rice's four-point
peace plan, but he said any accord must include more specifics,
including how and when the border would be demarcated and by whom.
	   ``We need to work out the details to achieve a lasting
solution,'' he said. ``This dispute has gone on for too long
already.''
	   Several African leaders called Afwerki over the weekend to
encourage a negotiated settlement.
	   Ethiopia's army outnumbers Eritrea's 40,000-strong force by
about three to one. Eritrea's tiny air force is no match for
Ethiopia's.
	   Mokonnen, a 27-year-old telephone operator who uses just one
name, said he was afraid, though optimistic that a peace pact would
be forged between the one-time allies.
	   ``We are still free. We are still brothers, only a few people
are doing this thing. Our government wants peace, and we are
struggling to solve it peacefully,'' he said.
	   Ethiopian jets bombed a military-civilian airport on the
outskirts of Asmara on Friday and Saturday, forcing embassies to
step up their evacuation plans.
	   American, Italian, German and British planes ferried more than a
thousand foreigners out of harm's way late Saturday and early
Sunday after Ethiopia agreed to temporarily halt bombing.
	   But the two countries dispute more than a half-dozen areas along
their common border.
	   Also Sunday, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported that the
leaders of both countries were willing to implement a Libyan plan
for a cease-fire and deploy an African peacekeeping force on their
border,
	   The report could not be independently confirmed in either
Ethiopia or Eritrea.
	   MENA said Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi received messages of
peace from the leaders who ``expressed their willingness'' to
accept the Libyan plan. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 6th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
