w2057 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AirFrance-Strike 4thLd-Writethru   06-07 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France pilots offer to work for free to fly World Cup fans
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with leader of French Senate condemning strike,
CLARIFIES that offer is for foreign fans. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PAR104/105
 &UR; By DEBORAH SEWARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ With their crippling strike about to enter its
second week, Air France pilots offered Sunday to work for free to
fly foreign World Cup ticket holders to the soccer championships.
	   The unexpected gesture came as the conflict appeared to harden
Sunday night, with Air France management expressing exasperation
with the pilots who walked off the job a week ago.
	   No new talks were in sight, and the conflict appeared certain to
enter its second week Monday. Air France said the strike had
already cost one billion francs (dlrs 166 million).
	   France's flagship carrier has said it will take three days for
service to return to normal once the strike ends, meaning the
walkout was sure to disrupt the World Cup, which begins Wednesday.
	   Christian Paris, spokesman for the main SNPL pilots' union,
proposed that Air France organize special flights for foreign World
Cup ticket holders and said the pilots would work without pay so
the fans would not miss the soccer championship.
	   Air France reacted quickly and said it would study the measure.
	   Despite the goodwill gesture, the situation was stalemated
Sunday night.
	   Pierre-Henri Gourgeon, the director general of Air France, said
the airline had ``exhausted its capacity of understanding with
regard to the pilots.''
	   Meanwhile, the company met Sunday with ground personnel and
flight attendants, worried that they have been left out of salary
talks between Air France and the pilots.
	   One of the unions representing ground personnel, the
Communist-backed General Labor Confederation (CGT), warned Friday
of a ``spread of the conflict'' unless Air France included other
airline workers in the talks.
	   Both the pilots and Air France were under pressure to end the
strike from the government, which is embarrassed by the conflict.
	   Rene Monory, the president of the French Senate, said Sunday the
pilots were giving the country a ``lamentable image.''
	   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said Saturday the government was
prepared to intervene but no concrete proposals emerged.
	   Talks between Air France and the pilots were suspended Saturday
after the pilots walked out of negotiations.
	   Public support for the pilots appeared lukewarm.
	   A poll in Sunday's edition of Le Journal du Dimanche showed just
38 percent of those surveyed were sympathetic to the strike. The
poll was carried out Friday by the CSA polling agency among 1,004
people. No margin of error was given.
	   The strike has inconvenienced thousands, including foreigners
fleeing fighting in Eritrea.
	   The pilots are protesting pay cuts planned by Air France in
order to save 500 million francs (dlrs 83 million) a year the
company says is needed to modernize the company.
	   Obstacles to an agreement are proposed salary reductions and a
plan to give pilots stock in exchange for the pay cut, as well as a
two-tier pay scale in which younger pilots earn less.
	   Only about 25 percent of Air France's flights were expected to
take off Monday.
	   Trains were expected to run on schedule Monday after strikes
disrupted service this weekend. Trains conductors have threatened a
walkout Wednesday.
	   Taxi drivers in Paris planned demonstrations Monday to protest
the recent killing of a taxi driver.
	   (dgs-parf) 	   
</TEXT>
