<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Nationwide Senior PGA,0537 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jacobs spoils Morgan-Irwin duel for first PGA victory
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL NEWBERRY &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALPHARETTA, Georgia (AP) _ John Jacobs picked up his first U.S.
PGA victory on Sunday, shooting a 5-under-par 67 to beat the senior
tour's two most dominating players in the Nationwide Championship.
	   The cigar-smoking Jacobs, who had never won on either the senior
or regular tours, finished with a 10-under 206 total, edging Hale
Irwin by one stroke and finishing two shots ahead of Gil Morgan and
Leonard Thompson.
	   Irwin and Morgan have ruled the senior circuit this year, each
winning three events.
	   Irwin came to the Golf Club of Georgia as the top money winner
with dlrs 1,051,850, having finished in the top five in all eights
tournaments he's played, while Morgan had dlrs 853,818 in earnings
and seven top-10 finishes.
	   But Jacobs spoiled the expected Morgan-Irwin showdown, moving
into the lead for good with a birdie at No. 17 and using his power
off the tee to secure the victory at 18.
	   ``It's pretty special to beat Gil Morgan and Hale Irwin when
they're playing well,'' said Jacobs, who picked up the largest
check of his career, dlrs 202,500. ``But it bothers me when people
say they're dominating the tour. They're not that much better than
a lot of other guys out here.''
	   Morgan began the final round tied for the lead with Bob Eastwood
at eight under and remained on top with birdies at 10 and 12. But
he fell apart down the stretch, bogeying three of the last five
holes.
	   ``Pressure was one factor, and some unfamiliarity with the golf
course hurt, too,'' said Morgan, who lost any chance to force a
playoff when he hit his second shot at 18 into the water. ``I
didn't leave myself with some very good shots coming in.''
	   Irwin, who started the day four shots off the lead, got to 10
under with three straight birdies, including a 50-foot (15-meter)
putt at No. 12 that had playing partner Walter Morgan bowing in
admiration.
	   But Irwin, playing his first senior event in four weeks,
couldn't keep the momentum going. An errant tee shot at 15 wound up
a bogey when he missed a 12-foot (3-meter) putt, and he squandered
potential birdie chances at 16 and 18.
	   ``I had a long ways to go,'' he said. ``I was a little too deep
in the field to pass as many guys as I needed to.''
	   Jacobs was three shots behind Gil Morgan and Eastwood at the
start of the round, a margin he wiped out by overpowering the front
nine for five birdies. Sticking mostly with his irons, he made five
birdie putts of less than 10 feet (3 meters) and made the turn with
a 31.
	   Jacobs bogeyed 14 to drop back to nine under, then secured the
victory with a brilliant 6-iron at the 199-yard 17th. The ball
rolled less than 2 feet (half a meter) from the hole and he tapped
in for birdie.
	   ``That was the nicest shot I've made in years,'' he said. ``It
went right where I aimed it.''
	   At the 533-yard (487-meter) 18th, Jacobs had no qualms about
going for the green in two, and he actually put his second shot
over the green when a 4-iron carried some 235 yards 215 meters). He
chipped down a slope and two-putted for the clinching par. 	   
</TEXT>
