<SLUG> BC-Dominican-UN-Visit,0174 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dominican president to present drug-control plan to United Nations
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Dominican President
Leonel Fernandez left Sunday for a United Nations meeting, where he
will present a regional drug-control proposal for the western
Caribbean.
	   He will present the plan Monday at a meeting of the
organization's General Assembly in New York City.
	   Drug experts say cocaine smuggling through the Dominican
Republic and adjacent Haiti has increased recently. U.S. officials
have estimated that 25 percent of the cocaine reaching the United
States comes by way of Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic.
	   A United Nations report released Friday claimed money laundering
in the country has tripled in the last three years, with most of
the money finding its way into real estate, car sales and shipping
deals.
	   After his presentation, Fernandez will meet with U.S.-based
members of his Dominican Liberation Party and with Dominican
community leaders in New York City. 	   
</TEXT>
