<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0710 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Eritreans braced for more bombing Sunday
by Ethiopian warplanes after a deadline passed for hundreds of
foreigners to flee to safety. Hectic diplomatic efforts were under
way to prevent the border conflict from exploding into a full-scale
war between the two East African nations. Eritreans scanned
cloudless blue skies Sunday and listened for the high-pitched
whoosh of the Ethiopian MiG-23 fighters that bombed their capital's
airport Friday and Saturday. But none came. Skirmishes were
reported, however, along the two countries' disputed border.
Ethiopia said Sunday it had reoccupied its border town of Zala
Anbessa, 100 kilometers (65 miles) southwest of Asmara, after a
daylong battle with Eritrean forces who captured the town last
week. (ERITREA-ETHIOPIA)
	   PARIS (AP) _ With their crippling strike about to enter its
second week, Air France pilots offered Sunday to work for free to
fly foreign World Cup ticket holders to the soccer championships.
The unexpected gesture came as the conflict appeared to harden
Sunday night, with Air France management expressing exasperation
with the pilots who walked off the job a week ago. No new talks
were in sight, and the conflict appeared certain to enter its
second week Monday. Air France said the strike had already cost one
billion francs (dlrs 166 million). France's flagship carrier has
said it will take three days for service to return to normal once
the strike ends, meaning the walkout was sure to disrupt the World
Cup, which begins Wednesday. (AIR FRANCE-STRIKE)
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ Afraid of surrendering Swiss leadership
in biotechnology, voters Sunday decisively rejected a proposal to
outlaw the production and patenting of genetically modified plants
and animals. Some 67 percent of the voters struck down the
initiative, which government and business leaders argued would
force a ``draconian'' end to research in Switzerland and send
highly paid jobs to other countries. The Swiss-based pharmaceutical
giants Roche and Novartis, both leaders in biotechnology
innovation, praised the vote. ``The way is now open for
Switzerland's industry and universities to carry on into the future
with their biomedical and pharmaceutical research,'' Roche said in
a statement. ``The people obviously listened to our arguments,''
added Novartis research chief Paul Herrling. (SWITZERLAND-GENE
VOTE)
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ With demand for illegal drugs rising,
leaders of the world's major drug-producing and drug-consuming
nations open a three-day conference Monday to discuss how to fight
the scourge. U.S. President Bill Clinton, who delivers the opening
address, has pledged to cut drug use by half in the United States _
the world's leading drug consumer _ by 2007. Latin American leaders
say their efforts to curtail drug production and trafficking will
fail unless Americans curb their appetite for drugs. The presidents
of Mexico, Venezuela, Peru and Colombia are expected to deliver
that message at the conference. The goal of the U.N. General
Assembly's ``special session on drugs'' is to endorse target dates
for governments to enact legislation on issues such as money
laundering, judicial cooperation, reducing demand for drugs and
stamping out cultivation of illicit crops. (UN-DRUG SUMMIT)
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's former President Suharto
turns 77 on Monday, but there will be no celebration for the man
who last month surrendered his 32-year iron grip on the world's
fourth most populous nation. Forced to quit after mobs went on a
rampage and angry protesters demanded he be tried for corruption,
Suharto has said nothing publicly since his May 21 resignation. In
contrast, his successor, new President B.J. Habibie, can't seem to
get enough of the limelight and is basking in the glory of rolling
back many of Suharto's draconian ways. Suharto remains holed up at
his private home in Jakarta, guarded by the powerful military from
growing calls for retribution against him and his super-rich
family. (INDONESIA-SUHARTO'S BIRTHDAY)
</TEXT>
