<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0797 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Tori Amos, Ivana Trump, fast ferry and Banff
television festival. Some items may also have moved as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Tori Amos knows she's not for everybody.
	   ``I'm an acquired taste _ I'm anchovies,'' the 34-year-old
singer says in the June 25 Rolling Stone magazine. ``And not
everybody wants those hairy little things. If I was potato chips, I
could go a lot more places, but I'm not.''
	   The daughter of a Methodist minister, Amos was a precocious
talent who at age 5 became the youngest-ever student at Baltimore's
prestigious Peabody Conservatory. She also was a precocious rebel.
At 11, Peabody threw her out for musical insubordination.
	   As a young woman in Los Angeles trying to make it in music or as
an actress, she did some commercials before forming the doomed band
Y Kant Tori Read, whose first album tanked after a review in
Billboard called her a bimbo. She didn't leave her apartment for a
week.
	   ``I cried constantly; I was on my knees,'' Amos said. ``From
child prodigy to musical joke in twenty years _ how do you
reconcile that?''
	   About the time her debut solo album ``Little Earthquakes'' came
out in 1992, Amos moved to Britain. ``Under the Pink'' followed in
1994 and ``Boys for Pele'' came out in 1996. Her latest record is
``From the Choirgirl Hotel.''
	   ___
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Socialite Ivana Trump doesn't want to pay the
private investigator she hired to spy on then-husband Donald Trump
and the woman he left her for, Marla Maples.
	   Maples later married Trump but has since split with the
millionaire real estate mogul.
	   Lawyers have failed to arrange a settlement in the lawsuit by
investigator James Mintz in a case that could reveal embarrassing
details of the bitter 1990 divorce battle, including details of
Trump's finances and his relationship with Maples while still
married.
	   ``It's a case that really re-rears ugly heads,'' Ivana Trump's
lawyer, Gary Lyman, says in Sunday's New York Post. ``This is
something I'd love to settle.''
	   Mintz is seeking payment of his dlrs 250,000 bill _ now up to
dlrs 400,000 with interest. Ivana Trump contends he overcharged her
and violated a dlrs 100,000 cap on spying services.
	   ``She thinks people see a deep pocket and they go for the
jugular,'' Lyman said.
	   If no settlement is reached, the case will go to trial in
Manhattan this summer.
	   ___
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ A ferry trying to smash the record for the
fastest Atlantic crossing by a passenger vessel had completed a
third of its 3,125-mile (5028-kilometer) journey in about one day,
organizers of the race said Sunday.
	   Following a brief delay, the Catalonia departed New York Harbor
at 6:35 a.m. Saturday, headed for Tarifa, Spain.
	   Weighing 400 tons, the fast ferry can carry 900 passengers at a
speed of 45 knots, or 51 mph (82 kph). It is scheduled to arrive in
Tarifa on Tuesday morning.
	   If successful, the Catalonia will become the latest winner of
the Hales Trophy, held since 1990 by Hoverspeed Great Britain. The
coveted award is given to commercial ships that average the highest
speed while traversing the Atlantic.
	   Previous trophy winners include the Lusitania and the Queen
Mary.
	   To capture the prize, Catalonia must top Hoverspeed's average
speed of 36.65 knots. Captain Leonel Torres has said the fast
ferry, owned by Argentine-based Buquebus and built by Incat of
Australia, can average 43 knots.
	   ___
	   ALTA, Alberta (AP) _ There are bound to be a lot more arguments
over the TV remote control at this year's edition of the Banff
Television Festival.
	   The 19th annual installment of the festival has reached a new
high in attendance with more than 1,600 people _ producers,
directors, actors and TV executives _ descending on this idyllic
Rocky Mountain resort town.
	   There were also a record number of entries _ 989, up from 722
last year _ submitted in the international competition from 40
countries for the Banff Rockie Awards.
	   The festival has major themes such as exploring public figures
and their private lives, and the impact of television on human
rights issues. Entries are seen by a seven-member international
jury of TV professionals from Australia, Canada, France, Japan,
Turkey, the United Kingdom and the United States.
	   Festival President Pat Ferns said the Monica Lewinsky story and
debate over the role the media played in the death of Princess
Diana lent themselves ideally to the festival.
	   ``We're trying to brand ourselves as the Olympics of
television,'' Ferns said. ``It is where the U.S. competes with the
rest of the world on an even playing field, and it is the most
comprehensive awards program in the world.''
</TEXT>
