<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs,0723 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Includes items on FIFA Congress; Bulgarian deja vu; Ronald de Boer;
</HEADLINE>
Azzurri &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ FIFA took time off from its war of succession to
honor a dozen soccer greats and promoters of the game in various
parts of the world.
	   While the battle between Lennart Johansson and Sepp Blatter over
the presidency of the world body enters its final round, the
organization bestowed its prestigious Order of Merit on Germany's
former striker Gerd Mueller, Brazil's goalkeeper during the
1950s-60s Gilmar, and Michelle Akers of the U.S. women's national
team.
	   Larbi Ben Barak, the first great African player _ known during
the 1930s-40s as the ``Black Pearl of Casablanca'' _ received a
posthumous award.
	   South African President Nelson Mandela was honored for his role
in reintegrating the country into international soccer, after it
had been banned from competing during the apartheid regime.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   COUDRAY-MONTCEAU, France (AP) _ There was a sense of deja vu
among the leadership of the Bulgarian national squad when they
learned that an early morning fire had damaged the kitchen of the
hotel they were supposed to move into later Sunday.
	   Upon arriving at their training headquarters 35 kilometers (22
miles) south of Paris, the Bulgarians were faced with the
possibility of having to search for new accommodations, much as
they had at the European Championship two years ago in England.
	   At that time, the team was traumatized when they were forced to
vacate their base camp in the seaside resort of Scarborough because
players said they hated the atmosphere in the hotel chosen by their
leadership.
	   But the damage caused by Sunday's blaze proved minimal, and the
hotel _ together with its kitchen _ will continue to operate
normally, management said.
	   ``It is a nice place, I've been here before,'' commented Ivan
Slavkov, president of the Bulgarian Football Union.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Italian midfielder Francesco Moriero said
Sunday he loves the ``creative'' Latin American soccer and predicts
that Brazil and Argentina will be the most likely World Cup
finalists.
	   ``Of course I think Italy also has big chances to reach the top
four in the competition,'' the Inter Milan player said.
	   He also expressed ``a lot of respect'' for Chile, Italy's first
opponent in Group B on Thursday.
	   ``It's a humble but determined team, and includes a pair of
great strikers, (Ivan) Zamorano and (Marcelo) Salas,'' he said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Thirty million guilders (dlrs 15
million) isn't enough _ at least that's what Ajax Amsterdam has
told English league champion Arsenal regarding its bid for
midfielder Ronald de Boer.
	   ``A transfer is out of the question and will stay that way,''
Ajax financial director Maarten Oldenhof said Sunday, according to
Dutch television news' textual service. It was not clear when Ajax
rejected the bid. A club spokesman could not immediately be reached
for more details.
	   De Boer and his twin brother Frank, who both will play for the
Netherlands in the World Cup finals which start Wednesday in
France, have contracts until 2004 at the Amsterdam powerhouse but
both have made no secret of their desire for a transfer.
	   ``Until that time (2004), we will not let him go, whatever
offers we get,'' Oldenhof said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ About 400 vocal Italian fans watched
Italy's 7-0 victory against the regional selection of Oise in a
tuneup game Sunday.
	   It was Italy's last warmup before its World Cup debut against
Chile at Bordeaux Thursday.
	   However the big event of the region was elsewhere, at nearby
Chantilly, where thousands of people attended the prestigious Prix
de Diane horse race.
	   Italian fans were especially supportive of especially
second-half substitute Filippo Inzaghi, who scored three goals
against the French amateurs.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Christian Vieri says that scoring goals is
not his obsession _ an unexpected remark by a striker who led the
Spanish league in scoring this year.
	   ``I don't think one must judge you from the number of goals,''
the 24-year-old forward of Atletico Madrid said Sunday. ``I always
engage at 100 percent. If I don't score but I play at my best,
nobody can blame me.''
</TEXT>
