<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Korea,0465 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: As South Korea prepares for Mexico, striker nurses knee
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ERICA BULMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ South Korea is recharging its strength to play
Mexico in its opening France 98 match. Advancing to the second
round is the goal, but chances may ride on whether striker Hwang
Sun-hong recovers from a knee injury.
	   The South Koreans, which arrived in Paris on Friday, are quietly
preparing, practicing and planning in a remote area in the
outskirts of Paris in the hopes of optimizing their chances of
winning the nation's first match in five World Cup appearances.
	   While Belgium is regarded as the other ``weakling'' in Group E,
South Korea figures to have its best chance of a first-round
victory against South Korea. The Netherlands is the seeded team in
the group.
	   ``Our team expects to win against Mexico,'' Chun Hanjin, the
South Korean team's vice-manager, said Sunday. ``The odds of
winning against the Netherlands are ... somewhat lower. And Belgium
is a decent opponent.''
	   South Korea is counting on the Mexicans' similar physique and
style of play to lean in its favor, Chun explained. Asia's No. 1
team is also leery of any team from Europe.
	   ``Belgium is still a European team so we'll have to be
cautious,'' said Chun. ``Asian football has not shown its strength
against a European team.
	   ``There are many older players on the Belgian team but in Korea
we call Belgium 'Old Fox.' It is older and maybe not so fast but it
has experience and is sly. They know the game.''
	   Korea's chances of beating Mexico next Saturday (June 13) in
Lyon may have been dented when veteran striker Hwang Sun-hong
injured his knee in a tackle during a 1-1 draw against China on
Thursday.
	   ``His injury is not that serious,'' said Chun. ``He seriously
injured his right knee a long time ago so he's worried about this
new injury to his left knee. But he had it checked out and there's
no physical injury as such.''
	   ``He says it bothers him a little, though.''
	   Hwang said on Friday the accident would not prevent him from
playing.
	   However, coach Cha Bum-kun feels it will be impossible for the
29-year-old striker to play against Mexico, South Korea's press
officer Song Ki-ryong told The Associated Press.
	   ``Hwang says 'yes' and Cha says 'no,''' said Song, who gives
South Korea a 30 percent chance of advancing to the second round.
``But Cha has the final say. For the moment I'm not sure what the
final decision will be.''
	   In the meantime, the 2002 World Cup co-hosts are just relaxing.
	   ``For the moment we are just taking it easy,'' said Chun.
``We're all getting some rest. Besides there is nothing else to do
around here. We're in a pretty remote area.'' 	   
</TEXT>
