<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Le Mans 24 Hours,0560 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Porsche pressure proves too much for Toyota at Le Mans
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDREAS EVAGORA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LE MANS, France (AP) _ Porsche has proven that experience and
not just endurance is key to success at the Le Mans 24 Hour race.
	   Two hours before the end of the race, Toyota seemed set for its
first Le Mans triumph, but pressure from two Porsche cars, followed
by a late Toyota disaster, sent the crown to the German constructor
for a record 16th time.
	   Porsche simply refused to give up hope, perhaps knowing that Le
Mans is famous for wrecking high hopes at the most unexpected time.
	   Porsche, which won seven straight Le Mans races in the 1980s,
has now won the last three contests here.
	   The Porsche GT1 driven by Alan McNish of Britain and France's
Laurent Aiello and Stephane Ortelli went on to win the contest
Sunday afternoon, speeding round the 13.6-kilometer (8.456-mile)
circuit 351 times.
	   ``When we were behind near the end we were pushing our car to
the limit and hoped that the Toyota would make a mistake,'' McNish
said. ``We needed to see if they could take the pressure. They
couldn't.''
	   Another Porsche GT1, driven by Germany's Jorg Muller and Uwe
Alzen and Bob Wolleck of France, was second with 350 laps.
	   In third place was Kazuyoshi Hoshino, Aguri Suzuki and Masahiko
Kageyama in a Nissan R390, the first time three Japanese drivers
have shared a single podium at Le Mans.
	   ``There's so much experience in this Porsche camp.'' McNish
added. ``We know that this race is never over until the checkered
flag goes up.''
	   Sunday morning Thierry Boutsen, Ralf Kelleners and Geoff Lees
gave the Toyota GT1 the lead in the 20th hour.
	   In fact, the key moment came 85 minutes from the end when flames
suddenly appeared from the Toyota's gearbox after it had turned the
Mulsanne Corner.
	   Soon, many in the Toyota pit were in tears as it became clear
that the Le Mans prize would again be heading Porsche's way.
	   ``We were 44 seconds behind when that happened,'' McNish
recalled after the race. ``But you never know what might happen at
this race.''
	   The Toyota team was desolate after the race.
	   ``Thierry deserved to win after driving so well overnight,''
said Toyota teammate Martin Brundle. ``The whole team has worked so
hard and we are all terribly disappointed to lose the race this
way. It's awful to go out so close to the end.''
	   Only one Japanese manufacturer, Mazda in 1991, has ever won the
Le Mans race.
	   But Toyota technical director Andre de Cortenze, who tasted
victory with Peugeot in 1992 and 1993, vowed to return in 1999.
	   ``We have proved that we know how to win the Le Mans,'' he said.
	   After Mercedes and BMW each lost both of their cars early in the
race Saturday afternoon, the stage soon became set for a scrap
between Toyota, Porsche and Nissan.
	   Boutsen led for more than four hours on Saturday, but Porsche
dominated at the halfway stage, when its two cars were three laps
ahead of the field.
	   The Toyota car was only fifth, but clawed its way back to the
head of the field Sunday morning after Porsche suffered problems at
daybreak.
	   The Mercedes of German Bernd Schneider, which was fastest in
practice, fell out of the race with motor failure after just 90
minutes. 	   
</TEXT>
