<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar hits 140 yen in Tokyo, stocks down
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar broke through 140 yen in early
Tokyo trading Monday, hitting another seven-year high. Tokyo stock
prices fell moderately.
	   The dollar bought 140.28 yen in early trading, up 0.86 yen from
late Friday in Tokyo for a level not seen here since June 20, 1991.
	   On Friday, the dollar rose as high as 139.93 yen in New York
before setting at 139.75 yen. In thin weekend trading Sunday,
however, it also broke through 140 yen in New York.
	   The dollar's strength derived from fresh evidence of a robust
U.S. economy after the Labor Department reported on Friday the
nation's unemployment rate held to a 28-year-low of 4.3 percent in
May.
	   Also supporting the U.S. currency was the diminishing likelihood
the deputy finance ministers of the Group of Seven industrialized
nations will make a strong statement criticizing the current dollar
level, traders said.
	   Officials from the G-7 _ the United States, Japan, Germany,
Italy, Canada, Britain and France _ are scheduled to meet in Paris
on Tuesday.
	   Persistent pessimism over Japan's economy also continued to
weigh on sentiment among many investors, who have shifted to the
U.S. and German currencies in recent weeks.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
fell 39.91 points, or 0.26 percent, to 15,283.52 at the start of
Monday's trading session. On Friday, the average lost 103.04
points, or 0.67 percent.
	   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 2.82 points, or 0.23 percent, to 1,199.12. The
TOPIX closed down 5.56 points, or 0.46 percent.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond was unquoted in early trading. It's yield closed
Friday at 1.165 percent, with a price of 112.31 yen.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
