<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA-Michelob Light,0695 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sorenstam wins Michelob Light Classic third time in four years
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs &QL; 
 &UR; By R.B. FALLSTROM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. LOUIS (AP) _ This time, Annika Sorenstam won the LPGA
Michelob Light Classic the hard way.
	   Sorenstam was a three-stroke winner last year and ran away for a
10-stroke victory in 1996. On Sunday, it took birdies on two of the
last three holes to force a playoff before she beat Donna Andrews
on the second extra hole.
	   ``Normally, it seems like when I win I'm up there and I kind of
keep the lead the last few holes,'' said Sorenstam, who closed with
a 4-under-par 68, while Andrews, the second-round leader, had a 70.
``I had to go for every putt, because if I didn't she was going to
win.''
	   So far, this hasn't been a normal year for Sorenstam. She won
six tournaments last year when she was named LPGA player of the
year, and has 13 career victories. But this victory, worth dlrs
90,000, was her first of the year.
	   ``It means a lot just getting some of the burden off my back a
little bit,'' Sorenstam said. ``I've been playing well, I just
haven't been able to pull through.
	   ``One bad round has held me back, but not this week.''
	   Trailing by one stroke on the final hole in regulation,
Sorenstam came up with her best shot of the day. An approach from
about 90 yards (82 meters) left her less than a foot (meter) from
the cup and she tapped in for birdie to force the playoff.
	   Andrews thought Sorenstam had holed out the shot for the win.
	   ``She hit a great shot,'' Andrews said. ``I was glad just to
have a chance.''
	   Andrews had opened the door on No. 18 when she clipped a tree
with her second shot. She left her third shot short of the green,
but then chipped to about 5 feet (1.5 meters) and made the putt for
par.
	   The only playoff hole was No. 18 due to TV considerations. Each
parred the first extra hole.
	   ``Annika looked at me after we'd played it once and said `We
could be here all day, as consistent as you and I are,' '' Andrews
said. ``She's right. It's a hole you're going to make par on 90
percent of the time.''
	   The second time around, though, Andrews left a downhill birdie
attempt from about 15 feet (4.5 meters) a bit short and to the
left. Sorenstam then drilled a 4-footer (1.2-meter) for the
victory.
	   Andrews built a two-stroke lead with a 6-under-par 66 in the
second round of the event, which was shortened to three rounds by
rain. She trailed Sorenstam by one after six holes, and led by
three after 11.
	   ``I knew I needed to make a lot of birdies to even have a
chance,'' Sorenstam said. ``She didn't make any mistakes. She was
just a radar.''
	   Andrews has finished second in her last three tournaments. She
also took over the top spot on the money list ahead of Liselotte
Neumann with her check of dlrs 55,855 and a total of dlrs 465,434.
	   Sorenstam is third on the list with dlrs 387,765.
	   ``You know what?'' Andrews said. ``I think if I finished second
in every tournament I'd be happy.''
	   It's been an emotional time for Andrews, playing her first
tournament after a two-week break. Last week, a 4-year-old horse
she owned died in complications from pregnancy, and she choked up a
bit after the final round.
	   ``I felt like there was a little angel on my shoulder,'' Andrews
said. ``Even when I hit bad shots, they ended up in good spots.''
	   Sorenstam birdied the first four holes to share the lead even
though Andrews birdied two of the first four. She even led by a
stroke after Andrews bogeyed No. 8. She followed that with a bogey
and double-bogey, blowing a 2-3 foot (.6-1 meter) putt on No. 9 to
fall back by two.
	   When Andrews holed out a putt from the fringe on No. 11, she had
a three-stroke lead. Sorenstam made a 20-foot (6.1-meter) birdie
putt on No. 13 and another birdie on No. 16 cut the gap to one.
	   Tour rookie Sara Hallock shot a 69 to finish third at five
under. Pat Hurst and Lorie Kane finished six strokes back, Hurst
with a final-round 69 and Kane with a 67.
	   Jackie Gallagher-Smith was the only other player below par,
closing with a 72 to finish at one under. 	   
</TEXT>
