<HEADER>
w2193 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Hanson     06-07 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Hanson </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hanson says criticism fuels support
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Maverick legislator Pauline Hanson on
Monday dismissed an attack on her views by Prime Minister John
Howard, saying criticism only increases her support.
	   Last week Howard abandoned his strategy of ignoring Hanson,
labeling her views dishonest, deranged and fanning racist
sentiments.
	   He was referring to her speech last week in which she claimed a
``collusion of Aboriginal separatists, the United Nations and the
disloyal and self-seeking globalists'' was seeking to dismember
Australia and set up taxpayer-funded Aboriginal states.
	   But in an interview on Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio
Hanson brushed off the criticism, saying support for her was
strong.
	   ``I think the general public just see me as one of them, they
just see me as an ordinary woman getting up and trying to have a
go,'' Hanson said.
	   ``And every time John Howard or anyone else comes out and has a
go at me, they feel as if they are taking it personally and they
don't like it.
	   ``It's like the `Aussie battler,' at least she's getting up
having a go, at least she's prepared to stand up for what she
believes in and she is only saying what we think, so every time
they knock her, hey mate, they're knocking me.''
	   The term ``Aussie battler'' describes a working class Australian
struggling to make a living.
	   Hanson said she was only voicing the views of her supporters who
are concerned about issues like unemployment and crime and wanted
to see all Australians treated equally.
	   Economic issues were more important than race issues, said
Hanson, who has called for a cutoff of Asian immigration and for an
end to welfare programs specific to Aborigines.
	   ``Australians are a very tolerant people and they realize that
Australia is a multi-racial country, (there are) people from all
different parts of the world that come here for a better way of
life,'' she said.
	   ``All we are saying is `Well look, welcome, but come here and be
Australian ... because otherwise it will only divide us as a
nation, divide us as a people.'''
	   Hanson said even if her One Nation Party only won a single seat
in the Queensland election on Saturday she will be ``the proudest
woman in Australia.'' 	   
</TEXT>
