<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0772 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Some items may have moved as separates
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Mexico, Guatemala, Colombia and Argentina.
 &UR; By The Associated Press

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexico has arrested the man suspected of
leading the Gulf drug organization, a newspaper reported Sunday.
Authorities would not confirm the report.
	   According to the newspaper Reforma, agents of the federal
attorney general's office arrested Salvador Gomez, known as ``El
Chava,'' early Friday morning in Matamoros, across the border from
Brownsville, Texas.
	   According to the newspaper report, Gomez was accompanied by one
of his lieutenants and a federal highway policemen. They were also
arrested, and the three were flown to Mexico City, Reforma said.
	   Gomez, a former policeman, is reported to head the Gulf drug
organization, based in Matamoros, having risen from the ranks and
assumed leadership in 1997 by shooting his strongest rival in the
face.
	   The competition occurred after former cartel boss Juan Garcia
Abrego was captured in 1996 and deported to the United States. He
was sentenced to life in prison for smuggling 15 tons of cocaine
into the United States.
	   Under Garcia Abrego, the Gulf organization once was Mexico's
second-largest drug group, smuggling hundreds of tons of Colombian
cocaine into the United States each year.
	   The dominant drug gang now is the Arrellano Felix group, based
in Tijuana.
	   ___
	   CHINAUTLA, Guatemala (AP) _ Guatemalans in 30 municipalities
turned out in huge numbers Sunday to elect mayors and city
councils.
	   Voting is obligatory in Guatemala, so even people with no
interest in the elections showed up at the ballot boxes.
	   ``I came to vote because I'm registered here, but I don't know
who the candidates are, and I don't know who I'll vote for,'' said
Maria del Rosario Munoz, a 27-year-old Indian in traditional dress
from this town six miles (10 kms) northwest of Guatemala City.
	   The elections Sunday were selecting local officials for 30 of
Guatemala's 320 municipalities, with 395,262 voters registered. The
mayors and town councils will be in power for 18 months, until
general elections next year replace them.
	   ___
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ One of Colombia's last remaining major
drug bosses, Caribbean cartel leader Alberto Orlandez Gamboa, was
captured in the northern port of Barranquilla, the deputy national
police director announced Sunday.
	   His appearance had been altered by hair implants and his pockets
were full of cash.
	   Orlandez, alias ``The Snail,'' allegedly smuggled tons of
cocaine to Europe and the United States since at least as early as
1991. He has been indicted in Miami federal court on charges of
drug trafficking and money laundering, said the police official,
Gen. Luis Ernesto Gilibert.
	   He said Colombia's foreign ministry would decide whether to
extradite Orlandez for trial to the United States under last year's
law that reinstated extradition.
	   The 43-year-old Orlandez was arrested Saturday, ringed by
bodyguards and carrying false identification documents and dlrs
U.S. 5,000 in cash, police said. He faces charges of murder,
kidnapping and illicit enrichment in Colombia.
	   More than 5 tons of cocaine shipments owned by Orlandez have
been seized in Miami, New York, Lake Charles, Louisiana, Panama and
other locations since 1991, police said.
	   ___
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ The leader of the Communist Party
of the Russian Federation said Sunday that President Boris Yeltsin
has installed in his country ``a feudal mafia,'' following the
disappearance of the Soviet Union.
	   ``In my country, nobody is building capitalism. We are victims
of the constant robbery and looting of our national resources''
Gennady Zyuganov said at a press conference in the central
headquarters of the Argentine Communist Party.
	   He predicted ``a chaotic situation if Yeltsin sticks to his
present economic model.''
	   According to Zyuganov, 20 million people are now unemployed in
Russia ``and another 15 million are leading a miserable life.''
	   Zyuganov said he intends to reinforce links with Latin American
leftist organizations. He arrived Saturday from Brazil and is
scheduled to fly Sunday night to Cuba for a two-day visit.
	   ``In the case of Cuba, our relations have been very strong for a
long time, and we plan to strengthen them'', he said.
	   Zyuganov depicted the current United States economic blockade
against Cuba as ``a political anachronism'' and praised the Cuban
people ``for being able to reform their system without sacrifying
its social achievements.''
</TEXT>
