<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-Horn of Africa Conflict,0816 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopia-Eritrea conflict shows regional leaders follow their own
</HEADLINE>
agenda &QL; 
 &UR; With Eritrea-Ethiopia &QL; 
 &UR; AP News Analysis &QL; 
 &UR; By SUSAN LINNEE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The unexpected outbreak of hostilities between
Ethiopia and Eritrea serves as a strong reminder that former rebel
leaders groomed by the United States to form the vanguard of an
``African renaissance'' are following their own agenda _ and it is
not necessarily to contain Islamic fundamentalism or promote
regional stability.
	   Ethiopia's May 13 warning to Eritrea to withdraw from its
territory or face the consequences was the first public indication
that their months-long discussions about the border separating the
two nations in the Horn of Africa had run aground.
	   Feisty and much smaller Eritrea, an Italian colony from 1885 to
1941, replied that it had violated no boundary but would gladly
submit to international mediation. Eritrea came under a United
Nations mandate after World War II, was annexed by Ethiopia in
1962, and went on to fight a 30-year war of liberation.
	   U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Susan Rice, widely considered
the godmother of the Clinton administration's ``new'' African
policy, twice rushed to Ethiopia and Eritrea to talk sense to Prime
Minister Meles Zenawi and President Isaias Afwerki.
	   But the former rebel comrades-in-arms went ahead last week and
bombed each other anyway. Eritrea claims Ethiopia hit its main
military airport first; Ethiopia says it only retaliated for an
Eritrean airstrike on Mekele, the capital of its northern Tigray
region, in which it said 44 civilians were killed.
	   Scholars of Eritrea and Ethiopia doubt that contested border
areas are the real reason behind the conflict. They say the
marriage of convenience that brought Isaias' Eritrean People's
Liberation Front and Meles' Tigray People's Liberation Front
together to oust Ethiopian military ruler Col. Mengistu Haile
Mariam in 1991 has hit the rocks.
	   Isaias, 51, wants to show his younger colleague Meles, 46, _ and
the world _ that he can go it alone, without bowing to all the
conditions attached to international aid. Although he supports a
market economy, Isaias heads a highly centralized one-party state.
	   Meles, a member of the northern Tigray minority who has promoted
ethnic-based federalism and pays lip service to multipartyism, has
been harshly criticized by the majority Amharas and Oromos for
giving up Eritrea _ and its two Red Sea ports of Assab and Massawa
_ in return for Isaias' help.
	   It is also thought that Meles may be trying to show hard-liners
within his own movement that he is not soft on Eritrea, which he
apparently believed he could keep in hand, especially when both
countries shared a common currency, the birr.
	   But Eritrea's creation of the nakfa late last year forced
Ethiopia to peg all cross-border transactions, including use of
Assab's port, in hard-to-come-by dollars since neither of the two
African currencies is convertable.
	   Senior U.S. officials have not customarily intervened so
publicly in African conflicts.
	   But Rice, a protegee of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, is the prime mover behind the policy to contain _ or
unseat _ Sudan's National Islamic Front government.
	   A key element in this policy is a U.S.-underwritten association
of countries headed by former rebels, including historically
Christian-dominated Eritrea, Ethiopia, Uganda and Rwanda. The first
three have common _ and troubled _ borders with Sudan.
	   There is concern that a drawn-out conflict between Ethiopia and
Eritrea will undermine the U.S.-financed informal alliance of
countries headed by former rebels that is the cornerstone of the
policy.
	   These countries include Christian Ethiopia, Eritrea, Uganda and
Rwanda, and the leaders of all four pride themselves on their
independence of mind.
	   The first three have common _ and troubled _ borders with Sudan.
	   Eritrea, one of the world's poorest countries, has been hosting
the National Democratic Alliance of ousted former Sudanese Prime
Minister Sadiq al Mahdi, which attacks northeastern Sudan.
	   Reports _ which have landed a local correspondent for the French
news agency Agence France-Presse in an Asmara prison without charge
for more than a year _ indicate that Eritrean troops have been
fighting alongside the DNA.
	   Ethiopia offers haven to the rebel Sudan People's Liberation
Army, which Uganda also supports.
	   Rwanda, the co-author with the United States of a
so-far-unsuccessful four-point Eritrea-Ethiopia peace proposal, has
close ties with Eritrea, from which it has purchased at least 12
Soviet-era tanks with which to fight Hutu rebels.
	    &UR; ___
	   Editor's Note _ Susan Linnee is chief of bureau for East Africa
and has been reporting on Africa for more than a decade.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ANALYSIS-Horn of Africa Conflict; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
