r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo     06-07 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0703 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb police beat protesters in Kosovo's capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo PRI101 &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb forces pressed their campaign
against separatist rebels in the Kosovo countryside, while police
swinging clubs beat protesters at an independence rally in the
provincial capital.
	   At least six ethnic Albanians were injured Sunday when more than
100 police broke up the demonstration in Pristina, which had
largely escaped the violence that has convulsed the secessionist
province of Serbia in recent months.
	   Meanwhile, Serb forces reportedly continued shelling suspected
militant positions in western Kosovo as part of a stepped-up
campaign that has killed at least 50 people, according to ethnic
Albanian officials, and 200 others have been missing since late
May.
	   The violence has sent thousands of refugees fleeing ruined
villages, some to neighboring nations and has aroused alarm among
Western powers that a war is in the making that could spread to
other Balkan states.
	   Ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the 2.2 million
inhabitants of Kosovo, and most demand to secede from Serbia, which
along with Montenegro makes up Yugoslavia. Western powers oppose
any change of borders, but want the Serbs to cease their offensive
and give Kosovo the autonomy taken away by Serbia in 1989.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton spoke to British Prime Minister Tony
Blair on Sunday and they agreed to send a ``strong message'' that
the Serb offensive is unacceptable, a Blair aide said.
	   The United States and others planned deliberations this week on
what steps to take. British newspapers said the powers might
discuss military intervention.
	   In Washington, a top U.S. senator said Sunday that Kosovo ``has
the potential to become another Bosnia.''
	   ``We cannot allow this slaughter to occur. Once again the
Serbians are out of control. Something should be done,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott said on CNN's ``Late Edition.''
	   Lott, a Republican from Mississippi, said he would not rule out
the use of American troops. He said the United States should
``always be reluctant to use military force,'' but ``I'm not saying
we should not consider troops if it continues the way it is
going.''
	   In Turkey, there were fears that the violence in Kosovo could
derail a meeting of Balkan foreign ministers.
	   Foreign Ministers from Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Macedonia,
Romania and Yugoslavia will attend the two-day meeting that starts
Monday, while Bosnia and Slovenia have sent deputy ministers. They
are nominally to discuss economic cooperation and the region's
communications, energy and transportation infrastructure.
	   But sources close to the foreign ministers said Sunday that
Yugoslavia's refusal to allow any reference to the
Albanian-dominated secessionist Serbian province of Kosovo could
torpedo a joint declaration calling for closer regional
cooperation.
	   In Pristina, the relative peace was shattered Sunday when police
charged the approximately 1,000 protesters gathered for the 57th
consecutive daily rally against the Serbs' violent rule in Kosovo.
	   One protester could be seen bleeding in the street after he was
hit in the head by a policeman's gun butt and then kicked
repeatedly.
	   Albanian TV in Tirana reported that the Serbs shelled at least
two Kosovo villages Sunday. It also said ethnic Albanian militants
blew up the police headquarters in Ratkoc, and amid fierce fighting
between the two sides all the Serb residents and police had fled.
	   It was not known how much of a setback the Serb offensive has
dealt the province's clandestine rebels, known as the Kosovo
Liberation Army. The militants claim to control about 40 percent of
the southern province of Serbia.
	   The rebels, who are winning increasing support among Kosovo's
ethnic Albanians, appealed in a statement Sunday in the newspaper
Koha Ditore for more fighters to join them.
	   ``Come to strengthen our troops against the enemy artillery and
enemy infantry,'' the KLA statement said.
	   Pope John Paul II called on the world Sunday to act against
violence and repression in Kosovo. 	   
</TEXT>
