<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Dollar Slumps </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australian dollar slides towards record low
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The Australian dollar continued its
plunge toward 12-year record lows Monday despite attempts by the
Reserve Bank of Australia to halt its slide.
	   ``The Australian dollar will remain under pressure until
something fundamental changes in Asia,'' said Commonwealth Bank
senior manager for foreign exchange Kurt Magnus.
	   By late morning the local currency hit a near 12-year low of
59.77 U.S. cents, a level not seen since 1986.
	   The Australian dollar fell as low as 60 U.S. cents during
offshore trading Friday night. It closed in Sydney at 60.51 U.S.
cents.
	   Dealers said the central bank intervened in the market as
recently as Monday morning to attempt to prop up the ailing
currency by buying Aussie dollars.
	   ``We've got it on good authority that the RBA's been in to
smooth and test the currency and take some heat out of the
market,'' Macquarie Bank foreign exchange associate director Brent
Aggar said.
	   The RBA has already spent about U.S. dlrs 1.8 billion (3 billion
Australian dollars) in a largely futile attempt to prop up the
currency.
	   The Australian dollar's record low of 57.10 US cents was struck
in July 1986. 	   
</TEXT>
