<HEADER>
w2254 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Lebanon-Hezbollah     06-07 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Lebanon-Hezbollah's Future,0792 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
From militia to movement, Hezbollah faces uncertain future
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-Hezbollah-Military, FEA-Hezbollah-Glance &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NY312-316. AP Graphic BEIRUT &QL; 
 &UR; By ANTHONY SHADID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Lebanon's Hezbollah, a shadowy band of
Islamic militants that has transformed itself into a formidable
populist movement, should be the envy of guerrilla groups anywhere.
	   Its dedicated fighters number only in the hundreds, yet they are
threatening to oust the Israeli army, one of the world's toughest,
from the rocky hills of Lebanon's south. Its spies have infiltrated
Israel's allied militia. And its struggle has won surging
popularity across a country whose name still evokes images of
discord and civil war.
	   But an Israeli withdrawal _ an idea touted more and more by an
Israeli government conscious of the war's unpopularity at home _
may pose Hezbollah its greatest challenge since it was forged from
the chaos and strife of Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon.
	   Ironically, victory over Israel could amount to a setback.
	   ``The war has given the party a great deal of power, a great
deal of prestige and a great deal of recognition,'' said Farid el
Khazen, a professor at the American University of Beirut. ``Without
the war, Hezbollah will be deflated.''
	   Already, its leaders are pondering what comes next, and the
speculation drives to the heart of Hezbollah's identity.
	   Having transformed itself from a militia to a movement, can it
overhaul itself yet again? More important, what shape will
Hezbollah take in the unruly tumult of Lebanese politics: charity
organization, political party or grassroots movement?
	   Its success in remaking itself could point the way for other
radical Islamic groups to integrate themselves into Arab societies
by forgoing violence for perhaps more effective politicking.
	   Today's Hezbollah is a far cry from the feared group linked to
the 1983 bombing of a U.S. Marine barracks, which killed 240
Americans, and the kidnapping of more than 50 foreigners amid the
anarchy that defined Lebanon during its 1975-90 civil war.
	   Abroad, the attacks brought Hezbollah a notoriety it is still
trying to live down despite its steadfast denials of any role. The
U.S. State Department, for one, insists it still engages in
terrorism. At home, its zeal in smashing up Beirut bars and banning
card-playing at cafes as un-Islamic bolstered a robust image as a
collection of religious fanatics.
	   In recent years, however, Hezbollah has gone from issuing
religious edicts declaring Lebanon's government criminal to running
candidates in elections for parliament.
	   It neither can nor wants to shed its image as a religious party
representing Shiite Muslims, Lebanon's largest sect. But its
leaders routinely speak out about unemployment and the rising cost
of living, complaints voiced by other opposition parties.
	   And from years of secrecy and shunning outsiders, the group now
runs a sophisticated press office, its well-dressed functionaries
carrying cellular phones and volunteering an electronic mail
address. It owns a television and radio station, publishes a weekly
newspaper and advertises an Internet site. It even backs a soccer
team.
	   ``The tools of Hezbollah have changed and the way it works has
changed,'' said Nayef Kraim, the group's spokesman.
	   By far, though, Hezbollah draws its greatest support from
success on the battlefield. With Syrian and Iranian backing, it
launches dozens of raids every month aimed at an Israeli army that
has controlled southern Lebanon for 20 years as a way of guarding
Israel's northern frontier.
	   In April, Hezbollah attacked Israel and its Lebanese allies 117
times, the largest number of raids in more than a decade.
	   The attacks followed Israel's declaration that it would withdraw
if it received security guarantees _ a proposal that Hezbollah read
as a sign of approaching victory. While not saying it will stop
fighting Israel, Hezbollah has made clear that once Israeli forces
withdraw, the Lebanese army will take over in the south _ a promise
many in Lebanon read as a tacit pledge to end the war.
	   But that success makes many ponder the future. Even Hezbollah
cadres acknowledge the uncertainty.
	   ``We don't expect to be heroes forever,'' said Mohammed Hijazi,
a director of a Hezbollah-run hospital in Beirut.
	   The Lebanese government will likely demand that Hezbollah
surrender its weapons. The war's end may require, as well, a
departure from the martial image the group has long fostered: Its
fighters are called ``mujahideen,'' or religious warriors, and its
banner features a fist clutching a Kalashnikov rifle.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
