<DOCNO> APW19980607.1028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 06/07/1998 22:07:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2255 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Lebanon-Hezbollah 1stAdd   06-07 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Lebanon-Hezbollah's Future, 1st Add,0390 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIRUT: Kalashnikov rifle.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Publicly, the movement does not worry.
	   ``Hezbollah has become a part of the Lebanese fabric, and it has
a part in the political and social reality,'' Sheik Naim Kassem,
the group's deputy leader, said in an interview. ``Its role is not
limited to the resistance to the occupation only.''
	   Indeed, Hezbollah spends tens of millions of dollars a year _
made possible by Iran _ to run nine schools and three hospitals,
provide drinking water to Beirut's Shiite Muslim slums and rebuild
homes damaged in the fighting with Israel.
	   For some, that helping hand could ensure Hezbollah's continued
popularity among the poor.
	   ``People love the people who serve them,'' said Adel Ollaik, who
runs a Hezbollah hospital in Nabatiyeh, a southern town within
sight of Israeli positions. ``After the war, Hezbollah will succeed
more because the social institutions will become stronger.''
	   Others see the charity work as only a step in Hezbollah's
pursuit of its political ambitions, unfettered by the burdens of
waging war but coping with a loss of the popularity won in the
struggle.
	   The movement still supports the creation of an Iranian-style
Islamic state in Lebanon, but it rarely declares so in public. In
interviews, its leaders say Hezbollah will push the idea through
dialogue, not force, and acknowledge that the reality of 18 sects
in a country still scarred by communal war rules out an Islamic
state soon.
	   The new arena is the 128-seat parliament, where seven Hezbollah
members already sit. Like other Islamic parties, they rail against
the corruption and cronyism endemic to Lebanese capitalism.
	   The war's end could make possible another step in the movement's
moderation: from militants to successful guerrillas to a grassroots
movement competing in Lebanese politics _ a transformation some
call its ``Lebanonization.''
	   But without the support it derives from the war, Hezbollah will
inevitably become more vulnerable, many say.
	   ``Hezbollah's leadership today is very pragmatic and very much
in tune with Lebanese communal politics,'' said Khazen, the
university analyst. ``They are efficient, well-organized and they
play the game well.''
	   ``But the game,'' he added, ``will become more competitive.''
</TEXT>
