r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Hezbollah-Militar     06-07 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Hezbollah-Military,0383 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Better trained, Hezbollah ups pressure on Israel in Lebanon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-Lebanon-Hezbollah's Future &QL; 
 &UR; By ANTHONY SHADID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) _ Across the war-scarred wadis of
southern Lebanon, Hezbollah was once notorious for sending waves of
zealous fighters in reckless, frontal assaults on Israeli army
positions.
	   Many were simply mowed down.
	   Today, Israeli soldiers patrolling the south face a far more
sophisticated opponent. Hezbollah's guerrillas are better trained
and better organized and have a far better chance of getting home
alive.
	   The militia's striking transformation stands as the driving
force behind a possible Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon,
which Israel has controlled either by itself or through proxies for
20 years as a way to protect its northern territory from guerrilla
attacks.
	   ``One thing that makes Hezbollah stand out is that they are good
students,'' said Timur Goksel, spokesman for U.N. peacekeepers in
Lebanon who has served in the south since 1979. ``They take their
lessons very carefully, and they learn from their mistakes.''
	   Hezbollah is thought to have anywhere from 300 to 1,000 trained
fighters, with many more armed supporters. Other than night-vision
equipment, much of their arsenal is low-tech: sniper rifles,
mortars, rocket-propelled grenades and Soviet-designed rockets.
	   Their intelligence has improved markedly, and supporters have
successfully infiltrated the demoralized South Lebanon Army, a
militia trained and equipped by Israel, security officials say.
	   As important is the group's ability to sustain losses. Sixty-six
guerrillas were killed last year, among them the 19-year-old son of
Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, Hezbollah's leader.
	   Just 39 Israeli soldiers were killed over the same period, but
the figure was higher than in past years and has led in part to the
war's growing unpopularity inside Israel.
	   Across Lebanon, volunteers collect money for the guerrillas, who
are known collectively as the Islamic resistance.
	   But the big money comes from Iran, which is believed to
contribute dlrs 10 million to dlrs 20 million a month to Hezbollah.
Twenty percent to 25 percent of that goes to fighting the war.
</TEXT>
