<SLUG> BC-FEA-Hezbollah-Glance,0274 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Facts and figures on Hezbollah's work in Lebanon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-Lebanon-Hezbollah's Future &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Some facts about Hezbollah:
	   ___
	   HISTORY _ Formed in 1982 with Iranian help during Israel's
invasion of Lebanon. Began as radical offshoot of Amal, Shiite
Muslim movement that remains its biggest competitor. Linked to
bombing of U.S. Marine barracks in 1983, bombings of two American
Embassy buildings and kidnappings of more than 50 foreigners.
Moderated in recent years, emerging as strong political force.
	   ___
	   CONSTITUENCY _ Draws support from Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiite
Muslims, country's biggest sect but long neglected by government.
Popular in southern Lebanon, Bekaa Valley in eastern Lebanon and
poor southern suburbs of Beirut.
	   ___
	   CHARITY WORK _ Operates nine schools, three hospitals, 13 dental
clinics. Provides drinking water to Beirut slums, rebuilds roads
and houses destroyed in fighting in south. Refuses to disclose
budget, but Iran estimated to provide dlrs 10 million- dlrs 20
million a month.
	   ___
	   MILITARY _ Believed to have 300-1,000 fighters, facing Israeli
force of 1,500 soldiers and 2,500 allied Lebanese militiamen. Armed
mainly with mortars, rockets, rocket-propelled grenades and rifles.
Training and intelligence have improved.
	   ___
	   POLITICS _ Factions remain within Hezbollah, but Sheik Hassan
Nasrallah exercises clear control as secretary-general. Runs
television and radio station and weekly newspaper. Seven members
sit in Lebanon's parliament. Vocal critic of corruption, inflation,
unemployment.
</TEXT>
