w2278 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-China-RemakingPar     06-07 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-China-Remaking Paradise,1004 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In new step for `Workers Paradise,' China tries social security
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-Paradise-New Farmers, FEA-Paradise-Bird Help &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY300 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHARLES HUTZLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIYUAN, China (AP) _ Communist welfare helped drive Shanxi
Textile Printing and Dyeing Factory into bankruptcy.
Capitalist-style social security helped dig it out.
	   Located in China's rusting heartland of heavy industry, Shanxi
Textile had the typical ailments of state industries: bad
management, glutted markets and swarms of workers _ 10,000 strong
in this case, all guaranteed lifetime jobs and benefits.
	   ``Our burdens were too heavy. From birth to death we were
responsible for their nursery school, primary school, middle
school, then on to work and retirement. It was too much,'' said
Wang Yuhao, one of the factory's senior managers.
	   So when Shanxi Textile went bankrupt, the Taiyuan city
government tapped new social welfare funds to provide for old and
unwanted employees, making the factory more attractive to
investors.
	   China is dismantling the employer-based socialist welfare state
that was once the hallmark of the communists' ``workers paradise''
but left state industries uncompetitive. In its place, a new
government-administered social welfare system is being constructed,
more Western in style and decidedly bare bones.
	   Old-age pensions and formerly free health care are being
retooled and once unneeded unemployment insurance being invented.
It's the social spending side of what has been dubbed China's ``New
Deal'' _ a public works program to invigorate a slowing economy and
find jobs for millions of laid-off workers as decrepit state
industries cope with free-market reforms.
	   ``If we want labor mobility, we must have a social security
system,'' said Gu Shengzu, vice mayor of Wuhan, another ailing,
aging industrial city in central China.
	   A new social security system is crucial to preventing unrest as
the ruling Communist Party purges the economy of the last traces of
central planning and, in the process, breaks its promise of
lifetime job security for urban workers.
	   Questions persist whether the government can build a social
safety net fast enough to handle the swelling unemployed or even
come up with the money to build it. But China's new pragmatic
premier, Zhu Rongji, has partly staked his reformist mandate on the
program's success.
	   A new Ministry of Labor and Social Security has been set up as
part of Zhu's sweeping government restructuring. Provinces have
been ordered to unify by year's end the patchwork of unemployment,
pension and health funds now run, often badly, by local
governments.
	   The need for a social safety net is desperately evident in
Taiyuan, the grimy capital of China's coal country in Shanxi
province 400 kilometers (250 miles) southwest of Beijing.
	   Local officials and state business executives freely admit many
factories have not paid their workers in a year. At mammoth Taiyuan
Iron and Steel, with 60,000 active and retired workers on its
payrolls, most production lines operate only when the rare order
comes in.
	   Although idled workers are legion, outright unemployment is
sparse because many state factories still remain responsible for
providing stipends and subsidized housing for laid-off employees.
	   ``Because there's no social security system in China,
unemployment has become this extraordinarily big deal,'' said Zhang
Jidong, general manager of Taiyuan Copper Industry Corp., a
state-run smelter burdened with more than 4,000 workers.
	   Zhang laid off 500 last year, mainly by leasing them the
restaurants, shops and other sideline businesses his company was
running to provide employees with subsidized daily comforts. He
kept several chicken and duck farms to pay pensions for 600
retirees. If allowed, he would fire 2,000 more workers.
	   Taiyuan is trying to meet the demands of reform. An unemployment
insurance program, started in 1994, now covers more than 3,700
enterprises. Firms pay 1 percent of their payrolls and an
additional 0.5 percent is taken from each worker's wages.
	   If laid off, workers can draw 75 percent of their pay _ with a
monthly minimum of 175 yuan (dlrs 21) _ for two years. Instead of
lifetime job security, unemployed residents of Taiyuan are now
guaranteed 120 yuan (dlrs 15) a month in welfare payments
indefinitely if they cannot find work.
	   When Shanxi Textile was allowed to declare bankruptcy in late
1996 _ then also a rare move for a state company _ the city used
its unemployment fund to provide 5.3 million yuan (dlrs 640,000) to
encourage some workers to take early retirement and to pay for
unemployment benefits and job training for others.
	   About 4,000 younger able-bodied workers were invited to stay on
with the factory, which was reorganized with the help of two new
investors as Xinkai Textile Printing and Dyeing Co. Ltd.
	   ``Now, the new company just deals with production,'' said Wang,
the former manager at the old mill who now is a director at the
revived factory.
	   For social security to succeed nationwide, the government must
force the booming private sector, not just unhealthy state firms,
to take part. In Taiyuan, payroll taxes for unemployment, health
insurance and pensions account for nearly a third of employer
expenses, said the city labor bureau's director, Zhao Qingsheng.
	   Beijing and provincial capitals may find it hard to wrest
control of funds from local governments. Although social welfare
funds are supposed to be invested solely in low-risk treasury
bonds, local governments have diverted money to build airports,
roads and drinking water systems and, in Taiyuan, buy cars.
	   With money in short supply, weak businesses and a relatively
poor working class, China plans to keep its social security system
no-frills.
	   ``We can't make the payments too high like in some developed
countries or nobody would want to work. That's no good,'' Zhao
said.
</TEXT>
