<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar tops 140 yen in Tokyo, stocks down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with midday stock, bond and currency prices

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar broke through the 140-yen level for
the first time in seven years and showed no signs of slowing in
morning trading in Tokyo on Monday. Japanese stock prices slipped.
	   The dollar bought 140.69 yen at midday, up 1.27 yen from late
Friday in Tokyo and its highest point since June 20, 1991. In New
York, the dollar settled at 139.75 yen on Friday.
	   The dollar crossed the 140-yen line for the first time in thin
weekend trading Sunday in New York.
	   The dollar's strength sprang from fresh evidence of a robust
U.S. economy after the Labor Department reported on Friday the
nation's unemployment rate held to a 28-year-low of 4.3 percent in
May.
	   Also supporting the U.S. currency was the diminishing likelihood
the Group of Seven industrialized nations will make a strong
statement criticizing the current dollar level, traders said.
	   Officials from the G-7 _ the United States, Japan, Germany,
Italy, Canada, Britain and France _ are scheduled to meet in Paris
on Tuesday.
	   Persistent pessimism over Japan's economy also continued to
weigh on sentiment among many investors, who have sold yen to shift
money into more robust markets in the United States and Europe.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
edged down 26.03 points, or 0.17 percent, to 15,297.40 at the close
of the morning session. On Friday, the average lost 103.04 points,
or 0.67 percent.
	   The benchmark average started lower on small-lot selling as the
yen's weakening discouraged some investors about the outlook for
Japan's economy.
	   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 3.43 points, or 0.29 percent, to 1,198.51. The
TOPIX closed down 5.56 points, or 0.46 percent.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond was unchanged at 1.165 percent. Its price fell
slightly to 112.30 yen from 112.31 yen on Friday.
 &UR; (mef-km-dj)
</TEXT>
