<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Paradise-New Farmers,0730 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China's jobless city dwellers head for the countryside
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-China-Remaking Paradise &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY301 &QL; 
 &UR; By ELAINE KURTENBACH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   EIGHT MOUTHS VILLAGE, China (AP) _ In the heyday of China's
embrace of radical communism, millions of young urban Chinese were
sent to the countryside _ a sentence to years of drudgery, hunger
and loneliness.
	   Most eventually escaped back to the cities. But in a telling
sign of China's progress toward capitalism, some who escaped are
trickling back to the farms, this time in search of economic
opportunity.
	   Yu Yuzhu joined China's burgeoning ranks of jobless city workers
three years ago. Now the 40-year-old former school teacher views
that setback as a turning point.
	   ``Losing my job could have been a bad thing but, in fact, it was
my chance,'' Yu says as she feeds corn, barley and beans to pairs
of plump white pigeons at the Eight Mouths Pigeon Farm near
Beijing.
	   A testament to her land's past use as a communal pig farm,
fading white characters painted on the walls of Yu's farm proclaim:
``Only socialism can save China.''
	   These days, however, Beijing's government is encouraging
residents to follow the example set by Yu and other entrepreneurs
in putting unfarmed land in the countryside to profitable use.
	   Some transplants are growing fruit trees or medicinal herbs or
raising horses, pigs or ducks on marginal land rented from
villages, officials say. The city also has rented out farm plots
and greenhouses in Shunyi county, north of the city, to grow
lucrative vegetable crops.
	   Many now turning to farming are among those who were forced to
live and labor with peasants during the 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution, when at then leader Mao Tse-tung's urging, the nation's
politics swung toward a utopian vision of communism.
	   According to the state-run Beijing Youth Daily, the kind of
intensive, high-tech farming promoted in Shunyi can earn up to
240,000 yuan (dlrs 29,000) an acre (600,000 yuan or dlrs 72,640 a
hectare) _ a far cry from the miserable rations of sweet potatoes
and corn buns the ``rusticated youth'' lived on while toiling in
impoverished villages during the Cultural Revolution.
	   It is a signal of the desperation spreading through China's
cities that urban residents are looking for work in the
countryside. But despite the official campaign, it is an unlikely
option for most people, given the scarcity of usable farmland and
the tens of millions of hungry farmers migrating to the cities in
search of a living wage.
	   In China, only truly barren land is left unfarmed. And most
urbanites are loath to dirty their hands anyway.
	   ``Unfortunately, most Beijingers are too proud to work in the
countryside,'' says Duan Jianling, a city official. ``People should
be more open-minded.''
	   Yu was among the last students sent to the countryside, in
1977-78. Like many of her generation, she wanted to stay in school,
but politics intervened and she went to live in the mountains south
of Beijing when she was 20.
	   ``We were there to be taught. It was a completely passive
experience,'' Yu says. ``Now we are our own masters and I am the
one taking the initiative.''
	   After losing her job as a teacher, Yu helped a friend start a
nursery school. When that venture flopped, she turned to raising
pigeons for food.
	   Yu started her business in the courtyard of her mother-in-law's
village home, with her brother-in-law's help. They soon expanded
and moved to the former pig farm.
	   Raising pigeons can be a tricky business because the birds are
vulnerable to illness. While the birds don't mind northern China's
bitter winter cold, Yu's eight employees stay busy protecting them
from heatstroke during the sultry summer months.
	   Timing is crucial. Pigeons should be eaten when they are between
25 and 28 days old or they get to be too tough, Yu says.
	   Yu says she sells about 2,000 pigeons a month, but her success
worries her.
	   A popular dish in some parts of southern China, roasted pigeon
is relatively expensive and is not commonly eaten by northern
Chinese except as a health-boosting delicacy.
	   ``If we want to continue to breed so many pigeons, we have to
persuade northern Chinese to eat more,'' Yu says. ``You have to
always keep thinking of the next step ahead.''
</TEXT>
