<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Paradise-Bird Help,0422 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
From foes to friends: China's birds making comeback
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-China-Remaking Paradise &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY302 &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN LEICESTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Yin Guoqiang hasn't had a job in more than 10
years and, with factories firing workers all around, doesn't expect
one soon.
	   But he's not worried _ his feathered friends support him.
	   Yin, a former machine repairman, raises birds for a living. He's
one of a growing number of Beijing residents for whom parakeets,
parrots and other birds have become a vital source of income in
troubled times.
	   Keeping pet birds is an ancient Chinese tradition that for many
remains just a hobby. But for others, bird raising is big business,
so big that speculative fever has sent bird prices yo-yoing.
	   Capitalism's intrusion into the tranquil world of bird raising
owes much to unemployment. As overmanned state factories lay off
workers, good jobs are hard to find. The unemployed are improvising
to make ends meet.
	   Many go into business for themselves. Sidewalks and alleys are
filled with people peddling snacks, knickknacks and the like.
	   Others, like 40-year-old Yin, go to the Jade Dragonfly Bridge
market to wheel and deal in pet birds. The market is setting up new
stalls to accommodate the swelling ranks of bird raisers.
	   Small and easily transportable, birds are an ideal cottage
industry for China's capital, where space is limited and families
share small apartments. Some birds fetch as much as 20,000 yuan
(dlrs 2,440) a pair _ what the average Beijinger earns in about
three years.
	   Of Beijing's estimated 300,000 bird raisers, about two-thirds
are laid-off workers, and ``most have made bird rearing their one
and only economic support,'' the official Beijing Evening News
reported recently.
	   Yin, who deals from a flatbed tricycle, says even if he could
find a job, he probably wouldn't take it.
	   ``At least doing this, I'm the boss. I watch over the birds,''
he says. ``If I had a job, others would watch over me. They would
be the boss.''
	   Yin reaped a windfall last year when prices were pushed to a
peak by speculators. But when state-run news media warned a few
months ago that the market was overheating, prices plunged, Yin
says.
	   Today, Yin still earns enough from birds to live, but others
``lost a packet.''
	   ``They really wept,'' he adds. ``One day, they bought birds for
900 yuan (dlrs 108) a pair. A few days later, they were worth 100
yuan (dlrs 12).''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Paradise-Bird Help; CT:i; 
