<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US-MLS Roundup,0891 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Galaxy 5, Revolution 1
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PASADENA, Califlornia (AP) _ Ezra Hendrickson scored twice as
the Los Angeles Galaxy defeated the New England Revolution 5-1
Sunday in Major League Soccer play.
	   Welton, Greg Vanney and Mauricio Cienfuegos also scored for the
Galaxy (12-2) and Carlos Hermosillo had two assists in his MLS
debut.
	   Johnny Torres scored in the opening minute for New England
(4-8), which lost its fifth straight. The Revolution played the
last 63 minutes shorthanded after defender Manny Motajo was ejected
for a second yellow card.
	   Welton tied the score in the 38th minute with a league-leading
12 goals. Revolution goalkeeper Ian Feuer managed to get his right
hand on Vanney's powerful 30-yard shot, but Welton beat midfielder
Ted Chronopoulos and Feuer to the rebound, tapping a shot inside
the 6-yard (5.5-meter) line into the open goal.
	   Welton assisted on Cienfuegos' goals for a league-leading point
total of 33.
	   Hermosillo set up the tiebreaking goal in the 59th minute,
heading Welton's pass back to Cienfuegos, who shot from just inside
the penalty area.
	   Hendrickson scored in the 65th and 72nd minutes. Hermosillo, who
was assigned to the Galaxy Saturday, also assisted on Vanney's
68th-minute goal.
	   Los Angeles out-shot New England 25-8 and led 8-3 in shots on
goals. Feuer made three saves, while Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin
Hartman made two.
	   Motajo, who played with the Galaxy during its inaugural 1996
season and was playing his first match for New England, tripped
Wellington Sanchez and Cienfuegos in the same sequence. He had also
received a yellow card in the 20th minute for a tackle from behind.
Under MLS rules, Motajo will be suspended for the Revolution's next
match, Sunday against Chicago.
 &UR; Burn 5, United 4, SO
	   In Washington, Ted Eck atoned for an own goal by scoring the
shootout clincher Sunday and the Dallas Burn beat D.C. United 5-4,
their first loss at home this season.
	   The upset came just three days after Dallas (8-5) took the worst
defeat in MLS history, 8-1 to the Los Angeles Galaxy.
	   United (12-4) came into the game with an 8-0 mark at RFK
Stadium, but the Burn outscored D.C. 3-1 in the shootout.
	   Dallas had taken a 4-3 lead late in regulation when Mickey
Trotman tapped in a rebound of a shot by Brian Haynes. Moments
later, United knotted the score when a pass by A.J. Wood deflected
off the head of Burn defenseman Tom Soehn and past his own
goalkeeper Mark Dodd, forcing the shootout.
	   Richard Farrer and Temoc Suarez, who each scored their first
goal of the season in the first half, joined Eck in scoring in the
shootout for the Burn.
	   Brian Kamler scored the only United goal in the shootout. Dodd,
who had seven saves in the game, had saves against Jaime Moreno and
Tony Sanneh in the shootout.
	   Dallas' other goal was on a penalty kick by Damian in the second
half.
	   Roy Lassiter scored twice for United and Marco Etheverry added a
goal.
	   Lassiter's second goal, his eighth in nine games with United,
tied the game 3-3 in the 70th minute.
	   The eight goals scored in regulation were an MLS record for RFK
Stadium. The four goals were a season-high by Dallas.
	   Dallas played without midfielder Leonel Alvarez, who was
suspended after being ejected during the loss to Los Angeles. D.C.
United was without defenders Eddie Pope and Jeff Agoos, who are
playing in the World Cup.
	   Every MLS team except Dallas will be missing players the next
several weeks because of the World Cup the next several weeks. In
all, 21 MLS players are in France for the tournament, including 16
on the U.S. team. Columbus will miss five players, a league high.
 &UR; MetroStars 2, Fusion 1
	   In Fort Lauderdale, Florida, Miles Joseph's goal in the 88th
minute off an assist from Eduardo Hurtado gave the New York-New
Jersey MetroStars a 2-1 victory Sunday, sending the Miami Fusion to
their fifth consecutive loss.
	   The game was played in 97-degree heat before 9,073 fans at
Lockhart Stadium. The MetroStars improved to 7-6 and kept their
hold on third place in the MLS East with 19 points. The Fusion, who
outshot the MetroStars 28-11, dropped to 5-9 with 11 points.
	   Joseph, who came on as a second-half sub, took a perfectly
played through ball from Hurtado and beat Miami goalkeeper Scott
Budnick with a left-footed shot to the far post. The Fusion have
given up a league-high nine goals in the final 10 minutes this
season.
	   New York-New Jersey led 1-0 at halftime on Giovanni Savarese's
goal in the 36th minute. Savarese pounced on a loose ball and shot
into an open net after Budnick mishandled a pass intended for
MetroStars midfielder Diego Sonora. The goal was Savarese's fifth
this season.
	   Miami's Diego Serna equalized in the 63rd minute when he took a
short pass from Dan Stebbins and beat goalie Tony Meola from close
range. The goal marked the first time season the Fusion have tied a
game after allowing the opening goal.
	   Meola was outstanding down the stretch as Miami pressured a
worn-out MetroStars defense. He punched a header by Roger Thomas
over the bar in the 80th minute and stopped David Vaudeuil from
eight yards just five minutes later.
	   After Joseph's goal, Meola made clutch saves on Miami's Pablo
Mastroeni and Cle Kooiman to preserve the win.
</TEXT>
