<SLUG> BC-Japan-France-Banks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three Japanese banks to close operations in Paris
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Three large Japanese banks will shut down their
branches in Paris to cut costs and consolidate operations elsewhere
in Europe, bank officials and media said Monday.
	   Sanwa Bank Ltd., Japan's third-largest private lender, will
close its Paris office within the year and move the operations to
London, said spokesman Haruhiko Kimura.
	   With the creation of a single European currency, the bank will
be able to streamline management by concentrating its European
lending business in a single office, Kimura said.
	   ``We see London as more of an international financial center,''
Kimura said.
	   Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
Ltd. will also close their branches in the French capital within
three years, the Nihon Keizai business daily reported Monday.
	   A smaller bank, Yasuda Trust &AMP; Banking Co., also plans to shut
down all European branchs except its Luxembourg office, the paper
said.
	   Burdened by 76 trillion yen (dlrs 550 billion) in bad loans from
the collapse of Japan's property market in the early 1990s,
Japanese banks have been forced to cut back at home and abroad.
	    &UR; (mef)
</TEXT>
