<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Sea Power </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines eyes electricity from ocean currents
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippine government has
received an offer from Italy to help it harness the sea as an
inexpensive source of electrical power.
	   This was disclosed over the weekend by trade secretary Cesar
Bautista, who said the offer came from the University of Naples.
	   The offer has received an endorsement from the European Union,
which has promised the Philippines a dlrs 500,000 grant to finance
a feasibility study for the proposed project, he said.
	   The proposal calls for the construction and operation of power
generators that will run on turbines driven by sea currents. The
concept is ideal for the Philippines, an archipelago composed of
thousands of islands _ and plenty of water.
	   ``The idea here is to use the water velocity to generate
electricity,'' said Bautista, adding that the turbines are
practically ``maintenance-free'' and thus inexpensive to operate.
	   Bautista, however, didn't disclose the cost of putting up such a
facility.
	   He said such plants would be ideal for providing electricity to
villages located near water with a strong enough current to run the
turbines. The University of Naples has identified eight such sites,
he said.
	   Bautista said similar projects are currently operating in the
Mediterranean, the Atlantic, South America and China, but this
would be the first in Southeast Asia.
</TEXT>
