<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Recession </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bank chairman warns of Singapore recession unless government acts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The chairman of one of Singapore's biggest
banks warned of a recession if the government does not take action
now to stimulate the economy, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   Wee Cho Yaw, chairman of United Overseas Bank, told The Straits
Times that the current economic situation in the small island
republic was the worst he had seen in his 40-year banking career.
	   The Singapore government has stood staunchly by earlier
predictions that the economy would grow at least 2.5 percent this
year.
	   But the forecast was made before the economic turmoil in
neighboring Indonesia worsened and other regional economies began
to exhibit signs of a slowdown into zero growth or outright
recession.
	   At least two private investment houses have already predicted
that the Singapore economy will fall into recession this year,
though a recent newspaper survey of 15 analysts and economists
showed an average forecast of 1.5 percent growth.
	   Finance Minister Richard Hu defended the government forecasts in
Parliament last week, though he conceded that the authorities stood
ready to implement a stimulus package soon if new figures indicate
a likely recession.
	   In his interview with The Straits Times, bank chairman Wee said
Asia's financial crisis far exceeds the last major economic
challenge Singapore faced, a recession in 1985.
	   He said the government forecast was unlikely to be achieved and
urged immediate action.
	   ``If there is no growth, or a mere 1 percent growth, then the
government will have to inject more funds into the system,'' Wee
was quoted as saying.
	   These could include tax cuts and more spending on
infrastructure, he said.
</TEXT>
